urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.170#An unordained homecoming then for the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.171#If Hera had not had a word with Athena:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.172#"This is awful. Child of Zeus, Mystic Daughter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.173#Of the Aegis-Holder, are we going to allow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.174#The Greeks to go home just like that, run away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.175#To their own country over the sea's broad back?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.176#They're just going to hand Priam and the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.177#The glory, not to mention Helen of Argos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.178#For whose sake many a Greek has perished in Troy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.179#Far from his homeland. Go down there now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.180#Along the ranks of the bronze-shirted Greeks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.181#And with your mild words restrain each man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.182#Don't let them haul their curved prows to the sea."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.183#And Athena streaked down from Olympus' crags,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.184#Her eyes like owls', grey in the blue air,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.185#And came quickly to the ships in the beachhead camp.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.186#She found Odysseus there, his mind like Zeus' own,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.187#Standing in thought. He had not laid a hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.188#On his benched, black ship, and his heart was heavy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.189#The owl-eyed goddess stood close to him and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.190#"Son of Laertes in the line of Zeus, wily Odysseus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.191#Are you Greeks going to run away just like that,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.192#Home to your fatherland over the sea's broad back?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.193#Are you just going to hand Priam and the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.194#The glory, not to mention Helen of Argos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.195#For whose sake many a Greek has perished in Troy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.196#Far from his homeland? Now go down along
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.197#All the ships of the bronze-shirted Greeks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.198#And with your mild words restrain each man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.199#Don' let them haul their curved prows to the sea."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.200#Odysseus knew that voice, and he set off at a run,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.201#Throwing his cloak behind him---Eurybates
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.202#The herald, his man from Ithaca, gathered it up---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.203#And he went up to Agamemnon and got from him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.204#His ancestral staff, that splinter of eternity,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.205#And with it went along the ships of the Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.206#Whenever he encountered a chieftain or the like,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.207#He tried to restrain him with gentle words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.208#"What's gotten into you? I don't mean to frighten you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.209#As if you were a coward, but sit down here yourself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.210#And make your men sit down. You don't really know
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.211#Agamemnon's mind. He's just testing us now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.212#But before long he's going to come down on us hard.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.213#Didn't we all hear what he said in council?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.214#If he gets angry the whole army had better watch out.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.215#Kings are bred by Zeus and have tempers to match."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.216#But if he caught any of the ordinary soldiers yelling,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.217#He would belt him with the staff and bawl him out:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.218#"You there, who do you think you are? Sit still
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.219#And listen to your betters. You're a weakling,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.220#Unfit for combat, a nothing in battle and in council.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.221#Do you think every Greek here can be a king?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.222#It's no good having a carload of commanders. We need
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.223#One commander, one king, the one to whom Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.224#Son of Cronus the crooked, has given the staff
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.225#And the right to make decisions for his people."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.226#And so Odysseus mastered the army. The men all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.227#Streamed back from their ships and huts and assembled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.228#With a roar.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.229#A wave from the restless, churning sea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.230#Crashes on a beach, and the water seethes and thunders.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.231#They had all dropped to the sand and were sitting there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.232#Except for one man, Thersites, a blathering fool
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.233#And a rabble rouser. This man had a repertory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.234#Of choice insults he used at random to revile the nobles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.235#Saying anything he thought the soldiers would laugh at.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.236#He was also the ugliest soldier at the siege of Troy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.237#Bowlegged, walked with a limp, his shoulders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.238#Slumped over his caved-in chest, and up top
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.239#Scraggly fuzz sprouted on his pointy head.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.240#Achilles especially hated him, as did Odysseus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.241#Because he was always provoking them. Now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.242#He was screaming abuse at Agamemnon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.243#The Achaeans were angry with him and indignant,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.244#But that didn't stop him from razzing the warlord:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.245#"What's wrong, son of Atreus, something you need?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.246#Your huts are filled with bronze, and with women
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.247#We Achaeans pick out and give to you first of all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.248#Whenever we take some town. Are you short of gold?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.249#Maybe some Trojan horse breeder will bring you some
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.250#Out of Ilion as ransom for his son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.251#Whom I or some other Achaean has captured.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.252#Maybe it's a young girl for you to make love to
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.253#And keep off somewhere for yourself. It's not right
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.254#For a leader to march our troops into trouble.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.255#You Achaeans are a disgrace, Achaean women, not men!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.256#Let's sail home in our ships and leave him here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.257#To stew over his prizes so he'll have a chance to see
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.258#Whether he needs our help or not. Furthermore,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.259#He dishonored Achilles, who's a much better man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.260#Achilles doesn't have an angry bone in his body,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.261#Or this latest atrocity would be your last, son of Atreus!"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.262#That was the abuse Agamemnon took
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.263#From the mouth of Thersites. Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.264#Was on him in a flash, staring him down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.265#With a scowl, and laid into him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.266#"Mind your tongue, Thersites. Better think twice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.267#About being the only man here to quarrel with his betters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.268#I don't care how bell-toned an orator you are,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.269#You're nothing but trash. There's no one lower
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.270#In all the army that followed Agamemnon to Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.271#You have no right even to mention kings in public,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.272#Much less badmouth them so you can get to go home.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.273#We have no idea how things are going to turn out,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.274#What kind of homecoming we Achaeans will have.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.275#Yet you have the nerve to revile Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.276#Son of Atreus, the shepherd of his people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.277#Because the Danaan heroes are generous to him?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.278#You think you can stand up in public and insult him?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.279#Well, let me tell you something. I guarantee
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.280#That if I ever catch you running on at the mouth again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.281#As you were just now, my name isn't Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.282#And may I never again be called Telemachus' father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.283#If I don't lay hold of you, strip your ass naked,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.284#And run you out of the assembly and through the ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.285#Crying at all the ugly licks I land on you."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.286#And with that he whaled the staff down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.287#On Thersites' back. The man crumpled in pain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.288#And tears flooded his eyes. A huge bloody welt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.289#Rose on his back under the gold stave's force,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.290#And he sat there astounded, drooling with pain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.291#And wiping away his tears. The troops, forgetting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.292#Their disappointment, had a good laugh
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.293#At his expense, looking at each other and saying:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.294#"Oh man! You can't count how many good things
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.295#Odysseus has done for the Greeks, a real leader
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.296#In council and in battle, but this tops them all,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.297#The way he took that loudmouth out of commission.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.298#I don't think he'll ever be man enough again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.299#To rile the commanders with all his insults."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.300#That's what they were saying in the ranks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.301#Then Odysseus, destroyer of cities, stood up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.302#Holding the staff. Owl-eyed Athena transformed herself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.303#Into a herald and silenced the troops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.304#So that every last man in the Greek army
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.305#Would listen closely to what he had to say:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.306#"Son of Atreus, the Greeks are out to make you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.307#My lord, the most despised man on earth,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.308#And they have no intention of keeping the promise
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.309#They made to you when they set out from Argos---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.310#Not to return until you pulled down Ilion's walls.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.311#They are like little children or widow women,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.312#The way they whine to each other about going home.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.313#God knows it's hard enough to make a man give up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.314#And go back. A man gets discouraged when he spends
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.315#Even one month away from his wife on his ship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.316#Battling winter winds and the surging sea.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.317#For us, it's nine years we've been here now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.318#I can't blame our men for getting discouraged
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.319#As they wait beside their beaked ships. But still,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.320#It would be a disgrace to go home empty-handed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.321#After all this time. So bear up, friends,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.322#And let's stay long enough to find out whether
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.323#Calchas has prophesied truly or not.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.324#Everyone here---and I'm talking about all of us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.325#Not carried off by the wings of death---remembers it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.326#It seems like just yesterday when the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.327#Were mustered at Aulis with their cargo of sorrows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.328#For Priam and the Trojans. We were gathered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.329#Around a spring, offering sacrifice on sacred altars,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.330#Perfect hecatombs, beneath a beautiful plane tree
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.331#From under which the shining water flowed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.332#Then we saw it: a serpent, its back blood-red,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.333#Horrible---the Olympian himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.334#Must have brought it into the daylight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.335#It slithered out from the altar and up the plane tree.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.336#A sparrow's fledglings were nested
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.337#On the topmost branch, eight little birds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.338#Trembling under the leaves, or nine, counting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.339#The mother who hatched them, and the serpent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.340#Devoured them all as they cheeped pitifully.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.341#The mother fluttered around, mourning her nestlings,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.342#But he coiled and got her by the wing as she shrieked.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.343#After he had eaten the sparrow and her young,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.344#The very god who revealed him turned him to stone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.345#An unmistakable portent from Zeus, son of Cronus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.346#We stood there in awe of what had happened,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.347#This prodigy that crept into our sacrifice.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.348#Calchas was quick to pronounce its prophetic meaning:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.349#'Why are you silent, all you long-haired Greeks?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.350#This great portent is a message from Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.351#Whose glory shall never die---a portent late in coming,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.352#And late to be fulfilled. As this serpent devoured
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.353#The sparrow's children and the bird herself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.354#Eight hatchlings, nine, counting the mother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.355#So will we for as many years wage this war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.356#But in the tenth year we will capture the city.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.357#That was his prophecy, and it has all come true.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.358#So let's have every Greek who ever strapped on armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.359#Stay put, until we capture Priam's great city!"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.360#He finished. And the Greeks cheered, so loud
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.361#That the wooden hulls of the ships boomed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.362#With their approval of godlike Odysseus' speech.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.363#Then Nestor, the Gerenian rider, addressed them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.364#"Bah, you're carrying on like silly boys
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.365#Who have no business at all fighting a war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.366#What will become of our compacts and oaths?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.367#Into the fire with our resolutions and plans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.368#The pure wine we poured out, the handclasps
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.369#We trusted in! We are wrangling with words now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.370#And will not find thereby the ways or means
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.371#To stay the course for long.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.372#Son of Atreus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.373#Assert yourself, and resume your command
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.374#Of the Greek forces in all their grueling battles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.375#To hell with those one or two Achaeans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.376#With private plans---which will come to nothing---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.377#To return to Argos before we know for sure
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.378#Whether Zeus' promise was a lie or not.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.379#I say that the Aegis-Holder nodded his assent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.380#On that day when the Argives came in their ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.381#With their cargo of carnage and death for the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.382#Lightning on the right, favorable signs revealed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.383#No man here should be in a hurry to go home
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.384#Until he has spent the night with some Trojan's wife
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.385#As revenge for Helen's struggles and groans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.386#But if anyone is so almighty eager
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.387#To go back home, let him touch his black ship---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.388#So he can seal his fate before the whole army.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.389#But now, my lord, be prudent and take the advice,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.390#Hardly negligible, that I am about to give.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.391#Divide the men by tribes and clans, Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.392#So that clans and tribes can support each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.393#If you do this and the army complies,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.394#You will know which of your captains is a coward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.395#And which is brave, and so too with the soldiers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.396#For they will fight as units.You will know too
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.397#Whether it is heaven's will that you not take the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.398#Or that your men are cowards and witless in war."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.399#He spoke, and Lord Agamemnon answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.400#"Once again, Nestor, the best speech of all.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.401#Father Zeus, Athena, and Apollo, give me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.402#Ten such counsellors, and Priam's city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.403#Would lay her head in our lap, taken and ravaged.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.404#But Zeus, son of Cronus, has given me grief,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.405#Embroiling me in pointless quarrels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.406#Yes, Achilles and I argued over a girl,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.407#And it was I who grew angry first.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.408#If we two could agree, there would not be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.409#The slightest postponement of evil for Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.410#But go eat now, so we can get this battle together.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.411#Sharpen your spears and dress your shields,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.412#Lay out fodder for your horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.413#And inspect your chariots. We're going to war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.414#We're going to fight all day and hate every minute
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.415#Without any breaks until it's too dark to see.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.416#It's going to be chests sweating under shield straps,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.417#Hands sore from gripping spears, horses sweaty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.418#From pulling us around in our polished cars.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.419#And if I catch anyone even thinking about
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.420#Staying out of the fight back here with the ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.421#The dogs and birds will have him by nightfall."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.422#The cheer that followed this speech came on like a wave
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.423#That pounds a high cliff, a wave swollen by wind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.424#Against a jutting crag that is constantly worried
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.425#By wind-driven waves from every direction.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.426#The men stood up and scattered to their ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.427#Made fires in their huts and took their meal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.428#And each made sacrifice to his favorite god,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.429#Praying to escape from battle alive.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.430#The warlord Agamemnon sacrificed a fat bull,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.431#Five years old, to Cronus' almighty son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.432#And he summoned the elders, the best of the Achaeans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.433#Nestor first of all, and the warlord Idomeneus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.434#Then the two Ajaxes, and Tydeus' son, Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.435#And as the sixth, Odysseus, Zeus' match in wisdom.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.436#Menelaus, the rallier, came on his own,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.437#Knowing what his brother was up against.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.438#They stood 'round the ox and took up the barley grains,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.439#And the warlord Agamemnon led them in prayer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.440#"Zeus, most glorious, most great,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.441#Dark Cloud that art in heaven,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.442#May the sun not set nor darkness gather
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.443#Until I have cast Priam's roof beam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.444#Smoldering to the ground, and burned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.445#His doorways with consuming fire.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.446#And may I tear Hector's heart out with bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.447#And may many of his comrades
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.448#Fall headlong around him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.449#Face down in the dust."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.450#But Zeus would not grant his prayer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.451#Not yet. He accepted Agamemnon's sacrifice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.452#But blew upon his woes and increased them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.453#After the prayers and the strewing of barley
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.454#They cut the ox's throat and flayed it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.455#Jointed the thighbones and wrapped them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.456#In a layer of fat with cuts of meat on top.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.457#These they roasted over split kindling wood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.458#When the thigh pieces were charred and they had
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.459#Tasted the tripe, they cut the rest into strips,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.460#Skewered it on spits, and roasted it carefully.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.461#When they were done and the feast was ready,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.462#Feast they did, and no one lacked an equal share.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.463#When they had eaten and drunk to their heart's content,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.464#Nestor the Gerenian horseman spoke:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.465#"Son of Atreus, my lord Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.466#Let us remain gathered here no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.467#Nor delay the work that the gods have given us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.468#Have the heralds of the bronze-armored Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.469#Make proclamation all through the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.470#And muster the army. We will patrol camp
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.471#In a group, to waken Ares more quickly."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.472#He spoke, and the warlord Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.473#Ordered the heralds to muster the troops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.474#In battle formation. They gave their skirling cry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.475#And all the commanders around Atreus' son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.476#Hurried to have their men fall in.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.477#And in their midst Athena, eyes like slate,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.478#Carried the aegis, priceless and out of all time,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.479#Pure gold tassels flying in the wind, each
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.480#Woven strand worth a hundred oxen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.481#And the goddess herself, glowing like moonlight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.482#Rushed over the sand, sweeping them on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.483#And stiffening their hearts, so that for each of them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.484#To die in battle was sweeter than going home.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.485#A fire raging through endless forests
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.486#In a mountain range can be seen far away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.487#As a distant glow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.488#Likewise the glare
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.489#From the advancing army's unimaginable bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.490#An eerie light that reached the stratosphere.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.491#Migratory birds---cranes, geese, or long-necked swans---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.492#Are gathering in a meadow in Asia
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.493#Where the river Caystrius branches out in streams.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.494#For a while they fly in random patterns
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.495#For the pure joy of using their wings,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.496#But then with a single cry they start to land,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.497#One line of birds settling in front of another
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.498#Until the whole meadow is a carpet of sound.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.499#Likewise from the ships and huts, tribe after tribe
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.500#Poured out onto the Scamander's floodplain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.501#And the ground groaned and reverberated
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.502#Under their feet and the hooves of their horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.503#And they stood in the flowering meadow there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.504#Countless as leaves, or as flowers in their season.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.505#Innumerable throngs of buzzing flies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.506#Will swarm all over a herdsman's yard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.507#In springtime, when milk wets the pails---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.508#Likewise the throngs of long-haired Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.509#Who stood on the plain facing the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.510#Intent on hammering them to pieces.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.511#And as goatherds easily separate out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.512#Wide flocks of goats mingled in pasture,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.513#So the commanders drew up their troops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.514#To enter battle, and Lord Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.515#Moved among them like Zeus himself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.516#The look in his eyes, the carriage of his head,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.517#With a torso like Ares', or like Poseidon's.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.518#Picture a bull that stands out from the herd
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.519#Head and horns above the milling cattle---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.520#Zeus on that day made the son of Atreus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.521#A man who stood out from the crowd of heroes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.522#Tell me now, Muses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.523#Who live on Olympus---for you are
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.524#Goddesses, and are present,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.525#And know all things, while we
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.526#Hear only reports and know nothing---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.527#Who were the Greek captains and lords?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.528#The rank and file I could never name,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.529#Not even if I had ten tongues, ten mouths,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.530#A voice that never broke, and a bronze heart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.531#Unless the Olympian Muses, daughters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.532#Of Zeus, called to my mind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.533#All those who came under Ilion's walls.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.534#Now I will call the roll of the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.535#The Boeotians were led by PENELEUS and LEITUS,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.536#With Arcesilaus, Protoenor, and Clonius.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.537#Their towns were Hyria,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.538#rocky Aulis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.539#and Schoenus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.540#Scolus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.541#ridged Eteoneus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.542#Thespeia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.543#Graea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.544#Broad Mycalessus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.545#Harma,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.546#Eilesion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.547#Erythrae,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.548#Eleon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.549#Hyle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.550#Peteon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.551#Ocalea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.552#Medeon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.553#Copae,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.554#Eutresus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.555#Dovecoted Thisbe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.556#Coroneia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.557#grassy Haliartus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.558#Plataea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.559#Glisas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.560#Lower Thebes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.561#Onchestus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.562#Posideon, with its grove,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.563#and Arne, its vineyards,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.564#Mideia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.565#sacred Nisa,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.566#and on the coast, Anthedon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.567#Fifty ships, and aboard each ship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.568#One hundred and twenty young men of Boeotia.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.569#The Minyans from Aspledon and Orchomenos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.570#Were led by ASCALAPHUS and IALMENUS,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.571#Sons of Ares, born to Astyoche, then a virgin,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.572#In the palace of Actor, son of Azeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.573#When she had the god in her upstairs room.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.574#Their thirty vessels were drawn up in rows.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.575#The Phocians were led by SCHEDIUS and EPISTROPHUS,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.576#Sons of Iphitos, grandsons of Naubolus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.577#Their towns were Cyparissus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.578#and rocky Pytho,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.579#Sacred Crisa,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.580#Daulis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.581#Panopeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.582#Anemoria,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.583#Hyampolis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.584#on the river Cephisus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.585#And Lilaea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.586#by the springs of Cephisus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.587#Forty black ships formed their contingent,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.588#And their leaders marshalled their ranks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.589#Left of the Boeotians as they readied for war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.590#The Locrians were led by swift AJAX,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.591#Son of Oïleus, not as great as Telamonian Ajax,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.592#Not nearly, a small man who wore a linen corselet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.593#But with a spear the best soldier in Greece.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.594#They lived in Cynus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.595#and Ophus and Calliarus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.596#In Bessa and Scarphe
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.597#and lovely Augeiae,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.598#In Tarphe and Thronion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.599#by the streams of Boagrius.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.600#Ajax led forty black ships, manned by Locrians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.601#Who dwell over against sacred Euboea.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.602#The Abantes, who hold Euboea and Chalcis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.603#Eretria and the vineyards of Histiaea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.604#Seaside Cerinthus and the steep stronghold of Dios,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.605#And those in Carystus and also in Styra,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.606#Were led by ELEPHENOR, a scion of Ares
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.607#And son of Chalcodon. He was chief of the Abantes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.608#A spirited people, swift and hot-tempered,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.609#Their hair long in the back, spearmen eager
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.610#With outstretched spears to rend enemy corselets.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.611#Forty black ships followed Elephenor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.612#Those who held Athens---the well-founded citadel
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.613#And the land of Erechtheus, whom Athena fostered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.614#After the grain field bore him, and made him live
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.615#In her own rich precinct, where Athenian youths
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.616#Still propitiate him yearly with rams and bulls---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.617#These were led by MENESTHEUS, Peteos' son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.618#This man had no equal anywhere on earth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.619#At marshalling chariots and infantry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.620#Rivalled only by Nestor, who was his elder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.621#Fifty black ships followed Menestheus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.622#AJAX led from Salamis twelve ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.623#And stationed them by the Athenian contingent.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.624#Those who held Argos and walled Tiryns
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.625#And Hermione and Asine, on the deep gulf,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.626#Troezen and Eionae and vine-clad Epidaurus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.627#And the Achaean youths in Aegina and Mases---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.628#All these were led by DIOMEDES and STHENELUS,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.629#Son of Capaneus, with EURYALUS as a third.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.630#But the commander in chief was Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.631#And eighty black ships followed him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.632#Those who held Mycenae's citadel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.633#And wealthy Corinth,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.634#and those in Cleonae
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.635#And in Orneiae
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.636#and lovely Araethyrea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.637#And in Sicyon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.638#where Adrastus first was king,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.639#And those in Hyperesia
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.640#and steep Gonoessa,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.641#And in Pellene,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.642#and around Aegium,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.643#Throughout all Aegialus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.644#and around wide Helice---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.645#All these were commanded,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.646#a hundred ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.647#By Lord AGAMEMNON,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.648#son of Atreus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.649#His contingent was far the largest and best,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.650#And among them he put on his gleaming bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.651#Glorying, preeminent among all,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.652#And the army he led was largest of all.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.653#Those who lived
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.654#in Lacedaemon's gulches,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.655#In Pharis and Sparta,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.656#in dove-haunted Messe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.657#And those in Bryseiae
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.658#and lovely Augeiae,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.659#And Amyclae and Helus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.660#a citadel by the sea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.661#And those in Laas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.662#and the environs of Oetylus---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.663#These were led
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.664#by Agamemnon's brother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.665#MENELAUS,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.666#whose voice carried in battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.667#In sixty ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.668#marshalled separately.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.669#And he moved among them with confidence,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.670#Urging them into war. He wanted most of all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.671#Requital for Helen's struggles and groans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.672#Those who lived in Pylos and lovely Arene,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.673#In Thyron, ford of Alpheius, and Aipy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.674#In Cyparisseis and Amphigeneia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.675#In Pteleos and Helus and Dorium, where
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.676#The Muses met Thamyris and stopped his song
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.677#As he journeyed from Eurytus' house in Oechalia
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.678#Boasting he would win even if the Muses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.679#Daughters of Zeus, were to sing against him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.680#And in anger they maimed him, took away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.681#His melody and silenced his lyre---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.682#All these Gerenian NESTOR led, and had
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.683#Ninety hollow ships drawn up in rows.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.684#Those who held Arcadia in Cyllene's shadow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.685#Beside Aepytus' tomb, where men fight hand to hand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.686#And those in Pheneos and Orchomenos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.687#In Rhipe and Stratia and windy Enispe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.688#Those who held Tegea and Mantinea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.689#Those who held Stymphalus and lived in Parrhasia---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.690#All these AGAPENOR led, Ancaeus' son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.691#Fifty ships, and each ship had on board
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.692#Many Arcadians who knew how to fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.693#Agamemnon himself had given them ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.694#To cross over the sea's grey wine,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.695#For the Arcadians knew nothing of sailing the sea.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.696#Those from Buprasium
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.697#and shining Elis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.698#And the land that Hyrmine
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.699#and Myrsinus enclose
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.700#On the coast,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.701#and between Olen rock and Alesium---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.702#All those had four leaders, each with ten ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.703#With many Epeians aboard. The captains were
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.704#AMPHIMACHUS and THALPIUS, both of Actor's line,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.705#One Cteatus' son, the other of Eurytus;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.706#Third was mighty DIORES, son of Amarynceus;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.707#Fourth was godlike POLYXEINUS, Augeias' son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.708#Those from Dulichium
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.709#and the holy islands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.710#The Echinaes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.711#that lie in the sea offshore from Elis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.712#Had MEGES as leader, peer of Ares,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.713#Whom Phyleus dear to Zeus had begotten,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.714#The horseman Phyleus who once upon a time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.715#Had moved to Dulichium angry with his father.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.716#Forty black ships followed Meges to Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.717#ODYSSEUS led the proud Cephallenians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.718#Who held Ithaca
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.719#and forested Neriton,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.720#And those in Crocyleia
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.721#and rugged Aigilips,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.722#In Zacynthus and Samos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.723#and all those who lived
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.724#Along the mainland coast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.725#opposite these islands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.726#Odysseus led them, peer of Zeus in counsel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.727#And twelve vermillion prows followed him to Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.728#The Aetolians were led by Adraemon's son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.729#THOAS. They lived in Pleuron, Olenos, Pylene,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.730#In seaside Chalcis and rocky Calydon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.731#For great-hearted Oeneus' sons were gone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.732#And he himself was dead, and blond Meleager,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.733#Who once was told to rule all Aetolia.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.734#Forty black ships followed Thoas to Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.735#The Cretans were led by IDOMENEUS.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.736#Their cities were Cnossus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.737#and walled Gortys,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.738#Lyctus and Miletus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.739#and lime-white Lycastus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.740#Phaestus and Rhytium,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.741#well-peopled cities,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.742#And all who dwelled in Crete's hundred towns.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.743#Idomeneus, famed for his spear, was captain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.744#As was MERIONES, who could kill like Ares.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.745#Eighty black ships sailed with them to Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.746#Heracles' son TLEPOLEMUS, a good man, and big,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.747#Led nine ships from Rhodes. The Rhodians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.748#Were divided into three contingents:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.749#Lindos, Ialysus, and lime-white Cameirus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.750#They were led by the warrior Tlepolemus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.751#Born to great Heracles by Astyocheia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.752#Whom he had taken out of Ephyre
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.753#And away from the river Selleis, after
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.754#Pillaging the cities of many a hero.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.755#But when Tlepolemus came of age in the palace,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.756#He killed his father's dear uncle, Licymnius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.757#A scion of Ares, then getting on in years.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.758#He quickly built a fleet, gathered a following,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.759#And took flight on the sea, threatened by the other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.760#Sons and grandsons of mighty Heracles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.761#He came to Rhodes in his painful wanderings,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.762#And his people settled in three regions by tribes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.763#They were loved by Zeus, who rules gods and men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.764#And the son of Cronus showered them with wealth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.765#NIREUS led three trim ships from Syme.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.766#Nireus was the son of Aglaia and Charops,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.767#King of Syme, and was the handsomest man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.768#Of all the Danaans who came to Troy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.769#After the flawless son of Peleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.770#But he was weak, and few men followed him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.771#Those who held
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.772#Nisyrus and Carpathus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.773#Casus and Cos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.774#Eurypylus' city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.775#And the Calydnian islands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.776#Were led by PHEIDIPPUS and ANTIPHUS,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.777#The two sons of Thessalus, Heracles' son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.778#Their thirty vessels were drawn up in rows.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.779#Those who inhabited
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.780#Pelasgian Argos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.781#And lived in Alos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.782#Alope, and Trachis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.783#And held Phthia and Hellas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.784#land of fair women,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.785#And were known as MYRMIDONS,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.786#Hellenes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.787#Achaeans---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.788#ACHILLES commanded their fifty ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.789#But none of them now thought of gruesome war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.790#Since there was no one to lead them into the ranks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.791#The great sprinter lay idle in their beachhead camp,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.792#Nursing his wrath because of the girl,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.793#Fair-haired Briseis, whom he had taken,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.794#After great effort, out of Lyrnessus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.795#When he sacked that town and levelled Thebes' walls
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.796#And cut down Mynes and Epistrophus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.797#King Evenos' sons, great warriors both.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.798#Heartsick for her, and angry, Achilles lay idle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.799#But he would rise again soon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.800#Those in Phylace
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.801#and flowering Pyrasus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.802#Demeter's sanctuary,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.803#and those in Iton,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.804#Mother of flocks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.805#in Antron, by the sea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.806#And in the grasslands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.807#of Pteleos---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.808#All these were led by Protesilaus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.809#While he still lived. The black earth now held him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.810#His wife, cheeks torn, was left in Phylace,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.811#His house half-built. A Dardanian killed him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.812#As he leapt from his ship, the first Greek ashore.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.813#His men were not leaderless---though they missed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.814#Their leader---for PODARCES marshalled them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.815#Son of Ipichlus Phylacides, rich in flocks, and
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.816#Protesilaus' brother. But Protesilaus was older
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.817#And a better man, a hero, and though his men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.818#Did not lack a leader, they yearned for him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.819#Forty black ships followed Protesilaus to Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.820#Those in Pherae beside Lake Boebeis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.821#And in Boebe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.822#Glaphyrae,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.823#and well-built Iolkos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.824#Were in eleven ships led by EUMELUS,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.825#Admetus' son by a glorious woman,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.826#Alcestis, loveliest of Pelias' daughters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.827#Those in Methone and Thaumacia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.828#In Meliboea and rugged Olizon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.829#Came in seven ships led by PHILOCTETES,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.830#The great archer, and aboard each ship
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.831#Were fifty oarsmen skilled with the bow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.832#But Philoctetes now lay in pain on an island,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.833#Sacred Lemnos, where the Achaeans stranded him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.834#Afflicted with a wound from a deadly snake.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.835#He lay there in anguish, but the Greeks at Troy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.836#Would soon remember Lord Philoctetes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.837#Nor were these men leaderless. MEDON
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.838#Marshalled them, Oïleus' bastard son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.839#Whom Rhene bore to the pillager Oïleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.840#Those in Tricca and craggy Ithome,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.841#And those in Oechalia, Eurytus' city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.842#Were led by the two sons of Asclepius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.843#PODALEIRIUS and MACHAON, good healers both,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.844#With thirty vessels drawn up in rows.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.845#Those who held Ormenios and the spring Hypereia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.846#And Asterion and Titanos' white peaks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.847#Were led by EURYPYLUS, Euaemon's great son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.848#Forty black ships sailed with him to Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.849#Those who held Argissa,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.850#and lived in Gyrtone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.851#In Orthe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.852#Elone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.853#and white-bricked Oloöson,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.854#Were led by POLYPOETES, staunch in battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.855#Son of Peirithous, whom deathless Zeus begot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.856#Gloried Hippodameia conceived Polypoetes that day
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.857#When Peirithous punished the shaggy centaurs,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.858#Drove them from Pelion and to the Aethices.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.859#Leonteus shared the command, Caeneus' grandson.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.860#Forty black ships sailed with them to Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.861#GOUNEUS led twenty-two ships from Cyphus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.862#And with him came the Enines and Paraebi,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.863#Who had settled around wintry Dodona
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.864#And in the fields around the stream Titaressus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.865#A tributary of the Peneius. Its lovely water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.866#Does not mingle with Peneius' silver eddies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.867#But glides on its surface like olive oil,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.868#A branch of Styx, the dread water of oaths.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.869#The Magnetes, who lived around Peneius
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.870#And forested Pelion, were led by swift PROTHOUS,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.871#Son of Tenthredon, in forty black ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.872#These were the leaders of the Danaans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.873#But tell me now, Muse, who were the best
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.874#Of men and of horses in the Atreides' army?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.875#The best horses were the mares of Eumelus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.876#Swift as birds, of the same age, with matching coats,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.877#And their backs were as even as a levelling line.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.878#Apollo Silverbow had bred them in Pereia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.879#A team of mares who bore Panic in battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.880#The best warrior was Telamonian Ajax---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.881#While Achilles was in his rage. For Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.882#Was second to no one, as were the horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.883#That bore Peleus' flawless son. But now he lay idle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.884#Among his beaked, seagoing hulls, furious
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.885#With Agamemnon, the shepherd of the people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.886#The son of Atreus. Achilles' men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.887#Amused themselves on the shore, throwing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.888#The discus and javelin and shooting their bows.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.889#The horses stood beside their chariots
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.890#Champing lotus and marsh parsley.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.891#The chariots lay covered in their owners' huts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.892#The men missed their leader. They tramped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.893#Through the camp and had no part in fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.894#The army marched, and it was as though the land
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.895#Were swept with fire. Earth groaned beneath them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.896#As beneath Zeus when in his wrath he thunders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.897#And lashes the country of the Arimi with lightning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.898#Where men say Typhoeus lies in the ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.899#So the earth groaned under their feet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.900#As they pressed on quickly over the plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.901#Zeus notified the Trojans of all this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.902#By sending Iris streaking down to Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.903#She found the citizens assembled in one body,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.904#Young and old alike, near Priam's gate, talking.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.905#Iris positioned herself nearby
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.906#And made her voice sound like Polites'---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.907#A son of Priam who, trusting his speed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.908#Often sat as lookout on top of the barrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.909#Of old Aesytes, watching for any movement
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.910#Of Greek troops from their ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.911#Using his voice, the goddess said to Priam:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.912#"Sir, you are as fond of endless speeches now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.913#As you were in peacetime. But this is war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.914#I have been in a battle or two, but never
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.915#Have I seen an army like this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.916#Covering the plain like leaves, or like sand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.917#As it advances to attack the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.918#Hector, you're in charge of this operation.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.919#But because there are so many allies here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.920#With different languages from points abroad,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.921#Each captain should give the word to his own men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.922#And lead them out marshalled by cities."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.923#Hector knew this was a goddess's speech
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.924#And dismissed the assembly. They rushed to arms.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.925#All the gates were opened, and the troops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.926#Poured through them, on foot and in war cars.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.927#In front of the city there is a steep hill
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.928#Out in the plain, level terrain all around it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.929#Men call this hill Batieia. Immortals call it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.930#The barrow of Myrine the Dancer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.931#It was here that the Trojans and their allies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.932#Drew up their troops in companies.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.933#The Trojans were led by great HECTOR,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.934#Son of Priam, in his shining helmet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.935#His contingent was far the largest and the best,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.936#Arrayed for battle, resolute with their spears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.937#The Dardanian troops were led by AENEAS,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.938#Whom bright Aphrodite bore to Anchises,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.939#A goddess lying with a mortal man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.940#In the foothills of Ida. Sharing the command
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.941#Were Antenor's two sons, Archelochus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.942#And Acamas, skilled in all forms of combat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.943#The Troes, who lived in wealthy Zeleia
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.944#At Ida's foot, and drank the Aesepus' dark water,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.945#Were led by the glorious son of Lycaon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.946#PANDARUS, whose bow was a gift from Apollo.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.947#Those who held Adrasteia and the deme Apaesus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.948#And Pityeia and the steep Mount Tereia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.949#Were led by ADRASTUS and AMPHIUS,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.950#With linen corselets, sons of Merops and Percote.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.951#This man knew divination, and forbade his sons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.952#To go to war, but they would not listen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.953#For Death's black birds were calling them on.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.954#Those who lived around Percote and Practios,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.955#Who held Sestus and Abydus and bright Arisbe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.956#Were led by ASIUS Hyrtacides, a born leader,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.957#Asius, whom his great chestnut horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.958#Had drawn from Arisbe and the river Selleis.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.959#The Pelasgian tribes, ferocious spearmen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.960#From fertile Larisa, were led by HIPPOTHOUS
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.961#With his brother PYLAEUS. They were sons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.962#Of Pelasgian Lethus, grandsons of Teutamus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.963#ACAMAS and PEIROUS led all the Thracians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.964#Beyond the strong current of the Hellespont.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.965#EUPHEMUS captained the Ciconian spearmen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.966#Son of Troezenus and grandson of Ceas.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.967#PYRAECHMES led the distant Paeonians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.968#With curved bows, from Amydon and the river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.969#Axius, whose water flows fairest over the earth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.970#PYLAEMENES, shaggy heart, led the Paphlagonians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.971#From the land of the Eneti, where the mules run wild.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.972#Their cities were Cytoros and Sesamos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.973#And they lived around the river Parthenios
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.974#In Cromna, Aegialos, and high Erythini.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.975#ODIUS and EPISTROPHUS led the Halizones
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.976#From distant Alybe, ancient source of silver.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.977#The Mysians were led by CHROMIS
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.978#And ENNOMUS, who foretold the future
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.979#From the flight of birds, but could not ward off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.980#The black birds of death. They would be slain in the river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.981#By the terrible sword of swift Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.982#Aeacus' grandson, when he killed many there.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.983#PHORCYS and ASCANIUS led the Phrygians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.984#From distant Ascania, battle-hungry troops.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.985#The Maeonians were led by MESTHLES and ANTIPHUS,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.986#Talaemones' sons, whose mother was the nymph
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.987#Of Lake Gygaea, under Mount Tmolus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.988#NASTES led the Carians, who spoke a foreign tongue.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.989#Their strongholds were Miletus, and Mount Phthires,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.990#The streams of Maeander, and Mycale's steep crests.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.991#AMPHIMACHUS shared the command with Nastes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.992#Who came to the war wearing gold like a girl,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.993#The fool, but it could not save him from death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.994#Achilles killed him in his rush through the river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.995#Without a second thought, and bore off the gold.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.996#SARPEDON and GLAUCUS captained the Lycians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:2.997#Who came from the faraway, swirling Xanthus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.1#Two armies,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.2#The troops in divisions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.3#Under their commanders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.4#The Trojans advancing across the plain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.5#Like cranes beating their metallic wings
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.6#In the stormy sky at winter's onset,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.7#Unspeakable rain at their backs, their necks stretched
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.8#Toward Oceanic streams and down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.9#To strafe the brown Pygmy race,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.10#Bringing strife and bloodshed from the sky at dawn,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.11#While the Greeks moved forward in silence,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.12#Their breath curling in long angry plumes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.13#That acknowledged their pledges to die for each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.14#Banks of mist settle on mountain peaks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.15#And seep into the valleys. Shepherds dislike it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.16#But for a thief it is better than night,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.17#And a man can see only as far as he can throw a stone.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.18#No more could the soldiers see through the cloud of dust
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.19#The armies tramped up as they moved through the plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.20#And when they had almost closed---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.21#Was it a god?---no, not a god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.22#But Paris who stepped out from the Trojan ranks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.23#Leopard skin on his shoulders, curved bow, sword,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.24#And shaking two bronze-tipped spears at the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.25#He invited their best to fight him to the death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.26#When Menelaus, who was Ares' darling, saw him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.27#Strutting out from the ranks, he felt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.28#As a lion must feel when he finds the carcass
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.29#Of a stag or wild goat, and, half-starving,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.30#Consumes it greedily even though hounds and hunters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.31#Are swarming down on him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.32#It was Paris all right,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.33#Who could have passed for a god,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.34#And Menelaus grinned as he hefted his gear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.35#And stepped down from his chariot. He would
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.36#Have his revenge at last. Paris' blood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.37#Turned milky when he saw him coming on,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.38#And he faded back into the Trojan troops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.39#With cheeks as pale as if he had seen---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.40#Had almost stepped on---a poisonous snake
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.41#In a mountain pass. He could barely stand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.42#As disdainful Trojans made room for him in the ranks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.43#And Hector, seeing his brother tremble at Atreus' son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.44#Started in on him with these abusive epithets:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.45#"Paris, you desperate, womanizing pretty boy!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.46#I wish you had never been born, or had died unmarried.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.47#Better that than this disgrace before the troops.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.48#Can't you just hear it, the long-haired Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.49#Chuckling and saying that our champion wins
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.50#For good looks but comes up short on offense and defense?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.51#Is this how you were when you got up a crew
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.52#And sailed overseas, hobnobbed with the warrior caste
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.53#In a foreign country and sailed off with
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.54#A beautiful woman with marriage ties to half of them?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.55#You're nothing but trouble for your father and your city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.56#A joke to your enemies and an embarrassment to yourself.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.57#No don't stand up to Menelaus: you might find out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.58#What kind of a man it is whose wife you're sleeping with.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.59#You think your lyre will help you, or Aphrodite's gifts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.60#Your hair, your pretty face, when you sprawl in the dust?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.61#It's the Trojans who are cowards, or you'd have long since
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.62#Been dressed out in stones for all the harm you've done."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.63#And Paris, handsome as a god, answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.64#"That's only just, Hector. You've got a mind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.65#Like an axe, you know, always sharp,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.66#Making the skilled cut through a ship's beam,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.67#Multiplying force---nothing ever turns your edge.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.68#But don't throw golden Aphrodite's gifts in my face.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.69#We don't get to choose what the gods give us, you know,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.70#And we can't just toss their gifts aside.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.71#So all right, if you want me to fight, fine.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.72#Have the Trojans and the Greeks sit down,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.73#And Menelaus and I will square off in the middle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.74#To fight for Helen and all her possessions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.75#Winner take all.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.76#And everyone else will swear oaths of friendship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.77#You all to live here in the fertile Troad,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.78#And they to go back to bluegrass Argos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.79#And Achaea with its beautiful women."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.80#Hector liked what he heard.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.81#He went out in front along the Trojan ranks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.82#Holding a spear broadside and made them all sit down.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.83#Greek archers and slingers were taking aim at him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.84#And already starting to shoot arrows and stones
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.85#When Agamemnon boomed out a command
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.86#For them to hold their fire. Hector was signalling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.87#That he had something to say, and his helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.88#Caught the morning sun as he addressed both armies:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.89#"Listen to me, Trojans, and you warriors from Greece.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.90#Paris, on account of whom this war began, says this:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.91#He wants all the Trojan and Greek combatants
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.92#To lay their weapons down on the ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.93#He and Menelaus will square off in the middle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.94#And fight for Helen and all her possessions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.95#Winner take all.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.96#And everyone else swears oaths of friendship."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.97#Utter silence,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.98#Until Menelaus, who was good at the war shout, said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.99#"Now listen to me, since my pain is paramount
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.100#In all this. It may be that the Greeks and Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.101#Can at last call it quits. We've had enough suffering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.102#From this quarrel of mine that Paris began.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.103#Whichever of us is due to die, let him die.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.104#Then the rest of you can be done with each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.105#Bring a pair of lambs, a white one and a black,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.106#For Earth and Sun. Our side will bring another for Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.107#And have Priam come, so he can swear oaths himself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.108#In person, since his sons are arrogant perjurers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.109#Who would just as soon trample on Zeus' solemn word.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.110#Younger men always have their heads in the clouds.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.111#An old man looks ahead and behind, and the result
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.112#Is far better for both parties involved."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.113#You could see their mood brighten,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.114#Greeks and Trojans both, with the hope
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.115#That this wretched war would soon be over.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.116#They pulled their chariots up in rows,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.117#Dismounted, and piled up their weapons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.118#There was not much space between the two armies.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.119#Hector dispatched two heralds to the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.120#To fetch the lambs and summon Priam.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.121#Agamemnon sent Talthybius back to the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.122#With orders to bring back a lamb.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.123#While these human heralds were off on their missions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.124#Iris, the gods' herald (who is also the rainbow),
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.125#Came to white-armed Helen disguised as Laodice,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.126#Her sister-in-law and Priam's most beautiful daughter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.127#She found Helen in the main hall, weaving a folding mantle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.128#On a great loom and designing into the blood-red fabric
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.129#The trials that the Trojans and Greeks had suffered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.130#For her beauty under Ares' murderous hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.131#Iris stood near Helen and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.132#"Come and see, dear lady, the amazing thing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.133#The Greek and Trojan warriors have done.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.134#They've fought all these years out on the plain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.135#Lusting for each other's blood, but now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.136#They've sat down in silence---halted the war---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.137#They're leaning back on their shields
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.138#And their long spears are stuck in the sand.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.139#But Paris and Menelaus are going to fight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.140#A duel with lances, and the winner
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.141#Will lay claim to you as his beloved wife."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.142#The goddess's words turned Helen's mind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.143#Into a sweet mist of desire
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.144#For her former husband, her parents, and her city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.145#She dressed herself in fine silvery linens
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.146#And came out of her bedroom crying softly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.147#Two maids trailed behind, Aethrê,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.148#Pittheus' daughter, and cow-eyed Clyménê.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.149#They came to the Western Gate,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.150#Where a knot of old men sat---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.151#Priam, Panthous, Thymoetes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.152#Lampus, Clytius, Hicetaon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.153#(Who was in Ares' bloodline)
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.154#Ucalegon and Antenor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.155#Who lived and breathed wisdom---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.156#These veterans sat on the wall by the Western Gate,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.157#Too old to fight now, but excellent counsellors.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.158#Think of cicadas perched on a branch,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.159#Their delicate voices shrill in the woods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.160#Such were the voices of these Trojan elders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.161#Sitting on the tower by the Western Gate.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.162#When they saw Helen coming
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.163#Their rasping whispers flew along the wall:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.164#"Who could blame either the Trojans or Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.165#For suffering so long for a woman like this."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.166#"Her eyes are not human."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.167#"Whatever she is, let her go back with the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.168#And spare us and our children a generation of pain."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.169#But Priam called out to her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.170#"Come here, dear child, sit next to me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.171#So you can see your former husband
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.172#And dear kinsmen. You are not to blame
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.173#For this war with the Greeks. The gods are.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.174#Now tell me, who is that enormous man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.175#Towering over the Greek troops, handsome,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.176#Well-built? I've never laid eyes on such
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.177#A fine figure of a man. He looks like a king."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.178#And Helen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.179#The sky's brightness reflected in her mortal face:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.180#"Reverend you are to me dear father-in-law,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.181#A man to hold in awe. I'm so ashamed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.182#Death should have been a sweeter evil to me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.183#Than following your son here, leaving my home,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.184#My marriage, my friends, my precious daughter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.185#That lovely time in my life. None of it was to be,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.186#And lamenting it has been my slow death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.187#But you asked me something, and I'll answer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.188#That man is Agamemnon, son of Atreus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.189#A great king and a strong warrior both.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.190#He was also my brother-in-law---shameless bitch
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.191#That I am---if that life was ever real."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.192#The old man was lost in reverie and wonder:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.193#"The son of Atreus. Born to power and wealth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.194#Blessed by the gods. Now I see
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.195#How many Greek lads you command.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.196#I thought I saw it all when I went
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.197#To Phrygia once and saw thousands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.198#Of soldiers and gleaming horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.199#Under the command of Otreus and Mygdon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.200#Massed by the banks of the Sangarios,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.201#An army in which I myself served
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.202#On that fateful day when the Amazons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.203#Swept down to fight against men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.204#They were nothing compared to these wild-eyed Greeks."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.205#Then he saw Odysseus and asked:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.206#"Now tell me about this one, dear child,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.207#Shorter than Agamemnon by a head
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.208#But broader in the shoulders and chest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.209#His armor is lying on the ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.210#And he's roaming the ranks like a ram,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.211#That's it, just like a thick-fleeced ram
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.212#Striding through a flock of silvery sheep."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.213#And Helen, Zeus' child:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.214#"That is Laertes' son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.215#The master strategist Odysseus, born and bred
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.216#In the rocky hills of Ithaca. He knows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.217#Every trick there is, and his mind runs deep."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.218#Antenor turned to her and observed astutely:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.219#"Your words are not off the mark there, madam.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.220#Odysseus came here once before, on an embassy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.221#For your sake along with Menelaus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.222#I entertained them courteously in the great hall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.223#And learned each man's character and depth of mind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.224#Standing in a crowd of Trojans, Menelaus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.225#With his wide shoulders, was more prominent,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.226#But when both were seated Odysseus was lordlier.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.227#When it came time for each to speak in public
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.228#And weave a spell of wisdom with their words,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.229#Menelaus spoke fluently enough, to the point
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.230#And very clearly, but briefly, since he is not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.231#A man of many words. Being older, he spoke first.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.232#Then Odysseus, the master strategist, rose quickly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.233#But just stood there, his eyes fixed on the ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.234#He did not move his staff forward or backward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.235#But held it steady. You would have thought him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.236#A dull, surly lout without any wit. But when he
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.237#Opened his mouth and projected his voice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.238#The words fell down like snowflakes in a blizzard.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.239#No mortal could have vied with Odysseus then,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.240#And we no longer held his looks against him."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.241#The third hero old Priam saw was Ajax.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.242#"And who is that giant of a Greek over there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.243#Head and shoulders above the other Achaeans?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.244#And Helen, shining in her long trailing robes:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.245#"That is big Ajax, the army's mountain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.246#Standing beyond him is Idomeneus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.247#Like a god, with his Cretan commanders.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.248#He used to come often from Crete
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.249#And Menelaus would entertain him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.250#In our house. And now I can make out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.251#All the other Greeks, those I know
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.252#And whose names I could tell you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.253#But there are two commanders I do not see,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.254#Castor the horsebreaker and the boxer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.255#Polydeuces, my brothers, born of one mother.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.256#Either they didn't come here from lovely Lacedaemon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.257#Or else they did come in their seagoing ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.258#But avoid the company of the fighting men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.259#In horror of the shame and disgrace that are mine."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.260#But they had long been held by the life-giving earth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.261#There in Lacedaemon, their ancestral land.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.262#And now the heralds came up to the town
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.263#With the sacrificial victims, the two rams,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.264#And as fruit of the fields, hearty wine
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.265#In a goatskin bag. The herald Idaeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.266#Held a gleaming bowl and a golden chalice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.267#And roused the old man with this speech:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.268#"Rise, son of Laomedon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.269#The best men of Troy and Achaea summon you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.270#Down to the plain to swear solemn oaths.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.271#Paris and Menelaus will fight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.272#A duel for the woman, and she will
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.273#Follow the winner with all her possessions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.274#Everyone else will swear oaths of friendship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.275#We to live here in the fertile Troad,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.276#And they to go back to bluegrass Argos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.277#And Achaea with its beautiful women."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.278#The old man stiffened.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.279#He ordered his companions to yoke his horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.280#Then mounted himself and took the reins.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.281#Antenor rode with him in the beautiful chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.282#And they drove out through the Western Gate
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.283#And onto the plain. They pulled up in the space
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.284#Between the two armies and stepped down to the earth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.285#Agamemnon rose,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.286#And Odysseus, deep in thought.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.287#Heralds brought the animals for the oaths
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.288#And mixed wine in the great bowl.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.289#They poured water over the kings' hands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.290#Then Agamemnon drew the knife
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.291#That hung by his sword scabbard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.292#And cut hairs from the rams' heads.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.293#The heralds gave these to the leaders on both sides,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.294#And Agamemnon lifted his palms to the sky:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.295#"Zeus, Father, Lord of Ida,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.296#Greatest and most glorious;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.297#Helios who sees all and hears all;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.298#Rivers and Earth, and Powers below
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.299#Who punish perjurers after death,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.300#Witness and protect these sacred Oaths:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.301#If Paris Alexander kills Menelaus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.302#Helen and all her goods are his,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.303#And we will sail away in our ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.304#But if Menelaus kills Paris,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.305#The Trojans will surrender Helen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.306#With all her goods and pay the Argives
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.307#A fit penalty for generations to come.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.308#If Priam and Priam's sons refuse,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.309#Upon Paris' death, this penalty to me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.310#I swear to wage this war to its end."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.311#He spoke, then slashed the rams' throats
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.312#And put the gasping animals on the ground,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.313#Their proud temper undone by whetted bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.314#Then they all filled their cups
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.315#With wine from the bowl and poured libations
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.316#To the gods eternal and prayed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.317#Greek and Trojan alike, in words like these:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.318#"Zeus almighty and most glorious
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.319#And all you other immortal gods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.320#Whoever breaks this oath and truce,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.321#May their brains spill to the ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.322#Like this wine, theirs and their children's,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.323#And may other men master their wives."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.324#But Zeus would not fulfill their prayers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.325#Then Priam spoke his mind:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.326#"Hear me, Trojans and Achaean soldiers:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.327#I am going back now to windswept Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.328#Since I cannot bear to see with my own eyes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.329#My dear son fighting with Menelaus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.330#Who is dear to Ares. Zeus and the other immortals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.331#Doubtless know whose death is destined."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.332#And this man who was a god's equal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.333#Loaded the rams onto his chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.334#For interment in Trojan soil, mounted,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.335#And took the reins. Antenor stood behind him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.336#And together they drove back to Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.337#Priam's son Hector and brilliant Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.338#First measured off an arena and then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.339#Shook lots in a bronze helmet to decide
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.340#Which of the two would cast his spear first.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.341#You could see hands lifted to heaven
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.342#On both sides and hear whispered prayers:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.343#"Death, Lord Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.344#For whichever of the two
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.345#Started this business,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.346#But grant us your peace."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.347#Great Hector shook the helmet, sunlight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.348#Glancing off his own as he looked away,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.349#And out jumped Paris' lot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.350#The armies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.351#Sat down, rank after rank, tooled weapons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.352#And high-stepping horses idle by each man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.353#The heroes armed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.354#Paris, silken-haired Helen's present husband,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.355#Bound greaves on his shins with silver clasps,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.356#Put on his brother Lycaon's breastplate,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.357#Which fit him well, slung around his shoulders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.358#A bronze sword inlaid with silver
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.359#And a large, heavy shield. On his head he placed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.360#A crested helmet, and the horsehair plume
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.361#Nodded menacingly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.362#Likewise Menelaus' gear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.363#They put their armor on in the ranks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.364#And then stepped out into no-man's-land,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.365#A cold light in their eyes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.366#Veterans on both sides, horse-breaking Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.367#And bronze-kneed Greeks, just sat and stared.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.368#They stood close, closer, in the measured arena,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.369#Shaking their spears, half-mad with jealousy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.370#And then Paris threw. A long shadow trailed his spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.371#As it moved through the air, and it hit the circle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.372#Of Menelaus' shield, but the spearpoint crumpled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.373#Against its tough metal skin. It was Menelaus' turn now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.374#And as he rose in his bronze he prayed to Zeus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.375#"Lord Zeus, make Paris pay for the evil he's done to me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.376#Smite him down with my hands so that men for all time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.377#Will fear to transgress against a host's offered friendship."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.378#With this prayer behind it Menelaus' spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.379#Carried through Paris' polished shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.380#And bored into the intricate breastplate,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.381#The point shearing his shirt and nicking his ribs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.382#As Paris twisted aside from black fatality.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.383#Menelaus drew his silver-hammered sword
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.384#And came down with it hard on the crest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.385#Of Paris' helmet, but the blade shattered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.386#Into three or four pieces and fell from his hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.387#Menelaus groaned and looked up to the sky:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.388#"Father Zeus, no god curses us more than you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.389#I thought Paris was going to pay for his crimes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.390#And now my sword has broken in my hands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.391#And my spear's thrown away. I missed the bastard!"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.392#As Menelaus spoke he lunged forward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.393#And twisted his fingers into the thick horsehair
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.394#On Paris' helmet, pivoted on his heel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.395#And started dragging him back to the Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.396#The tooled-leather chinstrap of Paris' helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.397#Was cutting into his neck's tender skin,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.398#And Menelaus would have dragged him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.399#All the way back and won no end of glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.400#But Aphrodite, Zeus' daughter, had all this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.401#In sharp focus and snapped the oxhide chinstrap,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.402#Leaving Menelaus clenching an empty helmet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.403#Which the hero, spinning like a discus thrower,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.404#Heaved into the hands of the Greek spectators.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.405#Then he went back for the kill.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.406#But Aphrodite
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.407#Whisked Paris away with the sleight of a goddess,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.408#Enveloping him in mist, and lofted him into
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.409#The incensed air of his vaulted bedroom.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.410#Then she went for Helen, and found her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.411#In a crowd of Trojan women high on the tower.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.412#A withered hand tugged at Helen's fragrant robe.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.413#The goddess was now the phantom of an old woman
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.414#Who had spun wool for Helen back in Lacedaemon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.415#Beautiful wool, and Helen loved her dearly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.416#In this crone's guise Aphrodite spoke to Helen:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.417#"Over here. Paris wants you to come home.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.418#He's propped up on pillows in your bedroom,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.419#So silky and beautiful you'd never think
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.420#He'd just come from combat, but was going to a dance,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.421#Or coming from a dance and had just now sat down."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.422#This wrung Helen's heart. She knew
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.423#It was the goddess---the beautiful neck,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.424#The irresistible line of her breasts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.425#The iridescent eyes. She was in awe
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.426#For a moment, and then spoke to her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.427#"You eerie thing, why do you love
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.428#Lying to me like this? Where are you taking me now?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.429#Phrygia? Beautiful Maeonia? Another city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.430#Where you have some other boyfriend for me?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.431#Or is it because Menelaus, having just beaten Paris,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.432#Wants to take his hateful wife back to his house
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.433#That you stand here now with treachery in your heart?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.434#Go sit by Paris yourself! Descend from the gods' high road,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.435#Allow your precious feet not to tread on Olympus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.436#Go fret over him constantly, protect him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.437#Maybe someday he'll make you his wife---or even his slave.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.438#I'm not going back there. It would be treason
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.439#To share his bed. The Trojan women
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.440#Would hold me at fault. I have enough pain as it is."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.441#And Aphrodite, angry with her, said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.442#"Don't vex me, bitch, or I may let go of you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.443#And hate you as extravagantly as I love you now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.444#I can make you repulsive to both sides, you know,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.445#Trojans and Greeks, and then where will you be?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.446#Helen was afraid, and this child of Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.447#Pulled her silvery-white linens around her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.448#And walked silently through the Trojan women,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.449#Eluding them completely. The goddess went ahead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.450#And led her to Paris' beautiful house. The servants
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.451#Suddenly all found something to do.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.452#Helen moved like daylight to the vaulted bedroom,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.453#Where Aphrodite, smiling, placed a chair for her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.454#Opposite Paris. Helen, daughter of Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.455#Sat down and, averting her eyes, said reproachfully:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.456#"Back from the war? You should have died out there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.457#Beaten by a real hero, my former husband.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.458#You used to boast you were better than Menelaus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.459#When it came to spear work and hand-to-hand combat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.460#Why don't you go challenge him to fight again,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.461#Right now? I wouldn't recommend it, though,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.462#A fair fight between you and Ares' redhead darling.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.463#You'd go down in no time under his spear."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.464#Paris answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.465#"Don't insult me, Helen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.466#Menelaus beat me this time---with Athena's help.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.467#Next time I'll beat him. We have gods on our side too.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.468#Enough of this.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.469#Let's go to bed now and make love.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.470#I've never wanted you so much,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.471#Not even when I first took you away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.472#From Lacedaemon in my sailing ship
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.473#And made love to you on the island of Cranae.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.474#I want you even more now than I wanted you then."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.475#He walked to the bed, and Helen followed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.476#While the two of them slept in their bed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.477#Menelaus prowled the ranks looking for Paris.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.478#The Trojan troops, as much as they would have liked to,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.479#Could not produce him. To a man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.480#They hated Paris as they hated death itself.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.481#So Agamemenon, as commander-in-chief, proclaimed:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.482#"Hear me, Trojans, allied troops, and Dardanians:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.483#The victory clearly belongs to Menelaus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.484#Surrender therefore Argive Helen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.485#And all the possessions that come with her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.486#We will further assess a suitable penalty,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.487#A tribute to be paid for generations to come."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:3.488#Thus Agamemnon. And the Greeks cheered.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.1#The gods were seated with Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.2#On his golden terrace, and Hebe
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.3#Was pouring them nectar. They toasted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.4#Each other with golden cups
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.5#As they looked out at Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.6#Zeus all at once
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.7#Started to provoke Hera with taunts:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.8#"Well, Menelaus has a pair of goddesses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.9#To help him, Hera of Argos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.10#And Athena the Defender,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.11#But they prefer to sit on the sidelines
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.12#Enjoying themselves. Aphrodite, now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.13#Smiling as always, stays with her hero
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.14#And manages to stave off his doom.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.15#Did you see how she saved him just now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.16#When it looked like he was about to die!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.17#Still, Menelaus, Ares' favorite, clearly won.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.18#But we should decide all this now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.19#Should we let war rage again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.20#Or establish peace between the two sides?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.21#If somehow we all could agree to do this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.22#Priam's city might still be a place to live,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.23#And Menelaus could take Argive Helen home."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.24#He had no sooner finished
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.25#Than Athena and Hera were whispering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.26#To each other with their heads together,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.27#Plotting trouble for the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.28#Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.29#Didn't say a word, although she was furious
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.30#With her father.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.31#Hera, however,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.32#Couldn't contain her anger, and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.33#"Awesome son of Cronus! What a thing to say!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.34#How dare you undo all my hard work.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.35#The sweat I sweated driving my poor team
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.36#To raise an army against Priam and his sons!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.37#Do it. But don't expect us all to approve."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.38#Zeus brooded like a thunderhead, and answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.39#"I don't understand you, woman. What have
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.40#Priam and his children done to you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.41#That you are so fixed on demolishing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.42#Ilion's stronghold down to its last well-laid brick?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.43#Do you think if you were to enter its gates,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.44#Get inside its long walls, and chew up Priam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.45#And Priam's children raw, and the rest of the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.46#You might find some relief from this livid hate?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.47#Do as you please. I don't want this quarrel
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.48#To become a source of strife between us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.49#But I'll tell you this, and you take it to heart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.50#The next time I have a passion to smash a city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.51#And I choose one with men dear to you in it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.52#Don't try to curb my anger. Just let me do it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.53#I've given in to you, though unwilling at heart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.54#For of all the cities under the sun and stars,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.55#Of all the cities on earth that men inhabit,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.56#Sacred Ilion is the dearest to my soul,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.57#And Priam and the people of ashen-spear Priam.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.58#My altar there has never lacked libations
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.59#Or the steamy savor that is our due worship."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.60#And Hera, the queen, her eyes big as an ox's:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.61#"There are three cities especially dear to me:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.62#Argos, Sparta, and broad Mycenae.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.63#Waste these if they ever annoy you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.64#I won't stand in the way or take it too hard.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.65#Even if I begrudged you their destruction,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.66#What could I do against your superior strength?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.67#Still, it's not right to cancel all my hard work.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.68#I too am a god, from the same stock as you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.69#The eldest daughter of devious Cronus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.70#And honored both by position of birth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.71#And as the wife of the lord of all the immortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.72#Let's call this a draw and yield to each other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.73#I to you, and you to me, and the other gods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.74#Will all fall in line. Quickly now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.75#Dispatch Athena into the war zone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.76#To maneuver the Trojans to break the truce
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.77#And do some damage to the exultant Greeks."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.78#Zeus had no wish to argue this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.79#And he winged these words to Pallas Athena:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.80#"Go down instantly to the battlefield.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.81#Get the Trojans to break the truce
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.82#And do some damage to the exultant Greeks."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.83#Athena had been longing for action.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.84#She flashed down from the peaks of Olympus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.85#Like a star that the son of devious Cronus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.86#Sends as a portent to sailors, or to an army
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.87#Camped on a wide plain, a brilliant meteor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.88#That sheds sparks all along its shining furrow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.89#This was Pallas Athena rocketing down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.90#Into no-man's-land. They were frozen with awe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.91#Horse-breaking Trojans and bronze-kneed Greeks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.92#Soldiers glancing at each other, saying things like:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.93#"We'll be fighting again soon."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.94#"This could mean peace."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.95#"It means war, if Zeus wants to bring it."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.96#While they exchanged words to this effect,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.97#Athena blended into the crowd, disguised
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.98#As a Trojan, Antenor's son Laodocus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.99#A good man with a spear, and went in search
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.100#Of Pandarus and found that son of Lycaon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.101#Strong and not a blemish on him, standing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.102#With rank on rank of tough, shield-bearing troops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.103#Around him, his men from the banks of Aesepus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.104#Athena stood next to him and her words flew fast:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.105#"If you listened to me, wise son of Lycaon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.106#You would take a shot at Menelaus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.107#And win glory and gratitude from the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.108#Especially from prince Alexander.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.109#He would give you splendid gifts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.110#If he saw Menelaus, Atreus' warrior son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.111#Felled by your arrow and laid on the pyre.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.112#Come on, one swift arrow aimed at Menelaus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.113#And vow to Apollo, the Wolf-born Archer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.114#That you will offer a hundred firstling lambs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.115#When you come home to your city, sacred Zeleia."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.116#Athena spoke and convinced the fool.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.117#He took out his polished bow, made of the horns
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.118#Of a wild ibex that he himself had killed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.119#As it came from behind a rock. Waiting for it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.120#He shot it in the chest, and it fell back in a cleft.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.121#The horns measured sixteen palms from the head,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.122#And the worker in horn fitted them together,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.123#Smoothed it all and tipped it with gold.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.124#This was the bow he bent, bracing it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.125#Carefully on the ground while his men concealed him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.126#With shields, so the Greeks couldn't react
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.127#Before Menelaus was hit. He took the lid
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.128#From the quiver and drew out a feathered arrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.129#Barbed with black pain, that had never been shot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.130#He fit the bitter arrow quickly to the string
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.131#And vowed to Apollo, the Wolf-born Archer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.132#He would offer a hundred firstling lambs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.133#When he came home to his city, sacred Zeleia.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.134#He drew back the notched arrow until the string
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.135#Reached his nipple and the iron arrowhead the bow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.136#Which bent until it arched into a circle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.137#Then snapped back twanging, and the string hummed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.138#As the arrow needled over the crowded plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.139#But the gods were watching you, Menelaus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.140#Yes, and especially Athena, who stretched out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.141#Her immortal hand and whisked the arrow away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.142#From your bare flesh as lightly as a mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.143#Sweeps a fly from her sleeping child.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.144#The goddess redirected the arrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.145#To the golden clasps of your belt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.146#Where the corselet had an extra fold.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.147#The bitter arrow hit the buckled belt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.148#And drove right through its rich design
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.149#And pierced the filigreed corselet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.150#And penetrated even the kilt-piece beneath
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.151#That he wore as proof against javelins.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.152#The arrow's tip just grazed the human skin,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.153#And dark blood started to flow from the wound.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.154#In Maeonia and Caria women stain ivory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.155#With scarlet, to be cheek pieces for horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.156#Such a piece will lie in a treasure chamber,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.157#And though many horsemen pray to use it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.158#As an ornament for the horse and glory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.159#For the driver, it lies there as a king's prize.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.160#That, Menelaus, was how your thighs were stained
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.161#With blood, and your fine shins and ankles beneath.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.162#The warlord Agamemnon went numb
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.163#When he saw black blood flowing from the wound,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.164#As did Menelaus himself, whom Ares loved.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.165#But when he saw that the ferrule and barbs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.166#Had not gone in, he breathed easier and revived.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.167#Agamemnon, though, was still groaning deeply,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.168#Holding Menelaus' hand, and his comrades
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.169#Added their groans. Agamemnon spoke for them all:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.170#"Dear brother, my oath was your death,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.171#Setting you up to fight the Trojans for us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.172#And now they've trampled their oath and hit you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.173#But oaths are not empty: we pledged lambs' blood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.174#Poured strong wine, and clasped our right hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.175#If the Olympian does not act on this immediately
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.176#He will in good time, and they will pay heavily
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.177#With their heads, their wives, and their children.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.178#Deep down inside I know this for sure:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.179#There will come a day when holy Troy will perish,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.180#And Priam and the people under Priam's ashen spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.181#Zeus himself, throned in heaven on high,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.182#Will shake his dark aegis over them all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.183#In his wrath for this treachery. This shall be done.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.184#But dreadful grief will be mine if you die,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.185#Menelaus, and meet your destiny now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.186#I will return to Argos in utter disgrace,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.187#For the Greeks will turn their minds homeward now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.188#And we will leave Priam and the Trojans to boast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.189#They have Argive Helen. And your bones will rot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.190#As you lie in Trojan soil, your work unfinished.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.191#And some arrogant Trojan will say as he leaps
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.192#Onto the barrow of glorious Menelaus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.193#'So much for the wrath of Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.194#Who led the Greek army here for nothing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.195#And has now gone home to his native land
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.196#With empty ships, and without good Menelaus.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.197#On that day may the earth gape open for me."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.198#And Menelaus, cheering him up:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.199#"It's all right. Don't frighten the others.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.200#The arrow didn't hit a fatal spot. My belt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.201#Stopped it before it got in very far, that
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.202#And the banded kilt-piece the bronzesmiths made."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.203#And lord Agamemnon's response:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.204#"May it be so, dear Menelaus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.205#But our physician will palpate the wound
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.206#And apply medications to stop the pain."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.207#And he said to Talthybius, the godlike herald:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.208#"Talthybius, call Machaon here on the double,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.209#Asclepius' son, our faultless physician,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.210#To see Menelaus. Someone has shot him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.211#Someone really good with a bow, a Trojan
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.212#Or Lycian, to his glory and our grief."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.213#Following his orders, the herald
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.214#Went through the welter of Greek bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.215#Looking for Machaon, and spotted him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.216#Standing in the midst of his men, tough
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.217#Shield-bearing troops from Tricca's pastures.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.218#He came up to him and spoke winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.219#"Son of Asclepius, lord Agamemnon calls you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.220#To see Menelaus. Someone has shot him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.221#Someone really good with a bow, a Trojan
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.222#Or Lycian, to his glory and our grief."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.223#Machaon's heart was pounding as he made his way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.224#Across the crowded sand and through the troops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.225#Until he came to where Menelaus lay wounded,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.226#All the army's best gathered around him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.227#In a circle, into which he stepped like a god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.228#And quickly drew the arrow from the clasped belt.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.229#As it came out the barbs were broken backward.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.230#Then he undid the metallic belt and, beneath it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.231#The band with the beaten bronze kilt-piece.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.232#When he saw the wound the arrow had made
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.233#He sucked out the blood and smeared on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.234#Soothing ointments Chiron had given his father.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.235#While they were attending to Menelaus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.236#The Trojans came on under their shields,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.237#As the Greeks strapped on their gear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.238#And reminded themselves of the joys of war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.239#Agamemnon swung into action.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.240#You could not have detected in him then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.241#Any tendency toward sloth or cowardice.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.242#He left his bronze-filigreed chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.243#With his squire, Eurymedon, who held
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.244#The snorting horses off to the side,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.245#And charged him to have them ready
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.246#Should he become fatigued. Then he set out,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.247#On foot, to tour the ranks of his army.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.248#He had two set speeches. When he saw men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.249#Eager to fight, he used encouraging words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.250#"Soldiers of Greece, keep up your fighting spirit!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.251#Father Zeus will not aid Trojan perjury.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.252#Those who violated their sacred oaths
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.253#Will have vultures feeding on their pudgy flesh,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.254#And their wives and children will be our cargo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.255#After we have taken their city's high rock."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.256#But when he saw men shirking the rigors of war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.257#He scalded their ears with words like these:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.258#"You pansy archers, you're a disgrace to Greece!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.259#Standing here like a bunch of knock-kneed fawns
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.260#Worn out from running across a wide field,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.261#Gaping stupidly without an ounce of strength left.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.262#Are you waiting for the Trojans to come over here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.263#Where your pretty boats are lined up on the shore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.264#So you can see if Zeus will lend you a hand?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.265#Thus Agamemnon, ranging through the troops,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.266#And in his tour he came to where the Cretans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.267#Were arming themselves around their commander,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.268#Idomeneus, a man with a razor-sharp mind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.269#And the imposing presence of a wild boar,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.270#As he stood in the front ranks, while Meriones
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.271#Was busy marshalling the lines in the rear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.272#The warlord Agamemnon liked what he saw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.273#And had some cordial words for Idomeneus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.274#"Idomeneus, I hold you in the highest regard,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.275#Both in war and in every other activity,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.276#Certainly in the feast, when the Argive lords
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.277#Mix wine in the bowl at the council of elders.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.278#Even if every flowing-haired Greek chieftain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.279#Drinks a fixed measure, your cup stays full,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.280#And you drink, as I do, to your heart's content.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.281#To battle then, and live up to your old boasts!"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.282#And Idomeneus, the Cretan commander:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.283#"Son of Atreus, you can count on me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.284#To live up to my original pledge.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.285#But rouse the other flowing-haired Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.286#So we can get into battle. The Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.287#Have broken their oath. They will suffer and die
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.288#For violating their sacred word."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.289#Agamemnon smiled and moved on,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.290#Coming next to the two captains
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.291#Who shared the name Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.292#As they were strapping on their helmets.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.293#Behind them a cloud of infantry loomed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.294#A goatherd standing on a rocky lookout
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.295#Sees a cloud moving in over the purple sea.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.296#As a westerly gale sweeps it closer to land
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.297#It looks blacker than pitch. The sea ruffles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.298#Beneath it, the air suddenly turns cold,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.299#And the goatherd drives his flock to a cave.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.300#So the dark battalions behind the two Ajaxes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.301#Squall lines of young men nurtured under the sky,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.302#Bristling with shields and spears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.303#Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.304#Was glad to see them, and his words flew out:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.305#"Ajax, both of you, Achaean commanders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.306#I would be out of line if I issued you orders.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.307#You push your men to fight hard on your own.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.308#By Father Zeus, by Athena and Apollo,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.309#If all of my men had your kind of heart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.310#King Priam's city would soon bow her head,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.311#Taken and ravaged under our hands."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.312#He spoke and moved on to the next contingent.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.313#There he found Nestor, the clear-toned orator,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.314#Urging his Pylians on to battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.315#And arraying them around his captains:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.316#Great Pelagon, Alastor, Chromius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.317#Haemon, and Bias, shepherd of his people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.318#Nestor positioned the chariots in front
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.319#And massed the best foot soldiers at the rear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.320#Within this double wall he stationed the riffraff,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.321#So that willing or not they would be forced to fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.322#Nestor briefed his charioteers first,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.323#Reminding them to control their horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.324#And not drive recklessly into the mêlée:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.325#"Now don't get overconfident, any of you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.326#Or be too eager to fight the Trojans alone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.327#In front of the rest. But no falling back either.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.328#Either course will weaken the line.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.329#When you make contact with an enemy chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.330#Stay in your own and thrust with your spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.331#These are battle-proven, time-tested tactics
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.332#Used by our ancestors to capture walled towns."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.333#The old man had years of experience in battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.334#The warlord Agamemnon was glad to see him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.335#And addressed him with winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.336#"Nestor, old sir! If only your knees
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.337#Were as strong as your spirit, but old age
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.338#Has worn you down. I'd rather have
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.339#Someone else old, and you among the young."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.340#And Nestor, the Gerenian horseman, answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.341#"Son of Atreus, I wish so myself! To be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.342#As I was when I killed Ereuthalion!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.343#But the gods do not give us all things at once.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.344#I was young then, and now I am old.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.345#Even so, I will be with the charioteers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.346#And urge them on with counsel and words,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.347#As is an elder's privilege. Spearwork
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.348#Is for the young men, who trust their strength."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.349#And Agamemnon moved on, glad in his heart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.350#He found Menestheus next, Peteus' son, standing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.351#With his Athenians, masters of the war cry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.352#And farther up the line crafty Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.353#With his tough Cephallenians. These troops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.354#Had not yet heard a signal---since the armies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.355#On both sides were just now starting to move---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.356#And were waiting for other Greek battalions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.357#To advance and begin the attack on the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.358#When the warlord Agamemnon saw them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.359#He sent a few barbed words winging their way:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.360#"Son of Peteus---a king nurtured by Zeus---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.361#And you, with all your famous dirty tricks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.362#Why are you lagging back here, waiting for others?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.363#You two should be taking your stand up front
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.364#And throwing yourselves into the heat of battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.365#Both of you are first in line when you hear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.366#I am giving a feast for the council of elders.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.367#You like to eat roast meat well enough then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.368#And drink cups of honeyed wine all night,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.369#But now you'd be glad to see ten Greek battalions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.370#Carving up the enemy ahead of you with bronze."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.371#Odysseus scowled darkly as he answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.372#"What kind of talk is that, Agamemnon?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.373#How can you say we are slack in battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.374#Whenever the Greeks engage the Trojans?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.375#You will have a chance to see, if you really care,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.376#How Telemachus' father mixes it up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.377#With the horse-whipping Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.378#What you're saying now is a lot of hot air."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.379#Agamemnon could see he was angry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.380#And, with a smile, he took back his words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.381#"Son of Laertes in the line of Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.382#Odysseus, the master tactician,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.383#I don't mean to give you a hard time.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.384#You and I understand each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.385#Go now. We will make it up later.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.386#If there have been any hard words here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.387#May the gods blow them away on the winds."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.388#Leaving them there he went on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.389#And found Diomedes, son of Tydeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.390#Standing by his horses and chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.391#With Sthenelus, Capaneus' son, at his side.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.392#When the warlord Agamemnon saw them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.393#He sent a few barbed words winging their way:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.394#"What's this, the son of the hero Tydeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.395#Squinting down the lanes of battle from the rear?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.396#It wasn't like Tydeus to cower like this.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.397#He fought the enemy out front with his friends,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.398#As those who saw him in action say. I never
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.399#Saw him myself, but they say he was the best.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.400#He came to Mycenae once, not as an enemy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.401#But as a guest, when he and Polyneices
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.402#Were taking the field against Thebes' sacred walls.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.403#They needed allies, and the Mycenaeans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.404#Were ready to accede to their request,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.405#But Zeus changed their minds with unlucky omens.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.406#So they left and came in their journey
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.407#To the Asopus' deep reeds and grassy banks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.408#And the Achaeans sent Tydeus out again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.409#On another mission, north to Thebes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.410#So he went, and found a crowd of Cadmeians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.411#At a feast in mighty Eteocles' house.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.412#Alone as he was, and a stranger there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.413#The horseman Tydeus was not afraid.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.414#He challenged them all to athletic contests
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.415#And easily won every single event,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.416#So much help did Athena give him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.417#The Cadmeians were angry, and when he left
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.418#They laid an ambush along his route back,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.419#Fifty young men under two commanders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.420#Maeon, son of Haemon, a match for the gods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.421#And Autophonus' son, staunch Polyphontes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.422#But Tydeus brought them to an ugly end,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.423#Killing all but one. Maeon alone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.424#He allowed to return, persuaded by portents.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.425#That's what Tydeus the Aetolian was like,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.426#But he had a son who cannot fight so well,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.427#Though he speaks better in council."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.428#He spoke, and Diomedes said nothing at all,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.429#A mark of respect for the royal reproach.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.430#But Capaneus' son, Sthenelus, responded:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.431#"Son of Atreus, don't lie when you know
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.432#How to speak the plain truth. We are proud
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.433#That we are better than our fathers. We took
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.434#Thebes with its seven gates, a lesser army
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.435#Against a stronger wall, trusting in the gods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.436#But our fathers perished by their own recklessness.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.437#So don't put them on a level with us."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.438#Diomedes frowned at this and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.439#"Take it easy there, and listen to me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.440#I don't hold anything against Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.441#For getting the troops into gear. After all,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.442#He has more at stake here, greater glory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.443#If the Greeks win and capture Ilion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.444#And greater grief if the Greeks are defeated.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.445#Let's you and I just keep our minds on fighting."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.446#And he jumped down from his chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.447#In full metal. The clang of bronze on his chest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.448#As he moved out would have unnerved anyone.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.449#A swollen wave pushed by the West Wind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.450#Moves closer and closer to a thundering beach.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.451#It crests in deep water and then breaks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.452#Onto the shore with a huge roar and curls over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.453#And around the jutting rocks in a spray of brine.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.454#So too wave after wave of Greek battalions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.455#Moving into combat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.456#The captains
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.457#Issued commands; the rest marched on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.458#In such an eerie silence you would have said
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.459#That not a soldier in the army had a voice,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.460#But in fact the silence was terror
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.461#Of their commanders, and only the mute glow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.462#From their detailed weaponry signalled their advance.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.463#Not so with the Trojan army.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.464#More ewes than anyone could ever count
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.465#Are penned in the court of a man of means,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.466#Waiting, waiting to give their white milk
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.467#And bleating incessantly when they hear the lambs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.468#Thus the clamor from the immense Trojan muster,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.469#Not one voice, one language,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.470#But a cacophony of tongues from different lands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.471#Behind them, Ares, as behind the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.472#The goddess Athena with sea-grey eyes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.473#And on both sides Terror and Panic
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.474#And Ares' murderous sister, Eris,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.475#Small when her crest first appears
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.476#But so ravenous and relentless in her ways
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.477#That she soon thrusts her head into the sky
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.478#Even while she keeps her feet on the earth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.479#This horror now infused equal parts of strife
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.480#Into both armies as she patrolled their ranks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.481#Swelling the volume of human suffering.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.482#When the two sides closed with each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.483#They slammed together shields and spears,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.484#Rawhide ovals pressed close, bronze thoraxes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.485#Grinding against each other amid the groans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.486#And exultations of men being slain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.487#And of those slaying, as the earth ran with blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.488#Swollen winter torrents flow together
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.489#Where two valleys meet. The heavy water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.490#From both streams joins in a gorge,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.491#And far off in the mountains
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.492#A shepherd hears a single, distant roar.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.493#Equally indistinguishable the shrieking
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.494#Of these warriors laboring in union.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.495#Antilochus drew first blood, killing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.496#Echepolus, one of Troy's best.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.497#The quick thrust of Antilochus' spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.498#Glanced off the rim of his plumed helmet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.499#But the bronze point pegged his forehead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.500#And bored through the bone. Darkness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.501#Enveloped him as he fell like a wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.502#As he went down, Elephenor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.503#The Abantes' captain, grabbed him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.504#By the feet and tried to drag him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.505#Quickly out of range to strip the armor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.506#This effort was short-lived. As Elephenor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.507#Stooped to haul the corpse, Agenor saw him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.508#And where his shield left his left side exposed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.509#Agenor thrust, crumpling him with his spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.510#The life drained out of him, and over his body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.511#The fighting intensified, Greeks and Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.512#Battering each other like leaping wolves.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.513#One early victim was Anthemion's son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.514#Simoeisius, a blossoming lad
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.515#Whom Telamonian Ajax marked and hit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.516#His mother bore him on the Simois' banks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.517#On her way down from the slopes of Ida
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.518#Where she had gone to see her family's flocks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.519#So his parents called him Simoeisius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.520#But he died before he could pay them back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.521#For rearing him. As he advanced
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.522#In the Trojan front lines, the bronze point
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.523#Of Ajax's spear pierced his right nipple
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.524#And ripped through his shoulder. He fell
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.525#Down to the ground and lay in the dust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.526#A poplar that has grown up in rich bottom soil,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.527#With a smooth trunk branching out at top,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.528#Catches the eye of a wainwright, who wants
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.529#To curve it into a pole for a fine chariot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.530#He cuts it with a few flashing strokes of his axe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.531#And now it lies drying by the river bank.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.532#When Ajax had dispatched him, Antiphus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.533#One of Priam's sons, gleaming in his corselet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.534#Threw his javelin at him through the crowd,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.535#Missing Ajax but hitting a man named Leucas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.536#One of Odysseus' companions, in the groin,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.537#As he was hauling the body off to one side.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.538#The corpse fell from his hands and he slumped over it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.539#Odysseus took his death hard. He strode forward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.540#Through the front ranks glowing in his bronze
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.541#And, sweeping the enemy lines with his eyes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.542#Cast his javelin. The Trojans fell back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.543#As the javelin homed in on Democoön,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.544#Priam's bastard son from his horse farm in Abydos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.545#With the weight of Odysseus' anger behind it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.546#The spearpoint entered one temple and came out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.547#Through the other. Darkness enveloped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.548#Democoön's eyes. He fell with a thud,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.549#And his armor clattered on his back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.550#The Trojan front lines, and Hector with them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.551#Gave ground. The Greeks cheered, dragged off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.552#The bodies, and charged far ahead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.553#Apollo,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.554#Looking down at all this from Pergamum,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.555#Was indignant, and yelled to the Trojans:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.556#"Get back into the fight! Greek skin
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.557#Is not stone or iron. It will not deflect bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.558#Nor is Achilles, son of Thetis, in combat,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.559#But nurses his rage in the beachhead camp."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.560#Thus the dread god spoke from the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.561#But the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.562#Were urged on by Zeus' daughter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.563#Wherever she saw them faltering.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.564#Diores, though, was skewered by Fate.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.565#Peirus, the Thracian leader, had caught him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.566#Just above the ankle with a jagged stone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.567#That crushed both tendons and bones.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.568#He fell backward into the dust, hands stretched
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.569#Toward his friends, gasping out his life.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.570#Peirus ran up and finished him off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.571#With a slicing spear thrust near his navel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.572#His guts spilled out, and everything went black.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.573#As Peirus jumped back, Thoas the Aetolian
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.574#Hit him in the chest above the nipple.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.575#The bronze caught in his lung. Thoas closed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.576#Pulled the spear out, drew his sword
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.577#And slashed his belly open. This finished him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.578#But Thoas did not get to strip off Peirus' armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.579#Because his men, top-knotted Thracians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.580#With long spears in hand, drove him off,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.581#Big as he was, and sent him reeling.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.582#And so the two lay side by side in the dust,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.583#The Thracian leader stretched out by the Epeian,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.584#And around them many others were killed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.585#No one could trust his immunity any longer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.586#Not even those who had danced their way through
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.587#Unscathed until now, led by the hand of Pallas Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.588#Through the hail of whetted bronze instruments.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.589#This was a day many Greeks and Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:4.590#Paired off with each other to lie in the dust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.1#Pallas Athena now gave to Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.2#Tydeus' son, the strength and courage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.3#That would make him shine
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.4#Among the Greeks and win him glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.5#Starlight flowed from his helmet and shield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.6#As if Sirius had just risen from the sea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.7#Before dawn in autumn, and that brightest of stars
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.8#Was blazing from his torso and face
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.9#Instead of from the sky.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.10#Athena aimed him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.11#To where the battle was thickest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.12#There was a Trojan named Dares,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.13#A rich man without a blemish on him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.14#And a priest of Hephaestus. He had two sons,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.15#Phegeus and Idaeus, trained warriors.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.16#These two now separated themselves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.17#From the crowd and went for Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.18#They in their chariot, he on foot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.19#When they closed, Phegeus threw.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.20#His spear sailed high, passing well over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.21#The left shoulder of Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.22#Who kept on coming, launching a shot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.23#That hit Phegeus' chest between his nipples
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.24#And knocked him from his rig. Idaeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.25#Jumped for it, abandoning his chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.26#And his slain brother, whose prostrate corpse
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.27#He did not have the courage to defend.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.28#He himself would not have escaped black death
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.29#If Hephaestus had not got him out of there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.30#Wrapping him in night, so that the old man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.31#His priest, would not be utterly bereaved.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.32#Diomedes did get the horses though,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.33#And had his men drive them back to the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.34#When the Trojans saw Dares' two sons,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.35#One in flight, the other dead by his chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.36#Their hearts shrivelled. Athena's cold grey eyes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.37#Bored in on Ares. She took his hand and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.38#"Ares, you bloodthirsty marauder,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.39#Why don't we let the Greeks and Trojans fight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.40#And see to which side Father Zeus gives glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.41#We'd both best withdraw, and avoid his anger."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.42#And with that she led Ares away from the battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.43#And made him sit on the Scamander's sandy banks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.44#While the Greeks pushed the Trojans back. Each leader
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.45#Took out his man. First, the warlord Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.46#Knocked Odius, the Halizones' commander,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.47#Out of his chariot as he led the retreat,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.48#Planting a spear between his shoulder blades
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.49#And driving it out through his chest. He fell
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.50#With a thud, and his armor clanged on his body.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.51#Idomeneus killed Phaestus, the Maeonian
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.52#Who had come from Tarne's black soil,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.53#Threading his spear through his right shoulder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.54#As he tried to mount his chariot but instead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.55#Fell back from it into the loathsome dark.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.56#Idomeneus' squires stripped off his armor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.57#Menelaus killed Scamandrius.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.58#This man had been taught to hunt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.59#By Artemis herself, and could shoot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.60#Any animal the mountain forest nourished.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.61#But neither the goddess nor all his old skill
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.62#In archery could help him now. Menelaus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.63#Planted a spear between his shoulder blades
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.64#And drove it out through his chest. He fell
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.65#With a thud, and his armor clanged on his body.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.66#Meriones killed Phereclus, whose father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.67#Was Tecton and grandfather Harmon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.68#And who was himself a skilled craftsman,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.69#For Pallas Athena loved him prodigiously.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.70#He could build all sorts of intricate things,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.71#And had built for Paris the doomed hulls
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.72#That first spelled evil for Troy, and for himself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.73#Since he had no inkling of the gods' oracles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.74#Meriones ran him down from behind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.75#And hit him in the right buttock. The spearpoint
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.76#Slid beneath the bone clear through the bladder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.77#He fell to his knees, and groaned as death took him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.78#Meges took out Pedaeus, Antenor's son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.79#Though he was a bastard, Theano raised him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.80#As one of her own, to please her husband.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.81#Now Meges got close enough to him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.82#To send his spear through the tendon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.83#At the back of his neck and on into his mouth,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.84#Cutting away the tongue at its root. He fell
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.85#Into the dust, his teeth clenched on cold bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.86#Eurypylus got Hypsenor, son of Dolopion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.87#And honored priest of the River Scamander.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.88#Euaemon's glorious son Eurypylus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.89#Caught up with him as he sprinted away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.90#And, without breaking stride, slashed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.91#At the man's shoulder with his sword
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.92#And lopped off his arm, which fell
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.93#In a bloody mass to the ground. Death
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.94#Covered his eyes with a purple haze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.95#This was their labor in the crush of battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.96#As for Diomedes, you could not tell
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.97#Which side he belonged to, Greek or Trojan,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.98#As he boiled across the plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.99#A winter torrent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.100#Will sweep away the thickset riprap
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.101#Meant to contain it, and flood over also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.102#The vineyard walls, when the rain of Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.103#Makes its swollen waters suddenly rise
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.104#And obliterate many fine human works.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.105#So too before Tydeus' son were driven
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.106#Thick Trojan battalions. Many as they were,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.107#They could not withstand this single human tide.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.108#When Pandarus saw him storming across the plain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.109#And driving entire battalions before him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.110#He bent his curved bow and, taking aim at Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.111#Hit him on the fly in his right shoulder,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.112#The arrow piercing the corselet plate
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.113#And spattering it with blood as it punched through.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.114#And Pandarus whooped:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.115#"Got him! Take heart, Trojan horsemen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.116#The best of the Achaeans is hit! I don't think
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.117#He will hold up long under that stiff shaft
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.118#If Apollo in truth sent me forth from Lycia."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.119#Half prayer, half boast. But the arrow didn't kill him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.120#Diomedes took cover next to his horses and car
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.121#And, still standing, said to Sthenelus, his driver:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.122#"Son of Capaneus, get down from the car
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.123#And pull this arrow out of my shoulder."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.124#Sthenelus vaulted down to the ground,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.125#Steadied himself, and drew the arrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.126#Clean through his shoulder and out the other side.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.127#Blood spurted through the linked tunic,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.128#And Diomedes, good at the war shout, prayed:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.129#"Hear me, daughter of Zeus! If ever
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.130#You stood by my father's side, a friend
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.131#In the heat of battle, stand by me now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.132#Goddess Athena. Deliver unto me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.133#And place within the range of my spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.134#The man who hit me before I saw him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.135#And boasted I would not see for long
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.136#The brilliant light of Helios the Sun."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.137#Pallas Athena heard Diomedes' prayer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.138#She made his body lithe and light,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.139#Then feathered these words into his ear:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.140#"Go after the Trojans for all you're worth,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.141#Diomedes. I have put into your heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.142#Your father's heroic temper, the fearless
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.143#Fighting spirit of Tydeus the horseman,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.144#Tydeus the Shield. And I have removed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.145#The mist that has clouded your eyes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.146#So that now you can tell god from man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.147#Do not fight with any immortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.148#Who might come and challenge you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.149#Except Aphrodite, daughter of Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.150#If she comes you may wound her with bronze."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.151#With these words the grey-eyed one was gone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.152#And Diomedes returned to the front.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.153#He had been eager before to fight the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.154#But now his fury was tripled.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.155#A shepherd wounds a lion as he leaps a pen's wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.156#But far from being weakened, the lion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.157#Gains in strength, and the unprotected flock
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.158#Is little more than a pile of bloody fleece
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.159#Before the angered lion leaps out again.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.160#So too Diomedes among the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.161#Killing next Astynous and Hypeiron,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.162#One with a spearcast above his nipple,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.163#The other with a swordstroke to the collar-bone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.164#Shearing off the entire shoulder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.165#From the neck and back. He let them lie
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.166#And went after Abas and Polyidus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.167#Sons of old Eurydamas, who read dreams,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.168#But read no dreams for them when they left home.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.169#Diomedes cut them down and moved on.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.170#There were two more brothers, Xanthus and Thoön,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.171#Sons of Phaenops, who loved them well.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.172#He was worn out with old age and its miseries
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.173#And had no other son to be his heir.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.174#Diomedes killed them too, taking their lives
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.175#And leaving for the father sorrow and grief.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.176#They would not live to be welcomed home,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.177#And others would divide their inheritance.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.178#His next victims were two sons of Priam,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.179#Echemmon and Chromius, in one chariot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.180#Diomedes jumped on them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.181#as a lion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.182#Leaps on a heifer grazing peacefully
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.183#In a woodland pasture, and breaks her neck.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.184#It was a brutal dismount the son of Tydeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.185#Forced them to make. He then stripped their armor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.186#And his men drove their horses back to the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.187#Aeneas saw him wrecking the Trojan ranks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.188#And made his way through the busy spears
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.189#Searching for Pandarus. When he found him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.190#Looking like the match for a god that he was,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.191#He went up to him and had this to say:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.192#"Pandarus, where are your arrows and bow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.193#And your fame? No one here or in all Lycia
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.194#Can compete with you or claim to be better.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.195#Say a prayer to Zeus and take a shot at this man---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.196#Whoever he is---who is beating the daylights
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.197#Out of the Trojans, some of our best too.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.198#It could be he's a god, angry with the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.199#Over some sacrifice. That would be tough."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.200#Lycaon's splendid son came back with this:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.201#"Aeneas, he looks like Diomedes to me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.202#His shield, his grooved helmet, his horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.203#I'm not at all sure that he's not a god,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.204#But if he is who I think he is, Tydeus' son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.205#He's not fighting like this without some god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.206#Standing at his side and cloaked in mist.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.207#I swear one of the immortals turned aside
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.208#An arrow I already shot at him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.209#Just as it struck. It wound up hitting him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.210#In the right shoulder, clean through his breastplate.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.211#I thought I had sent him down to Hades,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.212#But I didn't get him. Some god is sure angry.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.213#Anyway, I don't have a chariot now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.214#Or horses to pull it---not that there aren't eleven
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.215#Beautiful new chariots back in Lycaon's palace,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.216#Covered with cloths, and a yoke of horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.217#Beside each one eating white barley and spelt.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.218#Yes, and Lycaon, the old spearman,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.219#Told me as I left to go to war mounted,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.220#Advice I should have taken but didn't,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.221#Sparing the horses because I was afraid
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.222#That in an army this big they would lack feed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.223#And they had been used to eating all they wanted.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.224#So I left them, and came to Ilion on foot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.225#Trusting my bow, for all the good it has done.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.226#I've taken shots at two of their best,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.227#Diomedes and Menelaus, and hit them both,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.228#Drew blood for sure, and only made them madder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.229#Curse the day I took my bow from its peg
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.230#And led my Trojan troops to lovely Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.231#As a favor to Hector. If I ever return
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.232#And see my land, my wife, and my high-roofed home,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.233#May my throat be cut by a thief in the night
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.234#If I fail to smash my bow in pieces
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.235#And throw it in the fire. It's been a piece of junk."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.236#And Aeneas, the Trojan commander, replied:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.237#"Don't talk like that. Things won't get any better
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.238#Until you and I take a chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.239#And face him in combat. Come on, get in mine,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.240#And you'll see what the horses of Tros can do.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.241#They know how to eat up the plain, and how to
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.242#Cut and turn, in pursuit or flight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.243#And they will get us back to the city in safety
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.244#If Zeus gives Diomedes the glory again.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.245#Get in and take the lash and the reins,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.246#And I'll dismount to fight; or you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.247#Take him on, and leave the horses to me."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.248#Lycaon's splendid son came back with this:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.249#"Keep the reins, Aeneas, and drive your own horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.250#They will pull better for a driver they know
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.251#In case we have to run from the son of Tydeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.252#I wouldn't want them to be spooked, and shy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.253#From pulling us out because they miss your voice---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.254#Not with Diomedes all over us. He'd kill us both
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.255#And make off with your horses. No, you drive them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.256#And I'll meet his charge with my spear."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.257#So they mounted the chariot and drove off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.258#Full speed ahead toward the son of Tydeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.259#Sthenelus saw them coming and said to Diomedes:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.260#"Here comes a duo now with muscle to spare
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.261#And hot to fight you. One is good with a bow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.262#Pandarus, who boasts he is Lycaon's son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.263#The other is Aeneas, who says his mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.264#Is Aphrodite, and Anchises his father.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.265#Let's retreat in the chariot. Calm down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.266#And get out of action or you'll get yourself killed."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.267#Diomedes looked him up and down and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.268#"Don't talk to me about retreating, Sthenelus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.269#It's not in me to dodge a fight. Besides,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.270#I still have my strength. I'm not even going
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.271#To get in the chariot, much less retreat in it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.272#I'll take them on just like this. Pallas Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.273#Won't let me back down. As for these two,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.274#Their horses won't be carrying them both away,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.275#Even if one of them manages to escape.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.276#And one thing more. Athena has many plans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.277#But if she does give me the glory here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.278#And I kill them both, hold our horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.279#On this spot, tying the reins to the chariot rail,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.280#And rush Aeneas' horses. Drive them back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.281#Away from the Trojans and to the Greek lines.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.282#These horses come from the stock that Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.283#Gave to Tros as payment for his son Ganymede.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.284#The finest horses under the sun. Anchises
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.285#Stole some of the breed from Laomedon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.286#By secretly putting his mares to them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.287#And so got six colts born in his own palace.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.288#Four he kept for himself and reared at the stall,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.289#And two he gave to Aeneas, superb warhorses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.290#If we could take these, it'd be a real coup."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.291#Thus Diomedes and his driver.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.292#Their two opponents
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.293#Drove their thoroughbreds hard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.294#And quickly closed the gap, and Pandarus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.295#Lycaon's splendid son, called out:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.296#"You're tough, Diomedes, a real pedigreed hero.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.297#So I only stung you with that arrow?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.298#Well, let's see what I can do with a spear."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.299#The shaft cast a long shadow as it left his hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.300#And hit Diomedes' shield. The bronze apex
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.301#Sheared through and stopped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.302#Just short of his breastplate.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.303#Pandarus, thinking he had hit him, whooped again:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.304#"Got you right through the belly, didn't I?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.305#You're done for, and you've handed me the glory."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.306#Diomedes answered him levelly:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.307#"You didn't even come close, but I swear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.308#One of you two goes down now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.309#And gluts Ares with his blood."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.310#His javelin followed his voice, and Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.311#Guided it to where the nose joins the eye-socket.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.312#The bronze crunched through the pearly teeth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.313#And sheared the tongue at its root, exiting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.314#At the base of the chin.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.315#Pandarus fell from the car,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.316#His armor scattering the hard light
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.317#As it clattered on his fallen body.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.318#His horses shied---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.319#Quick movement of hooves---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.320#As his soul seeped out into the sand.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.321#Aeneas vaulted down with his shield and spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.322#Afraid that the Greeks might drag the body away.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.323#He straddled it like a lion sure of its strength,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.324#Spear straight out, crouched behind his shield's disk,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.325#Only too glad to kill whoever stood up to him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.326#His mouth open in a battle-howl.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.327#But Tydeus' son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.328#Levered up in one hand a slab of stone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.329#Much too large for two men to lift---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.330#As men are now---lifted it and smashed it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.331#Into Aeneas' hip, where the thighbone turns
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.332#In the socket that medics call the cup.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.333#The rough stone shattered this joint and severed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.334#Both tendons, ripping open the skin. The hero
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.335#Sank to his knees, clenching the dirt with one hand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.336#While midnight settled upon both his eyes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.337#That would have been the end of Aeneas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.338#But his mother Aphrodite, Zeus' daughter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.339#(Who bore Aeneas to Anchises the oxherd),
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.340#Had all this in sharp focus. Her milk-white arms
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.341#Circled around him and she enfolded him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.342#In her radiant robe to prevent the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.343#From killing him with a spear to the chest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.344#As she was carrying him out of the battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.345#Sthenelus remembered the instructions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.346#Diomedes had given him. He held his own horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.347#Away from the boiling dust, tying the reins
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.348#To the chariot rail, and, on foot, stampeded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.349#Aeneas' beautiful horses toward the Greek lines,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.350#Giving them to Deipylus, the boyhood friend
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.351#He valued most and whose mind was like his,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.352#To drive back to the ships. Then he mounted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.353#His own chariot, took the glossy reins in hand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.354#And drove his heavy-hooved horses off to find
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.355#Tydeus' son, who was himself in armed pursuit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.356#Of Aphrodite. Diomedes knew
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.357#This was a weakling goddess, not one of those
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.358#Who control human warfare---no Athena,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.359#No Enyo here, who demolishes cities---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.360#And when he caught up to her in the mêlée
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.361#He pounced at her with his spear and, thrusting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.362#Nicked her on her delicate wrist, the blade
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.363#Piercing her skin through the ambrosial robe
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.364#That the Graces themselves had made for her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.365#The cut was just above the palm, and the goddess'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.366#Immortal blood oozed out, or rather
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.367#The ichor that flows in the blessed gods' veins,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.368#Who, eating no bread and drinking no wine,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.369#Are bloodless and therefore deathless as well.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.370#The goddess shrieked and let her son fall,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.371#And Phoebus Apollo gathered him up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.372#In an indigo cloud to keep the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.373#From killing him with a spear to the chest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.374#And Diomedes, yelling above the battle noise:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.375#"Get out of the war, daughter of Zeus!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.376#Don't you have enough to do distracting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.377#Weak women? Keep meddling in war and
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.378#You'll learn to shiver when it's even mentioned."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.379#The goddess, in extreme distress now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.380#Went off in a daze. Wind-footed Iris
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.381#Took her and led her through the throng,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.382#Throbbing with pain, her pale skin bruised.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.383#After a while she found Ares, sitting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.384#On the left of the battle, his spear propped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.385#Against a bank of mist, his horses standing by.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.386#Aphrodite fell to her knees and begged
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.387#Her brother for his gold-frontleted horses:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.388#"Brother dear, lend me your horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.389#And help me get to Olympus. I'm hurt,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.390#Wounded by a mortal, Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.391#Who would fight even Father Zeus."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.392#Ares gave her the gold-frontleted horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.393#She mounted the chariot gingerly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.394#And Iris stepped in and took the reins.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.395#She cracked the whip and the team flew off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.396#And came in no time to steep Olympus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.397#The gods' homestead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.398#Iris, a blur of windy light,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.399#Halted the team, unyoked them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.400#And cast before them their ambrosial fodder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.401#Aphrodite went in to her mother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.402#Dione, and fell in her lap.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.403#And Dione,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.404#Cradling her daughter in her arms,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.405#And stroking her with her hand, said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.406#"Oh my poor baby, who did this to you?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.407#To treat you like this! What did you do?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.408#And Aphrodite, the goddess who loved to smile:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.409#"Tydeus' son wounded me, that bully
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.410#Diomedes, because I was carrying my son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.411#Out of range, Aeneas, who is my dearest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.412#The war has gone far beyond Trojans and Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.413#The Greeks are fighting the immortal gods."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.414#Dione answered in her lustrous voice:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.415#"You must bear it, my child. I know it hurts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.416#Many of us Olympians have suffered harm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.417#From men, giving tit for tat to each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.418#Ares did, when Otus and Ephialtes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.419#Those bullies, sons of Aloeus, kept him tied him up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.420#In a bronze jar for thirteen months.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.421#They would have destroyed the God of War
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.422#If their stepmother, beautiful Eëriboea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.423#Hadn't told Hermes. He got Ares out,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.424#But the painful bonds had about done him in.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.425#Hera suffered too, when Heracles shot her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.426#Right in the breast with a triple-pronged arrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.427#And there was no helping the pain she had then.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.428#Hades too, formidable as he is, had to endure
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.429#An arrow the same man shot him with
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.430#Among the dead in Pylos, making him suffer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.431#He went to the house of Zeus on Olympus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.432#In agony, pierced with pain. The arrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.433#Had driven right through his shoulder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.434#Paieon rubbed on an anodyne
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.435#And healed him, Hades being no mortal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.436#Heracles was simply outrageous and reckless
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.437#To provoke the Olympian gods with arrows.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.438#And now Athena has set this man upon you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.439#This fool Diomedes, who doesn't understand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.440#That a man who fights with gods doesn't last long,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.441#His children don't sit on his lap calling him 'Papa'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.442#To welcome him home from the horrors of war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.443#So as strong as he is, he had better watch out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.444#Or someone braver than you might fight him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.445#And Aegialeia, Adrastus' heroic daughter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.446#The wife of Diomedes, tamer of horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.447#Will wake her family from sleep with lamenting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.448#Her wedded husband, the best of the Achaeans."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.449#And with both her hands she wiped off the ichor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.450#The wrist was healed, and the pain subsided.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.451#Athena and Hera were looking on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.452#And making snide remarks to provoke Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.453#The grey-eyed goddess opened with this:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.454#"You won't get angry if I say something,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.455#Will you, Father Zeus? The truth is this:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.456#Aphrodite has been urging some Greek lady
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.457#To traipse after her beloved Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.458#And while she was stroking this gowned beauty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.459#She scratched her frail little hand on a golden brooch."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.460#The Father of Gods and Men smiled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.461#And calling Aphrodite said to her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.462#"Dear child, war isn't your specialty, you know.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.463#You just take care of the pleasures of love
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.464#And leave the fighting to Ares and Athena."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.465#While these gods were talking to each other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.466#Diomedes leapt upon Aeneas, even though
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.467#He knew Apollo's hands were there above him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.468#Great as Apollo was, Diomedes meant
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.469#To kill the Trojan and strip off his armor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.470#Three times he leapt in homicidal frenzy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.471#Three times Apollo flicked his lacquered shield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.472#But when he charged a fourth, last time,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.473#He heard a voice that seemed to come
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.474#From everywhere at once, and knew it was
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.475#Apollo's voice, saying to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.476#"Think it over, son of Tydeus, and get back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.477#Don't set your sights on the gods. Gods are
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.478#To humans what humans are to crawling bugs."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.479#Even at this, Diomedes only backed up a little,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.480#Just out of range of the wrathful god.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.481#And Apollo took Aeneas from the swarm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.482#Up to his temple on sacred Pergamum.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.483#There Leto and arrowy Artemis healed him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.484#In the great sanctuary, and made him glorious.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.485#And silver-bowed Apollo made a phantom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.486#To look like Aeneas, armor and all,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.487#And over this wraith the Greeks and Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.488#Battered each other with their rawhide shields
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.489#Until the edges were tattered into leather fringe.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.490#Apollo then called out to the God of War:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.491#"Ares, you bloodthirsty marauder,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.492#Would you be so kind as to take this Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.493#Out of action, before he goes up against Zeus?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.494#He's already wounded Cypris on the wrist,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.495#And came after me like a raging demon."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.496#Apollo then sat down on Pergamum's height,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.497#While Ares went to spur on the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.498#Disguised as Acamas, the Thracian commander.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.499#He called out to the well-born sons of Priam:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.500#"You sons of Priam, a king bred by Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.501#How long will you allow your men to be killed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.502#By the Achaean forces? Perhaps until
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.503#They are fighting right in front of our gates?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.504#Aeneas is down, son of noble Anchises,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.505#A man whom we honored as much as Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.506#Let's save our comrade from the boiling dust."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.507#This caught their attention. And Sarpedon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.508#Added his voice, scolding Hector sternly:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.509#"Where has your will to fight gone, Hector?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.510#You used to say you could hold the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.511#Without any allies, just yourself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.512#Backed by your brothers and sisters' husbands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.513#I don't see a single one of them now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.514#Who's not cringing like a dog before a lion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.515#The only ones fighting are us, the allies.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.516#I'm only an ally myself, from a long way off.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.517#It's a long way to Lycia, by eddying Xanthus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.518#Where I left my dear wife and baby boy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.519#And all my property and envied wealth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.520#And yet I press my Lycians into battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.521#And take on my man, with nothing of mine here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.522#For the Achaeans to take or drive away.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.523#But you can't even be troubled to urge your men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.524#To take a stand and defend their own wives.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.525#Watch out you're not caught like flies in a web,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.526#An easy prey for your enemies,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.527#Who will waste your populous city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.528#You should be worrying about this day and night
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.529#And begging the captains of your gallant allies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.530#To hold their ground---or take the heat yourself."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.531#Sarpedon's speech cut Hector to the quick.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.532#He leapt to the ground with all his gear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.533#And, brandishing a pair of sharp spears,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.534#Roamed the ranks, urging everyone to fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.535#The noise intensified, and with a roar
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.536#The Trojans whirled to face the Achaeans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.537#Who remained in tight formation and did not flinch.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.538#Wind carries chaff over the holy threshing floors
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.539#When men are winnowing, and Demeter herself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.540#Blonde in the blowing wind, separates
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.541#The grain from the chaff, and the piles of chaff
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.542#That accumulate grow whiter and whiter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.543#So too the Greeks under the cloud of white dust
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.544#Their horses' hooves kicked up from the plain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.545#As the chariots wheeled into action again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.546#And men locked up in hand-to-hand combat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.547#The bronze sky paled. Ares, who was everywhere
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.548#At once now, covered the battle with night
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.549#To help the Trojans, honoring the request
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.550#Of sungold Apollo, who had asked him to rouse
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.551#The Trojans' spirit when he saw that Athena,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.552#Who supported the Greeks, had gone off.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.553#Apollo chose this moment to send forth Aeneas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.554#From his rich sanctuary, infused with strength.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.555#Aeneas took his place in the ranks. The men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.556#Were glad to see him come back to join them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.557#Alive and well and in good fighting form.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.558#But they did not have time to question him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.559#Busy as they were with what Apollo was doing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.560#With the help of Ares and ravenous Strife.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.561#The Greeks were rallied by the two Ajaxes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.562#Along with Odysseus and Diomedes---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.563#Not that they quailed before the Trojan attack.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.564#In still weather, when the winds that usually
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.565#Scatter the shadowy clouds are asleep,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.566#Huge banks of mist lie absolutely steady
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.567#Where Zeus has set them on the mountain tops.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.568#The Greeks met the Trojans without a tremor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.569#Agamemnon ranged among them, commanding:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.570#"Be men, my friends. Fight with valor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.571#And with a sense of shame before your comrades.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.572#You're less likely to be killed with a sense of shame.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.573#Running away never won glory or a fight."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.574#And with a quick throw of his spear he hit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.575#One of Aeneas' men, Deicoön,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.576#Son of Pergasus, whom the Trojans respected
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.577#As much as Priam's sons, quick as he was
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.578#To fight in the front lines. Agamemnon's spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.579#Hit his shield, which did not stop the bronze point
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.580#From penetrating all the way through
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.581#And into his belly, below his belt. He fell
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.582#With a thud, and his armor clanged.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.583#Then Aeneas killed two of Greece's best,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.584#Crethon and Orsilochus, the sons of Diocles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.585#A man of substance who lived in Pherae
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.586#And was descended from the river Alpheus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.587#Whose broad stream flows through the Pylians' land,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.588#And who begot Ortilochus to rule over many.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.589#This Ortilochus was the father of Diocles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.590#Who had twin sons, Crethon and Orsilochus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.591#Highly trained warriors. They had just reached
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.592#Manhood when they went with the Argives
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.593#On the black ships to Ilion, famed for its horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.594#To win recompense for the sons of Atreus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.595#But death enfolded them both in that land.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.596#Two cubs a mother lion has reared in the mountains,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.597#Where the woods are thick, will begin snatching
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.598#Cattle and sheep from human settlements
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.599#And continue ravaging the flocks for years
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.600#Until humans finally hunt them down.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.601#So these two brothers, beaten to the ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.602#By Aeneas.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.603#They fell like tall fir trees,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.604#And as they fell Menelaus pitied them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.605#He strode through the foremost fighters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.606#Gleaming in his bronze and shaking two spears,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.607#Spurred on by Ares, whose intention was
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.608#That Menelaus go down at Aeneas' hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.609#But Antilochus, Nestor's son, saw him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.610#And strode through the front lines, afraid
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.611#That if anything happened to Menelaus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.612#The Greeks would be robbed of all their hard work.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.613#The two had just squared off, their spears
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.614#Pointed directly at each other, when Antilochus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.615#Took his place right next to Menelaus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.616#Aeneas, quick as he was in battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.617#Did not stay around when he saw the two of them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.618#Standing their ground together. They pulled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.619#The dead brothers back to the Achaean lines
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.620#And put them in their comrades' arms,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.621#Then returned to fight in the foremost ranks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.622#Working as a team, they killed Pylaemenes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.623#The great Paphlagonian commander,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.624#And Mydon his charioteer. Menelaus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.625#Put his spear through Pylaemenes' collarbone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.626#As he stood stock-still. His squire Mydon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.627#Was trying to turn the horses when Antilochus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.628#Hit him with a stone on the elbow. The reins,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.629#White with ivory, fell from his hands to the ground,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.630#And Antilochus jumped him, driving his sword
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.631#Through his temple. He gasped and pitched forward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.632#Landing headfirst in the soft, deep sand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.633#Where he stuck up to his shoulders, feet upright,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.634#And held that position for some time, until
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.635#His horses knocked him over with their hooves.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.636#Antilochus drove them back toward the camp.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.637#Hector saw all this from across the ranks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.638#And charged them with a shout. Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.639#Poured after him in force, led by Ares
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.640#And Enyo in her power, who held in her hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.641#The deafening, shameless horror of War.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.642#Ares cradled an enormous spear in his hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.643#And fell in with Hector, moving ahead of him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.644#Or a pace or two behind. Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.645#Stopped dead in his tracks when he saw him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.646#A man crossing the great plains comes to a river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.647#And is so startled when he sees the water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.648#Churning to the sea that he takes a step backward.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.649#So Diomedes gave ground, and said to his men:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.650#"Well, my friends, we always thought Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.651#Was a good man with a spear, a real fighter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.652#It turns out a god is always at his side,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.653#Ares right now, disguised as a mortal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.654#Keep your face toward the enemy and back up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.655#Steadily. Don't be too eager to fight with gods."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.656#Thus Diomedes, and the Trojans closed in.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.657#Hector killed two men, good fighters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.658#Menesthes and Anchialus, riding together.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.659#As they fell, big Ajax pitied them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.660#And came to stand close by. He threw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.661#His shining spear and hit Amphius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.662#Son of Selagus, a man from Paesus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.663#Who had rich farms there, but Fate led him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.664#To come to the aid of Priam and his sons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.665#Ajax's tree of a spear hit him in the belly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.666#Going right through the belt. He fell heavily,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.667#And Ajax rushed up to strip his armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.668#But was met with a hail of Trojan missiles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.669#Gleaming in the air, many of which
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.670#He collected on his shield. Still, big Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.671#Planted his heel upon the corpse and pulled out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.672#His bronze spear. He was not able, though,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.673#To get the armor unstrapped, pressed as he was
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.674#By the spears, and fearing a pincer movement
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.675#By the numerous and now confident Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.676#Big as Ajax was, they pushed him back,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.677#And he staggered as he gave ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.678#While these struggles were going on,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.679#Fate aroused Tlepolemus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.680#A son of Heracles, tall and handsome,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.681#To go up against godlike Sarpedon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.682#When these two were in range of each other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.683#Son and grandson of Zeus in the clouds,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.684#It was Tlepolemus who was first to speak:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.685#"Well, well, Sarpedon the Lycian.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.686#What are you doing skulking around here?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.687#You wouldn't know what to do in a fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.688#They lie when they say you're a son of Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.689#You don't even come close to the heroes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.690#Who were born from Zeus in the old days---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.691#Like my father, lion-hearted Heracles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.692#Who came here once for Laomedon's mares
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.693#With only six ships and a few men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.694#But sacked Troy and emptied her streets.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.695#You have a coward's heart, and your race is dying.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.696#Your coming from Lycia is not going to help
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.697#The men of Troy. I don't care how strong you are,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.698#You're going through Hades' gates, beaten by me."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.699#And Sarpedon, the Lycian commander:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.700#"Tlepolemus, your father sacked Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.701#Because Laomedon was foolish enough
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.702#To deride the man who had helped him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.703#And withhold the horses he had come so far to get.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.704#As for you, I'm going to work out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.705#A bloody death for you. You're going to give
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.706#Glory to me, and your soul to Hades."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.707#Sarpedon spoke, and Tlepolemus lifted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.708#His ash-wood spear. They both cast at once,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.709#And the spears crossed in flight. Sarpedon's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.710#Hit Tlepolemus full in the neck. The point
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.711#Passed completely, and painfully, through,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.712#And ebony night enfolded his eyes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.713#Tlepolemus' spear hit Sarpedon's left thigh.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.714#The point slashed through with a vengeance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.715#And grazed the bone, but his father saved him, for now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.716#Sarpedon's men carried him out of battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.717#The long spear trailing heavily. In their haste,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.718#No one noticed it or thought to draw it out,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.719#Which would have allowed him to use his legs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.720#It was difficult work tending him at all.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.721#On the other side, the Greeks bore Tlepolemus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.722#Away from the fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.723#Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.724#Saw all this and longed for action.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.725#He debated inwardly whether he should
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.726#Pursue the son of thundering Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.727#Or take instead many Lycian lives.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.728#It was not Odysseus' fate to kill Sarpedon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.729#So Athena focussed his mind on the Lycians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.730#He killed Coeranus, Alastor, and Chromius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.731#Alcandrus, Halius, Noemon, and Prytanis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.732#And he would have killed more, but Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.733#Was quick to see what was going on,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.734#And strode through the foremost fighters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.735#Helmet shining above his flaming bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.736#Bringing terror to the Greeks and joy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.737#To Sarpedon, who groaned as he spoke:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.738#"Son of Priam, don't let me lie here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.739#As prey for the Greeks. Help me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.740#If I must die, let me die in your city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.741#Since I will never return to my own land
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.742#To make glad my wife and infant son."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.743#Hector did not waste any time answering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.744#But sprinted past, helmet glancing in light,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.745#In his passion to drive the Argives back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.746#And kill as many of them as he could.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.747#And godlike Sarpedon was made to sit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.748#Beneath the beautiful oak sacred to Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.749#And Pelagon, his comrade, pulled the spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.750#Out of his thigh. His spirit left him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.751#And a mist poured down over his eyes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.752#Then the North Wind blew upon him, and he
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.753#Breathed again, though he had gasped out his soul.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.754#Under pressure from Ares and Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.755#The Greeks neither turned and made for their ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.756#Nor held their own in the fight, but eased themselves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.757#Backward, now that they knew the Trojans had Ares.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.758#The killing began with certain Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.759#Distinguished as Hector's and Ares' victims:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.760#Godlike Teuthras; Orestes, a horsedriver;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.761#Oenomaus and Trechus, Aetolian spearmen;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.762#Helenus, son of Oenops; and Oresbius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.763#A prosperous Boeotian with a gilded corselet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.764#The havoc continued, and when Hera noticed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.765#That the Greeks were being crushed in battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.766#Her words flew fast to Pallas Athena:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.767#"This is a disaster, daughter of Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.768#Our word to Menelaus that he would go home
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.769#With Troy demolished will come to nothing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.770#If we allow Ares to rage on like this.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.771#Come. It's time we remembered how to fight."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.772#Athena, the grey-eyed goddess, agreed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.773#And Hera, queen of heaven, daughter of Cronus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.774#Got busy harnessing the horses, gold-frontleted,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.775#While Hebe slid the bronze, eight-spoked wheels
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.776#Onto the car's iron axle, wheels with pure gold rims
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.777#Fitted with bronze tires, a stunning sight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.778#And the hubs spinning on both sides were silver.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.779#The car's body was made of gold and silver straps
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.780#Stretched tight, and had a double railing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.781#From it projected a silver pole, and at its end
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.782#Hebe bound the golden yoke, and on that she hung
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.783#The golden harness. Hera led the quick-hooved horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.784#Beneath the yoke, her heart pounding for war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.785#Athena, meanwhile, Zeus' favorite daughter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.786#Let her supple robe slip down to her father's floor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.787#This embroidered garment her own handiwork.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.788#She put on one of cloudy Zeus' tunics
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.789#And strapped on her armor. Around her shoulders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.790#She flung the tasselled aegis, bordered with Rout
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.791#And inset with the blood-chilling horrors of War,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.792#In the center of which was a Gorgon's head,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.793#The dread insignia of Zeus Aegis-Holder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.794#On her head she put a gold helmet, knobbed and horned,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.795#And embossed with a hundred cities' soldiery.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.796#She stepped into the blazing chariot cradling a spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.797#Long and thick enough for heaven's daughter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.798#To level battalions of heroes in her wrath.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.799#Hera quickly flicked the horses with the lash,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.800#And the automatic gates of heaven
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.801#Groaned open, as willed by the Hours,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.802#Who control access to Olympus and heaven,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.803#Opening and shutting the dense cloudbanks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.804#Through this gate they drove the patient horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.805#And found Zeus sitting apart from the other gods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.806#On the highest peak of ridged Olympus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.807#White-armed Hera reined in the horses there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.808#And put her questions to the Most High:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.809#"Father Zeus, doesn't Ares infuriate you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.810#With his reckless destruction of so many Greeks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.811#Much to my sorrow, while Cypris and Apollo,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.812#Smug at their success, are lounging around
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.813#With this mindless bully who knows no law?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.814#Father Zeus, will you be angry with me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.815#If I knock Ares silly and out of the battle?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.816#And Zeus, clouds scudding around him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.817#"Better to put Athena on him;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.818#She's always been the best at giving him grief."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.819#White-armed Hera did not disobey.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.820#She lashed the horses and they flew with a will
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.821#Between the starry heavens and earth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.822#One bound of the gods' horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.823#Takes them as far into the misty distance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.824#As a lookout can see over the wine-blue Aegean.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.825#When they came to Troy and to the confluence
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.826#Of the Scamander and Simois rivers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.827#The white-armed goddess reined in the horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.828#Unyoked them, and shed a thick mist around them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.829#Simois made ambrosia sprout up for them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.830#The two goddesses, though passionate to come
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.831#To the aid of the Greeks, stepped forward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.832#As quietly as doves. They were soon in the thick of things
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.833#Where the army's elite, drawn to Diomedes' strength,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.834#Clustered around him like huge animals, lions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.835#Or razorback hogs that can rip a man apart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.836#Hera took her stance there and transformed herself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.837#To look like Stentor, whose bronze voice sounds as loud
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.838#As fifty voices combined. And she yelled:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.839#"For shame, Greeks! You're all show and no fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.840#When godlike Achilles used to enter battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.841#The Trojans wouldn't so much as leave their gates
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.842#Out of fear for what his spear could do.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.843#Now they have us backed up against our ships."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.844#This got their fighting spirit up. Meanwhile,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.845#Grey-eyed Athena flashed to Diomedes' side.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.846#She found that prince beside his horses and car,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.847#Cooling the wound from Pandarus' arrow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.848#The sweat where his broad shield strap rubbed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.849#Was bothering him, and his arm was sore.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.850#He was lifting the strap and wiping off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.851#The dark, clotted blood when the goddess,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.852#Casually grasping the horses' yoke, said to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.853#"You're not very much like your father, you know.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.854#Tydeus had a small build, but he was a fighter---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.855#Even when I wouldn't allow him to fight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.856#Or show his stuff. Like the time he came to Thebes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.857#As a solo envoy to all those Cadmeians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.858#I ordered him to keep his peace at the banquet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.859#But he had a lot of heart, as he always had,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.860#And challenged the Cadmeian youths and beat them all,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.861#Effortlessly. Of course I was there beside him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.862#But you, I stand by you, I protect you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.863#I tell you not to worry, to fight the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.864#And here you are, either bone-tired
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.865#Or paralyzed with fear. No, you're no son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.866#Of Tydeus or grandson of sharp old Oeneus."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.867#And Diomedes, as tough as they come, answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.868#"I know it's you, goddess, daughter of Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.869#And so I will answer you frankly. No, I'm not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.870#Paralyzed by fear, and I'm not slacking off.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.871#But I am following the orders you gave me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.872#When you told me not to fight face to face
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.873#With any of the gods except Aphrodite.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.874#If she came, you said I could wound her with bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.875#That's why I've withdrawn and given orders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.876#For all of the troops to fall back to this spot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.877#I know that Ares is controlling the battle."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.878#And Athena, whose eyes were as grey as owls:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.879#"Diomedes, son of Tydeus, I do love you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.880#You don't have to fear Ares or any other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.881#Of the immortals. Look who is here beside you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.882#Drive your horses directly at Ares
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.883#And when you're in range, strike.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.884#Don't be in awe of Ares. He's nothing but
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.885#A shifty lout. He promised Hera and me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.886#He would fight against Troy and help the Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.887#Now he's turned Trojan and abandoned us."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.888#With that, she pulled Sthenelus back and pushed him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.889#Off the chariot. Sthenelus went flying,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.890#And Athena got in next to Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.891#Who seemed to glow beside the eager goddess,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.892#And the solid-oak axle groaned under the load
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.893#Of an awesome deity and a hero at his best.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.894#Pallas Athena handled the reins and whip
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.895#And drove the horses directly at Ares,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.896#Who at that moment was stripping the armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.897#From a warrior named Periphas, a huge man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.898#Aetolia's finest and his father's glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.899#Ares was busy removing the dead man's armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.900#And getting smeared with blood. Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.901#Put on Hades' helmet so Ares couldn't see her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.902#But Ares did see Diomedes, and when he did,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.903#He dropped Periphas to lie in his own gore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.904#And headed straight for the hero.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.905#As soon as they were in range of each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.906#Ares leaned out over his horses' backs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.907#And thrust, frantic for a kill. Athena's hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.908#Deflected the spear in mid-air and sent it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.909#Sailing harmlessly over Diomedes' chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.910#And when Diomedes thrust next,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.911#She drove his spear home to the pit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.912#Of Ares' belly, where the kilt-piece covered it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.913#The spearhead sliced right through to the flesh,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.914#And when Diomedes pulled it out,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.915#Ares yelled, so loud you would have thought
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.916#Ten thousand warriors had shouted at once,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.917#And the sound reverberated in the guts of Greeks and Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.918#As if Diomedes had struck not a god in armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.919#But a bronze gong nine miles high.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.920#After a period of heat, when the low clouds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.921#Are massed like wool, you will sometimes see
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.922#A darker clot of air whirling off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.923#On its way to becoming a tornado---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.924#That is how Ares appeared to Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.925#Moving off through the clouds and up the big sky.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.926#He quickly scaled the heights of Olympus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.927#Sat down sulking beside Cronion Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.928#Showed him the immortal blood oozing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.929#From his wound, and whined these winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.930#"Father Zeus, doesn't it infuriate you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.931#To see this violence? We gods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.932#Get the worst of it from each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.933#Whenever we try to help out men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.934#Why did you have to give birth to that madwoman,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.935#Your marauding daughter who is always
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.936#Breaking the rules? All the rest of us gods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.937#Every one on Olympus, listen to you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.938#But she can say or do whatever she wants.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.939#You even urge her on, your grey-eyed girl.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.940#Just now she's been egging on Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.941#To rampage against the immortal gods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.942#He wounded Cypris first, got her on the wrist,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.943#Then charged at me like an avenging spirit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.944#My fast footwork saved me, or I would be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.945#Lying in a heap of gruesome corpses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.946#Or barely alive from taking hits from his spear."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.947#And Zeus, from under thunderhead brows:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.948#"Shifty lout. Don't sit here by me and whine.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.949#You're the most loathsome god on Olympus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.950#You actually like fighting and war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.951#You take after your hardheaded mother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.952#Hera. I can barely control her either.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.953#One way or another, she got you into this.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.954#Be that as it may, I cannot tolerate your being in pain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.955#Your mother did, after all, bear you to me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.956#But if you were born to any other god,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.957#You'd be long buried in hell below the Titans."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.958#And he called Paieon to doctor his wound.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.959#Paieon rubbed on an anodyne to kill the pain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.960#And then,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.961#As quickly as white milk
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.962#Thickened with fig juice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.963#Curdles when stirred,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.964#Paieon healed impetuous Ares.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.965#And Hebe bathed him and dressed him handsomely,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.966#And he sat beside Zeus exulting in glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.967#Then back to the palace of great Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.968#Came Argive Hera and Athena the Protector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:5.969#Having stopped brutal Ares from butchering men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.1#The battle was left to rage on the level expanse
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.2#Between Troy's two rivers. Bronze spearheads
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.3#Drove past each other as the Greek and Trojan armies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.4#Spread like a hemorrhage across the plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.5#Telamonian Ajax, the Achaean wall,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.6#Was the first Greek to break the Trojan line
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.7#And give his comrades some daylight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.8#He killed Thrace's best, Acamas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.9#Son of Eussorus, smashing through the horn
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.10#Of his plumed helmet with his spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.11#And driving through until the bronze tip
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.12#Pierced the forehead's bone. Acamas' eyes went dark.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.13#Diomedes followed up by killing Axylus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.14#Teuthras' son, a most hospitable man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.15#His comfortable home was on the road to Arisbe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.16#And he entertained all travellers, but not one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.17#Came by to meet the enemy before him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.18#And save him from death. Diomedes killed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.19#Not only Axylus but Calesius, his driver,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.20#Two men who would now be covered by earth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.21#Then Euryalus killed Opheltius and Dresus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.22#And went on after Aesepus and Pedasus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.23#Twins whom the naiad Abarbarea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.24#Bore to Bucolion, Laomedon's eldest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.25#Though bastard son. He was with his sheep
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.26#When he made love to the nymph. She conceived,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.27#And bore him the twins whom Euryalus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.28#Now undid. He left their bright bodies naked.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.29#Then Polypoetes killed Astyalus;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.30#Odysseus got Pidytes with his spear;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.31#And Teucer took out Aretaon, a good man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.32#Nestor's son Antilochus killed Ablerus;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.33#The warlord Agamemnon killed Elatus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.34#Who lived in steep Pedasus on the Satnioeis;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.35#Leitus killed Phylacus as he fled;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.36#And Eurypylus unmanned Melanthius.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.37#But Menelaus took Adrastus alive.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.38#Adrastus' terrified horses became entangled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.39#In a tamarisk as they galloped across the plain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.40#And, breaking the pole near the car's rim,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.41#Bolted toward the city with the others.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.42#Their master rolled from the car by the wheel
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.43#And fell face-first into the dust. Menelaus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.44#Came up to him with his long-shadowed spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.45#And Adrastus clasped his knees and prayed:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.46#"Take me alive, son of Atreus, and accept
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.47#A worthy ransom from the treasure stored
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.48#In my father's palace, bronze, gold, wrought iron.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.49#My father would lavish it all on you if he heard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.50#I was still alive among the Achaean ships."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.51#The speech had its intended effect.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.52#Menelaus was about to hand him over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.53#To be led back to the ships, but Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.54#Came running over to call him on it:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.55#"Going soft, Menelaus? What does this man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.56#Mean to you? Have the Trojans ever shown you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.57#Any hospitality? Not one of them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.58#Escapes sheer death at our hands, not even
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.59#The boy who is still in his mother's womb.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.60#Every Trojan dies, unmourned and unmarked."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.61#And so the hero changed his brother's mind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.62#By reminding him of the ways of conduct and fate.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.63#Menelaus shoved Adrastus aside,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.64#And Agamemnon stabbed him in the flank.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.65#He fell backward, and the son of Atreus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.66#Braced his heel on his chest and pulled out the spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.67#Then Nestor shouted and called to the Greeks:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.68#"Soldiers of Greece, no lagging behind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.69#To strip off armor from the enemy corpses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.70#To see who comes back to the ships with the most.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.71#Now we kill men! You will have plenty of time later
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.72#To despoil the Trojan dead on the plain."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.73#Nestor's speech worked them up to a frenzy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.74#And the Trojans would have been beaten
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.75#Back to Ilion by superior force
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.76#Had not Helenus, Priam's son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.77#And Troy's prophet, approached Aeneas and Hector:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.78#"Aeneas and Hector, the Trojans and Lycians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.79#Are counting on you. You two are the leaders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.80#In every initiative in council and battle---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.81#So make a stand here. Go through the ranks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.82#And keep our men back from the gates,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.83#Before they run through them and fall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.84#Into their women's arms, making our enemies laugh.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.85#Once you have bolstered our troops' morale,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.86#We will stand our ground and fight the Danaans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.87#Tired as we are. We have our backs to the wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.88#Hector, go into the city and find our mother.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.89#Tell her to take a company of old women
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.90#To the temple of Athena on the acropolis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.91#With the largest and loveliest robe in her house,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.92#The one that is dearest of all to her,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.93#And place it on the knees of braided Athena,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.94#And promise twelve heifers to her in her temple,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.95#Unblemished yearlings, if she will pity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.96#The town of Troy, its wives and its children,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.97#And if she will keep from holy Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.98#Wild Diomedes, who is raging with his spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.99#I think he's the strongest of all the Achaeans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.100#We never even feared Achilles like this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.101#And they say he is half-divine. But this man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.102#Won't stop at anything. No one can match him."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.103#Hector took his brother's advice.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.104#He jumped down from his chariot with his gear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.105#And toured the ranks, a spear in each hand.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.106#He urged them on, and with a trembling roar
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.107#The Trojans turned to face the Achaeans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.108#The Greeks pulled back. It looked to them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.109#As if some god had come from the starry sky
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.110#To help the Trojans. It had been a sudden rally.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.111#Hector shouted and called to the Trojans:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.112#"Soldiers of Troy, and illustrious allies,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.113#Remember to fight like the men that you are,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.114#While I go to the city and ask the elders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.115#Who sit in council, and our wives, to pray
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.116#To the gods and promise bulls by the hundred."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.117#And Hector left, helmet collecting light
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.118#Above the black-hide shield whose rim tapped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.119#His ankles and neck with each step he took.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.120#Then Glaucus, son of Hippolochus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.121#Met Diomedes in no-man's-land.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.122#Both were eager to fight, but first Tydeus' son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.123#Made his voice heard above the battle noise:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.124#"And which mortal hero are you? I've never seen you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.125#Out here before on the fields of glory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.126#And now here you are ahead of everyone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.127#Ready to face my spear. Pretty bold.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.128#I feel sorry for your parents. Of course,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.129#You may be an immortal, down from heaven.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.130#Far be it from me to fight an immortal god.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.131#Not even mighty Lycurgus lived long
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.132#After he tangled with the immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.133#Driving the nurses of Dionysus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.134#Down over the Mountain of Nysa
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.135#And making them drop their wands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.136#As he beat them with an ox-goad. Dionysus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.137#Was terrified and plunged into the sea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.138#Where Thetis received him into her bosom,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.139#Trembling with fear at the human's threats.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.140#Then the gods, who live easy, grew angry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.141#With Lycurgus, and the Son of Cronus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.142#Made him go blind, and he did not live long,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.143#Hated as he was by the immortal gods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.144#No, I wouldn't want to fight an immortal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.145#But if you are human, and shed blood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.146#Step right up for a quick end to your life."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.147#And Glaucus, Hippolochus' son:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.148#"Great son of Tydeus, why ask about my lineage?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.149#Human generations are like leaves in their seasons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.150#The wind blows them to the ground, but the tree
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.151#Sprouts new ones when spring comes again.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.152#Men too. Their generations come and go.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.153#But if you really do want to hear my story,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.154#You're welcome to listen. Many men know it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.155#Ephyra, in the heart of Argive horse country,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.156#Was home to Sisyphus, the shrewdest man alive,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.157#Sisyphus son of Aeolus. He had a son, Glaucus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.158#Who was the father of faultless Bellerophon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.159#A man of grace and courage by gift of the gods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.160#But Proetus, whom Zeus had made king of Argos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.161#Came to hate Bellerophon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.162#And drove him out. It happened this way.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.163#Proetus' wife, the beautiful Anteia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.164#Was madly in love with Bellerophon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.165#And wanted to have him in her bed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.166#But she couldn't persuade him, not at all,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.167#Because he was so virtuous and wise.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.168#So she made up lies and spoke to the king:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.169#'Either die yourself, Proetus, or kill Bellerophon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.170#He wanted to sleep with me against my will.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.171#The king was furious when he heard her say this.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.172#He did not kill him---he had scruples about that---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.173#But he sent him to Lycia with a folding tablet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.174#On which he had scratched many evil signs,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.175#And told him to give it to Anteia's father,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.176#To get him killed. So off he went to Lycia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.177#With an immortal escort, and when he reached
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.178#The river Xanthus, the king there welcomed him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.179#And honored him with entertainment
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.180#For nine solid days, killing an ox each day.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.181#But when the tenth dawn spread her rosy light,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.182#He questioned him and asked to see the tokens
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.183#He brought from Proetus, his daughter's husband.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.184#And when he saw the evil tokens from Proetus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.185#He ordered him, first, to kill the Chimaera,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.186#A raging monster, divine, inhuman---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.187#A lion in the front, a serpent in the rear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.188#In the middle a goat---and breathing fire.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.189#Bellerophon killed her, trusting signs from the gods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.190#Next he had to fight the glorious Solymi,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.191#The hardest battle, he said, he ever fought,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.192#And, third, the Amazons, women the peers of men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.193#As he journeyed back the king wove another wile.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.194#He chose the best men in all wide Lycia
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.195#And laid an ambush. Not one returned home;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.196#Blameless Bellerophon killed them all.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.197#When the king realized his guest had divine blood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.198#He kept him there and gave him his daughter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.199#And half of all his royal honor. Moreover,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.200#The Lycians cut out for him a superb
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.201#Tract of land, plow-land and orchard.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.202#His wife, the princess, bore him three children,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.203#Isander, Hippolochus, and Laodameia.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.204#Zeus in his wisdom slept with Laodameia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.205#And she bore him the godlike warrior Sarpedon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.206#But even Bellerophon lost the gods' favor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.207#And went wandering alone over the Aleian plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.208#His son Isander was slain by Ares
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.209#As he fought against the glorious Solymi,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.210#And his daughter was killed by Artemis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.211#Of the golden reins. But Hippolochus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.212#Bore me, and I am proud he is my father.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.213#He sent me to Troy with strict instructions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.214#To be the best ever, better than all the rest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.215#And not to bring shame on the race of my fathers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.216#The noblest men in Ephyra and Lycia.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.217#This, I am proud to say, is my lineage."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.218#Diomedes grinned when he heard all this.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.219#He planted his spear in the bounteous earth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.220#And spoke gently to the Lycian prince:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.221#"We have old ties of hospitality!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.222#My grandfather Oeneus long ago
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.223#Entertained Bellerophon in his halls
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.224#For twenty days, and they gave each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.225#Gifts of friendship. Oeneus gave
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.226#A belt bright with scarlet, and Bellerophon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.227#A golden cup, which I left at home.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.228#I don't remember my father Tydeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.229#Since I was very small when he left for Thebes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.230#In the war that killed so many Achaeans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.231#But that makes me your friend and you my guest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.232#If ever you come to Argos, as you are my friend
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.233#And I your guest whenever I travel to Lycia.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.234#So we can't cross spears with each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.235#Even in the thick of battle. There are enough
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.236#Trojans and allies for me to kill, whomever
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.237#A god gives me and I can run down myself.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.238#And enough Greeks for you to kill as you can.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.239#And let's exchange armor, so everyone will know
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.240#That we are friends from our fathers' days."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.241#With this said, they vaulted from their chariots,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.242#Clasped hands, and pledged their friendship.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.243#But Zeus took away Glaucus' good sense,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.244#For he exchanged his golden armor for bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.245#The worth of one hundred oxen for nine.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.246#When Hector reached the oak tree by the Western Gate,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.247#Trojan wives and daughters ran up to him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.248#Asking about their children, their brothers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.249#Their kinsmen, their husbands. He told them all,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.250#Each woman in turn, to pray to the gods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.251#Sorrow clung to their heads like mist.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.252#Then he came to Priam's palace, a beautiful
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.253#Building made of polished stone with a central courtyard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.254#Flanked by porticoes, upon which opened fifty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.255#Adjoining rooms, where Priam's sons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.256#Slept with their wives. Across the court
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.257#A suite of twelve more bedrooms housed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.258#His modest daughters and their husbands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.259#It was here that Hector's mother met him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.260#A gracious woman, with Laodice,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.261#Her most beautiful daughter, in tow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.262#Hecuba took his hand in hers and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.263#"Hector, my son, why have you left the war
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.264#And come here? Are those abominable Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.265#Wearing you down in the fighting outside,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.266#And does your heart lead you to our acropolis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.267#To stretch your hands upward to Zeus?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.268#But stay here while I get you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.269#Some honey-sweet wine, so you can pour a libation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.270#To Father Zeus first and the other immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.271#Then enjoy some yourself, if you will drink.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.272#Wine greatly bolsters a weary man's spirits,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.273#And you are weary from defending your kinsmen."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.274#Sunlight shimmered on great Hector's helmet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.275#"Mother, don't offer me any wine.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.276#It would drain the power out of my limbs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.277#I have too much reverence to pour a libation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.278#With unwashed hands to Zeus almighty,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.279#Or to pray to Cronion in the black cloudbanks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.280#Spattered with blood and the filth of battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.281#But you must go to the War Goddess's temple
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.282#To make sacrifice with a band of old women.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.283#Choose the largest and loveliest robe in the house,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.284#The one that is dearest of all to you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.285#And place it on the knees of braided Athena.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.286#And promise twelve heifers to her in her temple,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.287#Unblemished yearlings, if she will pity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.288#The town of Troy, its wives, and its children,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.289#And if she will keep from holy Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.290#Wild Diomedes, who's raging with his spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.291#Go then to the temple of Athena the War Goddess,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.292#And I will go over to summon Paris,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.293#If he will listen to what I have to say.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.294#I wish the earth would gape open beneath him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.295#Olympian Zeus has bred him as a curse
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.296#To Troy, to Priam, and all Priam's children.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.297#If I could see him dead and gone to Hades,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.298#I think my heart might be eased of its sorrow."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.299#Thus Hector. Hecuba went to the great hall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.300#And called to her handmaidens, and they
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.301#Gathered together the city's old women.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.302#She went herself to a fragrant storeroom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.303#Which held her robes, the exquisite work
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.304#Of Sidonian women whom godlike Paris
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.305#Brought from Phoenicia when he sailed the sea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.306#On the voyage he made for high-born Helen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.307#Hecuba chose the robe that lay at the bottom,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.308#The most beautiful of all, woven of starlight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.309#And bore it away as a gift for Athena.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.310#A stream of old women followed behind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.311#They came to the temple of Pallas Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.312#On the city's high rock, and the doors were opened
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.313#By fair-cheeked Theano, daughter of Cisseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.314#And wife of Antenor, breaker of horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.315#The Trojans had made her Athena's priestess.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.316#With ritual cries they all lifted their hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.317#To Pallas Athena. Theano took the robe
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.318#And laid it on the knees of the rich-haired goddess,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.319#Then prayed in supplication to Zeus' daughter:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.320#"Lady Athena who defends our city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.321#Brightest of goddesses, hear our prayer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.322#Break now the spear of Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.323#And grant that he fall before the Western Gate,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.324#That we may now offer twelve heifers in this temple,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.325#Unblemished yearlings. Only do thou pity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.326#The town of Troy, its wives and its children."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.327#But Pallas Athena denied her prayer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.328#While they prayed to great Zeus' daughter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.329#Hector came to Paris' beautiful house,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.330#Which he had built himself with the aid
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.331#Of the best craftsmen in all wide Troy:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.332#Sleeping quarters, a hall, and a central courtyard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.333#Near to Priam's and Hector's on the city's high rock.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.334#Hector entered, Zeus' light upon him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.335#A spear sixteen feet long cradled in his hand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.336#The bronze point gleaming, and the ferrule gold.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.337#He found Paris in the bedroom, busy with his weapons,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.338#Fondling his curved bow, his fine shield, and breastplate.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.339#Helen of Argos sat with her household women
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.340#Directing their exquisite handicraft.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.341#Hector meant to shame Paris and provoke him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.342#"This is a fine time to be nursing your anger,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.343#You idiot! We're dying out there defending the walls.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.344#It's because of you the city is in this hellish war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.345#If you saw someone else holding back from combat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.346#You'd pick a fight with him yourself. Now get up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.347#Before the whole city goes up in flames!"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.348#And Paris, handsome as a god:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.349#"That's no more than just, Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.350#But listen now to what I have to say.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.351#It's not out of anger or spite toward the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.352#I've been here in my room. I only wanted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.353#To recover from my pain. My wife was just now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.354#Encouraging me to get up and fight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.355#And that seems the better thing to do.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.356#Victory takes turns with men. Wait for me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.357#While I put on my armor, or go on ahead---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.358#I'm pretty sure I'll catch up with you."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.359#To which Hector said nothing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.360#But Helen said to him softly:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.361#"Brother-in-law
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.362#Of a scheming, cold-blooded bitch,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.363#I wish that on the day my mother bore me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.364#A windstorm had swept me away to a mountain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.365#Or into the waves of the restless sea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.366#Swept me away before all this could happen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.367#But since the gods have ordained these evils,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.368#Why couldn't I be the wife of a better man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.369#One sensitive at least to repeated reproaches?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.370#Paris has never had an ounce of good sense
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.371#And never will. He'll pay for it someday.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.372#But come inside and sit down on this chair,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.373#Dear brother-in-law. You bear such a burden
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.374#For my wanton ways and Paris' witlessness.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.375#Zeus has placed this evil fate on us so that
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.376#In time to come poets will sing of us."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.377#And Hector, in his burnished helmet:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.378#"Don't ask me to sit, Helen, even though
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.379#You love me. You will never persuade me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.380#My heart is out there with our fighting men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.381#They already feel my absence from battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.382#Just get Paris moving, and have him hurry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.383#So he can catch up with me while I'm still
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.384#Inside the city. I'm going to my house now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.385#To see my family, my wife and my boy. I don't know
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.386#Whether I'll ever be back to see them again, or if
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.387#The gods will destroy me at the hands of the Greeks."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.388#And Hector turned and left. He came to his house
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.389#But did not find white-armed Andromache there.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.390#She had taken the child and a robed attendant
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.391#And stood on the tower, lamenting and weeping---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.392#His blameless wife. When Hector didn't find her inside,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.393#He paused on his way out and called to the servants:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.394#"Can any of you women tell me exactly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.395#Where Andromache went when she left the house?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.396#To one of my sisters or one of my brothers' wives?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.397#Or to the temple of Athena along with the other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.398#Trojan women to beseech the dread goddess?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.399#The spry old housekeeper answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.400#"Hector, if you want the exact truth, she didn't go
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.401#To any of your sisters, or any of your brothers' wives,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.402#Or to the temple of Athena along with the other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.403#Trojan women to beseech the dread goddess.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.404#She went to Ilion's great tower, because she heard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.405#The Trojans were pressed and the Greeks were strong.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.406#She ran off to the wall like a madwoman,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.407#And the nurse went with her, carrying the child."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.408#Thus the housekeeper, but Hector was gone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.409#Retracing his steps through the stone and tile streets
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.410#Of the great city, until he came to the Western Gate.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.411#He was passing through it out onto the plain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.412#When his wife came running up to meet him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.413#His beautiful wife, Andromache,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.414#A gracious woman, daughter of great
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.415#Eëtion, Eëtion, who lived in the forests of Plakos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.416#And ruled the Cilicians from Thebes-under-Plakos---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.417#His daughter was wed to bronze-helmeted Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.418#She came up to him now, and the nurse with her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.419#Held to her bosom their baby boy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.420#Hector's beloved son, beautiful as starlight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.421#Whom Hector had named Scamandrius
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.422#But everyone else called Astyanax, Lord of the City,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.423#For Hector alone could save Ilion now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.424#He looked at his son and smiled in silence.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.425#Andromache stood close to him, shedding tears,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.426#Clinging to his arm as she spoke these words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.427#"Possessed is what you are, Hector. Your courage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.428#Is going to kill you, and you have no feeling left
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.429#For your little boy or for me, the luckless woman
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.430#Who will soon be your widow. It won't be long
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.431#Before the whole Greek army swarms and kills you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.432#And when they do, it will be better for me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.433#To sink into the earth. When I lose you, Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.434#There will be nothing left, no one to turn to,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.435#Only pain. My father and mother are dead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.436#Achilles killed my father when he destroyed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.437#Our city, Thebes with its high gates,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.438#But had too much respect to despoil his body.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.439#He burned it instead with all his armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.440#And heaped up a barrow. And the spirit women
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.441#Came down from the mountain, daughters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.442#Of the storm god, and planted elm trees around it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.443#I had seven brothers once in that great house.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.444#All seven went down to Hades on a single day,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.445#Cut down by Achilles in one blinding sprint
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.446#Through their shambling cattle and silver sheep.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.447#Mother, who was queen in the forests of Plakos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.448#He took back as prisoner, with all her possessions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.449#Then released her for a fortune in ransom.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.450#She died in our house, shot by Artemis' arrows.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.451#Hector, you are my father, you are my mother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.452#You are my brother and my blossoming husband.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.453#But show some pity and stay here by the tower,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.454#Don't make your child an orphan, your wife a widow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.455#Station your men here by the fig tree, where the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.456#Is weakest because the wall can be scaled.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.457#Three times their elite have tried an attack here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.458#Rallying around Ajax or glorious Idomeneus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.459#Or Atreus' sons or mighty Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.460#Whether someone in on the prophecy told them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.461#Or they are driven here by something in their heart."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.462#And great Hector, helmet shining, answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.463#"Yes, Andromache, I worry about all this myself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.464#But my shame before the Trojans and their wives,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.465#With their long robes trailing, would be too terrible
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.466#If I hung back from battle like a coward.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.467#And my heart won't let me. I have learned to be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.468#One of the best, to fight in Troy's first ranks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.469#Defending my father's honor and my own.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.470#Deep in my heart I know too well
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.471#There will come a day when holy Ilion will perish,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.472#And Priam and the people under Priam's ash spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.473#But the pain I will feel for the Trojans then,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.474#For Hecuba herself and for Priam king,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.475#For my many fine brothers who will have by then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.476#Fallen in the dust behind enemy lines---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.477#All that pain is nothing to what I will feel
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.478#For you, when some bronze-armored Greek
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.479#Leads you away in tears, on your first day of slavery.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.480#And you will work some other woman's loom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.481#In Argos or carry water from a Spartan spring,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.482#All against your will, under great duress.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.483#And someone, seeing you crying, will say,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.484#'That is the wife of Hector, the best of all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.485#The Trojans when they fought around Ilion.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.486#Someday someone will say that, renewing your pain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.487#At having lost such a man to fight off the day
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.488#Of your enslavement. But may I be dead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.489#And the earth heaped up above me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.490#Before I hear your cry as you are dragged away."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.491#With these words, resplendent Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.492#Reached for his child, who shrank back screaming
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.493#Into his nurse's bosom, terrified of his father's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.494#Bronze-encased face and the horsehair plume
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.495#He saw nodding down from the helmet's crest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.496#This forced a laugh from his father and mother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.497#And Hector removed the helmet from his head
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.498#And set it on the ground all shimmering with light.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.499#Then he kissed his dear son and swung him up gently
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.500#And said a prayer to Zeus and the other immortals:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.501#"Zeus and all gods: grant that this my son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.502#Become, as I am, foremost among Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.503#Brave and strong, and ruling Ilion with might.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.504#And may men say he is far better than his father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.505#When he returns from war, bearing bloody spoils,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.506#Having killed his man. And may his mother rejoice."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.507#And he put his son in the arms of his wife,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.508#And she enfolded him in her fragrant bosom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.509#Laughing through her tears. Hector pitied her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.510#And stroked her with his hand and said to her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.511#"You worry too much about me, Andromache.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.512#No one is going to send me to Hades before my time,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.513#And no man has ever escaped his fate, rich or poor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.514#Coward or hero, once born into this world.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.515#Go back to the house now and take care of your work,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.516#The loom and the shuttle, and tell the servants
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.517#To get on with their jobs. War is the work of men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.518#Of all the Trojan men, and mine especially."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.519#With these words, Hector picked up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.520#His plumed helmet, and his wife went back home,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.521#Turning around often, her cheeks flowered with tears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.522#When she came to the house of man-slaying Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.523#She found a throng of servants inside,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.524#And raised among these women the ritual lament.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.525#And so they mourned for Hector in his house
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.526#Although he was still alive, for they did not think
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.527#He would ever again come back from the war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.528#Or escape the murderous hands of the Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.529#Paris meanwhile
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.530#Did not dally long in his high halls.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.531#He put on his magnificent bronze-inlaid gear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.532#And sprinted with assurance out through the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.533#Picture a horse that has fed on barley in his stall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.534#Breaking his halter and galloping across the plain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.535#Making for his accustomed swim in the river,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.536#A glorious animal, head held high, mane streaming
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.537#Like wind on his shoulders. Sure of his splendor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.538#He prances by the horse-runs and the mares in pasture.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.539#That was how Paris, son of Priam, came down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.540#From the high rock of Pergamum,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.541#Gleaming like amber and laughing in his armor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.542#And his feet were fast.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.543#He caught up quickly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.544#With Hector just as he turned from the spot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.545#Where he'd talked with his wife, and called out:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.546#"Well, dear brother, have I delayed you too much?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.547#Am I not here in time, just as you asked?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.548#Hector turned, his helmet flashing light:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.549#"I don't understand you, Paris.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.550#No one could slight your work in battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.551#You're a strong fighter, but you slack off---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.552#You don't have the will. It breaks my heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.553#To hear what the Trojans say about you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.554#It's on your account they have all this trouble.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.555#Come on, let's go. We can settle this later,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.556#If Zeus ever allows us to offer in our halls
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.557#The wine bowl of freedom to the gods above,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:6.558#After we drive these bronze-kneed Greeks from Troy."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.1#Hector rushed through the gates,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.2#And his brother Paris came with him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.3#Their hearts eager for battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.4#Zeus sometimes gives a tailwind to sailors
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.5#At just the moment their arms and legs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.6#Can push no more their polished firwood oars.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.7#So these two appeared to the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.8#Each took out his man, Paris killing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.9#Menesthius, son of ox-eyed Phylomedousa
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.10#And Areithous, whose iron mace ruled Arne.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.11#Hector's spearblade sliced Eioneus' neck
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.12#Beneath his bronze helmet; his limbs went limp.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.13#Elsewhere in the crush of battle, Glaucus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.14#Son of Hippolochus and Lycian commander,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.15#Hit Iphinous on the shoulder with his spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.16#As he clambered up behind his racing mares.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.17#He fell from his chariot and his limbs went slack.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.18#Athena's grey eyes had all this in focus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.19#And when she saw the Greeks being beaten
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.20#She swooped down from the peaks of Olympus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.21#To sacred Ilion. Apollo,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.22#Who wanted victory for the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.23#Saw her coming as he watched from his lookout
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.24#On Pergamum, and he rose up to meet her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.25#They met by the ancient oak tree.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.26#Lord Apollo, Zeus' son, spoke first:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.27#"Daughter of great Zeus, why have you come
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.28#Again from Olympus? What mission are you on now?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.29#Is it to turn the tide of battle for the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.30#Since you have no pity for the Trojans' losses?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.31#I have a better idea. Let's halt the bloodshed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.32#For today. They can fight later
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.33#With Ilion on the line, since you deathless ones
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.34#Have your hearts set on destroying this city."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.35#And the grey-eyed goddess Athena replied:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.36#"So be it, Apollo. This is just what I had in mind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.37#In coming from Olympus to the Trojans and Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.38#But how do you intend to stop them from fighting?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.39#Lord Apollo, son of Zeus, replied:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.40#"We could rouse the hard spirit of Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.41#And have him challenge one of the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.42#To fight against him, man to man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.43#The Greeks would be indignant and rouse someone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.44#To battle Hector in single combat."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.45#Grey-eyed Athena agreed to his plan.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.46#And Helenus, Troy's seer and Priam's son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.47#Understood in his heart what these gods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.48#Had agreed to. He went up to Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.49#And spoke to him in convincing tones:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.50#"Hector, son of Priam, Zeus' equal in wisdom,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.51#Will you listen to me? I am your brother.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.52#Have all the Greeks and Trojans sit down.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.53#Challenge the best of the Greeks to fight you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.54#Man to man in single combat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.55#It is not your fate to meet your end now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.56#Thus I have heard from the gods eternal."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.57#Thus Helenus, and Hector was persuaded.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.58#He went out in front along the Trojan ranks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.59#Holding a spear broadside, and they all sat down.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.60#Agamemnon had his Greeks sit down,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.61#And Athena and silver-bowed Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.62#Sat like vultures in Zeus' tall oak
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.63#Enjoying the warriors, who sat rank on rank,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.64#Bristling with shields, helmets, and spears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.65#As a fresh blast of the West Wind ripples
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.66#The sea, and the sea blackens beneath it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.67#So sat the ranks of Trojans and Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.68#Across the plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.69#And Hector spoke to them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.70#"Hear me out, Trojans, and Achaean warriors,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.71#Until I have spoken what my heart commands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.72#Zeus on high has made our oaths nothing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.73#Hostile to both sides, he means for us to fight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.74#Until you either take the towers of Troy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.75#Or are beaten down beside your seafaring ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.76#There are among you the best of all Greece.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.77#If any of you have the will to fight me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.78#None other than Hector, come forward now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.79#I declare these terms, with Zeus as my witness:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.80#If your champion cuts me down with bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.81#He can strip my armor and take it back to your ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.82#My body, though, he will return to my home
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.83#To be burned in honor by Trojans and their wives.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.84#If I kill him, if Apollo gives me that glory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.85#I will take his armor to holy Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.86#And hang it in the temple of the Archer God.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.87#The corpse I will send back to your hollow ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.88#So you long-haired Achaeans can give it burial
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.89#And heap up a tomb by the broad Hellespont.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.90#So someone in generations yet to come
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.91#Will say as he sails by on the darkening sea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.92#'That is the tomb of a man long dead,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.93#Killed in his prime by glorious Hector.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.94#Someone will say that, and my fame will not die."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.95#So he spoke, and they were all hushed and silent,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.96#Ashamed to refuse and afraid to accept.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.97#Finally, Menelaus stood up. He was groaning inwardly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.98#But spoke to them in contemptuous tones:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.99#"It seems we're good at threatening the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.100#But when it comes down to it we're women, not men!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.101#This day will go down in infamy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.102#If no Danaan meets Hector's challenge now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.103#May you all turn to mud, sitting here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.104#Without any guts and no call to glory!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.105#I'll put on armor myself. Win or lose,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.106#It's all in the hands of the immortal gods."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.107#And with that he put on his armor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.108#And yes, Menelaus, your life would have
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.109#Flickered out then in Hector's palms,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.110#Because he was far stronger, had not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.111#The Achaean commanders run up and grabbed you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.112#Agamemnon too, the great warlord,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.113#Holding you back with his right hand, saying:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.114#"Have you lost your royal mind, Menelaus?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.115#There's no call for you to behave like this.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.116#Get hold of yourself. You don't volunteer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.117#In the spirit of rivalry to fight someone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.118#You're no match for. This is Priam's son Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.119#We're talking about. Everyone fears him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.120#Even Achilles tightens up at the thought
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.121#Of facing him in battle, and he's far better than you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.122#Just sit down here with your troops now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.123#The Achaeans will come up with another champion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.124#And even if he's a fearless glutton for combat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.125#He'll be glad to bend his knees and rest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.126#If he ever gets out of this one alive."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.127#Agamemnon said all the right things
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.128#And changed his brother's mind. Relieved,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.129#Menelaus' aides took off his armor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.130#Then Nestor stood up and spoke:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.131#"It's a sad day for Greece, a sad day.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.132#Old Peleus the charioteer would groan,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.133#The Myrmidons' great counsellor and king
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.134#Who questioned me once in his house
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.135#And revelled in all our heroic lineages.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.136#If he were to hear of all these men cowering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.137#Before Hector, he would lift his hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.138#To the immortal gods and pray for his soul
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.139#To leave his body and sink into Hades.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.140#O Father Zeus and Athena and Apollo,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.141#If only I were young again, as in the days
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.142#The Pylians and spear-mad Arcadians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.143#Gathered near the rushing Celadon and fought
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.144#Under Pheia's walls by the streams of Iardanus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.145#On their side Ereuthalion, a man like a god,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.146#Stood forth as champion, wearing the armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.147#Of King Areithous, the mace-man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.148#As men and satin-waisted women called him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.149#Because he fought with neither bow nor spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.150#But broke battalions with his iron mace.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.151#Well, Lycurgus killed him, by guile, not strength,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.152#In a narrow pass where his mace of iron
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.153#Did him no good. Before he could react
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.154#Lycurgus skewered him with his spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.155#Down he went, and Lycurgus stripped from him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.156#The armor he had gotten from bronze Ares,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.157#And he wore that armor whenever he went to war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.158#And when Lycurgus was an old man in his halls
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.159#He gave it to Ereuthalion, who had been his squire.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.160#Wearing that armor he challenged all our best.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.161#They all trembled with fear. No one dared
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.162#But me---my heart pumped me up for battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.163#Although I was the youngest of them all.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.164#And so we fought, and Athena gave me glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.165#That was the tallest and strongest man I've ever killed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.166#An enormous hulk sprawled out on the ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.167#If I were as young now and my strength still firm,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.168#Helmeted Hector would have a fight on his hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.169#But now here you are, the best of the Achaeans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.170#And not one is ready to face off with this Trojan."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.171#The old man scolded them, and nine stood up.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.172#First up was the warlord Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.173#Followed by Tydeus' son Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.174#And the two Ajaxes, clothed in fury.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.175#Next were Idomeneus and his companion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.176#Meriones, who weighed in like Ares,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.177#And Eurypylus, Euaemon's fine son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.178#And up rose Thoas, and brilliant Odysseus---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.179#All of them willing to do battle with Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.180#Then the horseman Nestor spoke out again:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.181#"Now cast lots to see who will be chosen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.182#Whoever it is will enrich the Achaeans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.183#And enrich his own heart, if he gets out alive
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.184#From the grim business of bloody combat."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.185#He spoke, and each man marked his lot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.186#And cast it into Agamemnon's helmet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.187#Hands lifted to the gods, the troops said their prayers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.188#Someone would say with a glance at the sky:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.189#"Let it be Ajax, Father Zeus, or Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.190#Or the king of golden Mycenae himself."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.191#Nestor shook the helmet, and out jumped the lot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.192#Of the man they all wanted. It was Ajax's.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.193#A herald took it down the line from left to right
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.194#And showed it to each of the Achaean elite.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.195#They all disclaimed it until he came to Ajax,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.196#Who held out his hand. The herald gave him the lot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.197#When Ajax saw it was his, he smiled inwardly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.198#And threw it on the ground by his foot and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.199#"My friends, the lot is mine, and I'm glad of it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.200#Because I think I'm going to beat Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.201#But listen. While I am putting on my battle gear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.202#Pray to Lord Zeus, the son of Cronus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.203#Silently to yourselves, so the Trojans won't hear---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.204#Or pray openly, since there is no one we fear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.205#No one can drive me off against my will
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.206#By force or skill. I was born and bred
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.207#In Salamis, and I know I am no fool."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.208#Thus Ajax. You could hear the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.209#Saying their prayers to Lord Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.210#Eyes lifted up to broad, flat sky:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.211#"Father Zeus on Ida above,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.212#Grant the splendor of victory to Ajax,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.213#But if you love Hector and care for him too,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.214#Vouchsafe to both equal power and glory."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.215#While they prayed, Ajax was clapping on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.216#Gleaming bronze armor, and when every inch
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.217#Of his skin was covered he hustled forward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.218#Like the giant God of War himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.219#When he enters a soul-devouring battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.220#That men have joined but Zeus has ordained.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.221#Ajax was that big, a human barricade, a Greek wall,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.222#The gristle that was his face arranged in a smile,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.223#And with every huge stride the long shadow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.224#Of his spear sagged and quivered. The Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.225#Liked what they saw, but the Trojans trembled,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.226#And Hector felt his heart pounding in his chest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.227#It was impossible for him, though, to melt back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.228#Into the ranks: he had issued the challenge.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.229#Ajax kept coming, holding a shield that was like
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.230#A city tower, seven folds of oxhide
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.231#Mastered with bronze, the work of Tychius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.232#Whose shop was in Hyle, the best leather worker
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.233#On earth, who had made this shimmering shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.234#From seven tough hides and an eighth layer of bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.235#Telamonian Ajax held it in front of his chest now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.236#And put his face in Hector's as he said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.237#"Take a good look, Hector. This is what
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.238#The heroes are like in the Greek army
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.239#Even when Achilles isn't here smashing skulls.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.240#He's back there with the ships now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.241#Nursing his grudge against Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.242#But we still have a few good men to fight you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.243#More than a few. It's your move."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.244#Hector's helmet gathered the fading light:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.245#"Telamonian Ajax. Zeus-born. The Captain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.246#Don't try to unnerve me, as if I were
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.247#Some kid, or a woman who wouldn't know
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.248#One end of a spear from another.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.249#I've been in a few battles and killed a few men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.250#And I know a few moves. I can go with this shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.251#To the right or the left, dodge through charging horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.252#Or fight hand to hand with fancy footwork.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.253#But I'm not going to try anything fancy on you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.254#I'm going to hit you straight on, if my aim is good."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.255#The taunts were over. Hector carefully
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.256#Balanced his spear, and when he threw it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.257#Its long shadow swept over the earth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.258#And it bored through the bronze skin
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.259#Of Ajax's shield and through six oxhide layers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.260#But the seventh layer of leather stopped it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.261#It was Ajax's turn now. His long-shadowed spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.262#Crashed through the round of Hector's shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.263#And ripped into the intricate breastplate,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.264#The point shearing his shirt and nicking his ribs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.265#As Hector twisted aside from black fatality.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.266#They wrenched their spears back out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.267#And went at each other again,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.268#like lions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.269#After raw meat, or wild boars in rut.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.270#Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.271#Stabbed his spear dead center into Ajax's shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.272#But the bronze point crumpled on its surface,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.273#And Ajax was upon him, thrusting his spear hard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.274#Through Hector's shield. The force of the blow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.275#Stunned him, and the point grazed his neck,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.276#Drawing dark blood. This didn't stop Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.277#He gave ground and picked up a stone, gripping it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.278#In one hand, a huge black slab lying in the plain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.279#And heaved it onto Ajax's massive shield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.280#Hitting it on the boss. The bronze rang like a gong.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.281#Ajax in turn picked up a much bigger rock,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.282#The size of a millstone, and, whirling around,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.283#Put his enormous strength into the throw,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.284#Crushing Hector's shield and buckling his knees.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.285#He lay curled on his back under his shield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.286#But Apollo quickly put him on his feet again.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.287#And they would have gone at each other with swords
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.288#Had not the heralds, Zeus' messengers and men's,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.289#Come forward from both sides---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.290#Talthybius and Idaeus, prudent men both.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.291#They held their staffs between the two combatants,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.292#And Idaeus made this formal pronouncement:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.293#"Fight no more, dear sons, nor battle more.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.294#Zeus beyond the clouds loves you both,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.295#And you are both spearmen, as we all know.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.296#Now it is night, and it is good to yield to night."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.297#Telamonian Ajax said in response:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.298#"Have Hector speak these words, Idaeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.299#He was the one who challenged our best to fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.300#It's his call. I'll go along with what he says."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.301#And great Hector, helmeted in gold, replied:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.302#"Ajax, since a god has given you size and strength
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.303#And wisdom too, and you are the best of the Achaeans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.304#With a spear, let us call a truce to our hostilities
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.305#For today. Another time we will fight again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.306#Until Zeus grants one of us the victory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.307#Now it is night, and it is good to yield to night,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.308#You to make glad the Greeks beside your ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.309#And especially the kinfolk and friends you have;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.310#Myself to make glad throughout Priam's city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.311#The Trojans and their wives in long trailing robes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.312#Who will for my sake throng Ilion's shrines.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.313#But now we should exchange glorious gifts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.314#So that the Greeks and Trojans will say of us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.315#'They fought each other in soul-devouring strife,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.316#But agreed to part in the spirit of friendship.'"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.317#And he gave him his silver-studded sword
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.318#Along with its scabbard and tooled belt.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.319#Ajax gave him his own belt, bright with scarlet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.320#Then they parted. Ajax went to the Greeks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.321#Hector to the Trojans, who were glad to see him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.322#Coming back to join them, having escaped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.323#With his life from the grim hands of Ajax.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.324#They led him back to the city, scarcely believing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.325#He was really safe. On their side, the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.326#Led Ajax to Agamemnon, glad he had won.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.327#When they were in Agamemnon's quarters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.328#The warlord sacrificed an ox for them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.329#A bull of five years, to almighty Cronion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.330#They flayed and dressed it, jointed the limbs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.331#And sliced them skillfully, skewered the pieces,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.332#Roasted them carefully, and drew them off the spits.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.333#When they were done and the feast was ready,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.334#Feast they did, and no one lacked an equal share.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.335#The long chine was given in honor to Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.336#By the commander-in-chief, Lord Agamemnon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.337#When they had enough of food and drink,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.338#The first to spin out his plan was Nestor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.339#Whose advice had always seemed best before.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.340#He was full of good will in the speech he made:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.341#"Son of Atreus and Greek leaders all,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.342#Many of our flowing-haired boys are dead,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.343#Their blood spilled by Ares near the Scamander,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.344#Their souls bound for Hades. And so there is need
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.345#For the army to pause from combat, and at dawn
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.346#Collect the corpses and wheel them back here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.347#By ox and mule cart. We will burn them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.348#Near the ships, so that when we return to our land
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.349#We may bear their bones home to their children.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.350#Near the pyre we will heap a common barrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.351#Out on the plain, and up against it we will build
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.352#A high wall, working fast, a defense for our ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.353#And for ourselves, and set in it close-fitting gates,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.354#So there will be a way to drive chariots through.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.355#Just outside the wall we will dig a deep trench
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.356#As a hazard for enemy troops and horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.357#Should the proud Trojans ever press us hard."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.358#Thus Nestor, and all the kings assented.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.359#Meanwhile, on the acropolis of Troy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.360#An unruly assembly mobbed Priam's doors.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.361#Wise Antenor led off with this speech:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.362#"Hear me, Trojans and Dardanian allies,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.363#That I might speak my heart. All right, then.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.364#Let us give Helen of Argos to Atreus' sons,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.365#Her and her possessions, for them to take away.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.366#We are fighting in false faith and can have
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.367#No profit from it. This is our only hope."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.368#He had his say and sat down. Then up stood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.369#Rich-haired Helen's husband, godlike Paris,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.370#Who answered him with these winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.371#"I don't like what you are saying, Antenor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.372#You know how to speak better than this.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.373#But if you really mean what you are saying,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.374#Then the gods must have destroyed your wits.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.375#This is what I have to say to the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.376#And I'll say it straight out: I won't give her back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.377#But the treasure I brought with her from Argos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.378#I will give back, and add some of my own."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.379#He had his say and sat down. Then up rose
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.380#Dardanian Priam, peer of the gods in counsel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.381#Full of good will in the speech that he made:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.382#"Hear me, Trojans and Dardanian allies,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.383#That I might speak my heart. For the present,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.384#Take your dinner throughout the city as usual,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.385#And each man of you be alert and on watch.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.386#At dawn Idaeus will go to the Greek ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.387#To tell Atreus' sons, Menelaus and Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.388#The word of Alexander, who is the cause of this war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.389#And to propose an armistice to burn the dead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.390#Later we will fight again, until the deity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.391#Decides between us and bestows the victory."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.392#He spoke, they listened, and they did as he said.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.393#The army took their supper by platoons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.394#At dawn Idaeus went down to the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.395#And found the Greek warlords assembled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.396#Beside the stern of Agamemnon's vessel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.397#The wind from the Aegean carried his voice:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.398#"Son of Atreus, and Achaean princes all:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.399#Priam and the other lords of Troy bid me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.400#Tell you---and may it be sweet to your ears---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.401#The word of Alexander, the cause of our strife.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.402#All of the treasure he brought back to Troy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.403#In his ship's hold---would he had died beforehand---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.404#He will give back, and add some of his own.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.405#But the former wife of renowned Menelaus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.406#He will not give back, though the Trojans bid him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.407#As they bid me also, propose, if you are willing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.408#An armistice until we can burn the dead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.409#Later we will fight again, until the deity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.410#Decides between us and bestows the victory."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.411#He spoke, and they were all hushed in silence
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.412#Until Diomedes' martial voice boomed out:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.413#"Accept nothing from Alexander,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.414#Not even Helen! Even a fool can see
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.415#The noose is tightening around the Trojans."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.416#The Greeks cheered when they heard this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.417#Delighted with Diomedes' blunt reply,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.418#And Lord Agamemnon addressed Idaeus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.419#"Idaeus, you yourself hear the Greeks' answer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.420#And it is my pleasure too. As for burning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.421#The corpses, I do not begrudge it at all.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.422#One does not stint the dead, or deny to them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.423#The swift consolation of fire. May Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.424#Hera's thundering consort, witness our oaths."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.425#And he lifted up his staff to the gods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.426#Idaeus went back to sacred Ilion, where
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.427#Trojans and Dardanians sat in assembly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.428#Awaiting his return. He stood in their midst
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.429#And delivered his message, and they set to work
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.430#To bring in the dead and gather wood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.431#Likewise the Greeks, hurrying from their ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.432#Brought in their dead and gathered wood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.433#The sun's light lay new on the fields
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.434#As it rose from deep, soft waters of Ocean
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.435#And climbed the sky.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.436#The armies met on the plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.437#It was difficult to recognize each of the dead,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.438#But they washed the clotted blood with water,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.439#And, shedding hot tears, lifted them onto carts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.440#Great Priam would not allow his people
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.441#To wail aloud, so in silence they heaped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.442#The corpses on the pyre, grieving at heart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.443#And when they had burned them they returned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.444#To sacred Ilion. And the Greeks, too, heaped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.445#The corpses on their pyre, grief in their hearts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.446#And having burned them, returned to the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.447#It was twilight before the following dawn
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.448#When chosen Greek troops gathered at the pyre.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.449#Working fast, they heaped around it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.450#A common barrow extending out on the plain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.451#And up against it they built a high wall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.452#To protect their camp, complete with tight gates
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.453#So there would be a way to drive chariots through.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.454#Just outside the wall they dug a trench,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.455#Deep and wide, and in it planted stakes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.456#As the Greeks toiled, their hair flowing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.457#Around their shoulders and bronze chests,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.458#The gods, seated around lightning Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.459#Marvelled at their work. Poseidon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.460#Lord of the islands, was first to speak:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.461#"Father Zeus, is there now any mortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.462#In all the wide world who will tell the gods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.463#What he intends? Do you see that the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.464#Have built a wall and trench around their ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.465#Without offering us bulls by the hundred?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.466#Fame of this will reach as far as Dawn spreads light,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.467#And men will forget the wall that Apollo and I
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.468#Built with toil for the hero Laomedon."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.469#This provoked a troubled, gloomy response:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.470#"What a thing for you to say, you, the Temblor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.471#Some lesser god might fear this ploy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.472#But not you, whose fame will reach
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.473#As far as Dawn spreads light. Choose your time.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.474#When the Greeks have left with their ships for home,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.475#Smash the wall to bits and sweep it out to sea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.476#And cover the great beach again with sand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.477#So that the Achaeans' wall becomes a dwindling thought."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.478#As they spoke to each other in this way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.479#The sun went down, and the Greeks' work was done.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.480#They slaughtered oxen and took their supper
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.481#Outside their huts. Wine-ships from Lemnos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.482#Had just sailed in, sent by Jason's son, Euneus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.483#The son Hypsipyle bore to the great adventurer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.484#Euneus had shipped for the sons of Atreus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.485#Agamemnon and Menelaus, a special consignment,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.486#A thousand liters of sweet red. The other Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.487#Went on board to barter for their wine,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.488#Some with bronze, others with iron, hides,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.489#Cattle, or slaves. They made a rich feast.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.490#All night long the Greeks feasted, and the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.491#Feasted with their allies throughout the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.492#And all night long Zeus the Counsellor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.493#Devised evil for them, thundering terribly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.494#Pale fear seized them, and no man dared drink
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.495#Before spilling wine to Cronus' mighty son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:7.496#Sleep was welcome when it finally came.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.1#Dawn.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.2#Saffron light over all the earth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.3#Zeus, who plays in thunder, had the gods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.4#Assembled on the utmost peak
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.5#Of the rugged Olympic massif,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.6#And now enjoyed their undivided attention:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.7#"Listen to me, divine ones,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.8#So I can tell you what I want.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.9#What I don't want is any god---male or female---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.10#Attempting to brook my word. You are all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.11#To assent, so we can get this over with.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.12#If I catch any one of you with a private plan
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.13#To assist either the Greeks or Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.14#He---or she---will return to Olympus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.15#A crippled wreck---unless of course I hurl
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.16#Him---or her---into moldy Tartarus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.17#Down into the deepest underground abyss,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.18#Iron-gated and bronze-stooped,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.19#As far beneath Hades as the sky is above earth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.20#Then you will know who is supreme around here.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.21#Or would you like to find out now?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.22#Come on. Hang a gold cable down from the sky.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.23#All you gods and goddesses holding the end
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.24#Couldn't drag down from sky to earth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.25#Zeus the Master, no matter how hard you tried.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.26#But if I wanted to I could haul up all of you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.27#With the earth itself and the very sea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.28#Then loop the cable around a spur of Olympus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.29#And the totality would hang suspended in space.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.30#That's how superior I am to gods and men."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.31#They were stunned to silence, aghast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.32#At his words. It had been a masterful speech.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.33#Finally, grey-eyed Athena spoke up:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.34#"Well, our Father who art the highest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.35#We know very well your might is unyielding.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.36#Still, we have pity for the Danaan spearmen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.37#Who are now destined to die an ugly death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.38#We will withdraw from the war if you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.39#Command it. But we will still advise the Greeks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.40#So they won't all be casualties of your wrath."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.41#And Zeus, smiling at her, answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.42#"There, there, daughter. My heart really
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.43#Isn't in it. I want to be gentle to you, child."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.44#With that, he harnessed his horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.45#Bronze-hooved, gold-maned, and swift,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.46#And clothed himself in gold, and gripped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.47#His golden whip, and stepped onto his chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.48#And with a touch of his lash they were off,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.49#Flying between earth and the starry universe.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.50#He came to Ida, with its springs and wild beasts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.51#A mountain mother, and to Gargaros there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.52#Where his precinct and smoking altar stood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.53#There Zeus reined in his horses, unhitched them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.54#From the car, and shed upon them a heavy mist.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.55#Then he sat among the peaks exulting in glory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.56#With the city of Troy and the Greek ships in view.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.57#The Greeks were taking a hurried meal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.58#In their huts, and then armed themselves quickly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.59#Likewise the Trojans throughout the city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.60#A smaller army but much more desperate
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.61#To engage the enemy: they were fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.62#For their children and for their wives.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.63#All the gates were opened, and the troops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.64#Poured through them, on foot and in war cars.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.65#When the two sides closed with each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.66#They slammed together shields and spears---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.67#Rawhide ovals pressed close, bronze thoraxes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.68#Grinding against each other, and the groans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.69#Of men being slain and the cries of those slaying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.70#Hung in the air as the earth ran with blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.71#As long as the holy light climbed toward noon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.72#Soldiers on both sides were hit and fell.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.73#But when the sun straddled heaven's meridian,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.74#The Father stretched out his golden scales.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.75#On them he placed two dooms of agonizing death,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.76#One for the Trojans, one for the Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.77#He held the scales in the middle, and down sank
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.78#The Greek day of doom, down to the fertile earth,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.79#While the Trojans' soared up to the sky's expanse.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.80#Then Zeus thundered from Ida, and sent a blazing flash
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.81#Into the Greek army. The soldiers gaped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.82#In wonder, and their blood turned milky with fear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.83#Idomeneus lost his nerve and ran,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.84#Followed by Agamemnon and both Ajaxes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.85#Nestor was the only Greek commander left,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.86#Not that he wanted to stay, but Paris,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.87#Helen's fair-haired lord, had hit his trace horse
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.88#With an arrow to the forelock, and the animal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.89#Reared in pain, pawing the air frantically
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.90#And throwing the other horses into confusion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.91#As it writhed against the bronze point in its brain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.92#The old man was cutting the traces with his sword
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.93#When the horses of an enemy chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.94#Loomed ahead, Hector's horses, and yes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.95#Hector himself at the reins. Nestor's death
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.96#Would have been assured, had not Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.97#Had all this in sharp focus. His soldier's yell
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.98#Boomed across the plain to Odysseus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.99#"Son of Laertes, Odysseus, the clever Ithacan---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.100#Watch out you don't catch an arrow in your back,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.101#Retreating like some gutless wonder. Come on,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.102#Let's save the old man from this maniac."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.103#Odysseus didn't hear, or pretended not to.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.104#He went right past toward the Achaean ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.105#No matter. Alone as he was, Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.106#Shouldered his way over to Nestor's horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.107#And taking his stand said to the old man:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.108#"Here you are, old and broken down,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.109#With all these young bruisers at your throat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.110#Your driver isn't much help either, is he?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.111#Here, get up into my chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.112#And see what the horses of Tros can do.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.113#They know how to eat up the plain, and how to
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.114#Cut and turn, in pursuit or in flight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.115#I got them from Aeneas, a pair of real terrors.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.116#Our men can mind your horses. As for you and me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.117#Let's drive this team straight at the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.118#So that Hector too can feel my spear's bite."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.119#That was enough for the old Gerenian horseman.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.120#Sthenelus and Eurymedon tended his mares,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.121#And Nestor got in with Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.122#Taking the silky reins and touching the horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.123#With the lash. They closed ground quickly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.124#And Diomedes threw as Hector came at them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.125#Missing his target but hitting Hector's driver,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.126#Eniopoeus, square in the chest as he held the reins.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.127#He fell from the chariot, the horses swerved,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.128#And Eniopoeus' soul crawled off in the dust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.129#Hector took his death hard, but let him lie there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.130#As he went off to find another charioteer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.131#And soon found one, Archeptolemus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.132#Iphitus' son. Hector had him mount
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.133#Behind the horses, and put the reins in his hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.134#Things would have gone badly for the Trojans then,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.135#And they would have been penned in Ilion like lambs,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.136#Had Father Zeus not had all this in sharp focus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.137#He thundered terribly and threw a white lightning-bolt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.138#That landed in front of Diomedes' horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.139#And shot up in a flame of burning sulfur.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.140#The horses shied and backed into the car.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.141#The reins slipped out of Nestor's hands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.142#And with fear in his heart he said to Diomedes:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.143#"Son of Tydeus, turn your horses around.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.144#Zeus has given this man the glory today.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.145#Another day he may give it to us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.146#But no one can change the purpose of Zeus."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.147#And Diomedes, good at the war cry:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.148#"Yes, old sir, everything you say is right,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.149#But it cuts deep that Hector will someday crow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.150#'I made Tydeus' son turn tail and run.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.151#When he makes that boast to the men of Troy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.152#I'd just as soon fall through a crack in the earth."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.153#And Nestor, the Gerenian horseman:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.154#"What a thing for wise Tydeus' son to say.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.155#Hector may call you a coward and weakling,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.156#But the Trojans will not agree with him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.157#Nor will the Dardanians, nor will the widows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.158#Of all those men you laid low in the dust."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.159#And he wheeled the horses around and fled,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.160#Back through the tumult, with howling Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.161#Raining barbed missiles on them from behind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.162#And Hector's taunting voice in their ears:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.163#"Son of Tydeus, the Greeks used to honor you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.164#With the best seat, full cups, and red meat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.165#No more! It turns out you're no better than
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.166#A woman, a rag doll. Get out of here.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.167#Did you think I would just stand by and watch
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.168#While you climbed our walls and carried our women
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.169#Off in your ships? I'll send you to hell first."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.170#Diomedes was tempted to wheel around
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.171#And deal with Hector face to face.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.172#Three times he wavered and was about to turn,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.173#And every time Zeus thundered from Ida,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.174#Signalling that it was the Trojans' turn to win.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.175#Hector shouted to his troops:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.176#"Trojans, Lycians, Dardanian soldiers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.177#Remember to fight like the men that you are.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.178#Zeus I know has decreed glory for me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.179#And victory---and for the Danaans defeat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.180#Look at this puny wall they've put up.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.181#It will never withstand the force of our attack,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.182#And our horses will easily jump this ditch.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.183#Once I get to their ships, get me some fire
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.184#So I can burn the fleet and kill dazed Greeks in the smoke."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.185#Then he called to his horses:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.186#"Xanthus and Podargus, Aethon and Lampus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.187#Pay me back now for all the tender care
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.188#Andromache daughter of Eëtion showed you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.189#Setting out for you sweet mash with wine
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.190#Before serving a meal to me, her husband.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.191#Now pour on the speed, so we can capture
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.192#The world-renowned shield of Nestor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.193#Solid gold from the rods to the core,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.194#And Diomedes' corselet, forged by Hephaestus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.195#If we could take both of these, we could expect
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.196#The Greeks to sail away this very night."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.197#Thus Hector's vaunts, and Hera shook with rage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.198#As she sat on her throne, making Olympus tremble.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.199#She turned to the great god Poseidon and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.200#"Ah, Earthshaker, you have all that power,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.201#But no pity in your heart for the Danaans dying.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.202#And yet they honor you with many lovely gifts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.203#At Helice and Aegae, and up until now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.204#You wanted victory for them. If we had the will---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.205#All of us who favor the Greeks, to drive
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.206#The Trojans back and hold Zeus in check---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.207#He would sit alone and frustrated up there on Ida."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.208#And the Earthshaker's troubled, gloomy response:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.209#"That's reckless talk, Hera. Far be it from me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.210#To endorse a fight between Cronion Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.211#And all the rest of us. He is stronger by far."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.212#While they talked to each other this way,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.213#The space between the trenched wall and the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.214#Was crammed with horses and men with shields,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.215#Corralled there by Hector, son of Priam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.216#And peer of swift Ares, Zeus' glory upon him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.217#And he would have set fire to the upswept hulls
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.218#Had not Hera put it in Agamemnon's mind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.219#To make a last-ditch effort to rouse the Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.220#He went through the Achaean ships and huts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.221#Clutching his great purple cloak, and took his stand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.222#On the huge black hull of Odysseus' ship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.223#From which a shout would reach either end of camp,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.224#To Telamonian Ajax's quarters at one end
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.225#And Achilles' at the other, for these two heroes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.226#Had drawn up their ships at the extremities,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.227#Trusting their manhood and the strength of their hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.228#Agamemnon's voice reached every Greek ear:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.229#"For shame, Argives!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.230#You're nothing but poor excuses for soldiers!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.231#What happened to all our boasts, all the big talk
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.232#That we were the best? Remember Lemnos?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.233#All the beef and wine you ate there? Remember saying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.234#That each of you could take on a hundred Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.235#Two hundred? Well now we can't match even one,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.236#This Hector, who is about to burn our ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.237#Father Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.238#Has there ever been another mighty king
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.239#Whom you have blinded with blindness like this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.240#Robbed him of glory, as you have robbed me?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.241#And yet I never sailed past any altar of yours,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.242#I swear, on this misbegotten voyage here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.243#Without offering oxen at every single one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.244#In my zeal to make rubble of the walls of Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.245#At least, Zeus, grant me this prayer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.246#Let my people escape. Don't let the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.247#Annihilate the Achaeans like this."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.248#Zeus pitied his tears, and with a nod
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.249#Agreed that his people would not be destroyed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.250#He sent an eagle, the surest omen on wings,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.251#Holding in his talons a fawn, which he dropped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.252#Beside the altar where the Achaeans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.253#Sacrificed to oracular Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.254#When they saw that the bird had come from him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.255#The Greeks smiled, and counterattacked.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.256#Of all the Danaans, not one could claim
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.257#To cross the trench and engage the enemy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.258#Before Diomedes. The armored Trojan he killed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.259#Was named Agelaus, Phradmon's son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.260#He was in the act of wheeling his horses around
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.261#When Diomedes planted a spear in his back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.262#With enough force to drive it out through his chest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.263#He fell from his car with a clang of metal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.264#Next out were the two sons of Atreus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.265#Followed by both Ajaxes, clothed in fury.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.266#Then came Idomeneus and his companion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.267#Meriones, who weighed in like Ares,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.268#And Eurypylus, Euaemon's fine son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.269#Ninth was Teucer, stretching his bow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.270#As he took his stand behind Ajax's shield.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.271#Big Ajax would move his shield aside
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.272#And Teucer would spot his target and shoot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.273#His victim would drop in his tracks, and Teucer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.274#Would run back to Ajax like a child to its mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.275#And take cover again behind his shining shield.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.276#Teucer could do no wrong. In short order he killed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.277#Orsilochus, Ormenus, and Ophelestes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.278#Daetor, Chromius, and godlike Lycophontes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.279#Polyaemon's son Amopaon, and Melanippus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.280#When he had brought these down, one after another,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.281#His great bow devastating the Trojan ranks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.282#Agamemnon took notice and came by to say:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.283#"Teucer, my man, son of Telamon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.284#Keep shooting like this and you will save the day
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.285#For the Greeks, and be the light of Telamon's life,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.286#Who raised and cherished you in his own house
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.287#Though you were a bastard. Today you can
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.288#Bring glory to him, far away as he is.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.289#And I give you my solemn word of honor:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.290#If Zeus Aegis-Holder and Athena allow me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.291#To strip Troy down to its stone foundations,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.292#I will place in your hand special reward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.293#Second only to mine---a cauldron, or a chariot and team,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.294#Or a woman who will go to your bed."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.295#And Teucer, who was beyond reproach:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.296#"Most glorious son of Atreus, why urge me on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.297#When I'm at my top speed? I haven't let up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.298#Since we started to push them back to the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.299#I just pick my spots and shoot Trojans dead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.300#Eight long-tipped arrows I've let fly now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.301#And all of them are stuck in some hero's flesh.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.302#There's only this one mad dog I can't hit."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.303#And he let another arrow jump from the string
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.304#Straight for Hector. He longed to hit him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.305#But the arrow missed, finding instead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.306#The chest of Gorgythion, a son of Priam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.307#By a woman from Aesyme he had taken as wife,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.308#Castianeira, beautiful as a goddess.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.309#His head sagged to one side---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.310#like a poppy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.311#In a garden, heavy with seeds and spring rain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.312#Gorgythion's head, weighted with his helmet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.313#Teucer let another arrow jump from the string
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.314#Straight for Hector. He longed to hit him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.315#But missed again. This time Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.316#Made the arrow swerve, and this time it hit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.317#Archeptolemus, Hector's charioteer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.318#Square in the chest as he hurled himself on.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.319#He fell from the chariot, the horses shied,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.320#And Archeptolemus' life drained away in the dust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.321#Hector flushed with grief for his fallen driver
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.322#But let him lie there, and ordered Cebriones,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.323#Who was his own brother, and close at hand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.324#To take the reins. Cebriones did so,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.325#And Hector vaulted down from his chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.326#With a bloodcurdling scream. Scooping up a stone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.327#In one hand he made straight for Teucer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.328#Who had drawn an arrow from his quiver,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.329#Notched it on the string, and was pulling it back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.330#He was taking dead aim at Hector in his shining helmet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.331#When the stone caught him just where the collarbone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.332#Divides the neck from the chest, a vulnerable spot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.333#The jagged rock broke the string, his hand went numb;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.334#He staggered, fell to his knees, and dropped the bow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.335#When Ajax saw his brother go down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.336#He straddled him and sheltered him with his shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.337#Until two of his men, Mecistius and Alastor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.338#Bore him, groaning heavily, back to the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.339#Then once again the Olympian lifted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.340#The Trojans' spirits, and they pushed the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.341#Straight toward their deep ditch
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.342#With Hector out front, thoroughly enjoying himself.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.343#A hound goes after a wild hog or a lion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.344#Nipping at its buttocks from behind,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.345#Sure of its own speed but always watching
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.346#For its prey to whirl around.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.347#Thus Hector pressed the long-haired Greeks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.348#Picking off the hindmost one by one.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.349#They were in full retreat until they passed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.350#The palisade and ditch. By then many had fallen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.351#When they reached their ships they halted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.352#And called out to each other, and to every god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.353#They could think of, lifting their arms high,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.354#Palms flat to heaven, while Hector wheeled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.355#His glossy horses right and left, staring toward the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.356#With eyes like a Gorgon's, or like butchering Ares'.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.357#Watching all this, Hera was moved to pity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.358#And said to Athena in a flurry of words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.359#"Don't the two of us care any more that the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.360#Are being beaten? This may be the end.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.361#One single man, Priam's son Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.362#Is pushing them all to the brink of doom.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.363#His rampage is no longer bearable.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.364#Just look at how much harm he has done!"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.365#And the grey-eyed goddess said to her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.366#"I would love to have this man snuffed out,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.367#Killed by the Argives in his own native land.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.368#But my father is on a rampage himself now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.369#And constantly thwarts all my best efforts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.370#He has conveniently forgotten how many times
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.371#I rescued his son Heracles when he was struggling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.372#With Eurystheus' labors. He would cry to heaven
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.373#And Zeus would dispatch me to save his neck.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.374#Had I been sharp enough to know all this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.375#When he was sent to Hades to fetch the hellhound,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.376#He never would have made it back up from Styx.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.377#At any rate, Zeus hates me now and has executed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.378#The plan Thetis sold him on when she kissed his knees
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.379#And grabbed his beard, begging him to honor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.380#Her son Achilles, sacker of cities.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.381#Well, one day he'll call me his grey-eyed girl again.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.382#But for now, you get our horses ready
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.383#While I go to the house of Zeus Aegis-Holder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.384#And put on my war gear. I want to see
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.385#The expression on Hector's helmeted face
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.386#When we two appear in the lanes of battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.387#Many a Trojan will glut the dogs and birds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.388#With their soft flesh after they fall by the ships."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.389#Hera, the white-armed goddess, agreed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.390#And the queen of heaven, daughter of Cronus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.391#Hastened to harness the gold-frontleted horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.392#Athena, meanwhile, Zeus' favorite daughter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.393#Let her supple robe slip down to her father's floor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.394#This embroidered garment her own handiwork.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.395#She put on one of cloudy Zeus' tunics,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.396#Strapped on her battle gear, and then stepped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.397#Into the blazing chariot cradling a spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.398#Long and thick enough for heaven's daughter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.399#To level battalions of men in her wrath.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.400#Hera quickly flicked the horses with the lash,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.401#And the automatic gates of heaven
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.402#Groaned open, as willed by the Hours,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.403#Who control access to Olympus and heaven,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.404#Opening and shutting the dense cloudbanks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.405#Through this gate they drove the patient horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.406#Zeus saw them from Ida and seethed with anger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.407#He sent golden-winged Iris to bear this message:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.408#"Go, swift Iris. Turn them back,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.409#And don't let them come face to face with me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.410#It would not be pretty if we had to fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.411#This is my solemn word on the subject:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.412#I will maim their horses, throw them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.413#From the chariot, and smash it to bits.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.414#Not in ten circling years will they be healed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.415#Of the wounds the thunderbolt will inflict.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.416#The grey-eyed one must learn what it means
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.417#To fight with her father. As for Hera,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.418#I am not so angry with her, since she
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.419#Always opposes whatever I say."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.420#He spoke, and Iris stormed from Ida's peaks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.421#To the Olympic range, and caught them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.422#Just at the gates and repeated Zeus' words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.423#"Where are you two off to in such a hurry?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.424#Zeus will not allow you to help the Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.425#This is his solemn word on the subject:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.426#He will maim your horses, throw you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.427#From the chariot, and smash it to bits.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.428#Not in ten circling years will you be healed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.429#Of the wounds the thunderbolt will inflict.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.430#That's so you, grey eyes, will see
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.431#What it means to fight with your father.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.432#Hera he's not so upset with, since she
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.433#Always opposes whatever he says.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.434#But you are awesome indeed, and a fearless bitch,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.435#If you dare lift your spear against Zeus."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.436#Iris spoke and was gone in a blur of wind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.437#Hera turned to Athena and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.438#"Daughter of the Aegis-Holder, I can no longer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.439#Countenance our fighting with Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.440#For the sake of mere mortals. Let one fall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.441#And another live, as chance may have it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.442#And let Zeus judge by his own lights
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.443#Between Trojans and Greeks, as is only proper."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.444#With that she turned her hooved horses around.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.445#The Hours unyoked them for the goddesses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.446#And tethered them at their ambrosial stalls,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.447#And leaned the chariot on the shining gateway.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.448#They went inside and sat on golden thrones
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.449#With the other immortals, and nursed their grief.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.450#Zeus wheeled his chariot from Ida
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.451#To Olympus, where the gods sat assembled.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.452#No one less than Poseidon unyoked his team,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.453#Set the car on its stand, and draped it with a cloth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.454#While Zeus rumbled onto his golden throne
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.455#And mighty Olympus trembled under his feet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.456#Only Hera and Athena sat apart from Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.457#And failed to address him or ask him a question.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.458#He knew what was wrong and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.459#"Why are you two so upset, Athena and Hera?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.460#It's not battle fatigue. You two never get tired
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.461#Of pulverizing Trojans, your mortal enemies.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.462#It all comes down to this: these two hands are more powerful
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.463#Than all the gods on Olympus combined.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.464#As for you two, your shining limbs trembled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.465#Before you got close enough to see the front lines.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.466#And it's just as well, because one thing is certain:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.467#Once you had been struck by my thunderbolt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.468#You would never have made it back to Olympus."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.469#The two goddesses murmured to each other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.470#Huddling close and still scheming against Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.471#Athena kept silent and said nothing out loud,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.472#Although she was furious at her father Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.473#Hera, however, could not contain her anger:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.474#"The awesome son of Cronus has spoken again!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.475#We're all too familiar with your irresistible strength,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.476#But we still feel pity for the Danaan spearmen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.477#Who are now destined to die an ugly death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.478#Fine! We will withdraw from the war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.479#If you command it. But we will still advise the Greeks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.480#So they won't all be casualties of your wrath."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.481#And Zeus, clouds gathering around him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.482#"At dawn you will see Cronus' almighty son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.483#If you wish, my ox-eyed lady Hera,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.484#Making casualties of much of the Greek army.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.485#Hector will not be absent from the war
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.486#Until Achilles has risen up from beside his ship
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.487#On the day when the fighting for Patroclus' dead body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.488#Reaches its fever pitch by the ships' sterns.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.489#That is divinely decreed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.490#Your wrath is nothing to me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.491#Not even if you go to the deepest foundations
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.492#Of Earth and Sea, where Cronus and Iapetus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.493#Dwell out of the light of Hyperion the Sun,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.494#Cooled by no winds, in the trench of Tartarus---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.495#Not even then will I care that you are angry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.496#Because there is nothing more shameless than you."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.497#He spoke, and white-armed Hera said nothing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.498#The sunlight fell into the Ocean, drawing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.499#Black night over earth's fields, a sunset
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.500#The Trojans resented, but to the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.501#Welcome, thrice-prayed-for ebony night.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.502#Hector made camp, leading the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.503#Along the river some distance from the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.504#To an open space that was clear of the dead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.505#They stepped to the ground from their chariots
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.506#To hear Hector speak. In his hand was a spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.507#Sixteen feet long, bronze point gleaming, the ferrule gold.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.508#Leaning on this spear, he addressed the troops:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.509#"Hear me, Trojans, Dardanians, and allies.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.510#I had thought to destroy the Greeks and their ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.511#And be back by now to windy Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.512#But darkness intervened. This more than anything
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.513#Has saved them and their fleet parked on our beach.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.514#So for now, let us yield to black night
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.515#And prepare our supper. Unyoke your horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.516#And feed them. Bring cattle and sheep from the city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.517#And get bread and mellow wine from your houses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.518#And gather tons of firewood, so that all night long
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.519#Until early dawn we can burn fires enough
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.520#To light up the sky, in case the long-haired Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.521#Have any idea of sailing off by night.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.522#We'll not let them board their ships at ease
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.523#Or without a fight. Let them each have a wound
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.524#From an arrow or spear to brood over at home,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.525#A going-away present as they jump on their ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.526#And a lesson to others not to make war on Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.527#Heralds should proclaim throughout the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.528#That boys and greybeards bivouac tonight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.529#All around the city on our god-built walls.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.530#As for the women, each of them should light
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.531#A fire in her house. The city needs to guard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.532#Against a sneak attack while the army is away.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.533#Enough for now. This is sound strategy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.534#In the morning I will address the troops again.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.535#I hope and pray to Zeus and all gods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.536#To drive off this visitation of foreign dogs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.537#The fates have brought us in the black ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.538#For tonight, we will take care of ourselves.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.539#At the crack of dawn we arm ourselves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.540#And hit the Greeks hard in their beachhead camp.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.541#I will find out whether the great Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.542#Will drive me back from the ships to our wall,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.543#Or whether I will walk off with his bloody gear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.544#And tomorrow he will know what he is made of,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.545#And whether he can stand up to my spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.546#My hunch is that he will find himself lying wounded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.547#In the front lines, with his friends all around him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.548#At sunup tomorrow. I wish I were as sure
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.549#Of immortality and eternal youth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.550#And honor like Apollo's and Pallas Athena's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.551#As I am that this is a black day for the Greeks."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.552#Thus Hector, and the Trojans cheered.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.553#They unyoked their sweating horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.554#And tethered them with thongs to their chariots.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.555#They brought cattle and sheep from the city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.556#Got bread and mellow wine from their houses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.557#And gathered firewood. They offered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.558#Bulls by the hundred to the immortal gods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.559#And onshore winds carried the smoky savor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.560#Up to the sky. But the blessed ones disdained
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.561#To partake. They abhorred holy Ilion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.562#And Priam, and the people under Priam's ash spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.563#But the Trojans had great notions that night,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.564#Sitting on the bridge of war by their watchfires.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.565#Stars: crowds of them in the sky, sharp
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.566#In the moonglow when the wind falls
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.567#And all the cliffs and hills and peaks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.568#Stand out and the air shears down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.569#From heaven, and all the stars are visible
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.570#And the watching shepherd smiles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.571#So the bonfires between the Greek ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.572#And the banks of the Xanthus, burning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.573#On the plain before Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.574#And fifty men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.575#Warmed their hands by the flames of each fire.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.576#And the horses champed white barley,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.577#Standing by their chariots, waiting for Dawn
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:8.578#To take her seat on brocaded cushions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.1#So the Trojans kept watch. But Panic,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.2#Fear's sister, had wrapped her icy fingers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.3#Around the Greeks, and all their best
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.4#Were stricken with unendurable grief.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.5#When two winds rise on the swarming deep,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.6#Boreas and Zephyr, blowing from Thrace
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.7#In a sudden squall, the startled black waves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.8#Will crest and tangle the surf with seaweed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.9#The Greeks felt like that, pummeled and torn.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.10#Agamemnon's heart was bruised with pain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.11#As he went around to the clear-toned criers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.12#Ordering them to call each man to assembly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.13#But not to shout. He pitched in himself.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.14#It was a dispirited assembly. Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.15#Stood up, weeping, his face like a sheer cliff
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.16#With dark springwater washing down the stone.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.17#Groaning heavily he addressed the troops:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.18#"Friends, Argive commanders and counsellors:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.19#Great Zeus, son of Cronus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.20#Is a hard god, friends. He's kept me in the dark
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.21#After all his promises, all his nods my way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.22#That I'd raze Ilion's walls before sailing home.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.23#It was all a lie, and I see now that his orders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.24#Are for me to return to Argos in disgrace,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.25#And this after all the armies I've destroyed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.26#I have no doubt that this is the high will
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.27#Of the god who has toppled so many cities
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.28#And will in the future, all glory to his power.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.29#So this is my command for the entire army:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.30#Clear out with our ships and head for home.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.31#There's no hope we will take Troy's tall town."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.32#He spoke, and they were all stunned to silence,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.33#The silence of an army too grieved to speak,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.34#Until at last Diomedes' voice boomed out:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.35#"I'm going to oppose you if you talk foolishness---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.36#As is my right in assembly, lord. Keep your temper.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.37#First of all, you insulted me, saying in public
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.38#I was unwarlike and weak. Every Greek here,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.39#Young and old alike, knows all about this.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.40#The son of crooked Cronus split the difference
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.41#When he gave you gifts. He gave you a scepter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.42#And honor with it, but he didn't give you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.43#Strength to stand in battle, which is real power.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.44#Are you out of your mind? Do you really think
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.45#The sons of the Achaeans are unwarlike and weak?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.46#If you yourself are anxious to go home,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.47#Then go. You know the way. Your ships are here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.48#Right by the sea, and a whole fleet will follow you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.49#Back to Mycenae. But many a long-haired Achaean
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.50#Will stay, too, until we conquer Troy. And if they won't---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.51#Well, let them all sail back to their own native land.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.52#The two of us, Sthenelus and I, will fight on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.53#Until we take Ilion. We came here with Zeus."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.54#He spoke, and all the Greeks cheered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.55#The speech of Diomedes, breaker of horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.56#Then up stood Nestor, the old charioteer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.57#"Son of Tydeus, you are our mainstay in battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.58#And the best of your age in council as well.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.59#No Greek will find fault with your speech
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.60#Or contradict it. But it is not the whole story.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.61#You are still young. You might be my son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.62#My youngest. Yet you have given prudent advice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.63#To the Argive kings, since you have spoken aright.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.64#But I, who am privileged to be your senior,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.65#Will speak to all points. Nor will anyone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.66#Scorn my words, not even King Agamemnon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.67#Only outlaws and exiles favor civil strife.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.68#For the present, however, let us yield to night
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.69#And have our dinner. Guards should be posted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.70#Outside the wall along the trench. I leave
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.71#This assignment to the younger men. But you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.72#Son of Atreus, take charge. You are King.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.73#Serve the elders a feast. It is not unseemly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.74#Your huts are filled with wine which our ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.75#Transport daily over the sea from Thrace.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.76#You have the means to entertain us and the men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.77#Then choose the best counsel your assembled guests
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.78#Can offer. The Achaeans are in great need
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.79#Of good counsel. The enemies' campfires
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.80#Are close to our ships. Can this gladden any heart?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.81#This night will either destroy the army or save it."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.82#They all heard him out and did as he said.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.83#The guard details got their gear and filed out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.84#On the double under their commanders:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.85#Thrasymedes, Nestor's son; Ascalaphus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.86#And Ialmenus, sons of Ares; Meriones,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.87#Aphareus, and Diphyrus; and Creion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.88#The son of Lycomedes. Each of these seven
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.89#Had a hundred men under his command.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.90#Spears in hand, they took up their positions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.91#In a long line between the wall and the trench,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.92#Where they lit fires and prepared their supper.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.93#Agamemnon meanwhile gathered the elders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.94#Into his hut and served them a hearty meal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.95#They helped themselves to the dishes before them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.96#And when they had enough of food and drink,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.97#The first to spin out his plan for them was Nestor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.98#Whose advice had always seemed best before,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.99#And who spoke with their best interests at heart:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.100#"Son of Atreus, most glorious lord,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.101#I begin and end with you, since you are
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.102#King of a great people, with authority
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.103#To rule and right of judgment from Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.104#It is yours to speak as well as to listen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.105#And to stand behind others whenever they speak
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.106#To our good. The final word is yours.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.107#But I will speak as seems best to me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.108#No one will have a better idea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.109#Than I have now, nor has anyone ever,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.110#From the time, divine prince, you wrested away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.111#The girl Briseis from Achilles' shelter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.112#Defying his anger and my opposition.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.113#I tried to dissuade you, but you gave in
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.114#To your pride and dishonored a great man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.115#Whom the immortals esteem. You took his prize
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.116#And keep it still. But it is not too late. Even now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.117#We must think of how to win him back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.118#With appeasing gifts and soothing words."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.119#And the warlord Agamemnon responded:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.120#"Yes, old man, you were right on the mark
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.121#When you said I was mad. I will not deny it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.122#Zeus' favor multiplies a man's worth,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.123#As it has here, and the army has suffered for it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.124#But since I did succumb to a fit of madness,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.125#I want to make substantial amends.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.126#I hereby announce my reparations:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.127#Seven unfired tripods, ten gold bars,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.128#Twenty burnished cauldrons, a dozen horses---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.129#Solid, prizewinning racehorses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.130#Who have won me a small fortune---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.131#And seven women who do impeccable work,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.132#Surpassingly beautiful women from Lesbos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.133#I chose for myself when Achilles captured the town.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.134#And with them will be the woman I took,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.135#Briseus' daughter, and I will solemnly swear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.136#I never went to her bed and lay with her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.137#Or did what is natural between women and men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.138#All this he may have at once. And if it happens
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.139#That the gods allow us to sack Priam's city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.140#He may when the Greeks are dividing the spoils
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.141#Load a ship to the brim with gold and bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.142#And choose for himself the twenty Trojan women
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.143#Who are next in beauty to Argive Helen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.144#And if we return to the rich land of Argos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.145#He will marry my daughter, and I will honor him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.146#As I do Orestes, who is being reared in luxury.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.147#I have three daughters in my fortress palace,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.148#Chrysothemis, Laodice, and Iphianassa.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.149#He may lead whichever he likes as his bride
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.150#Back to Peleus' house, without paying anything,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.151#And I will give her a dowry richer than any
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.152#A father has ever given his daughter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.153#And I will give him seven populous cities,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.154#Cardamyle, Enope, grassy Hire,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.155#Sacred Pherae, Antheia with its meadowlands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.156#Beautiful Aepeia, and Pedasus, wine country.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.157#They are all near the sea, on sandy Pylos' frontier,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.158#And cattlemen live there, rich in herds and flocks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.159#Who will pay him tribute as if he were a god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.160#And fulfill the shining decrees of his scepter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.161#I will do all this if he will give up his grudge.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.162#And he should. Only Hades cannot be appeased,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.163#Which is why of all gods mortals hate him most.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.164#And he should submit to me, inasmuch as I
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.165#Am more of a king and can claim to be elder."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.166#And then spoke Nestor, the Gerenian rider:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.167#"Son of Atreus, most glorious Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.168#Your gifts for Achilles are beyond reproach.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.169#But come, we must dispatch envoys
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.170#As soon as possible to Achilles' tent,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.171#And I see before me who should volunteer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.172#Phoenix, dear to Zeus, should lead the way,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.173#Followed by Ajax and brilliant Odysseus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.174#Odius and Eurybates can attend them as heralds.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.175#Now bring water for our hands and observe silence,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.176#That we may beseech Zeus to have mercy on us."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.177#Nestor spoke, and his speech pleased them all.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.178#Heralds poured water over their hands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.179#And then youths filled bowls to the brim with drink
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.180#And served it all around, first tipping the cups.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.181#Having made their libations and drunk their fill,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.182#They went out in a body from Agamemnon's hut.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.183#Gerenian Nestor filled their ears with advice,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.184#Glancing at each, but especially at Odysseus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.185#On how to persuade Peleus' peerless son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.186#They went in tandem along the seething shore,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.187#Praying over and over to the god in the surf
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.188#For an easy time in convincing Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.189#They came to the Myrmidons' ships and huts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.190#And found him plucking clear notes on a lyre---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.191#A beautiful instrument with a silver bridge
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.192#He had taken when he ransacked Eëtion's town---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.193#Accompanying himself as he sang the glories
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.194#Of heroes in war. He was alone with Patroclus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.195#Who sat in silence waiting for him to finish.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.196#His visitors came forward, Odysseus first,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.197#And stood before him. Surprised, Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.198#Rose from his chair still holding his lyre.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.199#Patroclus, when he saw them, also rose,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.200#And Achilles, swift and sure, received them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.201#"Welcome. Things must be bad to bring you here,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.202#The Greeks I love best, even in my rage."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.203#With these words Achilles led them in
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.204#And had them sit on couches and rugs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.205#Dyed purple, and he called to Patroclus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.206#"A larger bowl, son of Menoetius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.207#And stronger wine, and cups all around.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.208#My dearest friends are beneath my roof."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.209#Patroclus obliged his beloved companion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.210#Then he cast a carving block down in the firelight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.211#And set on it a sheep's back and a goat's,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.212#And a hog chine too, marbled with fat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.213#Automedon held the meat while Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.214#Carved it carefully and spitted the pieces.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.215#Patroclus, godlike in the fire's glare,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.216#Fed the blaze. When the flames died down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.217#He laid the spits over the scattered embers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.218#Resting them on stones, and sprinkled the morsels
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.219#With holy salt. When the meat was roasted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.220#He laid it on platters and set out bread
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.221#In exquisite baskets. Achilles served the meat,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.222#Then sat down by the wall opposite Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.223#And asked Patroclus to offer sacrifice.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.224#After he threw the offerings in the fire,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.225#They helped themselves to the meal before them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.226#And when they had enough of food and drink,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.227#Ajax nodded to Phoenix. Odysseus saw this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.228#And filling a cup he lifted it to Achilles:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.229#"To your health, Achilles, for a generous feast.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.230#There is no shortage in Agamemnon's hut,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.231#Or now here in yours, of satisfying food.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.232#But the pleasures of the table are not on our minds.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.233#We fear the worst. It is doubtful
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.234#That we can save the ships without your strength.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.235#The Trojans and their allies are encamped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.236#Close to the wall that surrounds our black ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.237#And are betting that we can't keep them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.238#From breaking through. They may be right.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.239#Zeus has been encouraging them with signs,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.240#Lightning on the right. Hector trusts this---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.241#And his own strength---and has been raging
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.242#Recklessly, like a man possessed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.243#He is praying for dawn to come early
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.244#So he can fulfill his threat to lop the horns
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.245#From the ships' sterns, burn the hulls to ash,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.246#And slaughter the Achaeans dazed in the smoke.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.247#This is my great fear, that the gods make good
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.248#Hector's threats, dooming us to die in Troy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.249#Far from the fields of home. Up with you, then,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.250#If you intend at all, even at this late hour,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.251#To save our army from these howling Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.252#Think of yourself, of the regret you will feel
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.253#For harm that will prove irreparable.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.254#This is the last chance to save your countrymen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.255#Is it not true, my friend, that your father Peleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.256#Told you as he sent you off with Agamemnon:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.257#'My son, as for strength, Hera and Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.258#Will bless you if they wish, but it is up to you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.259#To control your proud spirit. A friendly heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.260#Is far better. Steer clear of scheming strife,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.261#So that Greeks young and old will honor you.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.262#You have forgotten what the old man said,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.263#But you can still let go of your anger, right now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.264#Agamemnon is offering you worthy gifts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.265#If you will give up your grudge. Hear me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.266#While I list the gifts he proposed in his hut:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.267#Seven unfired tripods, ten gold bars,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.268#Twenty burnished cauldrons, a dozen horses---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.269#Solid, prizewinning racehorses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.270#Who have won him a small fortune---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.271#And seven women who do impeccable work,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.272#Surpassingly beautiful women from Lesbos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.273#He chose for himself when you captured the town.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.274#And with them will be the woman he took from you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.275#Briseus' daughter, and he will solemnly swear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.276#He never went to her bed and lay with her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.277#Or did what is natural between women and men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.278#All this you may have at once. And if it happens
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.279#That the gods allow us to sack Priam's city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.280#You may when the Greeks are dividing the spoils
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.281#Load a ship to the brim with gold and bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.282#And choose for yourself the twenty Trojan women
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.283#Who are next in beauty to Argive Helen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.284#And if we return to the rich land of Argos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.285#You would marry his daughter, and he would honor you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.286#As he does Orestes, who is being reared in luxury.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.287#He has three daughters in his fortress palace,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.288#Chrysothemis, Laodice, and Iphianassa.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.289#You may lead whichever you like as your bride
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.290#Back to Peleus' house, without paying anything,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.291#And he would give her a dowry richer than any
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.292#A father has ever given his daughter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.293#And he will give you seven populous cities,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.294#Cardamyle, Enope, grassy Hire,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.295#Sacred Pherae, Antheia with its meadowlands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.296#Beautiful Aepeia, and Pedasus, wine country.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.297#They are all near the sea, on sandy Pylos' frontier,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.298#And cattlemen live there, rich in herds and flocks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.299#Who will pay you tribute as if you were a god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.300#And fulfill the shining decrees of your scepter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.301#All this he will do if you give up your grudge.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.302#But if Agamemnon is too hateful to you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.303#Himself and his gifts, think of all the others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.304#Suffering up and down the line, and of the glory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.305#You will win from them. They will honor you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.306#Like a god.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.307#And don't forget Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.308#You just might get him now. He's coming in close,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.309#Deluded into thinking that he has no match
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.310#In the Greek army that has landed on his beach."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.311#And Achilles, strong, swift, and godlike:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.312#"Son of Laertes in the line of Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.313#Odysseus the strategist---I can see
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.314#That I have no choice but to speak my mind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.315#And tell you exactly how things are going to be.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.316#Either that or sit through endless sessions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.317#Of people whining at me. I hate it like I hate hell
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.318#The man who says one thing and thinks another.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.319#So this is how I see it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.320#I cannot imagine Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.321#Or any other Greek, persuading me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.322#Not after the thanks I got for fighting this war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.323#Going up against the enemy day after day.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.324#It doesn't matter if you stay in camp or fight---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.325#In the end, everybody comes out the same.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.326#Coward and hero get the same reward:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.327#You die whether you slack off or work.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.328#And what do I have for all my suffering,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.329#Constantly putting my life on the line?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.330#Like a bird who feeds her chicks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.331#Whatever she finds, and goes without herself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.332#That's what I've been like, lying awake
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.333#Through sleepless nights, in battle for days
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.334#Soaked in blood, fighting men for their wives.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.335#I've raided twelve cities with our ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.336#And eleven on foot in the fertile Troad,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.337#Looted them all, brought back heirlooms
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.338#By the ton, and handed it all over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.339#To Atreus' son, who hung back in camp
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.340#Raking it in and distributing damn little.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.341#What the others did get they at least got to keep.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.342#They all have their prizes, everyone but me---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.343#I'm the only Greek from whom he took something back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.344#He should be happy with the woman he has.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.345#Why do the Greeks have to fight the Trojans?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.346#Why did Agamemnon lead the army to Troy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.347#If not for the sake of fair-haired Helen?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.348#Do you have to be descended from Atreus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.349#To love your mate? Every decent, sane man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.350#Loves his woman and cares for her, as I did,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.351#Loved her from my heart. It doesn't matter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.352#That I won her with my spear. He took her,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.353#Took her right out of my hands, cheated me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.354#And now he thinks he's going to win me back?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.355#He can forget it. I know how things stand.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.356#It's up to you, Odysseus, and the other kings
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.357#To find a way to keep the fire from the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.358#He's been pretty busy without me, hasn't he,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.359#Building a wall, digging a moat around it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.360#Pounding in stakes for a palisade.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.361#None of that stuff will hold Hector back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.362#When I used to fight for the Greeks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.363#Hector wouldn't come out farther from his wall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.364#Than the oak tree by the Western Gate.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.365#He waited for me there once, and barely escaped.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.366#Now that I don't want to fight him anymore,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.367#I will sacrifice to Zeus and all gods tomorrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.368#Load my ships, and launch them on the sea.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.369#Take a look if you want, if you give a damn,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.370#And you'll see my fleet on the Hellespont
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.371#In the early light, my men rowing hard.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.372#With good weather from the sea god,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.373#I'll reach Phthia after a three-day sail.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.374#I left a lot behind when I hauled myself here,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.375#And I'll bring back more, gold and bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.376#Silken-waisted women, grey iron---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.377#Everything except the prize of honor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.378#The warlord Agamemnon gave me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.379#And in his insulting arrogance took back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.380#So report back to him everything I say,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.381#And report it publicly---get the Greeks angry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.382#In case the shameless bastard still thinks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.383#He can steal us blind. He doesn't dare
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.384#Show his dogface here. Fine. I don't want
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.385#To have anything to do with him either.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.386#He cheated me, wronged me. Never again.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.387#He's had it. He can go to hell in peace,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.388#The half-wit that Zeus has made him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.389#His gifts? His gifts mean nothing to me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.390#Not even if he offered me ten or twenty times
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.391#His present gross worth and added to it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.392#All the trade Orchomenus does in a year,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.393#All the wealth laid up in Egyptian Thebes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.394#The wealthiest city in all the world,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.395#Where they drive two hundred teams of horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.396#Out through each of its hundred gates.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.397#Not even if Agamemnon gave me gifts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.398#As numberless as grains of sand or dust,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.399#Would he persuade me or touch my heart---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.400#Not until he's paid in full for all my grief.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.401#His daughter? I would not marry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.402#The daughter of Agamemnon son of Atreus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.403#If she were as lovely as golden Aphrodite
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.404#Or could weave like owl-eyed Athena.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.405#Let him choose some other Achaean
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.406#More to his lordly taste. If the gods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.407#Preserve me and I get home safe
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.408#Peleus will find me a wife himself.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.409#There are many Greek girls in Hellas and Phthia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.410#Daughters of chieftains who rule the cities.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.411#I can have my pick of any of them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.412#I've always wanted to take a wife there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.413#A woman to have and to hold, someone with whom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.414#I can enjoy all the goods old Peleus has won.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.415#Nothing is worth my life, not all the riches
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.416#They say Troy held before the Greeks came,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.417#Not all the wealth in Phoebus Apollo's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.418#Marble shrine up in craggy Pytho.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.419#Cattle and flocks are there for the taking;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.420#You can always get tripods and chestnut horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.421#But a man's life cannot be won back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.422#Once his breath has passed beyond his clenched teeth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.423#My mother Thetis, a moving silver grace,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.424#Tells me two fates sweep me on to my death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.425#If I stay here and fight, I'll never return home,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.426#But my glory will be undying forever.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.427#If I return home to my dear fatherland
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.428#My glory is lost but my life will be long,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.429#And death that ends all will not catch me soon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.430#As for the rest of you, I would advise you too
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.431#To sail back home, since there's no chance now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.432#Of storming Ilion's height. Zeus has stretched
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.433#His hand above her, making her people bold.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.434#What's left for you now is to go back to the council
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.435#And announce my message. It's up to them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.436#To come up with another plan to save the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.437#And the army with them, since this one,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.438#Based on appeasing my anger, won't work.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.439#Phoenix can spend the night here. Tomorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.440#He sails with me on our voyage home,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.441#If he wants to, that is. I won't force him to come."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.442#He spoke, and they were hushed in silence,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.443#Shocked by his speech and his stark refusal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.444#Finally the old horseman Phoenix spoke,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.445#Bursting into tears. He felt the ships were lost.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.446#"If you have set your mind on going home,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.447#Achilles, and will do nothing to save the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.448#From being burnt, if your heart is that angry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.449#How could I stay here without you, my boy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.450#All by myself? Peleus sent me with you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.451#On that day you left Phthia to go to Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.452#A child still, knowing nothing of warfare
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.453#Or assemblies where men distinguish themselves.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.454#He sent me to you to teach you this---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.455#To be a speaker of words and a doer of deeds.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.456#I could not bear to be left behind now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.457#Apart from you, child, not even if a god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.458#Promised to smooth my wrinkles and make me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.459#As young and strong as I was when I first left
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.460#The land of Hellas and its beautiful women.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.461#I was running away from a quarrel with Amyntor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.462#My father, who was angry with me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.463#Over his concubine, a fair-haired woman
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.464#Whom he loved as much as he scorned his wife,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.465#My mother. She implored me constantly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.466#To make love to his concubine so that this woman
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.467#Would learn to hate the old man. I did as she asked.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.468#My father found out and cursed me roundly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.469#Calling on the Furies to ensure that never
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.470#Would a child of mine sit on his knees.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.471#The gods answered his prayers, Underworld Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.472#And dread Persephone. I decided to kill him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.473#With a sharp sword, but some god calmed me down---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.474#Putting in my mind what people would say,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.475#The names they would call me---so that in fact
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.476#I would not be known as a parricide.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.477#From then on I could not bear to linger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.478#In my father's house, although my friends
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.479#And my family tried to get me to stay,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.480#Entreating me, slaughtering sheep and cattle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.481#Roasting whole pigs on spits, and drinking
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.482#Jar after jar of the old man's wine.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.483#For nine solid days they kept watch on me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.484#Working in shifts, staying up all night.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.485#The fires stayed lit, one under the portico
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.486#Of the main courtyard, one on the porch
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.487#In front of my bedroom door. On the tenth night,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.488#When it got dark, I broke through the latches
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.489#And vaulted over the courtyard fence,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.490#Eluding the watchmen and servant women.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.491#I was on the run through wide Hellas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.492#And made it to Phthia's black soil, her flocks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.493#And to Lord Peleus. He welcomed me kindly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.494#And loved me as a father loves his only son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.495#A grown son who will inherit great wealth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.496#He made me rich and settled me on the border,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.497#Where I lived as king of the Dolopians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.498#I made you what you are, my godlike Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.499#And loved you from my heart. You wouldn't eat,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.500#Whether it was at a feast or a meal in the house,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.501#Unless I set you on my lap and cut your food up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.502#And fed it to you and held the wine to your lips.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.503#Many a time you wet the tunic on my chest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.504#Burping up wine when you were colicky.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.505#I went through a lot for you, because I knew
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.506#The gods would never let me have a child
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.507#Of my own. No, I tried to make you my child,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.508#Achilles, so you would save me from ruin.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.509#But you have to master your proud spirit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.510#It's not right for you to have a pitiless heart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.511#Even the gods can bend. Superior as they are
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.512#In honor, power, and every excellence,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.513#They can be turned aside from wrath
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.514#When humans who have transgressed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.515#Supplicate them with incense and prayers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.516#With libations and savor of sacrifice.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.517#Yes, for Prayers are daughters of great Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.518#Lame and wrinkled and with eyes averted,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.519#They are careful to follow in Folly's footsteps,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.520#But Folly is strong and fleet, and outruns them all,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.521#Beating them everywhere and plaguing humans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.522#Who are cured by the Prayers when they come behind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.523#Revere the daughters of Zeus when they come,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.524#And they will bless you and hear your cry.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.525#Reject them and refuse them stubbornly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.526#And they will ask Zeus, Cronus' son, to have
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.527#Folly plague you, so you will pay in pain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.528#No, Achilles, grant these daughters of Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.529#The respect that bends all upright men's minds.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.530#If the son of Atreus were not offering gifts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.531#And promising more, if he were still raging mad,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.532#I would not ask you to shrug off your grudge
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.533#And help the Greeks, no matter how sore their need.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.534#But he is offering gifts and promising more,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.535#And he has sent to you a delegation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.536#Of the best men in the army, your dearest friends.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.537#Don't scorn their words or their mission here.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.538#No one could blame you for being angry before.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.539#We all know stories about heroes of old,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.540#How they were furiously angry, but later on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.541#Were won over with gifts or appeased with words.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.542#I remember a very old story like this, and since
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.543#We are all friends here, I will tell it to you now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.544#The Curetes were fighting the Aetolians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.545#In a bloody war around Calydon town.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.546#The Aetolians were defending their city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.547#And the Curetes meant to burn it down.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.548#This was all because gold-throned Artemis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.549#Had cursed the Curetes, angry that Oeneus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.550#Had not offered her his orchard's first fruits.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.551#The other gods feasted on bulls by the hundred,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.552#But Oeneus forgot somehow or other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.553#Only the sacrifice to great Zeus' daughter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.554#So the Archer Goddess, angry at heart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.555#Roused a savage boar, with gleaming white tusks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.556#And sent him to destroy Oeneus' orchard.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.557#The boar did a good job, uprooting trees
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.558#And littering the ground with apples and blossoms.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.559#But Oeneus' son, Meleager, killed it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.560#After getting up a party of hunters and hounds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.561#From many towns: it took more than a few men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.562#To kill this huge boar, and not before
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.563#It set many a hunter on the funeral pyre.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.564#But the goddess caused a bitter argument
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.565#About the boar's head and shaggy hide
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.566#Between the Curetes and Aetolians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.567#They went to war. While Meleager still fought
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.568#The Curetes had the worst of it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.569#And could not remain outside Calydon's wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.570#But when wrath swelled Meleager's heart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.571#As it swells even the hearts of the wise,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.572#And his anger rose against Althaea his mother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.573#He lay in bed with his wife, Cleopatra,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.574#Child of Marpessa and the warrior Idas.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.575#Idas once took up his bow against Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.576#To win lissome Marpessa. Her parents
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.577#Called the girl Halcyone back then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.578#Because her mother wept like a halcyon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.579#The bird of sorrows, because the Archer God,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.580#Phoebus Apollo, had stolen her daughter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.581#Meleager nursed his anger at Cleopatra's side,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.582#Furious because his mother had cursed him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.583#Cursed him to the gods for murdering his uncle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.584#Her brother, that is, and she beat the earth,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.585#The nurturing earth, with her hands, and called
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.586#Upon Hades and Persephone the dread,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.587#As she knelt and wet her bosom with tears,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.588#To bring death to her son. And the Fury
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.589#Who walks in darkness heard her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.590#From the pit of Erebus, and her heart was iron.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.591#Soon the enemy was heard at the walls again,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.592#Battering the gates. The Aetolian elders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.593#Sent the city's high priests to pray to Meleager
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.594#To come out and defend them, offering him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.595#Fifty acres of Calydon's richest land
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.596#Wherever he chose, half in vineyard,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.597#Half in clear plowland, to be cut from the plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.598#And the old horseman Oeneus shook his doors,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.599#Standing on the threshold of his gabled room,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.600#And recited a litany of prayers to his son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.601#As did his sisters and his queenly mother.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.602#He refused them all, and refused his friends,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.603#His very best friends and boon companions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.604#No one could move his heart or persuade him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.605#Until the Curetes, having scaled the walls
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.606#Were burning the city and beating down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.607#His bedroom door. Then his wife wailed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.608#And listed for him all the woes that befall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.609#A captured people---the men killed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.610#The town itself burnt, the women and children
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.611#Led into slavery. This roused his spirit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.612#He clapped on armor and went out to fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.613#And so he saved the Aetolians from doom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.614#Of his own accord, and they paid him none
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.615#Of those lovely gifts, savior or not.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.616#Don't be like that. Don't think that way,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.617#And don't let your spirit turn that way.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.618#The ships will be harder to save when they're burning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.619#Come while there are gifts, while the Achaeans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.620#Will still honor you as if you were a god.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.621#But if you go into battle without any gifts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.622#Your honor will be less, save us or not."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.623#And strong, swift-footed Achilles answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.624#"I don't need that kind of honor, Phoenix.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.625#My honor comes from Zeus, and I will have it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.626#Among these beaked ships as long as my breath
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.627#Still remains and my knees still move.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.628#Now listen to this. You're listening? Good.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.629#Don't try to confuse me with your pleading
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.630#On Agamemnon's behalf. If you're his friend
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.631#You're no longer mine, although I love you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.632#Hate him because I hate him. It's as simple as that.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.633#You're like a second father to me. Stay here,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.634#Be king with me and share half the honor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.635#These others can take my message. Lie down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.636#And spend the night on a soft couch. At daybreak
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.637#We will decide whether to set sail or stay."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.638#And he made a silent nod to Patroclus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.639#To spread a thick bed for Phoenix. It was time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.640#For the others to think about leaving. Big Ajax,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.641#Telamon's godlike son, said as much:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.642#"Son of Laertes in the line of Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.643#Resourceful Odysseus---it's time we go.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.644#I do not think we will accomplish
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.645#What we were sent here to do. Our job now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.646#Is to report this news quickly, bad as it is.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.647#They will be waiting to hear. Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.648#Has made his great heart savage.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.649#He is a cruel man, and has no regard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.650#For the love that his friends honored him with,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.651#Beyond anyone else who camps with the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.652#Pitiless. A man accepts compensation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.653#For a murdered brother, a dead son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.654#The killer goes on living in the same town
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.655#After paying blood money, and the bereaved
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.656#Restrains his proud spirit and broken heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.657#Because he has received payment. But you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.658#The gods have replaced your heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.659#With flint and malice, because of one girl,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.660#One single girl, while we are offering you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.661#Seven of the finest women to be found
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.662#And many other gifts. Show some generosity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.663#And some respect. We have come under your roof,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.664#We few out of the entire army, trying hard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.665#To be the friends you care for most of all."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.666#And Achilles, the great runner, answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.667#"Ajax, son of Telamon in the line of Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.668#Everything you say is after my own heart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.669#But I swell with rage when I think of how
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.670#The son of Atreus treated me like dirt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.671#In public, as if I were some worthless tramp.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.672#Now go, and take back this message:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.673#I won't lift a finger in this bloody war
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.674#Until Priam's illustrious son Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.675#Comes to the Myrmidons' ships and huts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.676#Killing Greeks as he goes and torching the fleet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.677#But when he comes to my hut and my black ship
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.678#I think Hector will stop, for all his battle lust."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.679#He spoke. They poured their libations
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.680#And headed for the ships, Odysseus leading.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.681#Patroclus ordered a bed made ready
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.682#For Phoenix, and the old man lay down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.683#On fleeces and rugs covered with linen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.684#And waited for bright dawn. Achilles slept
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.685#In an inner alcove, and by his side
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.686#Lay a woman he had brought from Lesbos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.687#With high, lovely cheekbones, Diomede her name,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.688#Phorbas' daughter. Patroclus lay down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.689#In the opposite corner, and with him lay Iphis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.690#A silken girl Achilles had given him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.691#When he took steep Scyrus, Enyeus' city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.692#By now Odysseus and Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.693#Were in Agamemnon's quarters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.694#Surrounded by officers drinking their health
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.695#From gold cups and shouting questions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.696#Agamemnon, the warlord, had priority:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.697#"Odysseus, pride of the Achaeans, tell me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.698#Is he willing to repel the enemy fire
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.699#And save the ships, or does he refuse,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.700#His great heart still in the grip of wrath?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.701#Odysseus, who endured all, answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.702#"Son of Atreus, most glorious Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.703#Far from quenching his wrath, Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.704#Is filled with even more. He spurns you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.705#And your gifts, and suggests that you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.706#Think of a way to save the ships and the army.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.707#He himself threatens, at dawn's first light,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.708#To get his own ships onto the water,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.709#And he said he would advise the others as well
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.710#To sail for home, since there is no chance now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.711#You will storm Ilion's height. Zeus has stretched
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.712#His hand above her, making her people bold.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.713#This is what he said, as these men here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.714#Who came with me will tell you, Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.715#And the two heralds, prudent men both.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.716#Phoenix will spend the night there. Tomorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.717#He sails with Achilles on his voyage home,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.718#If he wants to. He will not be forced to go."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.719#They were stunned by the force of his words
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.720#And fell silent for a long time, hushed in grief,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.721#Until at last Diomedes said in his booming voice:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.722#"Son of Atreus, glorious Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.723#You should never have pleaded with him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.724#Or offered all those gifts. Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.725#Was arrogant enough without your help.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.726#Let him do what he wants, stay here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.727#Or get the hell out. He'll fight later, all right,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.728#When he is ready or a god tells him to.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.729#Now I want everyone to do as I say.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.730#Enjoy some food and wine to keep up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.731#Your strength, and then get some sleep.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.732#When the rosy light first streaks the sky
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.733#Get your troops and horses into formation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.734#Before the ships. Fight in the front yourselves."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.735#The warlords assented, taken aback
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.736#By the authority of Diomedes' speech.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.737#Each man poured libation and went to his hut,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:9.738#Where he lay down and took the gift of sleep.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.1#All the other leaders of the Greek alliance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.2#Dozed through the night, subdued by soft sleep.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.3#But not Agamemnon. Sleep had no hold
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.4#On the troubled mind of the army's commander.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.5#Think of lightning: Hera's rich hair streams
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.6#In the sky when her husband builds storms---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.7#Heavy rain, or unspeakable hail, or snow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.8#That sifts down over cultivated land,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.9#Or the barbed-wire mouth of a battlefield.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.10#Thus Agamemnon, the density of the groans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.11#From his heart's deep core, his visceral fear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.12#Whenever he looked out over the Trojan plain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.13#He marvelled at how many fires burned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.14#Before Ilion's walls, and at the din of flutes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.15#And pipes, and the dull roar of humanity.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.16#And whenever he looked at the Greek ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.17#He pulled clumps of his hair out from the roots
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.18#In appeal to Zeus on high, and his heart ached.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.19#Nestor came to mind. He would go to Nestor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.20#And the two would find some way to save the army.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.21#He sat up and pulled on his tunic,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.22#Then laced on his sandals and threw a lion skin
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.23#Over his shoulders, a fiery, reddish thing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.24#That reached down to his feet. And he took his spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.25#Menelaus was just as troubled and sleepless.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.26#What would happen to all the Argives
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.27#Who had crossed the water for his sake
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.28#And come to Troy with war in their hearts?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.29#He drew around his shouders the dappled pelt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.30#Of a leopard, put a bronze helm on his head,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.31#And gripping his spear he went through camp
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.32#To waken his brother, the great warlord
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.33#Whom the common folk honored as a god.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.34#He found Agamemnon by the stern of his ship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.35#Putting on his armor and glad to see his brother.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.36#Menelaus, good at the war cry, said to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.37#"Brother, why are you arming yourself?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.38#To rouse someone to scout out the Trojans?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.39#I am afraid you will find few volunteers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.40#For this mission. To go alone by night
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.41#And spy on the enemy would take a brave man indeed."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.42#The warlord Agamemnon answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.43#"You and I need a plan, Menelaus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.44#A good one, to save the army and the ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.45#Now that Zeus has turned away from us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.46#He seems to prefer Hector's sacrifices to ours.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.47#I have never seen or heard of any one man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.48#Ever doing as much harm in a single day
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.49#As Hector has done today to our boys
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.50#By himself alone---and he is not even the son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.51#Of a goddess or god! Go now, run quickly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.52#Through the ships and summon Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.53#And Idomeneus, while I go to Nestor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.54#And see if he will go to the sentinels
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.55#And alert them. They would listen to him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.56#For his son is captain of the guard,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.57#He and Meriones, Idomeneus' comrade.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.58#It was to them especially we gave this command."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.59#And Menelaus, good at the war cry:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.60#"What are you telling me to do?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.61#To wait there with them until you come?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.62#Or run back after I have delivered your orders?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.63#And the warlord Agamemnon:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.64#"Wait there, or we may miss each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.65#As we cross the camp with all its paths.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.66#But give a shout wherever you go
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.67#And wake the men up. Call each man by name
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.68#And by his father's name, honoring them all.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.69#Let's you and I not be too proud to work.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.70#Zeus gave us this burden when we were born."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.71#And so Agamemnon sent his brother off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.72#But went himself to visit Nestor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.73#A shepherd to his people, and found him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.74#Lying on a soft bed next to his hut
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.75#And black ship. Beside him lay his rich gear---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.76#Shield, two spears, and gleaming helmet---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.77#And the shimmering belt he always wore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.78#When he armed to lead his men into battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.79#Nestor just didn't give in to grievous old age.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.80#He rose on his elbow and lifted his head,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.81#And asked these questions of Atreus' son:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.82#"Who are you, going alone through camp
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.83#In the dead of night when everyone's asleep?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.84#Are you looking for one of your mules
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.85#Or one of your friends? Speak out,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.86#And don't sneak up on me. What do you want?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.87#And Agamemnon, the great warlord:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.88#"Nestor, son of Neleus, our great glory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.89#You will know Agamemnon, Atreus' son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.90#The man whom Zeus besets with more troubles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.91#Than any man alive, as long as I draw my breath
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.92#And my knees still bend. I'm roaming like this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.93#Because sleep won't come, so worried am I
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.94#About the war and the Achaeans' troubles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.95#I'm so afraid for the army I'm losing my mind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.96#I toss and turn, my heart pounds through my chest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.97#And I can't stop trembling. If you want to help,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.98#Since it seems you can't sleep either,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.99#Come with me and let's go to the sentinels
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.100#So we can make sure they haven't fallen asleep
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.101#From fatigue and forgotten their watch.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.102#The enemy are bivouacked close by,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.103#And for all we know they might attack by night."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.104#And Nestor, the old Gerenian horseman:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.105#"Most glorious son of Atreus, lord Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.106#Zeus in his wisdom will not fulfill
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.107#All of Hector's hopes. No, his troubles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.108#Will be worse than ours, if only Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.109#Would have a change of heart and give up his grudge.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.110#Of course I will go with you, but we should
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.111#Wake up some others---Tydeus' son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.112#And Odysseus, and the swift Ajax,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.113#And Meges too. And someone should go
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.114#And summon the godlike Ajax as well,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.115#And Idomeneus, for their ships are the farthest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.116#As for Menelaus, dear and honored as he is,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.117#And even if it makes you angry, I will not shrink
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.118#From having a word with him myself, for sleeping
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.119#At a time like this and leaving you all the work.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.120#He should be hard at work beseeching all our best.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.121#This is a crisis we can no longer ignore."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.122#The warlord Agamemnon answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.123#"You may remind him of his responsibilities
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.124#Another time, old sir, and with my blessings.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.125#He is often unwilling to exert himself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.126#Not through sloth or lack of discernment,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.127#But in deference to my leadership.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.128#Just now, though, he awoke before I did
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.129#And came to me, and I sent him out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.130#To summon the men you are asking for.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.131#But we should go. We will find them at the gates
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.132#Among the guards, where I said they should gather."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.133#And Nestor, the old Gerenian horseman:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.134#"This is how he will earn the army's respect
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.135#And their compliance when he issues commands."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.136#So saying he pulled on his tunic,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.137#Laced sandals onto his supple feet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.138#And buckled around him a purple cloak,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.139#Two-ply and broad, with a thick nap.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.140#He grasped a mighty spear, tipped with honed bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.141#And went off through the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.142#Odysseus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.143#Who could match wits with Zeus, was the first
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.144#The old Gerenian horseman woke up.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.145#His voice echoed in Odysseus' dreaming mind,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.146#And the Ithacan came out of the hut and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.147#"Why are you going alone through the camp
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.148#In the dead of night? What's the emergency?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.149#And Nestor, the horseman of Gerenia:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.150#"Son of Laertes in the line of Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.151#Odysseus the strategist, don't be angry.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.152#We are under great duress. Come with us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.153#So we can rouse another whom we should consult
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.154#As we decide whether to fight or flee."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.155#And Odysseus, the master strategist,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.156#Got a shield from his hut and went with them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.157#They came to Diomedes, son of Tydeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.158#And found him outside his hut with his gear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.159#His men were sleeping all around him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.160#Using their shields for pillows, their spears
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.161#Driven upright in the ground on their spikes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.162#The bronze glittered like summer lightning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.163#The hero was asleep on an oxhide,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.164#A bright rug under his head. Nestor woke him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.165#Rolling him over with his heel, and scolded:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.166#"Up, son of Tydeus. Are you going to sleep all night?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.167#Don't you know the Trojans are encamped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.168#On the rising ground close by the ships?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.169#Diomedes was awake and up in an instant,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.170#And his words flew fast as he said to Nestor:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.171#"You're tough, old man, and you never quit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.172#Couldn't one of the younger generation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.173#Make the rounds waking up captains
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.174#All through camp? You're impossible, though."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.175#And Nestor, the horseman of Gerenia:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.176#"That was well said, friend. I myself have
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.177#Perfectly good sons, and there are many others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.178#Who could make the rounds and do the summoning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.179#But we are very hard-pressed. It all stands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.180#On a razor's edge now for the entire army,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.181#Ruin or survival. Now go rouse swift Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.182#And Meges---if you really feel sorry for me."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.183#Thus spoke Nestor. And Diomedes threw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.184#Over his shoulders a tawny lion skin
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.185#That reached to his feet. Grasping his spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.186#He went off to rouse and fetch the warriors.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.187#When they joined the sentinels they found them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.188#Wide awake, crouching down with their gear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.189#Dogs will watch a sheepfold all night long
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.190#With bloodshot eyes, but when they hear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.191#A predator approaching through the woods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.192#And then the noise of men and hounds around it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.193#Their sleepiness completely disappears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.194#So too these human eyes as the sentinels
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.195#Kept watch through the night, turning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.196#Toward the plain over and over again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.197#Whenever they thought they heard Trojans coming.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.198#It warmed Nestor's heart, and the old man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.199#Encouraged them with winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.200#"Just so, my boys, keep your watch. Stay awake,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.201#Or we will become sport for our enemies."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.202#And he hurried on through the trench, followed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.203#By all the captains summoned to this council,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.204#And by Meriones and Nestor's glorious son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.205#Whom they invited also. So they went through
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.206#And up from the trench and sat themselves down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.207#In an open spot where the ground was clear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.208#Of dead bodies, the very spot where Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.209#Had turned back from slaughtering the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.210#When night enfolded him. Sitting down there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.211#They held council, and Nestor began:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.212#"Well, my friends, is no one man enough
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.213#To go among the Trojans and take captive
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.214#Some straggler, or otherwise overhear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.215#What the enemy intends? Will they stay put
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.216#Out here by the ships, or withdraw to the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.217#Now that they have beaten the Achaeans back?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.218#A man might learn all this and return
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.219#Unscathed, and his glory among men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.220#Would reach the sky---and he would get gifts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.221#From every leader commanding ships here,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.222#From each a black ewe with a lamb beneath.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.223#What could be finer? And he would forever be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.224#Invited to feasts and to drinking parties."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.225#He finished, and they were hushed in silence.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.226#Then Diomedes rose to the occasion:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.227#"Nestor, my pride as a man urges me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.228#To go into the enemy camp over there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.229#But if another were to go with me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.230#It would help, and I would be more confident.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.231#When you work as a team, your partner helps see
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.232#What will work out best. Solo, you might see,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.233#But not as much, and you're short on wits."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.234#There was no shortage of volunteers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.235#To accompany Diomedes. Both Ajaxes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.236#Were ready, those servants of War,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.237#Ready was Meriones, and Nestor's son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.238#Ready Menelaus, the son of Atreus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.239#And Odysseus, who could endure anything,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.240#Ready to infiltrate the Trojan lines.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.241#Then the warlord Agamemnon spoke out:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.242#"Diomedes, son of Tydeus, dear to my heart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.243#Choose as your comrade whomever you want,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.244#The best of all these who put themselves forth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.245#Do not, out of deference, choose a lesser man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.246#And leave a better behind, deferring to birth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.247#And seniority, even if one is more royal."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.248#In truth, he was afraid for red-haired Menelaus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.249#Diomedes, good at the battle cry, said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.250#"If you really want me to make my own choice,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.251#How could I pass over godlike Odysseus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.252#Who has what it takes for any kind of work,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.253#The heart, the courage---and is Athena's friend.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.254#If he goes with me we could make it back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.255#Through blazing fire. He doesn't miss a thing."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.256#And Odysseus, who had endured many campaigns:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.257#"Diomedes, don't overrate my merits or my faults.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.258#You're talking to Greeks who know what's what.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.259#We'd better head out. It's very late,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.260#Getting on toward dawn. The stars have shifted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.261#And more than two-thirds of the night is gone."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.262#With that they put on their formidable gear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.263#Thrasymedes gave Diomedes a sword---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.264#He had left his own at his ship---and a shield.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.265#On his head he put a leather helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.266#Without horn or crest, the kind they call
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.267#A skullcap and that young warriors wear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.268#Meriones gave to Odysseus a bow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.269#A quiver, and a sword, while on his head
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.270#He put a helmet made of hide, stiffened
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.271#With numerous taut leather thongs inside
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.272#And faced outside with the gleaming white teeth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.273#Of a tusker boar set thick in alternate rows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.274#Cunningly and well. It was lined with felt.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.275#This helmet had been stolen by Autolycus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.276#From Amyntor's palace in Eleon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.277#And he gave it to Amphidamas of Cythera
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.278#To take to Scandeia, and Amphidamas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.279#Gave it as a guest gift to Molus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.280#Who gave it to his son Meriones to wear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.281#Now it protected Odysseus' head.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.282#When the two of them had all their gear on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.283#They headed out. Hard on their right
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.284#Pallas Athena sent a heron flying,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.285#And although they couldn't see the bird in the dark
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.286#They heard its night cry. Glad at the omen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.287#Odysseus said a prayer to Athena:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.288#"Hear me, child of Zeus Aegis-Holder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.289#You are ever by my side
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.290#In all my troubles, and you look over me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.291#Wherever I go. Be my friend
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.292#Once more, Athena, as never before.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.293#Grant that we return to the ships in glory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.294#Having done great deeds to confound the Trojans."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.295#And Diomedes, good at the battle cry:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.296#"Hear me also, mystic Daughter of Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.297#Go with me now even as you went
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.298#With my noble father Tydeus to Thebes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.299#When he went as envoy of the Achaeans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.300#Leaving them by the river Asopus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.301#He bore to the Cadmeians peaceful words
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.302#But on his return did violent deeds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.303#With you, divine one, standing beside him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.304#Be thou willing to stand by me now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.305#And I will sacrifice upon my return
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.306#A sleek heifer, broad-browed, unbroken,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.307#That man has not yet put under the yoke,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.308#And I will goldleaf her horns."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.309#Thus the heroes, and Athena heard them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.310#Their prayers said, the two moved forward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.311#Like two lions at midnight, picking their way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.312#Through corpses, weapons, and crusted black blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.313#Hector did not allow the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.314#To sleep either. He called together all their great,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.315#All of the Trojan leaders and chieftains,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.316#And laid before them this stratagem:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.317#"Who will volunteer for special duty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.318#And a hefty reward? I will guarantee
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.319#A chariot and two high-maned horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.320#The best in the Achaean beachhead camp,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.321#To the man who will dare to win himself glory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.322#By going close to the ships and spying out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.323#Whether they are still guarded as they used to be,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.324#Or whether our enemies, having suffered defeat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.325#At our hands, are planning their escape
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.326#And are too fatigued to watch through the night."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.327#He finished, and they were all hushed in silence.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.328#Among the Trojans was a certain Dolon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.329#Son of Eumedes, the godly herald, a man rich
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.330#In gold and bronze, ill-favored, but fast.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.331#He was the only brother among five sisters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.332#And the only Trojan to respond to Hector:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.333#"Hector, my pride as a man urges me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.334#To go close to the ships and scout around.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.335#But lift your staff and swear me an oath
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.336#That you really will give me the horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.337#And chariot, tricked in bronze, that carry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.338#The peerless Achilles. And I will not be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.339#A disappointment to you as a scout
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.340#But will go straight through their camp until I reach
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.341#Agamemnon's ship, where their leaders will be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.342#Deciding in council whether to fight or flee."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.343#So Hector took his staff and swore:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.344#"Zeus be my witness, Hera's thundering lord,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.345#That no other Trojan will drive these horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.346#But you alone will enjoy them forever."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.347#He swore an empty oath. Dolon, excited,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.348#Slung his curved bow around his shoulders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.349#Cloaked himself in a grey wolf skin
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.350#And put on a weasel cap. Taking a javelin
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.351#He left for the ships, but he never returned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.352#To bring any information to Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.353#He had passed the crowd of horses and men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.354#And was moving eagerly along when Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.355#Saw him coming and said to Diomedes:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.356#"There's someone coming from their camp,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.357#I don't know whether to spy on our ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.358#Or to strip one of the corpses. Let him get past
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.359#And down the plain a little. Then we can take him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.360#If he starts to outrun us, hem him in
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.361#Toward the ships and away from his camp.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.362#We don't want him to escape toward the city."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.363#So the two of them lay down among the dead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.364#Just off the path. Dolon ran by unaware
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.365#And had gone about the length of a furrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.366#A mule plows---they are better than oxen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.367#At pulling the plow in deep fallow land---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.368#When the two Greeks ran after him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.369#He stopped when he heard the sound, assuming
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.370#They were friends sent from the Trojan camp
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.371#To call him back, and that Hector had called a retreat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.372#They were within a spearcast before he realized
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.373#They were hostile. He started to run.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.374#Diomedes and Odysseus picked up their speed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.375#Like a pair of hounds on a hare or a doe
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.376#That goes bleating before it out in the woods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.377#They had him cut off and were hard in pursuit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.378#When Dolon was coming up to the sentinels
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.379#Athena put a burst of strength into Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.380#So that no other Achaean would be able to score
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.381#The first blow and Tydeus' son arrive too late.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.382#Diomedes closed the gap and called out:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.383#"Hold it. You're in spear range, and as good as dead."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.384#And he threw as he spoke, but purposely missed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.385#The point of the polished spear sailing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.386#Over the Trojan's right shoulder and into the ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.387#Dolon stopped in his tracks, terrified, stammering,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.388#His teeth chattering, and pale with fear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.389#His two pursuers came up, panting for breath,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.390#And seized his hands. Bursting into tears he said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.391#"Take me alive. I'm good for the ransom. At home
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.392#We have bronze and gold and well-wrought iron,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.393#And my father would give you unlimited ransom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.394#If he heard I was alive at the Achaean ships."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.395#And Odysseus, as wily as they come:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.396#"Get a grip, man. No one's going to kill you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.397#But tell me this, and give me a straight answer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.398#What are you doing out here by the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.399#Alone at night when everyone's sleeping?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.400#Do you have a mind to strip a corpse or two?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.401#Did Hector send you out on espionage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.402#Or are you acting on your own volition?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.403#Dolon's knees were shaking as he answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.404#"Hector lured me into this, filling my mind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.405#With foolish hopes. He promised to give me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.406#Achilles' horses and his chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.407#And he sent me out into the dead of night
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.408#To sneak up close to the enemy's ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.409#To find out whether they are guarded still,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.410#Or whether the Greeks, having suffered defeat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.411#At our hands, are planning their escape
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.412#And are too fatigued to watch through the night."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.413#Odysseus smiled at him wisely and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.414#"Your heart was set on a truly great reward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.415#Achilles' horses. But they are difficult
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.416#For mortal men to control. Only Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.417#Born of a goddess, can master them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.418#But tell me this, and give it to me straight:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.419#Where did you leave Hector when you left?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.420#Where is his battle gear and where are his horses?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.421#How are the Trojans encamped and guarded?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.422#And what is their plan? Will they stay put
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.423#Out here by the ships, or withdraw to the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.424#Now that they have beaten the Achaeans back?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.425#And Dolon, Eumedes' only son:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.426#"I'll tell you everything straight. Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.427#Is holding council at the tomb of Ilus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.428#Away from the turmoil. As for sentinels,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.429#None have been posted to guard the camp.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.430#The Trojans keep watch around their fires,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.431#Urging one and another to stay awake,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.432#But the allies, coming from many lands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.433#Are all asleep, leaving it to the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.434#To keep watch, since their own children
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.435#Are nowhere near, nor their women."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.436#Odysseus, full of cunning, continued:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.437#"Then are the allies camped with the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.438#Or apart by themselves? I want the details."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.439#Dolon, son of Eumedes, responded:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.440#"I'll tell you everything straight. Toward the sea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.441#Are the Carians and Paeonians, archers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.442#Along with the Leleges, Cauconians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.443#And the Pelasgi. Over toward Thymbre
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.444#Is the Lycian sector. The Mysians are there too,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.445#Along with the charioteers from Phrygia
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.446#And Maeonia. But why all these details?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.447#If you want to infiltrate the Trojan camp,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.448#The Thracians are here at this edge, just arrived
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.449#With their king Rhesus, son of Eïoneus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.450#He has the finest horses I ever saw, the greatest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.451#Whiter than snow and as fast as the wind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.452#His chariot is done in silver and gold,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.453#And he came with this massive gold armor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.454#Amazing to see, not what mortal men wear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.455#But what you'd expect on the deathless gods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.456#But look, take me to the ships now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.457#Or leave me tied up here, so you two can go
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.458#And see for yourselves if I'm telling the truth."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.459#Diomedes looked at him darkly and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.460#"Don't even think about getting off, Dolon---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.461#Although you've been a fine messenger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.462#You've fallen into our hands. If we let you go
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.463#You'll come to the Greeks' ships another time,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.464#Either to spy on us or to fight in combat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.465#If I take care of you now and make sure you're dead,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.466#You'll never worry the Greeks again."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.467#Dolon was reaching up to Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.468#In supplication---had almost touched his chin---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.469#When Diomedes sprang and with his sword
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.470#Severed the tendons at the nape of his neck.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.471#He was still shrieking when his mouth caught the sand.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.472#They stripped the ferret-skin cap from his head
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.473#And took the wolf's hide, the recurved bow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.474#And the long spear. Odysseus held these up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.475#And prayed to Athena the Despoiler:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.476#"Rejoice in these, Goddess, first of Olympians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.477#To receive our offerings. Guide us once more,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.478#Now to where the Thracians and their horses sleep."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.479#With that, he hoisted the gear into a tamarisk
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.480#And stashed it there, leaving as a marker
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.481#A bundle of branches that they couldn't miss
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.482#On their way back through the black rush of night.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.483#Then they went forward through the carnage and weapons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.484#Until they came to their goal: the Thracian camp.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.485#The exhausted soldiers were sound asleep, their gear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.486#In three neat rows on the ground around them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.487#And by each man stood his chariot team.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.488#Rhesus slept in the middle, his thoroughbreds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.489#Tethered by the reins to the chariot's deck.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.490#Odysseus pointed him out to Diomedes:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.491#"There he is, Diomedes, with his horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.492#The man that Dolon told us about.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.493#Well? Don't just stand there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.494#Slouching in your armor. Untie his horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.495#Or you kill the men and leave the horses to me."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.496#The Grey-Eyed One breathed into Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.497#And he went up and down the row of Thracians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.498#Killing them one by one. Their groans were ugly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.499#When the sword struck. The ground turned to red mud.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.500#A lion comes to an unguarded pen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.501#Of sheep or goats and leaps in with malice.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.502#So Tydeus' son went through the Thracians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.503#Until he had killed twelve. Odysseus, always thinking,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.504#Pulled each body out of the way by the feet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.505#As soon as Diomedes did his work with the sword,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.506#So that the combed horses would have an easy path
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.507#And not be spooked by having to step over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.508#Dead bodies, which they were as yet unused to.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.509#The thirteenth was Rhesus. As Tydeus' son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.510#Separated him from the sweetness of life,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.511#He gasped for breath. Diomedes stood over him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.512#That night, in a bad dream sent by Athena.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.513#By now Odysseus had the horses free
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.514#And roped together with the reins.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.515#He drove them out of the Trojan camp
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.516#With his bow, not having noticed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.517#The gleaming whip in the chariot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.518#He whistled over to Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.519#Who was pondering his next reckless move.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.520#Should he pull the chariot out by its pole,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.521#Or dump the gear piled in it and carry it out?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.522#Or should he just kill more Thracians?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.523#While he was weighing his options, Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.524#Stood near to him and said to the hero:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.525#"Time to get back, son of great Tydeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.526#To the hollow ships, before some other god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.527#Rouses the Trojans and you are chased back."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.528#He knew it was the voice of the goddess
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.529#And quickly mounted the horses. Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.530#Smacked them with his bow, and they made for the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.531#Apollo was out that night too,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.532#And when he saw Athena helping Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.533#He made his silver presence felt in the camp
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.534#And awakened Hippocoön, a Thracian lord,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.535#One of Rhesus' high-born kinsmen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.536#He started from his sleep, and when he saw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.537#The place empty where the horses had stood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.538#And the men gasping in pools of blood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.539#He groaned and called his old friend by name.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.540#Then everything was confusion and noise,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.541#The Trojans running up from all over the camp
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.542#To view the havoc wreaked by the warriors
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.543#Who by now were halfway back to the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.544#When they reached the spot where they had killed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.545#Hector's spy, Odysseus reined in the horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.546#Diomedes jumped down and handed up to him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.547#The bloody spoils, then mounted again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.548#And lashed the horses, who flew on to the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.549#Nestor heard the sound first and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.550#"Friends, Argive commanders and counsellors,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.551#I may be mistaken but still I must speak.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.552#The sound of horses' hooves strikes my ears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.553#Let us hope that Odysseus and strong Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.554#Have rustled some horses away from the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.555#But I fear in my heart that the best of the Argives
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.556#Have come to harm in the enemy camp."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.557#He was hardly finished when they arrived.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.558#They got down and were welcomed warmly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.559#With handclasps and gentle words.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.560#Gerenian Nestor was first with his questions:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.561#"Praise be, Odysseus, glory of the Greeks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.562#Where did you two come by these horses?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.563#In the Trojan camp? Or did you meet some god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.564#Who gave them to you? They shine like the sun.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.565#I'm always among the Trojans. Old I may be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.566#For a warrior, but I don't stay with the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.567#But I never saw such horses as these.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.568#No, I think a god met you and gave them to you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.569#Zeus in the clouds loves you both, as does
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.570#His grey-eyed daughter who bears the aegis."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.571#And Odysseus, wise in every way:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.572#"Nestor, son of Neleus, glory of the Greeks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.573#A god could easily give us, if he wanted,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.574#Even better horses. Such is heaven's power.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.575#No, these horses, old sir, have just come
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.576#From Thrace. Diomedes killed their master
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.577#And twelve of his comrades, all their best.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.578#And we got one more, a scout near the ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.579#Somebody Hector and the Trojan lords
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.580#Sent out to spy on our beachhead camp."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.581#And he drove the horses across the trench,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.582#Roaring with laughter. The others followed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.583#In high spirits, and when they came to Diomedes'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.584#Well-built shelter they bound them with thongs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.585#At the stall where his horses stood champing grain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.586#And on the stern of his ship Odysseus placed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.587#The bloody spoils of Dolon, until such time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.588#As they could prepare a sacrifice for Athena.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.589#Then they waded into the sea and let the waves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.590#Wash the thick sweat from their legs and necks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.591#Until they felt refreshed. Then they went to the tubs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.592#After their bath they rubbed on rich oil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.593#And sat down to eat, drawing off wine
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:10.594#From the brimming bowl to pour to Athena.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.1#Dawn left her splendid Tithonus in bed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.2#And rose to bring light to immortals and men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.3#As Zeus launched Eris, the goddess Strife,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.4#Down to the Greek ships, a talisman of War
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.5#Clutched in her hands. She took her stand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.6#Near the great black hull of Odysseus' ship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.7#Which lay in the middle, so a shout could reach
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.8#Ajax's huts on one end of camp and Achilles'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.9#On the other. These two had beached their ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.10#On the flanks, confident in their manhood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.11#Standing there, she emitted a yell that rose
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.12#In volume and pitch until it seemed to each Greek
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.13#That fighting to the death was far preferable
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.14#To sailing home in their hollow ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.15#Agamemnon boomed out a command
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.16#For his men to arm, and did so himself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.17#Strapping on sunlit bronze, his greaves first,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.18#Works of art, trimmed with silver at the ankles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.19#Then he covered his chest with a corselet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.20#A gift from the Cypriot king, Cinyras.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.21#News had reached Cyprus that the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.22#Were launching a fleet for Troy, and Cinyras
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.23#Sent this corselet as homage to the warlord.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.24#It had ten bands of dark blue enamel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.25#Twelve of gold, and twenty of tin.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.26#On either side were three enameled dragons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.27#With arching necks---iridescent as rainbows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.28#That Zeus anchors in cloud as portents for men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.29#And he slung a sword around his shoulders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.30#Golden bolts shining in the hilt. The sheath
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.31#Was silver, fitted with golden straps.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.32#Then he took up his shield, a crafted glory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.33#Of metalwork, ringed with bronze, bossed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.34#With white tin, and inlaid with dark cyan,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.35#A Gorgon flanked by Terror and Rout
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.36#Glaring out of the midnight blue center.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.37#The shield was hung with a baldric of silver
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.38#Upon which writhed an enameled dragon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.39#With three heads twisting from a single neck.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.40#He set upon his head a two-horned helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.41#With four bosses and a horsehair plume
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.42#That nodded menacingly on its crest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.43#The spears that he took tapered to bronze points
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.44#Honed with light. The sky caught their glare,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.45#And Hera and Athena thundered in response,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.46#Honoring the lord of gold-crusted Mycenae.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.47#The drivers had orders to keep their horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.48#In a steady line up and down the trench
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.49#While the heroes moved forward on foot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.50#In full battle gear. The shout the troops gave
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.51#When they finally charged filled the dawn sky.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.52#The charioteers let them have a long lead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.53#And then closed the gap from behind. Thunder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.54#Rolled up from the plain like black dust, and Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.55#Soon to be pitching strong souls into Hades,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.56#Rained drops of blood from the crystal air.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.57#Opposite them the Trojans, on rising ground,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.58#Gathered around their heroes, great Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.59#Polydamas, Aeneas, and Antenor's three sons,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.60#Polybus, Agenor, and young Acamas---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.61#All of whom could have passed as immortal gods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.62#Hector, behind the perfect circle of his shield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.63#Shone like a death star in a bank of clouds,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.64#Sometimes passing behind them as he moved
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.65#From the front lines to the rear, issuing commands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.66#And his bronze flashed like Zeus' lightning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.67#Reapers are working toward each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.68#In a rich man's field, cutting huge swaths
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.69#Of barley or wheat, and the grain falls in piles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.70#The Greeks and Trojans kept coming on.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.71#Turning their backs would have meant
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.72#A disastrous rout. They fought on equal terms,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.73#Head to head, going after each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.74#Like rabid wolves. Eris looked on rejoicing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.75#The only god who took the field that day.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.76#All of the others kept their peace,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.77#Idle in their homes on Olympus' ridges,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.78#Sulking because the Dark Cloud, Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.79#Meant to cover the Trojans with glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.80#The Patriarch paid them no mind. He sat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.81#Apart from the others in glorious solitude,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.82#Looking down at Troy and the Achaean ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.83#The flash of bronze, men killing and being killed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.84#As long as the holy light climbed toward noon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.85#Men were hit and fell on both sides of the battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.86#Toward evening, the woodsman turns home,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.87#His hands sore from swinging his axe
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.88#And his heart weary from felling tall trees,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.89#And all his desire is for the sweetness of food.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.90#About that time in the long afternoon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.91#The Danaans broke through, their captains calling,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.92#Calling each other through the ranks of men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.93#Until their valor split the enemy lines.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.94#Agamemnon led the way, taking out Bienor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.95#A Trojan commander, and his driver, Oïleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.96#Oïleus at least had the chance to jump down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.97#And face Agamemnon, but as he charged
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.98#The warlord's spear drove into his forehead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.99#Oïleus' heavy bronze helm had little effect
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.100#On the spear's sharp point, which penetrated
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.101#Not only the helmet's rim but the skull's bone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.102#Scrambling the grey stuff inside. So much
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.103#For these two. The warlord left them there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.104#Their naked chests gleaming in the level light,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.105#And went on to kill Isus and Antiphus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.106#Two sons of Priam, bastard and legitimate,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.107#Riding in one car. The bastard held the reins
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.108#And Antiphus stood by. Achilles once
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.109#Had bound these two with willow branches,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.110#Surprising them as they watched their sheep
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.111#On Ida's hills, and later released them for ransom.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.112#Now Agamemnon, Atreus' wide-ruling son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.113#Hit Isus with his spear above the nipple
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.114#And Antiphus with his sword beside his ear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.115#Knocking both from the car. As he was busy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.116#Stripping their armor he recognized their faces
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.117#From the time when Achilles had brought them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.118#Down from Ida and to the beachhead camp.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.119#Imagine how easily a lion crushes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.120#A pair of fawns in his powerful jaws.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.121#He has come to where they lie huddled together
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.122#On the forest floor, and has ripped out their hearts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.123#And though their mother is near she can do
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.124#Nothing to save them. Trembling herself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.125#She bolts through the thick woods, and sweat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.126#Glazes her skin as she flees the great cat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.127#The Trojans were chased off, none of them able
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.128#To help Agamemnon's two victims.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.129#Peisander and Hippolochus were next,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.130#Battle-hardened sons of Antimachus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.131#Who in the shrewdness of his heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.132#And in consideration of Paris' substantial gifts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.133#Had argued against surrendering Helen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.134#To blond Menelaus. Agamemnon now took
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.135#His two sons instead. Together in one car
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.136#They were trying to get their rearing horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.137#Under control---the reins had slipped from their hands---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.138#When Agamemnon charged them like a lion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.139#They fell to their knees in their chariot's basket:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.140#"Take us alive, son of Atreus, for ransom.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.141#Antimachus' palace is piled high with treasure,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.142#Gold and bronze and wrought iron our father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.143#Would give you past counting once he found out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.144#We were alive and well among the Greek ships."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.145#Sweet words, and they salted them with tears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.146#But the voice they heard was anything but sweet:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.147#"Your father Antimachus---if you really are
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.148#His sons---once urged the Trojan assembly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.149#To kill Menelaus on the spot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.150#When he came with Odysseus on an embassy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.151#Now you will pay for his heinous offense."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.152#He spoke, and knocked Peisander backward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.153#Out of his chariot with a spear through his chest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.154#And sent him sprawling on the ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.155#Hippolochus leapt down. Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.156#Used his sword to slice off both arms
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.157#And lop off his head, sending his torso
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.158#Rolling like a stone column through the crowd.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.159#He didn't bother them further, but pressed on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.160#To where the fighting was thickest, Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.161#In their leg-armor crowding in behind him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.162#Killing Trojans on foot, from chariots,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.163#Dust rolling up from the plain like thunder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.164#Under the horses' hooves, and all the while
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.165#In the blood-red bronze, Agamemnon killing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.166#Calling to his Greeks, the great warlord
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.167#Like fire consuming dry manzanita
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.168#When the winds rise up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.169#And the scrub forest is burned to its roots,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.170#The Trojans falling as they fled,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.171#And the horses, arching their necks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.172#Rattled empty cars along the lanes of war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.173#Feeling the absence of their faultless masters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.174#Who lay sprawled on the ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.175#Dearer now to vultures than to their wives.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.176#Zeus drew Hector out of the boiling dust,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.177#Out of the blood, out of the noise and the slaughter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.178#While Agamemnon pressed on,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.179#Howling to his Greeks to follow him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.180#Past the ancient tomb of Ilus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.181#Over the middle of the plain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.182#Beyond the windy fig tree
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.183#They rushed toward the city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.184#Yearned for it, the son of Atreus calling them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.185#Calling, his hard hands spattered with gore.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.186#But when they came to the Western Gate
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.187#And the oak tree there, the two armies halted,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.188#Waiting. There were still some Trojan stragglers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.189#Being driven across the plain like cattle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.190#In the dead of night a lion rushes a herd,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.191#Scattering them all, though only one heifer will die.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.192#He crushes her neck first in his teeth,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.193#Then greedily laps up all her soft insides.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.194#Agamemnon picked off the hindmost Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.195#One by one, toppling them from their chariots,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.196#And was coming up to Ilion's steep wall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.197#When the Father of Gods and Men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.198#Came down from heaven and onto Ida's peaks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.199#In one step, a thunderbolt in his hands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.200#And sent gold-winged Iris off with a message:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.201#"Go, swift Iris, and take word to Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.202#That as long as he sees Lord Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.203#Storming through the ranks and laying them low
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.204#He should hold back and order other troops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.205#To engage the enemy. But when at last
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.206#Agamemnon is wounded by an arrow or spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.207#And mounts his chariot, then will I
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.208#Loan Hector strength to kill and keep killing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.209#Until he comes to the thwarted ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.210#And the sun sets and sacred darkness falls."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.211#Thus Zeus, and Iris moved like rain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.212#Down from Ida's hills and to holy Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.213#Seeking Hector, splendor of Priam's house,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.214#And found him standing in his chariot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.215#Iris hovered nearby on windy feet:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.216#"Hector, son of Priam, Father Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.217#Has sent me here with a message for you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.218#As long as you see Lord Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.219#Storming through the ranks and laying them low
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.220#You should hold back and order other troops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.221#To engage the enemy. But when at last
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.222#Agamemnon is wounded by an arrow or spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.223#And mounts his chariot, then will Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.224#Loan you the strength to kill and keep killing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.225#Until you come to the thwarted ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.226#And the sun sets and sacred darkness falls."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.227#Iris spoke and was gone, and Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.228#Vaulted from his chariot with all his gear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.229#Brandishing a pair of spears he toured the troops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.230#And worked them into a frenzy for battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.231#A ripple moved through their lines as they turned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.232#And faced the Greeks. Over against them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.233#The Achaean forces stiffened their lines.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.234#The two armies were poised for battle, but one man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.235#Agamemnon, charged forward first,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.236#Determined to fight far in advance of all.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.237#And now, Muses, who reside on Olympus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.238#Tell me who came, of all the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.239#And their famed allies, to face Agamemnon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.240#It was Iphidamas, one of Antenor's sons,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.241#A good man, tall, bred on Thracian farmland.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.242#His mother was Theano, and her father,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.243#Cisseus, raised the boy from infancy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.244#When he came of age, Cisseus gave him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.245#His own daughter in marriage to keep him there.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.246#But Iphidamas left her in the bridal chamber
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.247#And went chasing after glory when he heard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.248#The Achaeans were coming. He sailed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.249#With twelve trim ships, left them at Percote,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.250#And came overland to Troy. Now he faced
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.251#Agamemnon, son of Atreus. When they closed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.252#To within range of each other, Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.253#Cast and missed. Iphidamas stepped in
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.254#And stabbed him just beneath the corselet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.255#Putting his weight behind the thrust
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.256#And trusting his strong wrist to drive the spear home
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.257#Through the glittering belt, but the point
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.258#Bent like lead as soon as it hit the silver.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.259#The great warlord seized the spear's haft
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.260#And with a lion's ferocity pulled it toward him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.261#And out of Iphidamas' hands. A sword stroke
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.262#To the neck made his body go slack,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.263#And Iphidamas fell in a sleep of bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.264#The town hero, far from his wedded wife,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.265#Who gave him no joy, though he gave much for her,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.266#A hundred head of cattle, a thousand sheep and goats
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.267#On promise from his countless herds.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.268#Agamemnon stripped his costly armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.269#And paraded it through the Achaean troops.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.270#When Antenor's eldest son, Coön,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.271#Saw his brother fall, his eyes stung with grief.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.272#Working his way to Agamemnon's blind side
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.273#He lunged with his spear and hit him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.274#Below his left elbow, the point piercing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.275#The forearm's sinew. The great warlord
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.276#Shuddered, but without missing a step
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.277#Jumped at Coön, who was now hauling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.278#His brother Iphidamas away by his foot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.279#The son of Atreus' wind-hardened spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.280#Caught him under his shield, and as his limbs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.281#Went slack, Agamemnon reached over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.282#His brother's body to sever his head.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.283#So Antenor's two sons fulfilled their destiny
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.284#Under the warlord's hands and sank into the gloom.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.285#Agamemnon continued his killing rampage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.286#With spear, sword, and chunks of rock
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.287#As long as blood flowed warm from the wound.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.288#But when the wound dried and the blood caked,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.289#The pain set in, needling and sharp,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.290#As if he were a woman in labor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.291#Struggling with the stabbing pain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.292#Hera's daughters dispense
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.293#When they preside at a childbirth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.294#Agamemnon, in agony, leapt onto his chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.295#And told the driver to make for the ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.296#Then boomed out a final order to his men:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.297#"Commanders of Greece, the battle is yours!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.298#Keep the war from our ships. Zeus almighty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.299#Has not seen fit to let me fight the whole day."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.300#And the charioteer lashed the horses on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.301#To the beached ships. Manes streaming,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.302#Chests flecked with foam, bellies dust-stained,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.303#They bore the wounded warlord from battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.304#When Hector saw Agamemnon leaving,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.305#He called to the Trojans and Lycians:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.306#"Trojans and Lycians, Dardanian warriors,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.307#Be men, my friends, and remember your valor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.308#Their best man is gone, and Zeus has granted me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.309#A great victory. Drive your horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.310#Directly at them and win the power and glory."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.311#And he set them on the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.312#The way a hunter sets his grinning dogs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.313#On a boar or a lion, leading the way himself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.314#Hector, son of Priam, peer of Ares, bane of mortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.315#Falling on the conflict the way a windstorm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.316#Falls on the sea and churns the violet water.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.317#He killed Asaeus first, and Autonous,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.318#And not a few other Danaan leaders---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.319#Dolops, son of Clytius, Opheltius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.320#Agelaus, Aesymnus, Orus, Hipponous---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.321#Then fell on the common soldiery.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.322#Imagine the westerly squalls you have seen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.323#Battering clouds in a silver sky.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.324#The waves curl and blister on the sea below,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.325#And lines of spray shear off in the wind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.326#Hector's assault was much like this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.327#With Greek heads toppling everywhere.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.328#He might have driven them once and for all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.329#Back to their ships in a final rout,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.330#Had not Odysseus called to Tydeus' son:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.331#"Diomedes, what's the matter with us? Have we
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.332#Forgotten how to fight? Take a stand here with me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.333#There'll be hell to pay if Hector takes the ships."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.334#And Diomedes, tough as nails:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.335#"I'm in it for the long haul. But our fun
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.336#Won't last long. The god in the clouds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.337#Has decided to boost the Trojans, not us."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.338#With that, he knocked Thymbraeus from his chariot---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.339#A spearcast to his left nipple---while Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.340#Took out Molion, his godlike protégé.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.341#They left them there with no more fight in them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.342#And moved on, working as a team, spilling guts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.343#Like a pair of boars that fall on a pack of dogs,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.344#Turning the Trojans back and giving the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.345#A welcome respite from Hector's onslaught.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.346#Two of their more notable victims
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.347#Were from Percote, sons of Merops,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.348#A skilled prophet who would not allow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.349#His sons to go to war. They went anyway,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.350#Led on by Death's blackness. Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.351#Robbed them of their lives and armor. Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.352#Did the same for Hippodamus and Hypeirochus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.353#Zeus, observing from Ida, reached down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.354#And stretched the battle line out evenly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.355#The killing continued. Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.356#Wounded the hero Agastrophus, Paeon's son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.357#On the hip with a thrust of his spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.358#Agastrophus looked for his horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.359#Forgot where his driver was holding them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.360#And lost his head. He was dead before long.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.361#When Hector spotted Odysseus and Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.362#Across the ranks, he mounted a charge.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.363#His shout brought with him battalions of Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.364#Diomedes, always there when you needed him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.365#Shuddered when he saw Hector coming on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.366#And said to Odysseus, who was a few yards away:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.367#"Here comes Hector, like a damned avalanche.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.368#Let's hold our ground and beat him off."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.369#He spoke, poised his long-shadowed spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.370#And cast, a good, hard shot to Hector's head.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.371#The spearpoint ricocheted off the helmet's rim,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.372#Bronze off bronze (Apollo had given him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.373#This three-ply crest), and never touched his skin.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.374#But Hector bounded back an amazing distance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.375#And took cover in the crowd, down on his knees
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.376#With one hand on the ground. He blacked out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.377#For some time, and then, while Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.378#Was tracking down his spear, revived again,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.379#Mounted his chariot, and drove off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.380#Through the throng, escaping a darker fate.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.381#Diomedes ran after him with his spear, shouting:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.382#"Got away again, didn't you, you dog?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.383#By the skin of your teeth! Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.384#Has bailed you out once more. You must be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.385#A regular devotee, praying each time you go out.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.386#I'll finish you off next time we meet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.387#If I have a god on my side. Meanwhile,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.388#Let's see who gets my business now."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.389#He spoke, and proceeded to strip the armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.390#From Agastrophus. But Alexander,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.391#Helen's fair-haired lord, was aiming an arrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.392#At the son of Tydeus, bracing himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.393#Against a pillar on the tomb of Ilus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.394#A Trojan elder in days gone by.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.395#Diomedes had unstrapped the gleaming corselet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.396#From Agastrophus' torso and was busy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.397#Removing the shield and heavy helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.398#When Paris drew the arrowhead back to the grip,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.399#Released the shaft, and scored a hit, the arrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.400#Passing through the instep of Diomedes' right foot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.401#And sticking in the ground. Paris laughed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.402#And, jumping out of his blind, crowed:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.403#"You're hit! My arrow didn't miss!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.404#I wish it had gone in your gut and killed you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.405#So the Trojans could have some breathing room.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.406#They're trembling like goats before a lion."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.407#There was no hint of fear in Diomedes' response:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.408#"You sissy, curly-haired pimp of a bowman!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.409#Why don't you come down and fight me man to man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.410#And see how far your bow and arrow get you?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.411#Boasting because you scratched my foot!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.412#I might as well have been hit by a woman
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.413#Or imbecile child. A weakling's weapon is blunt.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.414#When I throw a spear it kills you on contact---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.415#My throw makes it sharp---and your widow's cheeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.416#Are torn with grief, your children are fatherless,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.417#Your blood reddens the earth, and you rot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.418#With more birds than women around you."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.419#When Diomedes finished, Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.420#Stepped in front of him with his spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.421#Diomedes sat down behind him and pulled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.422#The arrow from his foot. The pain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.423#Was sickening. He limped onto his chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.424#And told the driver to head for the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.425#This left Odysseus alone. Every Greek
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.426#In the vicinity had fled in fear. Troubled,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.427#Odysseus said to no one but himself:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.428#"Now what? It will be bad enough
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.429#If I lose my nerve and run, but worse yet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.430#If I am caught here alone, as I will be,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.431#Since Zeus has scattered all the Danaans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.432#But why am I talking to myself like this?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.433#I know only cowards depart from battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.434#A real warrior stands his ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.435#Whether he is hit or hits another."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.436#While he thought it over, the Trojans closed in,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.437#Encircling their own peril.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.438#Dogs and hunters will go after a boar
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.439#From all sides, and when he comes out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.440#Of the deep brush, whetting his white tusks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.441#In his curving jaws, they charge at him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.442#And although the sound of his gnashing tusks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.443#Inspires sheer terror, they keep coming at him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.444#So too around Odysseus, dear to Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.445#The Trojans rushed in. Odysseus sprang
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.446#And hit Deiopites first, coming down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.447#With his sharp spear onto his shoulder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.448#Thoön and Eunomus were no great trouble,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.449#And then he stabbed Chersidamas in his navel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.450#Under his shield, as he leapt from his chariot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.451#Chersidamas fell and clawed at the dust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.452#Paying these no mind, he put his spear through
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.453#A man named Charops, whose brother, Socus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.454#Now came up to help him. Socus was rich
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.455#And well-born, a man the equal of a god.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.456#He put his face in Odysseus' and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.457#"So this is Odysseus, who can't get enough
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.458#Of cunning and trouble. Today you will either
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.459#Boast you have killed Hippasus' two sons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.460#Or go down yourself under my spear."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.461#And he hit the circle of Odysseus' shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.462#With such force that the spear fought its way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.463#All the way through, penetrated the metal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.464#Of the ornamented corselet, and ripped the flesh
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.465#From the side of his ribs, but Pallas Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.466#Would not let it pierce his inner organs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.467#Odysseus knew the wound was not fatal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.468#He pulled back a step and said to Socus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.469#"You're as good as dead, you sorry bastard.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.470#You may have put me out of commission,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.471#But this is the last day on earth for you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.472#Flattened by my spear you will give glory to me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.473#And your life to Hades, famed for his horses."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.474#This was enough for Socus. He turned to run,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.475#But as he was turning, Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.476#Rammed his spear between his shoulders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.477#And drove it all the way through to his chest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.478#He fell with a thud, and Odysseus exulted:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.479#"Ah, Socus, Death was too quick for you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.480#And you couldn't dodge it. Your parents
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.481#Will not close your eyes on a bier. No, birds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.482#Will eat your flesh raw, fanning their wings.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.483#But if I die, the Greeks will give me burial."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.484#So saying, he drew Socus' spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.485#Out of his flesh and from his bossed shield.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.486#Blood spurted out; the pain tore at his heart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.487#The Trojans, watching, signalled each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.488#And advanced in a body. Odysseus gave ground,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.489#Shouting to his comrades still on the field.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.490#Menelaus heard each call, and said to Ajax:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.491#"Telamonian Ajax, that is Odysseus shouting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.492#The Trojans must have cut him off.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.493#We've got to get over and lend a hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.494#Or the Trojans may overpower him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.495#Think what his loss would mean to the Greeks."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.496#With that he led the way through the turmoil, and Ajax,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.497#Who was something more than human, followed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.498#They found Odysseus beset by a crowd of Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.499#Yellow jackals in the mountains
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.500#Chase down an antlered stag wounded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.501#By a hunter's arrow. The stag
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.502#Has escaped the human and runs quickly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.503#As long as the blood flows warm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.504#And his knees have spring. Eventually,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.505#The arrow defeats him, and the jackals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.506#Tear him to pieces in the green shade,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.507#But then a mountain god brings a lion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.508#To raven them all, and the jackals scatter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.509#While the lion settles down to his meal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.510#With Trojans all over him, Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.511#Fell back on experience and instinct
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.512#To keep himself alive, shooting his spear out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.513#Whenever one of his assailants got too close.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.514#Then Ajax was there, planting himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.515#With his wall of a shield, and the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.516#Slunk off by ones and twos. Menelaus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.517#Led Odysseus away, holding him by his hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.518#Until his driver wheeled the chariot up.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.519#Then Ajax attacked, killing Dorycles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.520#One of Priam's bastard sons, and likewise
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.521#Lysander, Pyrasus, and Pylartes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.522#A mountain stream swollen by winter rains
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.523#Empties onto level ground, sweeping along
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.524#Desiccated oaks and pines and other flotsam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.525#That it finally dumps into the spreading sea.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.526#So too Ajax in spate across the plain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.527#Killing horses as well as men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.528#And Hector?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.529#As yet he knew nothing of all this.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.530#He was doing his fighting on the left flank
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.531#By the banks of the Scamander, where
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.532#The fighting was thickest, that is to say
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.533#Around great Nestor, and Idomeneus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.534#It was there that Hector was engaged,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.535#Using his chariot and spear to terrible effect
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.536#On the Trojan lines. Even so,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.537#The Greeks would not have backed up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.538#Had not Helen's fair-haired husband Paris
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.539#Stopped Machaon from his valorous exploits
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.540#With a three-pronged arrow into his shoulder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.541#The Greeks held their breath, terrified
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.542#That the battle would turn and Machaon be killed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.543#Idomeneus called over to Nestor:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.544#"Nestor, son of Neleus, mount your chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.545#And take Machaon back to the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.546#A medic is worth a battalion of men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.547#In pulling out arrows and dressing wounds."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.548#The old horseman did not need any urging.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.549#He mounted his chariot, and Machaon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.550#Asclepius' son and an inspired physician,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.551#God in beside him. At a touch of the lash
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.552#The horses stretched their necks toward the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.553#Cebriones saw that on the other side of the plain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.554#The Trojans were in rout, and he said to Hector:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.555#"While we dally with the Greeks over here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.556#On the battle's edge, there are Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.557#Beating a hasty retreat, men and horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.558#Before Ajax, son of Telamon. I know him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.559#From that wide shield of his that stretches
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.560#Around his shoulders. Let's drive over there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.561#To where the real killing is going on."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.562#His lash whistled in the air, and the horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.563#Their manes streaming, pulled the chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.564#At top speed over the corpses and shields,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.565#Their hooves gouging the dead. The axle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.566#Beneath and the chariot's rails above
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.567#Were spattered with blood kicked up by the horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.568#And turning wheels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.569#Hector yearned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.570#To penetrate the wall of Greek flesh
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.571#And shatter it to bits. The battle noise rose,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.572#And a moment later Hector was everywhere
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.573#Making lethal circles with his spear and sword
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.574#And massive stones, and avoiding only
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.575#A single man, Telamonian Ajax.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.576#But Zeus, from his high vantage point,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.577#Had decided it was time for Ajax to withdraw.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.578#As if in a trance, Ajax swung his seven-ply shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.579#Behind him, and with an anxious glance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.580#Over his shoulder, slunk away like a wild animal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.581#Turning around again and again in his slow retreat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.582#Dogs and country folk sometimes drive
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.583#A tawny lion away from a cattle pen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.584#They watch the whole night through to stop him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.585#From sinking his teeth into the herd's fattest bull,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.586#But the ravenous beast advances anyway,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.587#Only to be met with spears and firebrands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.588#Which he cannot face, for all his hungry power.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.589#At dawn the lion departs in a sullen mood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.590#So too Ajax, resenting every step he took
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.591#Back from the Trojans. He feared for the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.592#A donkey is usually too strong for boys
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.593#Who try to keep him out of a wheat field
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.594#And will wade right in although they break their sticks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.595#On his ribs. The boys keep beating him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.596#As he wastes the deep grain, but their childish strength
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.597#Can barely drive him out even after he is full.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.598#The Trojans and their allies kept up the pressure
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.599#On Ajax, hitting his shield with their polished spears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.600#Every now and again Ajax would remember
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.601#Who he was, and turn on them, pushing back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.602#Entire phalanxes of horse-taming Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.603#Then he would give ground, but even in retreat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.604#It was big Ajax who kept the enemy from the ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.605#Big Ajax who stood between the Trojans and the Greeks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.606#Collecting the spears that were thrown hard enough
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.607#To reach his enormous shield. Many fell short,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.608#Sticking in sand instead of the flesh they yearned for.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.609#Eurypylus, Euaemon's glorious son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.610#Saw the thicket of spears surrounding Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.611#And moved over to help. His first throw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.612#Hit Apisaon, Phausius' son, in the liver.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.613#The man crumpled, and Eurypylus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.614#Leapt upon him to unstrap his armor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.615#But as he was doing so, Paris Alexander
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.616#Saw him and drew his bow. The arrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.617#Hit Eurypylus in his right thigh. The shaft
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.618#Broke off, but it was all he could do
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.619#To drag his leg along as he made his way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.620#Back to the Greek lines, shrinking from death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.621#Then his shout rang in every Danaan ear:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.622#"Achaean captains! Rally around Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.623#And see to it that this day is not his last.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.624#He's under pressure from all sides
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.625#And won't pull through without our help.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.626#Make a stand for great Ajax, son of Telamon!"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.627#Thus the wounded Eurypylus, who was soon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.628#Surrounded by Greek troops leaning their shields
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.629#On their shoulders and holding their spears high.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.630#Ajax managed to get over to this group,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.631#And when he did, turned and took his stand.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.632#So the fight went on, like wildfire burning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.633#Meanwhile, the sweat-glazed mares of Neleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.634#Had pulled Nestor, and Machaon with him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.635#Out of the battle and into the Greek camp,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.636#And Achilles saw them as they went by.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.637#Achilles was standing on the stern of his ship
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.638#Gazing out at the blood, sweat, and tears
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.639#Of the Greeks in rout. And the great runner
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.640#Called to his comrade Patroclus from the ship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.641#And Patroclus heard him and came out of the hut
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.642#Like the god Ares. This was the beginning of evil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.643#For Menoetius' strong son, who now asked:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.644#"Why have you called me, Achilles? What do you want?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.645#And Achilles, the great runner, answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.646#"Son of Menoetius, my heart's companion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.647#If I have it right, the Greeks will soon be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.648#Grovelling before me. They've reached their limit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.649#But I want you to go now and ask Nestor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.650#Whom he is bringing wounded from battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.651#From behind, it looked just like Machaon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.652#Son of Asclepius, but I didn't see his face.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.653#The horses went by at a pretty good clip."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.654#Patroclus did as his beloved friend asked
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.655#And sprinted through the camp.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.656#Nestor had just reached his hut
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.657#And was stepping down from the chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.658#With Machaon. His squire Eurymedon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.659#Unhitched the old man's horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.660#And the two dried the sweat from their tunics
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.661#By standing in the onshore breeze for a while.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.662#Then they went into the hut and sat on chairs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.663#While Hecamede prepared a drink for them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.664#This woman, who had long, beautiful hair,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.665#Nestor had taken out of Tenedos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.666#When Achilles sacked it. She was the daughter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.667#Of a great man, Arsinous, and the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.668#Had chosen her for Nestor, their best in council.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.669#She now drew up for them a polished table
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.670#With blue enamelled feet, and set on it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.671#A bronze basket, and next to it an onion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.672#Grated for their drink, and pale green honey,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.673#And sacred barley meal. Then she set down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.674#A magnificent cup the old man had brought from home,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.675#Studded with gold rivets. It had four handles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.676#With a pair of golden doves pecking at each,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.677#And a double base beneath. Anyone else
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.678#Would have strained to lift the cup from the table
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.679#When full, but old Nestor raised it easily.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.680#Into this cup Hecamede, beautiful as a goddess,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.681#Poured Pramnian wine, grated goat cheese into it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.682#With a brazed grater, and sprinkled white barley on top.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.683#She motioned for them to drink. They did so,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.684#And when they had slaked their parching thirst,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.685#They began to swap tales and were enjoying themselves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.686#When Patroclus stood in the door, more like a god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.687#Than a man. Seeing him, the old man jumped up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.688#From his gleaming chair, took him by the hand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.689#Led him inside, and asked him to sit down.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.690#Patroclus refused, in no uncertain terms:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.691#"No thank you, venerable sir, no seat for me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.692#I have too much respect for Achilles, who sent me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.693#To ask you whom you have brought back wounded.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.694#But I see for myself it is Machaon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.695#And I will bring this news back to Achilles now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.696#You know, sir, what a hard man he is,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.697#Quick to blame even the blameless."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.698#And Nestor, the horseman from Gerenia:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.699#"And why does Achilles feel any sorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.700#For wounded Greeks? He has no idea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.701#Of the grief that has spread through the army.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.702#Our best men have been hit and are lying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.703#Wounded in camp. Diomedes is out,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.704#And Odysseus, a good man with a spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.705#Even Agamemnon has taken a hit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.706#Eurypylus, too, an arrow in his thigh.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.707#Machaon here I have just brought back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.708#With an arrow wound. But Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.709#For all his valor has no feeling for us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.710#Is he waiting until our ships go up in flames
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.711#On the shore of the sea, in spite of our efforts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.712#And we are all killed in a row? For my strength
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.713#Is not as it once was in my knotted limbs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.714#Oh to be young again, with my strength firm,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.715#As I was in the cattle wars with the Eleans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.716#When I killed Itymoneus, the valiant son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.717#Of Hypeirochus, a man of Elis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.718#During the drive back. Leading the charge
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.719#In the fight for his cattle, he was hit by my spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.720#And fell, and the country folk all fled in terror.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.721#The spoils we corralled from out of the plain!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.722#Fifty herds of cattle and as many flocks of sheep,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.723#As many droves of pigs, as many herds of goats.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.724#And one hundred and fifty chestnut horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.725#All mares, many with foals underneath.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.726#We drove them all into Pylos by night,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.727#Up to the citadel. And Neleus was glad
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.728#I had done so well, going to war as a boy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.729#At the crack of dawn the heralds invited
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.730#Anyone who was owed a debt in Elis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.731#To step forth. So the Pylians assembled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.732#And divided the spoils. Most claimed debts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.733#Since we in Pylos were few and hard-pressed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.734#For Heracles had come in recent years
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.735#And brought us grief, killing our best.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.736#I was one of the twelve sons of Neleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.737#And I alone was left; the others had perished.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.738#Emboldened at this, the Epeians in Elis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.739#Campaigned against us with reckless violence.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.740#Well, old Neleus chose a herd of cattle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.741#And a great flock of three hundred sheep,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.742#Herdsmen and all. For he was owed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.743#A great debt in Elis, four champion horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.744#A chariot team that had gone to the games
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.745#To race for a tripod, but which King Augeias
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.746#Had kept, sending the forlorn driver back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.747#Old Neleus was angry because of this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.748#And took high compensation. The rest he gave
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.749#For his folk to divide into equal shares.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.750#We were in the midst of all this distribution
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.751#And offering sacrifice throughout the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.752#When on the third day the Epeians arrived,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.753#Infantry and horse, at breakneck speed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.754#And with them were the two Moliones brothers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.755#Still just boys who didn't really know war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.756#Now there is a town, Thryoessa, a steep hill
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.757#Way down the Alpheius, Pylos' last outpost.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.758#There they encamped, with a mind to destroy it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.759#When they were through the plain, Pallas Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.760#Sped down to us from Olympus by night
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.761#And told us to arm. The army she assembled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.762#From all Pylos was more than eager, but Neleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.763#Would not allow me to arm, and hid my horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.764#For he did not think I understood warfare.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.765#Even so, on foot, I distinguished myself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.766#Among our horsemen, as Athena would have it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.767#There is a river Minyeius that hits the sea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.768#Close to Arene. There we waited for dawn,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.769#The Pylian horsemen and all the tribes on foot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.770#We marched out on the double with all our gear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.771#And at midday reached Alpheius' sacred stream.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.772#There we offered sacrifice to Zeus Almighty,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.773#A bull to Alpheius, a bull to Poseidon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.774#And a heifer of the herd to the Grey-eyed One.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.775#Then we had our supper by platoons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.776#And settled down to sleep in full battle gear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.777#Along the river banks. The Epeians were deployed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.778#Around the city, determined to destroy it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.779#But before they could a great battle loomed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.780#We attacked at daybreak, saying our prayers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.781#To Zeus and Athena, and in that conflict
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.782#I was first to kill my man and take his horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.783#This was Mulius, Augeias' son-in-law,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.784#Husband of his eldest daughter, blonde Agamede,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.785#Who knew every medicinal plant on earth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.786#I hit him with my bronze-tipped spear as he charged,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.787#And he fell in the dust. I leapt on his chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.788#And took my stand with the foremost fighters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.789#The Epeians fled when they saw him fallen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.790#The leader of their horse and best man in battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.791#I went after them like a black hurricane
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.792#And took fifty chariots, and beside each one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.793#Two men felled by my spear bit the dust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.794#And I would have killed the two Moliones also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.795#Had not their father, the wide-ruling Earthshaker,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.796#Saved them from war in a thick shroud of mist.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.797#Then Zeus granted the Pylians great power.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.798#We followed in pursuit across the broad plain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.799#Killing men and culling their fine battle gear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.800#Driving all the way to Buprasium's wheat fields,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.801#And the rock of Olen, and the hill that is called
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.802#Alesium, where Athena again turned back the foe.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.803#Then I killed the last man and left him. Our men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.804#Drove their horses from Buprasium to Pylos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.805#Praising Zeus among gods, and among men Nestor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.806#That is the sort of man I was. But Achilles?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.807#His valor is for himself alone. And yet I think
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.808#He will sorely lament the army's destruction.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.809#Ah yes, my young friend---Menoetius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.810#On the day he sent you forth from Phthia
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.811#To join Agamemnon, laid a charge on you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.812#Mustering the army throughout Achaea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.813#We had come to the well-built house of Peleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.814#And we found the hero Menoetius inside
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.815#With you and Achilles. The old horseman Peleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.816#Was burning a bull's fat thighbones to Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.817#Out in the courtyard. He held a golden cup
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.818#And poured flaming wine as the sacrifice blazed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.819#You two were busy with the flesh of the bull
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.820#When we appeared in the doorway. Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.821#Jumped up in astonishment, took us by the hand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.822#And led us inside. He had us sit down,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.823#Then set before us all that guests should have.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.824#When we had our fill of food and drink
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.825#I began to speak, urging that you come with us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.826#You were both right eager, and your fathers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.827#Laid on you both many commands. Old Peleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.828#Told Achilles to be preeminent always,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.829#But to you Menoetius gave this command:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.830#'My son, Achilles is higher born than you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.831#But you are older, though he is much stronger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.832#Advise him, speak to him wisely, direct him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.833#And he will be better off for obeying.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.834#Thus spoke the old man, but you have forgotten.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.835#Still, you should speak to Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.836#It is not too late, and he just might listen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.837#Who knows but that with the help of some god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.838#You might rouse his spirit? You are his friend,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.839#And it is good for friends to persuade each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.840#If some oracle, or a secret his mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.841#Has learned from Zeus, is holding him back,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.842#Let him send you out, let you lead a troop
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.843#Of Myrmidons and light the way for our army.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.844#If you wear his armor, and the Trojans think
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.845#You are he, they will back off and give the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.846#Some breathing space, what little there is in war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.847#Our rested men will turn them with a shout
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.848#And push them back from our ships to Troy."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.849#This speech put great notions in Patroclus' head,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.850#And he went sprinting down the line of ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.851#To Achilles. But when he reached Odysseus' hulls,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.852#Where the assembly grounds and altars stood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.853#He ran into Eurypylus limping in from battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.854#With an arrow in his thigh. Sweat poured down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.855#His neck and shoulders, and black blood pulsed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.856#From his terrible wound, but his spirit was strong.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.857#When Patroclus saw him he cried out in dismay:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.858#"Ah, you Greek heroes, you were all destined
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.859#To die far from home and glut Trojan dogs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.860#With your white fat. Eurypylus, tell me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.861#Is there any way to hold back Hector now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.862#Or will we all go down beneath his spear?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.863#And the wounded Eurypylus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.864#"We'll all be piling into our black ships soon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.865#We have no defense left. All our best
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.866#Have been hit and are laid up in camp,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.867#And the Trojans only get stronger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.868#Lend me a hand here. Lead me back to my ship
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.869#And cut this arrow out of my thigh.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.870#Wash the blood off in warm water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.871#And put some soothing poultices on it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.872#The good stuff. They say Achilles taught you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.873#And that he learned from Chiron, the just centaur.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.874#Our medics, Podalirius and Machaon---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.875#One is laid up wounded and needs a doctor himself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.876#And the other is out there fighting the Trojans."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.877#Menoetius' valiant son answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.878#"What are we going to do, Eurypylus?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.879#I am on my way to Achilles now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.880#With a message from Lord Nestor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.881#But you're hurting, and I won't let you down."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.882#He put his arm around Eurypylus' chest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.883#And helped him to his hut. His attendant,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.884#When he saw them, spread hides on the floor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.885#Patroclus had him lie down, and with a knife
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.886#Cut from his thigh the barbed arrow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.887#He washed the wound off with warm water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.888#And patted into it a bitter root
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.889#That he had rubbed between his hands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.890#An anodyne that took away the pain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:11.891#The bleeding stopped, and the wound was dry.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.1#While Patroclus doctored Eurypylus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.2#The battle raged on. The Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.3#Still had the protection of their trench
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.4#And the wide wall above it they had built
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.5#As the last line of defense for their ships---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.6#For the time being. When they built that wall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.7#And drove the trench around it to protect their ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.8#And all their plunder, they neglected to offer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.9#Formal sacrifice to the immortal gods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.10#Built against the will of the immortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.11#The wall could not endure for long.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.12#While Hector lived and Achilles raged
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.13#And the city of Priam was still unpillaged,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.14#The great wall of the Greeks stood firm.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.15#But when all the best Trojans had died
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.16#And many Greeks had fallen or had left
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.17#And after ten years Priam's city had fallen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.18#And the Greeks had sailed back to their native land,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.19#Then Poseidon and Apollo conspired
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.20#To sweep away the wall, bringing against it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.21#The might of all the rivers that flow down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.22#From Ida's mountains to the sea---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.23#Rhesus and Heptaporus, Caresus and Rhodius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.24#Granicus and Aesepus, shining Scamander
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.25#And Simois, along the banks of which
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.26#Many bullhide shields and helmets fell in the dust,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.27#And a generation of men who were half-divine.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.28#Phoebus Apollo turned all their mouths together
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.29#And for nine days sent their flood against the wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.30#Zeus poured down rain continually, the sooner
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.31#To wash the wall into the sea. The Earthshaker
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.32#Led the way, holding a trident in his hands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.33#And pushed into the waves all the foundations
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.34#Of beams and stones the Greeks had laid with toil.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.35#He made all smooth along the mighty Hellespont
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.36#And again covered the great shore with sand.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.37#The wall was gone. He turned the beautiful rivers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.38#Back to flow in their original channels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.39#This Poseidon and Apollo were to do
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.40#In time to come. But now the battle raged
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.41#On both sides of the well-built wall. The beams
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.42#Rang as they were struck, and the Greeks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.43#Whipped back by Zeus, were penned in with their ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.44#Terrified of Hector, who had engineered the rout
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.45#And who still fought like a howling wind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.46#When hunters are out with their dogs,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.47#Their prey, a wild boar or a lion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.48#Will suddenly feel its strength and turn.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.49#The men close their ranks like a wall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.50#And throw their javelins thick and fast,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.51#But the valiant animal stands its ground,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.52#And though its bravery will be its death,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.53#It charges the ranks of men, testing them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.54#And where it charges, the men fall back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.55#Hector kept urging his troops to cross the ditch.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.56#His horses stood at its edge, whinnying,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.57#But would not advance, spooked by the trench,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.58#Too broad to leap and too difficult to drive over.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.59#The banks hung over the sides, and sharp stakes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.60#Were planted in the farther, higher edge,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.61#A formidable obstacle for a horse and chariot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.62#But the foot soldiers were eager to give it a try.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.63#To that end Polydamas drew up to Hector and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.64#"Hector, and Trojan commanders all:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.65#It's not very smart of us to drive our horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.66#Across this trench, not with those sharp stakes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.67#Set in it, and the Greek wall just a little beyond.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.68#There's not enough space to dismount and fight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.69#And we'll suffer heavy casualties if we try.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.70#If the high lord of thunder has turned against them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.71#And it is his will to help the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.72#I would gladly see the Argives blotted out.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.73#But if they rally and we have to retreat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.74#And crash into the ditch, there won't be a man left
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.75#Even to bring the news back to the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.76#So this is what I say we should do.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.77#Let the squires hold the horses by the trench
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.78#While the rest of us advance on foot in full armor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.79#Massed behind Hector. The Greeks will not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.80#Withstand us if the noose is tight around them."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.81#It was sound advice, and Hector took it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.82#He vaulted to the ground in his armor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.83#And the other Trojans followed his example.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.84#They instructed their drivers to keep the horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.85#In good order by the ditch.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.86#The troops divided
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.87#Into five companies behind their commanders.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.88#Hector and Polydamas stood at the head
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.89#Of the two largest contingents, elite troops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.90#Eager to break the wall and fight by the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.91#Cebriones joined them in command (Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.92#Stationed a lesser man with his chariot).
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.93#The second company was led by Paris
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.94#Along with Agenor and Alcathous.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.95#Helenus and Deïphobus, sons of Priam,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.96#Led the third contingent, joined by Asius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.97#Hyrtacus' son, whose huge stallions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.98#Brought him from Arisbe and the river Selleis.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.99#Aeneas led the fourth contingent,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.100#Anchises' son with the sons of Antenor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.101#Archelochus and Acamas, as his lieutenants.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.102#Sarpedon commanded the allies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.103#And picked Glaucus and Asteropaeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.104#As his lieutenants, judging them to be the best
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.105#Next to himself. Sarpedon knew no peer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.106#Massed behind their leather shields
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.107#The Trojans attacked, confident
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.108#That nothing could stop them now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.109#From falling on the black ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.110#All of them followed Polydamas' strategy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.111#Except for Asius. This man, Hyrtacus' son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.112#Had no intention of leaving his horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.113#Behind with his squire, but chariot and all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.114#Drove toward the ships, and to his fate,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.115#Never in his glory as charioteer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.116#To drive back to windy Ilion again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.117#With his proud horses. No, his destiny lay
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.118#On the bronze point of Idomeneus' spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.119#Making for the left wing of the beachhead camp,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.120#Where the Greeks returning from battle entered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.121#With their horses and cars, Asius drove up to
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.122#The wide gate and found the doors
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.123#Not yet shut and barred, but held open by men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.124#Whose comrades were still returning from battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.125#Asius drove straight for the gates, followed by
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.126#His howling soldiers, confident that no Greek
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.127#Could keep them from the black ships now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.128#This was all childishness, for at the gates
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.129#They found two of Greece's finest warriors,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.130#Lapith spearmen, one a son of Peirithous,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.131#Polypoetes by name, and the other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.132#Leonteus, a match for brutal Ares himself.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.133#They were like a pair of oak trees
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.134#Planted before the high gates, these two,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.135#Trees that withstand wind and rain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.136#Day after day, with roots deep and strong.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.137#They met Asius' charge without a tremor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.138#These two Lapiths, trusting the strength of their hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.139#To beat off not only Asius but all his men too,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.140#Who were lifting their leather shields high
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.141#Around their warlord and his captains---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.142#Iamenus and Orestes and Adamas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.143#(Who was Asius' son), Thoön and Oenomaus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.144#The Lapiths had been inside for some time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.145#Rousing the Greeks to fight in defense
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.146#Of their ships, but when they saw the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.147#Attacking the wall and the Greeks in loud retreat,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.148#They rushed out to fight in front of the gate.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.149#They fought like a pair of wild boars
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.150#Holding off men and dogs in the mountains.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.151#Slanting in, they slash through trees,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.152#Cutting them off at the root, and the clashing noise
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.153#Of their tusks rises above the general tumult
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.154#Until someone gets lucky with a spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.155#The polished bronze clashed on the Lapiths' chests
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.156#As they took hits face on from the enemy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.157#They fought strongly, confident in their might
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.158#And in the support from those on the wall above
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.159#Who rained down stones from the fortifications
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.160#In defense of their own lives, their huts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.161#And their seafaring ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.162#The stones fell like snow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.163#Down to the ground, falling, falling, like flakes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.164#A cold wind from the shadowy clouds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.165#Drives thick and fast upon the bountiful earth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.166#Not only stones, but everything that is thrown
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.167#By men in war, a steady stream of missiles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.168#Flowed from the hands of Greeks and Trojans alike.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.169#Helmets and bossed shields rang hoarsely,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.170#Like bells struck by rough stones.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.171#And Asius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.172#Son of Hyrtacus, groaned, smacked his thighs,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.173#And like a man who has been wronged, spoke:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.174#"Father Zeus, or should I call you the Arch Deceiver?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.175#I never thought the Greeks had a chance against us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.176#They're like a swarm of wasps or bees, holed up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.177#In a hive they have built near a trail through cliffs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.178#And defending their young against hunters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.179#These men, even though they are only two,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.180#Will not yield the gate until they kill or are killed."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.181#These words had no effect upon the mind of Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.182#Who had decided to give all the glory to Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.183#Other battles were being fought around other gates.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.184#Even if I were a god I could not tell you all.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.185#Suffice it to say there was a firestorm of stone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.186#All around the wall, that the Greeks were hard-pressed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.187#To defend their ships, and that those gods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.188#Who abetted the Greeks were sorely distressed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.189#Over on the left, the Lapiths were fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.190#Polypoetes, Peirithous' son, threw his spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.191#Through the bronze cheek piece of Damasus' helmet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.192#The point splintered the bone and scrambled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.193#The grey stuff inside. He had been eager to fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.194#Polypoetes killed Pylon and Ormenus next.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.195#Leonteus meanwhile was doing his own damage,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.196#Hitting Hippomachus in the belt with his spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.197#Then darting through the crowd with sword drawn
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.198#And stabbing Antiphates in close fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.199#Sending him sprawling backward on the ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.200#Then, in order, he brought Menon, Iamenus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.201#And Orestes down to earth's bounty.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.202#While the Lapiths stripped their victims' bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.203#The troops with Hector and Polydamas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.204#For all their numbers and valor, and their eagerness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.205#To break through the wall and fight by the ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.206#Hesitated on the brink of the trench,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.207#Paralyzed by an omen, an eagle overhead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.208#That skirted their front lines from right to left,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.209#Clutching in its talons a huge scarlet snake,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.210#Still alive and with plenty of fight left.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.211#Curling around, the snake struck at the eagle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.212#Just below its neck, and, in a spasm of pain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.213#The great bird dropped it in the Trojan ranks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.214#And flew off shrieking on a blast of wind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.215#The soldiers shuddered at the glistening coils
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.216#Lying in their midst, a portent from heaven.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.217#Polydamas turned to Hector and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.218#"Hector, you always lay into me in assembly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.219#Even when I give sound advice, since it will not do
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.220#For a man of the people to cross you in council
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.221#Or in battle, instead of adding to your strength.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.222#Even so, I will speak now as seems best to me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.223#We should not fight the Danaans for their ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.224#It will turn out for us just as with this bird
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.225#That came to the Trojans as they were eager to cross.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.226#It skirted their front lines from right to left
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.227#Clutching in its talons a huge scarlet snake,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.228#But then let it fall before reaching its nest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.229#And never brought it home to give to its young.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.230#It will be the same with us. Even if our forces
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.231#Break through the Greek wall and its gates
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.232#And the enemy falls back, we will find ourselves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.233#Beating a disorderly retreat from the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.234#And leaving behind us many Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.235#Killed by the Achaeans in defense of their ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.236#This is how a soothsayer would respond, one who
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.237#Knows omens well and has the people's trust."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.238#Hector's bronze mask leaned toward Polydamas:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.239#"I don't like the way you're talking now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.240#You know how to speak better than this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.241#But if you really mean what you say,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.242#The gods themselves must have addled your wits,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.243#Telling me to ignore what thundering Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.244#Has assented to and held out to me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.245#Birds? You want me to obey birds,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.246#Polydamas? I don't care which way birds fly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.247#Right to the sunrise or left into the dusk.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.248#All we have to do is obey great Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.249#Lord of mortals and immortals alike.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.250#One omen is best: to fight for your country.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.251#Why should you be afraid of combat?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.252#Even if all the rest of us are killed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.253#At the Argive ships, you will be safe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.254#Since you don't have an ounce of fight in you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.255#But if I catch you holding back from battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.256#Or talking anybody else out of fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.257#You lose your life on the point of my spear."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.258#And he led them across the trench.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.259#To the noise of their advance Zeus now added
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.260#A wind from Ida's mountains that blew dust
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.261#Straight at the ships and the bewildered Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.262#The sky god was giving the glory to the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.263#And to Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.264#Trusting these portents
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.265#And their own strength, the Trojans did their best
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.266#To breach the wall. Pulling down pickets
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.267#And battlements, they threw them to the ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.268#And set to work prying up the huge beams
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.269#The Greeks had used to reinforce the wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.270#They were dragging these out, hoping to topple
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.271#The entire structure, but even then the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.272#Refused to give way, patching the battlements
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.273#With bullhide and beating off the invaders.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.274#Both Ajaxes were on the wall, patrolling it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.275#And urging on the troops, using harsh words,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.276#Gentle words, whatever it took
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.277#To get the men back into the fight:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.278#"Friends!---and I mean everyone from heroes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.279#To camp followers---no one ever said
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.280#Men are equal in war. There is work for us all.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.281#You know it yourselves. I don't want a single man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.282#To return to the ships now that you have heard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.283#The rallying cry. Keep the pressure on.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.284#Olympian Zeus may still grant us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.285#To drive the enemy back to the city."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.286#And they roused the Greeks to battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.287#Snow flurries fall thick on a winter's day
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.288#When Zeus in his cunning rouses himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.289#To show humans the ammunition he has.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.290#He lulls the winds and he snows and snows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.291#Until he has covered all the mountain tops,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.292#Headlands and meadows and men's plowed fields.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.293#And the snow falls over the harbors
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.294#And the shores of the grey sea, and only
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.295#The waves keep it off. The rest of the world
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.296#Is enveloped in the winter tempest of Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.297#The stones flew thick upon the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.298#And upon the Greeks, and the wooden wall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.299#Was beaten like a drum along its whole length.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.300#For all this, though, Hector and his Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.301#Would never have broken the barred gate
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.302#Had not Zeus roused his own son, Sarpedon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.303#Against the Greeks, as a lion against cattle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.304#Sarpedon held before him a perfect shield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.305#Its bronze skin hammered smooth by the smith,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.306#Who had stitched the leather beneath with gold
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.307#All around the rim. Holding this shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.308#And brandishing two spears, Sarpedon advanced.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.309#The mountain lion has not fed for days
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.310#And is hungry and brave enough to enter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.311#The stone sheep pen and attack the flocks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.312#Even if he finds herdsmen on the spot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.313#With dogs and spears to protect the fold,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.314#He will not be driven back without a try,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.315#And either he leaps in and seizes a sheep
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.316#Or is killed by a spear, as human heroes are.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.317#Godlike Sarpedon felt impelled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.318#To rush the wall and tear it down.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.319#He turned to Glaucus and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.320#"Glaucus, you know how you and I
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.321#Have the best of everything in Lycia---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.322#Seats, cuts of meat, full cups, everybody
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.323#Looking at us as if we were gods?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.324#Not to mention our estates on the Xanthus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.325#Fine orchards and riverside wheat fields.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.326#Well, now we have to take our stand at the front,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.327#Where all the best fight, and face the heat of battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.328#So that many an armored Lycian will say,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.329#'So they're not inglorious after all,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.330#Our Lycian lords who eat fat sheep
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.331#And drink the sweetest wine. No,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.332#They're strong, and fight with our best.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.333#Ah, my friend, if you and I could only
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.334#Get out of this war alive and then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.335#Be immortal and ageless all of our days.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.336#I would never again fight among the foremost
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.337#Or send you into battle where men win glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.338#But as it is, death is everywhere
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.339#In more shapes than we can count,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.340#And since no mortal is immune or can escape,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.341#Let's go forward, either to give glory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.342#To another man or get glory from him."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.343#Thus Sarpedon. Glaucus nodded, and the two of them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.344#Moved out at the head of a great nation of Lycians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.345#Menestheus, Peteos' son, saw them and shuddered,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.346#For they were advancing toward his part of the wall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.347#And bringing ruin with them. Menestheus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.348#Looked along the wall for a Greek captain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.349#Who would be able to avert this disaster.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.350#He saw both Ajaxes, who never seemed to tire,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.351#And Teucer, who had just come from his hut.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.352#They were near enough, but there was no way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.353#To make a shout reach them, not with all the noise
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.354#Filling the air, the crash of shields and helmets
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.355#And the pounding on the gates, which were all closed now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.356#And before each one of which the enemy stood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.357#Trying their best to break them and enter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.358#So Menestheus turned to the herald Thoötes:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.359#"Run, Thoötes, and call Ajax, or better yet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.360#Call both of them. All hell is going to break loose here.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.361#The Lycian leaders are bearing down on us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.362#And they've been awfully tough in the big battles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.363#If the fighting is too heavy for them both to come,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.364#At least get Telamonian Ajax here,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.365#And Teucer too, who is good with a bow."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.366#And the herald was off, running along the wall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.367#Until he came to the two Ajaxes, to whom he said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.368#"My lords Ajax, captains of the Achaeans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.369#The son of Peteos, nurtured of Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.370#Bids you come make a stand, however briefly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.371#In the battle there---both of you would be best---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.372#Since all hell is going to break loose there.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.373#The Lycian leaders are bearing down on us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.374#And they've been awfully tough in the big battles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.375#If the fighting is too heavy for both of you to leave,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.376#At least let Telamonian Ajax come,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.377#And Teucer too, who is good with a bow."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.378#Telamonian Ajax heard the herald out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.379#And said to his Oïlean counterpart:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.380#"Ajax, stay here with Lycomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.381#And keep these Danaans in the fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.382#I'm going to make a stand over there.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.383#When I've helped them out I'll come back here."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.384#Big Ajax left, and with him Teucer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.385#His natural brother, and Pandion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.386#Who carried Teucer's curved bow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.387#Moving along the inside of the wall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.388#They came to Menestheus' sector---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.389#And to men hard-pressed. The Lycians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.390#Were swarming up the battlements
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.391#Like black wind. The Greeks pushed back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.392#With a shout. In the combat that ensued
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.393#It was Telamonian Ajax who first killed his man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.394#Sarpedon's comrade Epicles, hitting him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.395#With a jagged piece of marble that lay on top
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.396#Of the heap of stones inside the wall there.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.397#You couldn't find a man alive now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.398#Who could lift that stone with both hands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.399#But Ajax swung it high and hurled it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.400#With enough force to shatter the four-horned helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.401#And crush Epicles' skull inside. He fell
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.402#As if he were doing a high dive from the wall,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.403#And his spirit left his bones. Then Teucer hit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.404#A fast charging Glaucus with an arrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.405#Where he saw his arm exposed. This stopped him cold,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.406#And he leapt back from the wall, hiding his wound
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.407#From Greek eyes and his pride from their taunts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.408#It pained Sarpedon to see Glaucus withdraw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.409#But it didn't take away any of his fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.410#He hit Alcmaon, son of Thestor, with his spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.411#Jabbing it in, and as he pulled it out again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.412#Alcmaon came forward with it, falling headfirst
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.413#And landing with a clatter of finely tooled bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.414#Sarpedon wrapped his hands around the battlement
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.415#And pulled. The whole section gave way, exposing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.416#The wall above and making an entrance for many.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.417#Ajax and Teucer attacked him together.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.418#Teucer's arrow hit his shield's bright belt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.419#Where it slung across his chest, but Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.420#Beat off the death spirits. He would not allow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.421#His son to fall by the ships. Big Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.422#Leapt upon him at the same moment,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.423#Thrusting his spear into Sarpedon's shield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.424#But could not push the point through.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.425#He did make him reel backward, though.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.426#Sarpedon collected himself a short distance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.427#Back from the wall. He was not giving up.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.428#His heart still hoped to win glory here.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.429#Wheeling around he called to his godlike Lycians:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.430#"Lycians! Why are you slacking off from the fight?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.431#Do you think I can knock this wall down alone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.432#And clear a path to the ships? Help me out here.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.433#The more men we have the better the work will go."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.434#The Lycians cowered before their warlord's rebuke,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.435#Then tightened the ranks around him even more.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.436#The Greeks strengthened their positions on the wall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.437#And steeled themselves for a major battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.438#For all their strength the Lycians were unable
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.439#To break the wall, nor could the Greek spearmen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.440#Push them back once they were close in.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.441#They fought at close quarters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.442#like two men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.443#Disputing boundary stones in a common field
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.444#And defending their turf with the measuring rods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.445#They had brought with them to stake their claims.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.446#Likewise the Trojans and Greeks, separated
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.447#By the palisade and reaching over it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.448#To hack away at each other's leather shields.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.449#Many were wounded, mostly those who turned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.450#Their unprotected backs to the enemy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.451#But many through their shields too, until
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.452#The whole wooden wall dripped with the blood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.453#Of soldiers from both sides. But the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.454#Could do nothing to drive the Greeks back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.455#An honest woman who works with her hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.456#To bring home a meager wage for her children
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.457#Will balance a weight of wool in her scales
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.458#Until both pans are perfectly level.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.459#So too this battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.460#Until Zeus exalted Priam's son Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.461#First to penetrate the Achaean wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.462#His shout split the air:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.463#"Move, Trojans!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.464#Let's tear down this Greek fence
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.465#And make a bonfire out of their ships!"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.466#They heard him, all right, and swarmed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.467#Right up the wall, climbing to its pickets
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.468#With spears in their hands, while Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.469#Scooped up a stone that lay by the gates,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.470#A massive boulder tapering to a point.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.471#It would take two men to heave it onto a cart---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.472#More than two as men are now---but Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.473#Handled it easily alone. Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.474#Lightened it for him, so that the stone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.475#Was no more to Hector than the fleece
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.476#Of a ram is to a shepherd who carries it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.477#Easily in his free hand. This was how
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.478#Hector carried it up to the gates,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.479#A set of heavy double doors, solidly built
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.480#And bolted shut by interlocked inner bars.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.481#Standing close to these towering doors, Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.482#Spread his feet to get his weight behind the throw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.483#And smashed the stone right into the middle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.484#The hinges broke off, and the stone's momentum
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.485#Carried it through, exploding the doors
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.486#And sending splintered wood in every direction.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.487#Hector jumped through, a spear in each hand.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.488#His face was like sudden night,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.489#And a dark gold light played about the armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.490#That encased his zealous bones. No one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.491#Could have stopped him, except the gods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.492#In his immortal leap through the ruined gate,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.493#And his eyes glowed with fire.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.494#Wheeling around
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.495#In the throng, Hector called to his Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.496#Who needed no persuasion, to scale the wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.497#Those who couldn't, swarmed through the gate.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.498#And the Greeks? In rout to their hollow ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:12.499#With a noise like the damned stampeded into hell.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.1#After Zeus had brought Hector and the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.2#To the Greek ships, he left the combatants
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.3#To their misery and turned his luminous eyes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.4#Far away, scanning the horse country of Thrace,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.5#The Mysians, who fight in tight formation,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.6#The Hippemolgi, whose diet is mares' milk,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.7#And the Abii, most righteous of humans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.8#And turned his eyes no more to Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.9#He never dreamed that any of the immortals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.10#Would go to help the Trojans or the Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.11#But Poseidon wasn't blind. He sat high
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.12#On the topmost peak of wooded Samothrace,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.13#Marvelling at the war going on beneath him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.14#He could see all of Ida, and Priam's city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.15#And the Greek ships, from where he sat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.16#The sea crawled beneath him. He pitied
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.17#The Greeks being beaten by the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.18#And he was furious with Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.19#Three enormous strides took him down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.20#The craggy mountain, and each footfall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.21#Sent tremors through the wooded massif
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.22#As the immortal sea god descended.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.23#A fourth step took him to his goal, Aegae,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.24#Where his fabulous palace was built,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.25#Shimmering gold in the depths of the bay.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.26#He harnessed to his chariot a team of horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.27#Bronze-hooved, gold-maned, and swift,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.28#And clothed himself in gold, and gripped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.29#His golden whip, and stepped onto his chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.30#And went driving over the waves. The sea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.31#Parted in joy before him, and all its denizens
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.32#Frolicked beneath him, acknowledging their lord.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.33#The chariot flew on---the bronze axle below
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.34#Never got wet---and the prancing horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.35#Took Poseidon to the Achaean ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.36#A wide cave is submerged in the deep water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.37#Midway betweeen Tenedos and rocky Imbros.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.38#The Earthshaker reined in his horses there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.39#Unhitched them, and threw out ambrosial fodder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.40#For them to eat. And he put hobbles of gold
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.41#On their feet so that they would wait there until
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.42#Their master returned. Then he went off to the Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.43#The Trojans were swarming behind Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.44#Like flame or rumbling wind, and their howls
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.45#Expressed their belief they would take the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.46#Of the Greeks and kill beside them all their best.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.47#But Poseidon, who circles the earth and shakes it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.48#Had emerged from the sea to urge on the Argives.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.49#He assumed the form and voice of Calchas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.50#And spoke to the Ajaxes, who were ready to hear:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.51#"You two men will save the Greek army
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.52#If you just summon your strength and don't panic.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.53#The Trojans aren't invincible. The Greek line
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.54#Will hold everywhere else they've climbed the wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.55#It's only here that I have a premonition
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.56#We might be hurt, where a firestorm rages
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.57#In the person of Hector, son of Zeus, as he says.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.58#May some god put in your hearts the will
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.59#To stand firm yourselves and encourage the others.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.60#You could force Hector back from the ships then,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.61#Even if the Olympian is behind his charge."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.62#And the Lord of Earthquake struck them both
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.63#With his staff and pumped strength into them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.64#Lightening their limbs and their hands and feet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.65#And the god himself rose like a hawk
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.66#That lifts itself from a sheer precipice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.67#And soars downwind after another bird.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.68#So Poseidon was gone across the dusty plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.69#Oïlean Ajax took all this in first
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.70#And said to Ajax, son of Telamon:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.71#"That was one of the Olympian gods, Ajax,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.72#Disguised as the seer, ordering us to fight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.73#Not Calchas himself, who reads birds for us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.74#I could tell from the tracks he made when he left.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.75#Gods are easy to recognize. As for me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.76#I never felt readier for battle. I'm itching to fight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.77#All the way down to my fingers and toes."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.78#Telamonian Ajax answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.79#"Me too. I can't wait to wrap my hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.80#Around a spear. I'm all pumped up, and my feet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.81#Are flying beneath me. Bring on Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.82#Just me and Priam's fighting machine."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.83#That was how they talked to each other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.84#Feeling the joy the god put in their hearts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.85#Meanwhile the Earthshaker was rousing the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.86#Who were catching their breath to the rear by the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.87#They were all done in by the hard fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.88#And couldn't take it when they saw the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.89#Clambering over the wall in droves.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.90#They watched helplessly, tears in their eyes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.91#And thought it was the end. But the Earthshaker
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.92#Slipped in among them and gave heart to the troops---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.93#Teucer first, then Leitus, the hero Peneleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.94#Thoas and Deipyrus, Meriones and Antilochus---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.95#He came to them all, and his words had wings:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.96#"Shame on you, Argives. To think I trusted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.97#You raw recruits to fight for our ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.98#If you're backing off when the going gets tough
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.99#Then this is the day we get beaten by the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.100#I can't believe what is before my eyes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.101#A disaster I thought would never happen---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.102#The Trojans going for our ships. Up until now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.103#They've been like spooked deer that dodge through the woods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.104#To become dinner for jackals, panthers, and wolves,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.105#Totally defenseless, no fight in them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.106#That's how the Trojans have been with us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.107#Unwilling to offer the slightest resistance.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.108#But now they're out fighting for our hollow ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.109#Because, thanks to our leader's cowardice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.110#And dissension in the ranks, we would rather be killed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.111#Beside our seagoing vessels than defend them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.112#But even if Agamemnon is completely to blame
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.113#For all this, because he dishonored Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.114#That's no reason for us go slack in war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.115#Let's do what good men do and make amends.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.116#It's no longer right for you to slough off,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.117#Not you, our army's best. I wouldn't bother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.118#With some sad sack who was sitting out the war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.119#But with you I couldn't be angrier.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.120#You've gone soft! And the upshot of your laxness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.121#Is going to be worse trouble to come, and soon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.122#Don't you remember what shame is, or retribution?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.123#Do you think this is some minor skirmish?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.124#This is Hector, showing his strength. He's smashed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.125#The gates open and has taken the war to our ships."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.126#In this way the Earthshaker roused the Achaeans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.127#The columns that formed around the two Ajaxes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.128#Were so tight they could have passed inspection
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.129#From Ares, or from Athena, the soldiers' goddess.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.130#These were hand-picked troops, Greece's best,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.131#Who awaited the Trojans and godlike Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.132#Spear on spear, shield overlapping shield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.133#They stood helmet to helmet, the horsehair plumes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.134#On the burnished crests brushing each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.135#When they nodded, and when they shook their spears
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.136#The shafts tickered against each other. Their minds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.137#Were fixed on the fight ahead of them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.138#The Trojans closed ranks and charged. Hector led them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.139#Driving straight ahead like a boulder from a cliff.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.140#A river swollen by winter rains
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.141#Will push a stone from a high crest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.142#Breaking it loose from its foundation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.143#By the sheer force of the water. The stone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.144#Knows no shame as it caroms downstream,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.145#Bounding high. The woods echo its sound,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.146#And nothing can stop it until it reaches
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.147#Level ground. But then it rolls no more.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.148#So too with Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.149#For a while he threatened
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.150#To cut his way to the sea through the ships and huts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.151#Killing as he went, but when he hit the Greek line
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.152#He was stopped cold, and the sons of the Achaeans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.153#Thrusting with swords and spears, pushed him back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.154#Shaken, Hector gave way, but his voice boomed out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.155#To the Trojans and their Lycian allies:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.156#"Stand your ground, men. This tight Greek formation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.157#Cannot contain me. They'll fall back under my spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.158#All right, if it is true that the best of the gods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.159#Hera's thundering husband, has urged me on."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.160#Hector's speech aroused their enthusiasm.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.161#Deïphobus, Priam's son, strode out,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.162#Almost danced out, behind the disk of his shield.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.163#Meriones took aim at him with a polished spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.164#And cast. The spear hit the taut bull's hide
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.165#But didn't pierce it, the long shaft shattering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.166#At its metal socket. Deïphobus held the shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.167#At arm's length, afraid the point would come through.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.168#Meriones made his way back to his own people,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.169#Angry because he had been cheated of victory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.170#And had broken his spear. He made his way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.171#Back through camp to retrieve a spare from his hut.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.172#The others fought on in the eye of war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.173#Teucer, son of Telamon, killed his man first,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.174#The spearman Imbrius. His father Mentor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.175#Raised horses, and he lived in Pedaeum
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.176#Before the war with his wife, Medicaste,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.177#One of Priam's bastard daughters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.178#When the Danaans came with their curved ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.179#He moved back to Ilion and had quarters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.180#In the house of Priam, who accorded him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.181#The same honor as his own natural children.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.182#Teucer jabbed his spear into his jaw,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.183#And when he pulled it out, Imbrius fell.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.184#He fell as an ash tree falls, a tree
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.185#That is a landmark on a mountain crest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.186#And when it is cut through with bronze axes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.187#It brings all its soft leafage down to the ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.188#Imbrius' tooled bronze clattered around him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.189#And Teucer rushed up to relieve him of it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.190#Hector cast at the moving target he made,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.191#But Teucer had his eye on the bright spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.192#And managed to dodge it. No matter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.193#It hit Amphimachus instead, whose lineage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.194#Went back through Cteatus to Poseidon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.195#Square in the chest as he entered battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.196#He crashed to the ground, bronze clattering,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.197#And Hector ran up to rip the helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.198#From Amphimachus' noble head.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.199#But he didn't get that far. Big Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.200#Lunged with his spear as Hector charged.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.201#The point never reached his bronze-cased skin
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.202#But it struck Hector's shield with enough force
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.203#To drive him back from both fallen bodies,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.204#Which the Greeks proceeded to drag away.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.205#Two Athenians, Stichius and Menestheus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.206#Hauled Amphimachus off to the Greek side,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.207#While the two Ajaxes did the same for Imbrius.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.208#Two lions have snatched a goat from snarling dogs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.209#And are carrying it off through thick underbrush,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.210#Holding it in their jaws high above the ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.211#They held Imbrius high and stripped him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.212#When they got the armor off, Oïlean Ajax,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.213#Angry for Amphimachus, lopped off his head
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.214#And whirled it like a ball through the crowd.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.215#It fell in the dust before Hector's feet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.216#Poseidon was pulsing with anger. His son's son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.217#Had fallen in the hard fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.218#He went through the ships and huts to rally
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.219#The Greeks and to build trouble for the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.220#Idomeneus, the great spearman, bumped into him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.221#As he came from a friend who had been wounded---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.222#A gash in the knee---and carried out of battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.223#He had just briefed the medics and was going
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.224#Back to his hut, anxious to return to the fight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.225#When the Earthshaker spoke to him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.226#Likening his voice to that of Andraemon's son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.227#Thoas, lord in Pleuron and steep Calydon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.228#And honored as a god by the Aetolians there:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.229#"Idomeneus, you, the Cretan commander,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.230#What has happened to all the threats
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.231#The Greeks once issued against the Trojans?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.232#And Idomeneus, commander of the Cretans:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.233#"Thoas, there's not a Greek here at fault,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.234#As far as I know. We're all experienced.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.235#No one has panicked; no one has deserted.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.236#My guess is that it is great Zeus' pleasure
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.237#That the Achaeans die a nameless death here,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.238#Far from Argos. But look, Thoas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.239#You have always held your own in battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.240#And now you're rallying others. Keep it up.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.241#Don't let anyone hang back from the fight."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.242#And Poseidon, who shakes the continents:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.243#"Idomeneus, may the man who willingly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.244#Shirks battle today never return from Troy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.245#But become a ragbone for the dogs of Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.246#Get your armor on and let's head out.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.247#We have to work together and do our best
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.248#To help out, even though we are only two.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.249#Teamwork makes even riffraff do well,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.250#And you and I know how to fight with the best."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.251#He spoke and returned, a god, to men's toil.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.252#When Idomeneus reached his well-built hut
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.253#He strapped on his armor, took two spears,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.254#And walked out like a lightning bolt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.255#That Zeus shakes down from Olympus' glare
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.256#As a sign to humans, blinding forks of light,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.257#The bronze on this hero's chest as he ran.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.258#Meriones, his second-in-command, met him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.259#Near the hut, where he was going to get a spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.260#For himself. Idomeneus boomed out at him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.261#"Meriones, son of Molus, old friend,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.262#What's this sprint away from the battle?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.263#Are you wounded? Were you nicked?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.264#Or do you have a message for me? Myself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.265#I'm not for sitting in the huts but for fighting."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.266#And Meriones, who knew what to say:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.267#"I came here for a spear, Idomeneus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.268#If there are any left in your hut. The one I had
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.269#Shattered when it hit Deïphobus' shield."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.270#And Idomeneus, the Cretan commander:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.271#"Spears? You can have twenty if you want,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.272#Standing along the white plaster wall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.273#As you go in, spears I take off Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.274#I kill in close combat. I have plenty,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.275#Shields too, and helmets, and breastplates."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.276#Meriones knew how to respond:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.277#"The hut by my tarred ships is also filled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.278#With Trojan spoils, but it's not close by.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.279#I know what it means to fight up front
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.280#And win my share of glory in war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.281#There might be one or two Greeks around
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.282#Who haven't noticed, but not you."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.283#And the Cretan commander:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.284#"I know you're good. Why talk about it?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.285#Look. Suppose we were all lined up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.286#For an ambush. At times like that it's obvious
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.287#Who has what it takes and who doesn't.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.288#Your coward will turn ten shades of green.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.289#He's unsteady, shifting his weight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.290#From one foot to another. His heart thumps
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.291#So loud you can hear it, and his teeth chatter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.292#As he keeps imagining his death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.293#The brave man, though, doesn't blanch
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.294#And is not too afraid when he gets in position.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.295#His only prayer is to get on with the battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.296#At a time like that no one would slight you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.297#If you were hit in battle or took a shot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.298#It wouldn't be in the back or the neck
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.299#But in your chest or belly as you came on hard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.300#In the front lines. Come on, though,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.301#Let's not stand around talking like kids.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.302#Someone might see us and really blow up.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.303#Go on in and get yourself a spear."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.304#Meriones ducked into the hut, got a spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.305#And followed Idomeneus, intent on war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.306#Ares himself sometimes goes to war
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.307#And takes with him his son, Rout,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.308#Who is as valiant as his father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.309#And can turn even the bravest man to flight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.310#They arm themselves and go forth from Thrace
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.311#To join either the Ephyri or Phlegyes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.312#But do not really care which side wins.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.313#Thus the two human captains
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.314#Going to battle in their bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.315#Meriones saying to Idomeneus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.316#"Where to, son of Deucalion?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.317#Should we enter on the right, center, or left,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.318#Where the Greeks will likely need help the most?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.319#And Idomeneus, the Cretan commander:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.320#"We have some good defense in the central ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.321#Both Ajaxes and Teucer, our best bowman
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.322#And a good man in hand-to-hand combat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.323#These will give Hector all he wants and more,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.324#No matter how tough he is. He'll be fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.325#Uphill all day trying to beat them back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.326#And burn the ships, and won't be able to
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.327#Unless Zeus himself throws a torch on the hulls.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.328#Ajax won't yield to anything human,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.329#That's for sure, anything that eats bread,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.330#Can be split with bronze, or crushed with stones.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.331#He wouldn't even give way to Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.332#Not in a close fight anyway, although no one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.333#Could touch Achilles in the open field.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.334#As for us, let's do as you suggest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.335#And go left, so we can find out whether
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.336#We'll give glory to another or another to us."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.337#He spoke, and Meriones, moving like Ares,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.338#Led the way to the left side of the camp.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.339#When the Trojans saw Idomeneus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.340#And his lieutenant in their buffed armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.341#It was as if they had spotted a fire.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.342#Calling to each other, they converged on the pair,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.343#Another knot in the battle by the sterns of the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.344#Howling winds with gusts up to fifty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.345#On a day when the gravel roadbeds are dry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.346#Will raise up indiscriminate clouds of dust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.347#That was how they closed with each other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.348#And all their blind desire was to shred flesh
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.349#With stropped bronze, eyes squinting against the glare
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.350#Of helmets and corselets---just polished that morning---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.351#And the confusion of shields, like so many suns
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.352#Shining through a bristling forest of spears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.353#It was glorious to see---if your heart were iron,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.354#And you could keep from grieving at all the pain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.355#There were two strong sons of Cronus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.356#Out that day, with opposing purposes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.357#As to which human heroes they should afflict.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.358#Zeus planned victory for Hector and the Trojans---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.359#To honor Achilles. He had no desire
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.360#To destroy the Greeks on Troy's dusty plain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.361#But meant only to honor Thetis and her son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.362#Poseidon, rising secretly from the grey salt sea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.363#Went among the Greeks, urging them on,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.364#Hating to see them beaten by the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.365#And was strongly resentful of his brother, Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.366#They were born of the same stock, but Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.367#Was born first, and he knew more, and so
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.368#Poseidon avoided giving aid openly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.369#But spurred on the Greeks disguised as a man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.370#So these two tightened the cords of war
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.371#And tied around each army in turn
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.372#A knot that brought many down to their knees.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.373#Idomeneus, hair flecked with grey and yelling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.374#For Greeks to back him up, jumped at the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.375#And scattered them with his first kill.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.376#This was Othryoneus, who, though from Cabesus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.377#Was one of Troy's inner circle. Smelling war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.378#He had come to the capital and asked to marry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.379#Priam's most beautiful daughter, Cassandra herself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.380#Promising no wedding gifts, but one great deed---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.381#That he would drive the Greeks from Trojan soil.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.382#Old Priam promised her with a nod of his head,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.383#And Othryoneus, putting his faith in promises,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.384#Went out to fight. Swaggering along,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.385#He made a perfect target for Idomeneus' spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.386#Which lodged in his belly under his useless corselet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.387#He fell heavily, and Idomeneus taunted him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.388#"You'll be the happiest man on earth,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.389#Othryoneus, if you accomplish all you promised
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.390#Dardanian Priam. We hear he promised you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.391#His own daughter. We could match his offer, you know,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.392#And give you Agamemnon's loveliest daughter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.393#Ship her here from Argos for the wedding,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.394#If only you'd switch to our side and conquer Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.395#Come on over to the ships so we can negotiate
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.396#This marriage. You'll find we offer easy terms."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.397#And he started to drag him off by one leg
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.398#Through the crowd, but Asius came to the dead man's aid,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.399#Advancing on foot just in front of his horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.400#Which his charioteer drove so closely behind him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.401#That their breath warmed his neck. He never got off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.402#The shot he wanted. Idomeneus was too quick,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.403#Catching him in the throat beneath the chin
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.404#And slicing the bronze clean through. Asius fell.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.405#A tree, oak, say, or poplar, or spreading pine,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.406#Falls in the forest when carpenters cut it down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.407#With their bright axes, to be the beam of a ship.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.408#Asius lay before his horses and chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.409#Groaning heavily and clawing the bloody dust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.410#His charioteer lost his wits completely
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.411#And in his terror didn't even have enough nerve
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.412#To turn the horses around and run for it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.413#Antilochus stitched him through the belly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.414#A neat shot just below his corselet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.415#And he fell gasping from his crafted chariot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.416#Antilochus drove the horses back to the Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.417#Deïphobus took Asius' death hard.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.418#He closed in on Idomeneus and cast,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.419#But Idomeneus saw his shot all the way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.420#And ducked behind his shield, a huge
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.421#Double oval of leather and bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.422#Fitted with two rods. Deïphobus' spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.423#Grated on the rim and sailed over,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.424#But, with all of Deïphobus' weight behind it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.425#Kept going and hit Hypsenor, Hippasus' son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.426#In the liver. His knees buckled,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.427#And Deïphobus crowed over him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.428#"Asius is avenged. When he goes down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.429#To Hades' cold gates he can be glad
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.430#That at least I have sent him some company."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.431#The Greeks winced at this boast,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.432#And no one more so than Antilochus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.433#Who did what he could for his fallen comrade,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.434#Standing over him and sheltering him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.435#With his shield until two of his men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.436#Mecisteus and Alastor, bore Hypsenor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.437#Groaning heavily, to the hollow ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.438#Idomeneus was still going strong,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.439#Doing his best to get the drop on some Trojan
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.440#Or just pound himself against their general menace,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.441#When the hero Alcathous appeared before him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.442#This man, son of Aesytes, beloved of Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.443#Had married Anchises' eldest daughter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.444#Hippodameia, darling of both her parents,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.445#Beautiful, clever with her hands, and wise,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.446#And now wife of the best man in all Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.447#This Alcathous Poseidon now mastered,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.448#Putting a spell on his shining eyes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.449#And paralyzing him so that he stood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.450#Rooted to the spot like a gravestone or tree,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.451#Unable to move or dodge the spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.452#That Idomeneus now put through his chest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.453#Cleaving the bronze breastplate that had always
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.454#Protected his flesh from fatal harm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.455#But that now rasped dryly around the wooden shaft.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.456#He fell backward, the spear's point
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.457#Fixed deep in the still beating heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.458#So that the upright shaft quivered a while
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.459#Until at last Ares put its fury at ease.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.460#Idomeneus gloated over him loud and long:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.461#"Are we even yet, Deïphobus, three deaths
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.462#For one? Do you want to boast some more?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.463#Why don't you get out here and face me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.464#So you can see a true descendant of Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.465#Minos, my grandfather, was his son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.466#Overlord of Crete by his divine will,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.467#And his son Deucalion fathered me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.468#Lord over many in the wide land of Crete.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.469#And now the ships have brought me here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.470#As a curse to your father and the other Trojans."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.471#He spoke, and Deïphobus couldn't decide
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.472#Whether he should step back and get help
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.473#Or take Idomeneus on by himself.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.474#He decided he'd better go get Aeneas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.475#And found him in the rear, the last man there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.476#Angry as always with Priam,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.477#Who utterly failed to honor his worth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.478#Deïphobus drew near, and his words flew fast:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.479#"Aeneas, counsellor of the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.480#Alcathous is down and you have to help
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.481#If you have any feeling at all for a kinsman,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.482#Your sister's husband, who cared for you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.483#When you were little. Come on, let's go.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.484#Idomeneus has killed him with his spear."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.485#This wrung Aeneas' heart, and he moved up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.486#To find Idomeneus. The war mattered to him now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.487#A great deal. Idomeneus was not one to run
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.488#Like a spoiled child, but stood his ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.489#A boar in the mountains is sure of his strength,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.490#And when gangs of hunters try to flush him out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.491#In some desolate spot, he waits as they come,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.492#Bristling his back, eyes blazing, whetting the tusks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.493#He will use to scatter the men and their dogs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.494#Idomeneus, famed for his spear, waited
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.495#As Aeneas came on.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.496#He didn't yield an inch,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.497#But he called to his friends---Ascalaphus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.498#Aphareus, Deïpyrus, Meriones,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.499#And Antilochus, masters of the war cry.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.500#His words flew out to them as he urged:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.501#"Come help me out, friends. I'm by myself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.502#And scared to death of this Aeneas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.503#Who's closing in fast. He's a hell of a fighter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.504#And in his prime. If we were his age
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.505#And in the mood we're in, it'd be over fast.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.506#He might still win big, but so might I."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.507#And they closed ranks, locking their shields.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.508#Opposite them, Aeneas called to his comrades,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.509#To Deïphobus and Paris and Agenor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.510#His peers in the Trojan command.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.511#Their troops flocked behind them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.512#Sheep following rams from pasture
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.513#To water, the shepherd's joy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.514#Aeneas that glad when he saw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.515#A nation of soldiers at his back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.516#They fought over Alcathous with their long pikes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.517#And the bronze plate on their chests rang like gongs,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.518#And above them all two men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.519#Idomeneus and Aeneas, like gods of war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.520#Strained to shred each other's flesh with cold metal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.521#Aeneas cast first, but Idomeneus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.522#Watching him all the way, sidestepped the missile,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.523#Which, launched by a strong arm but with nowhere to go,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.524#Burrowed, quivering, into the earth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.525#Idomeneus' throw hit Oenomaus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.526#Full in the belly, smashing the plates on his corselet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.527#And letting his entrails gush through the hole.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.528#He fell, clawing at the dust, Idomeneus' spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.529#Casting a long shadow on the plain. He pulled it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.530#From the corpse but could not get the armor off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.531#With all the pressure he was under. The veteran
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.532#Could no longer trust his feet in a charge,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.533#Either to follow his own throw or dodge another's,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.534#And so, unable also to get away quickly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.535#He had no choice but to stand and fight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.536#And beat off the pitiless day of doom.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.537#As he inched his way back, Deïphobus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.538#Whose anger toward him had not lost its edge,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.539#Took a shot at him. His spear burned the air
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.540#But missed Idomeneus again, hitting instead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.541#Ascalaphus, Ares' son, stitching his shoulder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.542#He fell to the ground and clawed at the dust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.543#Ares as yet knew nothing of his son's fall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.544#The blaring god sat under golden clouds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.545#On Olympus' peak, constrained from war
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.546#By Zeus' will, along with the other immortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.547#The fighting began over Ascalaphus' body.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.548#Deïphobus managed to tear off his helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.549#But dropped it when he was hit in the arm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.550#By Meriones' spear. It fell with a clang.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.551#Meriones sprang again, like a vulture,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.552#Pulled his spear out of Deïphobus' arm,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.553#Then drifted back into the ranks. Polites,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.554#Deïphobus' brother, wrapping his arms
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.555#Around his waist, escorted him out of harm's way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.556#And to the rear, where his horses stood waiting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.557#To pull him groaning in his ornamented chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.558#Back to the city, blood dripping from his arm.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.559#The rest fought on, drowning in their own noise.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.560#Aeneas jumped Aphareus, Caletor's son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.561#And, having a good angle on his throat,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.562#Sliced through it with his spear. Aphareus' head
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.563#Sank to one side, and his helmet clanged on his shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.564#As death hammered at his soul like a tinsmith.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.565#Antilochus, waiting for his moment,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.566#Caught Thoön turning his back. His quick thrust
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.567#Severed the vein that runs up to the neck,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.568#And Thoön was left supine in the dust
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.569#Stretching his arms out to his comrades.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.570#Antilochus leapt on top of him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.571#And began unbuckling the armor from his shoulders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.572#Keeping an eye on the Trojans who circled him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.573#They kept poking at his big, bright shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.574#Form every direction but couldn't stick a point
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.575#Into his flesh, this the doing of Poseidon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.576#Who guarded Nestor's son with all his power
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.577#No matter the spearpoints around him. Antilochus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.578#Was constantly engaged with the enemy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.579#His spear never at rest but always quivering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.580#With his desire to cast or thrust it home.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.581#He was taking dead aim at someone in the throng
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.582#When Adamas, Asius' son, zeroed in on him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.583#And hit his shield from point-blank range.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.584#The blue-maned sea god cancelled the shot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.585#And denied it the life of Antilochus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.586#Half the spear stuck in the shield like a charred stake,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.587#The other half lay on the ground. Adamas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.588#Knew fate when he saw it and backed away.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.589#But Meriones went after him, and his throw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.590#Caught Adamas where Ares hurts men worst,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.591#Sticking him between the navel and the genitals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.592#He doubled over, leaning into the shaft,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.593#And writhed and twisted the way a bull will
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.594#When mountain men tie it and drag it along.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.595#So too Adamas, but only for a while, until
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.596#The hero Meriones drew the spear from his gut.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.597#Then darkness drifted like a veil on his eyes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.598#In the hand-to-hand fighting, Helenus hit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.599#Deïpyrus' temple with a huge Thracian sword,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.600#Ripping the helmet from his head and sending it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.601#Rolling through the combatants' feet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.602#Until one of the Greeks scooped it up.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.603#By then Deïpyrus' eyes had gone black.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.604#The son of Atreus took his death hard---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.605#Menelaus, good at the war cry---and he strode
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.606#Menacingly toward the Trojan hero,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.607#Brandishing his sharp spear as Helenus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.608#Drew back his bow. They each shot at once,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.609#The spear and arrow crossing in mid-air,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.610#Helenus' needling arrow going on to hit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.611#Menelaus' breastplate and clang off the bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.612#Think of dark beans, or lentils, bounding up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.613#From the broad shovel a winnower wields
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.614#In a great threshing floor swept by shrill winds.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.615#Thus the arrow that ricocheted off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.616#Menelaus' corselet and went flying away.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.617#But Menelaus' own shot wasn't wasted,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.618#The sharp spearpoint hitting Helenus' bow hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.619#And going through it into the polished wood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.620#He fell back among his comrades, avoiding death,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.621#The ash-wood spear trailing from his hand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.622#Until great Agenor pulled it out for him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.623#And bound the hand with a strip of twisted wool,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.624#A sling actually, from his squire's kit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.625#Peisander now made straight at Menelaus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.626#Death drawing him on toward his fated end,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.627#To be killed by you, Menelaus, in the mêlée.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.628#When they were within range of each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.629#They each cast, Menelaus' spear missing wide,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.630#Peisander's hitting his shield but shattering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.631#At the socket against its metal face.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.632#Peisander still had hope for victory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.633#And when the son of Atreus leapt at him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.634#With his silver-studded sword, Peisander drew
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.635#From beneath his shield an axe of fine bronze
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.636#With a long haft of polished olive wood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.637#They struck each other at the same moment,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.638#Peisander's axe hitting Menelaus' helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.639#On the horn, just beneath the horsehair plume,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.640#Menelaus' sword smashing Peisander's brow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.641#Just above the nose. The bones snapped, both eyeballs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.642#Popped out in blood and dropped at his feet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.643#In the dust, and Peisander doubled over and fell.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.644#Menelaus put his foot on his chest, and as he
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.645#Ripped off his armor and gloated over him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.646#"All you Trojans will be leaving our ships like this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.647#You arrogant bastards! You can't get enough
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.648#Of fighting, can you? Can't get enough
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.649#Of abusing people, as you've abused me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.650#No room in your heart for the anger of Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.651#The Lord of Thunder, god of host and guest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.652#Whose wrath will destroy your towering city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.653#You came and took my bride, made off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.654#With all my stuff---and after you were her guest!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.655#And now you're all hot to burn our ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.656#Cut us off from the sea, and kill our men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.657#But you won't, for all your eagerness to fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.658#Father Zeus, they say you are the wisest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.659#Of gods and men. Yet all this is from you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.660#Somehow you honor these violent men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.661#These Trojans, with their reckless strength
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.662#And insatiable appetite for the horrors of war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.663#When it comes to getting enough, everyone else
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.664#Would rather have all they want of sleep or love,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.665#Of sweet song or fine dancing. But the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.666#Are gluttons for war, and cannot get enough."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.667#Thus Menelaus, as he stripped off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.668#The last bit of bloody gear and gave it to his men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.669#Then went back and took his place in the front.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.670#He was attacked immediately by Harpalion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.671#Who followed his father, king Pylaemenes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.672#To Troy and the war, but never returned home.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.673#His spear hit Menelaus' shield from close range,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.674#But not hard enough to go through. Unnerved,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.675#Harpalion drifted back to his comrades,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.676#Glancing warily over his shoulder,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.677#Half expecting to feel bronze in his skin.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.678#As he retreated Meriones shot at him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.679#The bronze-tipped arrow hit his right buttock, sliding
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.680#Beneath the bone and into his bladder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.681#Harpalion sank into his comrades' arms
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.682#And breathed out his life stretched on the ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.683#Like an earthworm in a pool of black blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.684#The Paphlagonians tended to him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.685#And took him on a chariot to sacred Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.686#In sorrow. His father went with them, weeping.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.687#Nothing would ever replace his dead son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.688#Paris was enraged at his killing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.689#Among the Paphlagonians Harpalion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.690#Had been his host, and in anger for his sake
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.691#He let fly an arrow tipped with bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.692#And a man named Euchenor got in its way.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.693#He was the son of the prophet Polyidus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.694#Rich, with estates in Corinth, a good man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.695#When he boarded ship for Troy he knew well
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.696#He was embarking on death, for his father,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.697#Old Polyidus, had told him often
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.698#That he must die of painful disease at home
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.699#Or be killed by Trojans amid Achaean ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.700#He chose to avoid both the heavy Greek fine
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.701#For avoiding service and the loathsome disease.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.702#Paris' arrow hit him behind his jawbone.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.703#His soul crawled out and the world went dark.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.704#The fight went on, like wildfire burning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.705#Hector, whom Zeus loved, did not know
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.706#That on the left side of the ships his army
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.707#Was succumbing to the Greeks, who were not far
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.708#From winning the day. The god who laps the earth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.709#And makes it tremble was urging them on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.710#And adding his own strength to their efforts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.711#Hector was still where he had first burst through
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.712#The gate and shattered the Greek ranks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.713#Close to where Ajax's and Protesilaus' ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.714#Were drawn up on the beach of the grey salt sea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.715#And the wall was lowest. Horses and men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.716#Fought furiously there, in the vortex of battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.717#There the Boeotians and fringed Ionians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.718#The Locrians, Phthians, and proud Epeians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.719#Had their hands full trying to repel
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.720#Hector's attack on the ships. Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.721#Was like a bright flame and could not be stopped,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.722#Not even by the Athenian elite,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.723#Whose captain was Menestheus, Peteos' son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.724#And who had with him men like Pheidas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.725#Stichius, and valiant Bias. The Epeians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.726#Were led by Meges, son of Phyleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.727#And by Amphius and Dracius; the Phthians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.728#By Medon and steady Podarces.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.729#Medon was a bastard son of Oïleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.730#And Ajax's brother, but he lived in Phylace,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.731#Far from his homeland, because he had killed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.732#A relative of Eriopis, his stepmother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.733#Whom Oïleus had married. Podarces
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.734#Was Iphiclus' son and Phylacus' grandson.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.735#Armed and in the front of the Phthian forces
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.736#They fought alongside the Boeotians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.737#To defend their ships. Oïleus' other son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.738#The swift Ajax, was inseparable
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.739#From Telamonian Ajax and would not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.740#Leave his side even for an instant.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.741#A team of oxen with faces dark as wine
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.742#Strain together at the jointed plow, pulling it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.743#Through a field that has not been worked in years.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.744#Sweat oozes up from the roots of their horns,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.745#And only the polished yoke holds them apart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.746#As they cut the furrow to the field's far edge.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.747#The two Ajaxes stood side by side in battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.748#Telamonian Ajax had his cadres with him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.749#And there was always someone to relieve him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.750#Of his heavy shield when he began to tire.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.751#But the Locrians commanded by Oïlean Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.752#Were not at his side. They were not trained
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.753#To stand and fight at close range, nor equipped:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.754#They had no bronze, plumed helmets, no shields,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.755#No ash-wood spears, but trusting to the bows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.756#And twisted wool slings they had brought
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.757#When they followed him to Troy, they now shot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.758#Thick and fast, trying to break the Trojan lines.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.759#In the front: troops in full battle gear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.760#Engaging Hector and his Trojans;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.761#In the rear: archers. And the Trojans, confounded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.762#By their arrows, were losing the will to fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.763#They would have been beaten miserably
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.764#From the beachhead camp back to windy Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.765#Had not Polydamas approached Hector and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.766#"Hector, you are a difficult man to persuade.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.767#Because Zeus has made you preeminent in war
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.768#You want to excel in counsel too.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.769#But you can't have everything. Zeus makes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.770#One man a warrior, another a dancer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.771#Another a singer, and in another's heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.772#He puts wisdom, by which many profit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.773#And which saves many, as the god himself knows best.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.774#So I will say to you what seems best to me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.775#All around you blazes a ring of war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.776#The Trojans have passed over the wall,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.777#But some are standing on the sidelines
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.778#And others are fighting in skirmishes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.779#Throughout the ships against superior numbers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.780#Let's fall back and regroup, weigh our options,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.781#And decide whether to attack the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.782#In the hope of victory from the god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.783#Or at least a safe retreat. As for myself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.784#I fear the Greeks will pay us back for yesterday.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.785#He is still waiting back there, you know, and he loves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.786#To fight. He won't sit out the whole war."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.787#This seemed like sound advice to Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.788#He leapt to the ground with his gear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.789#And his words flew to Polydamas:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.790#"Draw back all our best and keep them here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.791#While I go off to pass the word.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.792#I'll be back as fast as I can."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.793#And he went off like an avalanche
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.794#Down a mountain, speeding through the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.795#And their allies and shouting as he went.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.796#At the sound of his voice they all went back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.797#Toward Polydamas. Hector moved up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.798#To the fighters at the very front.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.799#He was looking for Deïphobus, for Helenus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.800#For Adamas and Adamas' father Asius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.801#And hardly found them unscathed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.802#They were either dead beside the Greek ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.803#Or nursing wounds inside the city walls.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.804#He did find Paris, though, Helen's lord,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.805#Urging on his men at the left side of battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.806#And started in on him with abusive epithets:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.807#"Paris, you desperate, preening pretty boy---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.808#Where is Deïphobus, and where are Helenus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.809#And Adamas and Adamas' father Asius?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.810#And where is Othryoneus? Troy is doomed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.811#The whole towering city as good as gone."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.812#And Paris, who could have passed for a god:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.813#"I see you're in a testy mood, Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.814#I may have held back from battle before,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.815#But not now. My mother didn't raise
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.816#A total weakling. Ever since you started
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.817#This attack on the ships we've been right here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.818#Engaging the Greeks. As for our comrades
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.819#You're asking about, they are dead,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.820#Except for Deïphobus and Helenus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.821#Who have gone off with spear wounds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.822#In their arms, saved by Zeus from death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.823#Now, lead on wherever you will,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.824#And we will follow. I don't think you will find us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.825#Lacking in determination, and we will fight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.826#To the best of our ability. No man can do more."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.827#Spoken like a hero. Hector calmed down,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.828#And they plunged into the brutal eye of combat,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.829#Which was around Cebriones and Polydamas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.830#And Phalces and Arthaeus, godlike Polyphetes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.831#Ascanius and Morys, son of Hippotion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.832#These had come from Ascania's farmland
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.833#The morning before, as replacement troops,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.834#And now Zeus roused them on to battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.835#Aching winds sweep down to the ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.836#Under rolling thunder from the patriarch Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.837#And then clash with the sea. The water moans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.838#And is whipped into wave after wave of arching,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.839#Seething breakers capped with white foam.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.840#The Trojans kept coming, rank on rank
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.841#Flashing with bronze, behind their captains.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.842#Hector, son of Priam, led them all,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.843#And he was like the War God himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.844#Behind his balanced shield, thick with hide
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.845#And layered with welded bronze, and on his head
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.846#The crest of his helm rippled in shining wind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.847#He kept testing the Greek lines here and there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.848#To see if they would yield before him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.849#As he came on behind his shield, but the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.850#Didn't flinch. Then big Ajax strode forward:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.851#"Come closer, sweetheart. No need to be coy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.852#We're not exactly inexperienced in war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.853#You know. It was Zeus who whipped us before.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.854#I'm sure you'd like to rip our ships apart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.855#But be just as sure we have hands to defend them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.856#Your city, with all its people, will likely fall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.857#A lot sooner, captured by us and plundered.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.858#As for you, the day will soon be here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.859#When you pray to Zeus and all immortals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.860#For your combed horses to outfly falcons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.861#And take you through the dusty plain to Troy."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.862#His words were not out before a bird flew past
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.863#On the right, a high-soaring eagle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.864#The Achaeans shouted, taking heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.865#At the omen. But Hector answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.866#"You bumbling ox, what a stupid thing to say.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.867#I wish it were as certain that I were Zeus' son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.868#And Hera my mother, and that I were honored
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.869#Equally with Apollo and Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.870#As it is that this day will bring doom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.871#To every last Greek, and you among them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.872#Killed by my long spear, if you have the guts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.873#To wait for it to pierce your lily-white skin
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.874#And leave your larded flesh to glut the dogs and birds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.875#Of Troy, after you have fallen amid the ships."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.876#With that he led the charge, followed by
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.877#Trojans shrieking at the top of their lungs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.878#The Greeks answered with cries of their own,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.879#Digging in their heels as Troy's best came on,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.880#And the noise from both armies blended together
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:13.881#And rose through the air to the brightness of Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.1#Nestor, drinking wine with Machaon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.2#Could not help but hear the screaming, and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.3#"Son of Asclepius, what do you make of this?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.4#Our boys are shouting much louder by the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.5#Now don't get up. Just keep sipping that wine
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.6#Until pretty Hecamede heats up a warm bath
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.7#And washes off all that clotted blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.8#Myself, I'll go to a lookout point now."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.9#With that, he picked up a metal-plated shield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.10#One of Thrasymedes' that was lying in the hut,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.11#And a heavy spear with a honed bronze point.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.12#He stepped outside and saw an ugly scene,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.13#The Greeks in rout and behind them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.14#The high-hearted Trojans, pouring through the wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.15#As the dark sea broods with a silent swell
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.16#And only a faint premonition of wind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.17#Is traced on its surface, and no crest forms
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.18#Until a decisive breeze comes down from Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.19#So the old man pondered which way to go---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.20#To join the Greek troops or to get Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.21#The son of Atreus, shepherd of his people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.22#He thought it over and went for Agamemnon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.23#The fighting continued, and the killing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.24#Armor rang under sword blades
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.25#And spearpoints nosed busily past plated shields.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.26#The wounded kings were coming up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.27#From their ships---Diomedes, Odysseus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.28#And Agamemnon---and met Nestor on the way.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.29#Their ships were drawn up far from the battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.30#On the sand by the grey sea, in the first row,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.31#And the wall was built near the last row, inland.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.32#The beach was wide but could not hold all the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.33#So they were drawn up in rows toward the plain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.34#And filled the space between the two headlands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.35#So the kings were coming up together,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.36#Leaning on their spears, to see the fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.37#And their hearts were grieved. Old Nestor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.38#Met them, and was hailed by Agamemnon:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.39#"Nestor, son of Neleus, glory of our army,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.40#Why have you left the battle and come here?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.41#I fear that Hector will make good on the threats
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.42#He levelled against us in the Trojan muster---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.43#That he would not return to Ilion until
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.44#He had burnt our ships and killed our men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.45#It's all coming true, just as he said.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.46#And the worst part is that all of the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.47#Are angry with me, just like Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.48#None of them is willing to defend our ships."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.49#And Nestor, the Gerenian horseman, answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.50#"Yes, this is how things are, and Zeus himself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.51#The thunder lord, could not make them otherwise.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.52#For the wall is down. We put our trust in it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.53#As a bulwark for our ships, and now the enemy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.54#Is at our ships, fighting relentlessly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.55#You cannot even tell in which direction
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.56#Our men are retreating, so confused
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.57#Is their slaughter, the air so filled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.58#With the noise of battle, up to the sky.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.59#We must take counsel in this situation,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.60#Not enter the battle ourselves.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.61#It is not possible for wounded men to fight."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.62#And Agamemnon, the warlord:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.63#"Well then, Nestor, the ships are under attack,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.64#And neither the wall nor the trench,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.65#Which we trusted to be a bulwark
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.66#For our beachhead camp, has been of any avail.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.67#It must be the pleasure of Zeus Almighty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.68#For us to die here, nameless and far from Argos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.69#I knew it when he was favoring the Greeks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.70#And I know now that he is giving the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.71#Glory from above and has tied our hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.72#So this is what I say we should all do now:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.73#Let's haul the first line of ships to the water,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.74#Get them afloat and moor them with anchors
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.75#Until darkness comes. If and when the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.76#Stop for the night, we can drag down the rest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.77#It is no shame to flee ruin, even by night.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.78#Better to give evil the slip than be caught by it."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.79#Odysseus looked him up and down, and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.80#"What kind of thing is that to say?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.81#You're a ruined man, son of Atreus, fit to command
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.82#Some ragtag army, but not to rule over men like us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.83#To whom Zeus has granted just one thing in life:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.84#To wind up wars like skeins of wool,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.85#From youth to old age, until the last of us dies.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.86#Do you really want to leave Troy behind,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.87#The great city that we've suffered so much for?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.88#Stop that talk before somebody hears you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.89#Words like that should never make it past your mouth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.90#You're a sceptered king commanding the loyalty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.91#Of an army of Greeks. You must have lost your mind,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.92#Ordering us to launch ships while the battle is raging.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.93#The Trojans, who are winning as it is,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.94#Will have all their prayers answered, and our army
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.95#Will be utterly crushed. Draw the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.96#To the sea, and the Greeks will be looking
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.97#Over their shoulders and give up the fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.98#Your plan will ruin us, Lord Agamemnon."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.99#To which Agamemnon briefly replied:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.100#"That cuts deep, Odysseus. I am not suggesting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.101#That the ships be launched against the Achaeans' will.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.102#I wish there were someone, young or old,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.103#With a better plan than mine. I would welcome that."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.104#Diomedes, the bull-roarer, had a response:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.105#"The man is here, no need for a long search,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.106#If you are willing to listen, and if none of you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.107#Will be upset because I am the youngest in years.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.108#There's nothing wrong with my lineage. My father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.109#Was Tydeus, who lies buried at Thebes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.110#My great-grandfather Portheus had three peerless sons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.111#Who lived in Pleuron and steep Calydon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.112#Agrios, Melas, and the horseman Oineus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.113#My father's father, the bravest of the three.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.114#My father left home and wandered to Argos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.115#As Zeus and the other gods no doubt willed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.116#He married one of Adrastus' daughters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.117#And lived in a rich house with many acres
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.118#In wheat and orchards, and many sheep.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.119#And he was the best spearman in all Argos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.120#You will have heard of all this and know it is true.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.121#So don't think I'm a coward by birth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.122#And reject anything worthwhile I might have to say.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.123#We must go down to the battle, injuries and all,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.124#Not to fight---we will stay out of range
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.125#To avoid taking wounds on top of wounds---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.126#But to spur the others on and send them in,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.127#Those who have been on the sidelines
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.128#Nursing their resentment and failing to fight."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.129#They heard him out and agreed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.130#Agamemnon led the way as they started out.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.131#Poseidon was not blind to any of this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.132#But went with them disguised as an old man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.133#He took Agamemnon by his right hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.134#And spoke to him words that winged home:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.135#"Well, son of Atreus, Achilles' dark heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.136#Must be laughing now, as he sees
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.137#The panic and slaughter of the Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.138#The man hasn't a shred of sense left, none,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.139#Damn him! May some god cripple him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.140#But the blessed ones aren't angry with you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.141#Not yet. There's still a chance you will see
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.142#The Trojan generals raise dust on the wide plain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.143#As they beat a retreat from your ships and huts."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.144#And as he sped over the plain, Poseidon yelled,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.145#So loud it seemed that ten thousand warriors
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.146#Had been enlisted by Ares and shouted at once.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.147#And the god's yell put into each Greek's heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.148#The strength to fight and battle on without pause.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.149#Standing on a crag of Olympus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.150#Gold-throned Hera saw her brother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.151#Who was her husband's brother too,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.152#Busy on the fields of human glory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.153#And her heart sang. Then she saw Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.154#Sitting on the topmost peak of Ida
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.155#And was filled with resentment. Cow-eyed Hera
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.156#Mused for a while on how to trick
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.157#The mind of Zeus Aegis-Holder,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.158#And the plan that seemed best to her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.159#Was to make herself up and go to Ida,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.160#Seduce him, and then shed on his eyelids
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.161#And cunning mind a sleep gentle and warm.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.162#She went to the bedroom her darling son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.163#Hephaestus had built for her, and closed
