urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.304#And Hera, with every intention to deceive:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.305#"I'm off to visit the ends of the earth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.306#And Father Ocean and Mother Tethys
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.307#Who nursed and doted on me in their house.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.308#I'm going to see them and try to resolve
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.309#Their endless quarrel. For eons now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.310#They've been angry and haven't made love.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.311#My horses stand at the foot of Ida,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.312#Ready to bear me over land and sea.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.313#I came here from Olympus for your sake,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.314#So you wouldn't be upset that I left
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.315#To visit Ocean without a word to you."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.316#And Zeus, clouds scudding about him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.317#"You can go there later just as well.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.318#Let's get in bed now and make love.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.319#No goddess or woman has ever
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.320#Made me feel so overwhelmed with lust,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.321#Not even when I fell for Ixion's wife,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.322#Who bore Peirithous, wise as a god;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.323#Or Danae, with lovely, slim ankles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.324#Who bore Perseus, a paragon of men;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.325#Or the daughter of far-famed Phoenix,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.326#Who bore Minos and godlike Rhadamanthus;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.327#Or Semele; or Alcmene in Thebes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.328#Who bore Heracles, a stouthearted son;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.329#And Semele bore Dionysus, a joy to humans;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.330#Or Demeter, the fair-haired queen;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.331#Or glorious Leto; or even you---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.332#I've never loved anyone as I love you now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.333#Never been in the grip of desire so sweet."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.334#And Hera, with every intention to deceive:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.335#"What a thing to say, my awesome lord.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.336#The thought of us lying down here on Ida
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.337#And making love outdoors in broad daylight!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.338#What if one of the Immortals saw us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.339#Asleep, and went to all the other gods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.340#And told them? I could never get up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.341#And go back home. It would be shameful.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.342#But if you really do want to do this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.343#There is the bedroom your dear son Hephaestus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.344#Built for you, with good solid doors. Let's go
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.345#There and lie down, since you're in the mood."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.346#And Zeus, who masses the clouds, replied:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.347#"Hera, don't worry about any god or man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.348#Seeing us. I'll enfold you in a cloud so dense
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.349#And golden not even Helios could spy on us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.350#And his light is the sharpest vision there is."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.351#With that he caught his wife in his arms.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.352#Beneath them the shining soil sprouted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.353#Fresh grass, and dewy lotus, and crocus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.354#And hyacinth, soft and thick, that kept them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.355#Up off the ground. And as they lay there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.356#A beautiful, golden cloud enfolded them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.357#And precipitated drops of glimmering dew.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.358#And so the Father slept soundly on Gargaron's peak,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.359#Mastered by Sleep and Love, and held his wife close.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.360#But sweet Sleep ran down to the Achaean ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.361#With a message for Poseidon the Earthshaker.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.362#He stood close to him, and his words winged home:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.363#"Help the Greeks all you want now, Poseidon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.364#And give them their glory, however brief,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.365#While Zeus still sleeps, for Hera has bedded him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.366#And I have wrapped him in downy slumber."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.367#Saying this, Sleep went off to the human world,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.368#Leaving Poseidon more determined than ever
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.369#To aid the Greeks. He sprang to the front and cried:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.370#"Achaeans! Are we going to concede victory to Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.371#So he can take our ships and claim the glory?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.372#That's how he's talking, now that Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.373#Is nursing his wrath on the beach by his hulls.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.374#But we won't miss him too much if the rest of us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.375#All pull together and help each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.376#Now here's what I want all of us to do.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.377#Get the biggest and best shields in the army,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.378#Strap on full-metal helmets, arm yourselves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.379#With the longest spears you can find,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.380#And let's move out! You have my word that Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.381#No matter how eager he is, won't hold his ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.382#Now let's go---and exchange gear if you have to,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.383#So that our best fighters have the biggest shields."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.384#He spoke, they listened, and they did as he said.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.385#And the kings, though wounded---Diomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.386#Odysseus, and Agamemnon---marshalled them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.387#Going through the ranks and switching armor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.388#So that the best men were using the best gear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.389#When their bodies were covered with burnished bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.390#They moved out, led by Poseidon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.391#Who held in his clenched fist a terrible sword,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.392#Its long edge like lightning, a weapon outlawed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.393#In mortal combat, sheer terror for men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.394#Opposite him, Hector marshalled the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.395#And the two of them tightened the cords of war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.396#Poseidon tossing his dark-blue mane and Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.397#Standing in a cone of cold light, while the sea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.398#Surged up to the Greek ships and huts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.399#The two sides closed with a pulsating roar.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.400#The pounding of surf when arching breakers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.401#Roll in from the deep under painful northern winds,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.402#Or the hissing roar of a forest fire
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.403#When it climbs the hills to burn all the woods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.404#Or the howling of wind when it is angry with oaks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.405#And moans and shrieks through their leafy branches
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.406#Will give you some idea of the uncanny noise
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.407#The Greeks and Trojans made when they clashed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.408#Hector struck first, a spearcast at Ajax,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.409#Who was in his line of fire. He didn't miss,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.410#But the spear hit Ajax where his two belts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.411#One for his shield, one for his silver-studded sword,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.412#Formed a protective cross over his skin.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.413#Angry that he had made a good throw for nothing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.414#Hector backstepped into the ranks of his army,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.415#Avoiding fate. But as he withdrew, big Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.416#Picked up one of the stones that had rolled underfoot---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.417#There were many of these, used as chocks for the ships---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.418#And caught Hector on the chest, above his shield's rim
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.419#Just under the neck, and sent him spinning like a top.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.420#He fell as a tree falls, an oak tree blasted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.421#By lightning from Zeus. The tree is uprooted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.422#And the air reeks of brimstone, and no one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.423#Who sees this from close up has any desire
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.424#To be near Zeus' thunderbolts ever again.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.425#So Hector fell to the ground in the dust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.426#The spear was knocked from his hand, but his shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.427#And helmet flew up in the air and then came down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.428#Clattering on the rest of his embellished armor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.429#The Greeks ran up screaming with delight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.430#Hurling javelins thick and fast, and hoping
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.431#To drag him off. But they couldn't touch him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.432#All Troy's best crowded around their hero---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.433#Polydamas, Aeneas, Agenor, Glaucus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.434#Sarpedon, the Lycian commander---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.435#No one neglected Hector. They circled him with shields
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.436#And lifted him up and away from war's toil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.437#Until they brought him to the rear of the battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.438#Where his horses stood with his charioteer and rig,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.439#Which took him groaning back toward the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.440#But when they reached the ford of the Xanthus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.441#The beautiful, swirling river that Zeus begot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.442#They lifted him from the chariot to the ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.443#And poured water on him. This brought him around.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.444#His eyes opened, and kneeling on his knees,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.445#He vomited up a cloud of black blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.446#Then he sank back to the ground, and darkness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.447#Covered his eyes. The blow still mastered his spirit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.448#When the Greeks saw that Hector was gone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.449#They remembered how much they loved to fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.450#First to draw blood was Oïlean Ajax.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.451#A quick leap and thrust of his spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.452#Brought down Satnius, son of Enops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.453#And a peerless Naiad who lived in the river,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.454#The Satnioeis, where he tended his flocks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.455#When Ajax's spear hit him on the flank
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.456#He fell on his back and became the center
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.457#Of some hard fighting. Polydamas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.458#Panthous' son, came up to help him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.459#And put his spear through the right shoulder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.460#Of Prothoënor, Areïlycus' son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.461#The spear's weight carried it clear through,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.462#And he fell to the earth clawing at the dust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.463#Polydamas gloated over him loudly:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.464#"Hah! Another great throw from the strong hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.465#Of the heroic son of Panthous,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.466#And another Greek has my spear in his flesh!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.467#Use it as a crutch on your way down to hell."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.468#This boast pained the Greeks, no one more so
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.469#Than Telamonian Ajax, who was closest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.470#To the man when he fell. Ajax's bright spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.471#Was in the air instantly, hurtling at Polydamas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.472#Who managed to dodge both its point and his death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.473#No matter. The spear lodged in Archelochus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.474#Antenor's son, whom the gods wanted to die.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.475#Just where the neck splices into the spine,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.476#At the topmost vertebra, the spearblade sheared
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.477#Through the double tendon. His mouth and nose
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.478#Hit the earth before his legs and knees.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.479#It was Ajax's turn to call to Polydamas:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.480#"What do you think, Polydamas? Was this man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.481#Worthy to be killed in return for Prothoënor?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.482#He wasn't simply a nobody, was he?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.483#Looks like he might be Antenor's brother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.484#Or his son. There's a family resemblance."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.485#He knew perfectly well who it was. The Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.486#Felt their chests tighten. Then Acamas, straddling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.487#His brother's body, stitched his spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.488#Through Promachus, the Boeotian,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.489#Who was trying to drag the corpse by its feet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.490#Into the clear. Acamas was exultant:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.491#"Try fighting sometime instead of issuing threats!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.492#We're not going to be the only side to suffer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.493#We're going to give as good as we get.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.494#How do you like the nap Promachus is taking,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.495#Courtesy of my spear? I didn't waste any time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.496#Collecting the price for my brother's blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.497#That's what family is for---to beat off ruin."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.498#The Greeks winced when they heard this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.499#No one more so than the warrior Peneleos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.500#He charged, and when Acamas did not wait
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.501#For his onslaught he hit Ilioneus instead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.502#This man's father was Phorbas, whom Hermes loved
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.503#More than any other Trojan and who had the flocks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.504#And wealth to prove it, but only one child,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.505#Ilioneus. Peneleos' spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.506#Went through his eye socket, gouging out the eyeball
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.507#And going clear through the nape of the neck.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.508#Ilioneus stretched out his hands as he settled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.509#Slowly to earth. Peneleos took out his sword
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.510#And hacked at his neck, severing the head,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.511#Helmet and all. The great spear was still stuck
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.512#In the eye socket. Peneleos held it up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.513#Like a poppy, and showing it to the Trojans, said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.514#"Kindly take word to Ilioneus' parents
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.515#To lament their prince in his family's halls,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.516#As the wife of Promachus, Agenor's son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.517#Will lament the absence of her cherished husband
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.518#When the Greeks return on their ships from Troy."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.519#He spoke, and the Trojans began to tremble,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.520#Eyes searching for an escape from death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.521#Muses who dwell on Olympus, tell me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.522#Who was the first Greek to bear away spoils
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.523#Once Poseidon had turned the battle's tide?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.524#Telamonian Ajax, who wounded Hyrtius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.525#Son of Gyrtius, leader of the Mysians.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.526#And Antilochus despoiled Phalces and Mermerus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.527#And Meriones slew Morys and Hippotion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.528#And Teucer stripped Prothoön and Periphetes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.529#And the son of Atreus wounded Hyperenor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.530#In the flank, and when the bronze clove through
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.531#All the bowels spilled out, and his soul rushed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.532#Through the gaping wound, and night covered his eyes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.533#But Ajax, Oïleus' swift son, killed the most.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.534#No one could chase down men in a rout
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:14.535#Faster than he, when Zeus makes them panic.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.1#The Trojans had retreated through the palisade
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.2#And trench, a beaten army, and had halted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.3#Beside their chariots, their faces pale
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.4#With terror, when Zeus awoke
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.5#On Ida's summit with Hera by his side.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.6#He jumped to his feet and saw the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.7#Being routed by howling Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.8#With Poseidon Lord among them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.9#And Hector lying on the plain, his friends
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.10#Crouched around him while he gasped for breath
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.11#In a haze of pain, and vomited blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.12#It was no flyweight Greek who had hit him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.13#The Father of Gods and Men felt pity for him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.14#And, scowling at Hera, delivered this speech:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.15#"Hera, you scheming bitch, this trick of yours
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.16#Has taken Hector out and routed his army.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.17#And you may be the first to profit from your plot---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.18#When I whip the living daylights out of you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.19#Or don't you remember when I strung you up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.20#With anvils hanging from your feet and gold
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.21#Unbreakable bands on your wrists? You dangled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.22#In the air among the clouds, and all the gods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.23#On high Olympus protested, but none
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.24#Could come to your rescue. If anyone tried
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.25#I'd send him sailing off our balcony---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.26#There wouldn't be much left when he hit the ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.27#Even so, my heart still ached for Heracles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.28#You and Boreas, whose squalls you suborned,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.29#Had maliciously driven him over the desert sea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.30#And brought him later to the great city of Cos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.31#I got him out of there and led him back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.32#To bluegrass Argos, after many labors.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.33#I remind you of this so you'll quit playing games
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.34#And see where this gets you, making love to me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.35#The way you did just now, and tricking me."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.36#The ox-eyed lady Hera stiffened at this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.37#And she feathered her words home carefully:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.38#"All right. I swear by Earth and Heaven above,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.39#And the subterranean water of Styx, the greatest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.40#And the most awesome oath a god can swear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.41#By your sacred head and by our marriage couch,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.42#Upon which I would never perjure myself---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.43#That it is not by my will that Poseidon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.44#Is hurting the Trojans and helping the Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.45#He's acting of his own free will, out of pity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.46#For the beating the Greeks are taking by their ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.47#But I would advise even him to toe the line
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.48#And follow wherever you lead, Dark Cloud."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.49#Zeus, the Father of Gods and Men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.50#Smiled at this and issued a swift reply:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.51#"Well, my ox-eyed Lady, if your mind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.52#Really were to be the same as mine, Poseidon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.53#Would find it difficult not to follow us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.54#So if you mean what you say, go back now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.55#To the gods and send Iris here, and Apollo,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.56#She to go down to the bronze-coated Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.57#And tell Lord Poseidon to desist from the war;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.58#And Phoebus Apollo to rouse Hector to fight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.59#Breathe strength into him again, so that he may
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.60#Forget the pain that now distresses him and
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.61#Drive the Achaeans back once more in flight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.62#So shall they flee in panic and fall dead among
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.63#The hollow ships of Peleus' son Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.64#Who will send forth his comrade Patroclus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.65#Whom illustrious Hector will kill with his spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.66#Before Ilion, after Patroclus himself has killed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.67#Many a youth, among them Sarpedon, my son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.68#In wrath for Patroclus Achilles will kill Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.69#From that time on I shall cause the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.70#To be driven back from the ships, until the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.71#Capture steep Ilion through Athena's counsel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.72#But until that time comes I will not cease
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.73#From my wrath or allow any immortal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.74#To bear aid to the Danaans until the desire
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.75#Of the son of Peleus is fulfilled, as I
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.76#Promised at the first with a nod of my head
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.77#On the day when Thetis begged me by my knees
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.78#To honor Achilles, sacker of cities."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.79#White-armed Hera was obedient to his word
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.80#And went from Ida's mountains to long Olympus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.81#The thought of a man who has seen the world
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.82#Travels quickly to any spot on the globe
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.83#When he wishes he were there---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.84#So Hera flew with the speed of desire
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.85#And came to Olympus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.86#She found the immortal gods assembled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.87#In the house of Zeus. When they saw her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.88#They were quick to toast her arrival.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.89#She ignored them all, but did take a cup
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.90#From lovely Themis, who had run up to greet her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.91#And who now addressed her with winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.92#"Hera, why have you come? You look so upset. Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.93#Must have really frightened you---your own husband!"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.94#The goddess, ivory-armed Hera, replied:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.95#"Don't get me started, Themis. You know yourself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.96#What a bully he is, and how stubborn. No,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.97#Let's get on with the feast, and you will hear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.98#Along with the others what Zeus means to do.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.99#It's not very pretty, and I rather doubt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.100#That anyone, mortal or god, will be pleased---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.101#Or if anyone will still have an appetite left."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.102#Hera composed herself and sat down.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.103#The gods' mood darkened. Hera smiled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.104#With her lips, but her dark brows were tense,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.105#And at last she burst out indignantly:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.106#"We're all simpering idiots to be angry with Zeus!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.107#We all want to get to him, to talk him down,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.108#To beat some sense into him, but does he care?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.109#He doesn't even notice! No, he sits apart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.110#Secure in his supreme, almighty power.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.111#You'll just have to take whatever grief
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.112#He dishes out to you. I'm afraid that now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.113#It's Ares' turn to suffer, seeing that his son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.114#Whom he loves more than any mortal man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.115#His dear Ascalaphus, has died in battle."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.116#When Ares heard this he smacked his muscled thighs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.117#With the flat of his hands and wailed out loud:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.118#"None of you Olympians can blame me now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.119#If I go to the Greek ships and avenge my son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.120#Not even if I am to be blasted by Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.121#And lie among corpses in the blood and dust."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.122#And he ordered his sons, Panic and Rout,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.123#To yoke his team while he buckled on armor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.124#The hostility between the gods and Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.125#Would have reached new heights then,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.126#Had not Athena, afraid for them all,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.127#Jumped from her throne, sped through the door,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.128#And disarmed Ares. She plucked the helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.129#From his head, the shield from his shoulders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.130#Took the stiff, bronze spear from his hands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.131#And gave the furious War God a tongue-lashing:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.132#"Are you out of your mind? Didn't you hear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.133#What Hera just said, or don't you care?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.134#Do you want more trouble than you can handle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.135#Forced to crawl back to Olympus yourself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.136#And sowing disaster for the rest of us?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.137#He'll leave the Trojans and Greeks, you know,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.138#And come back here to raise hell with us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.139#Mauling us all in turn, guilty or not.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.140#So please get over your anger for your son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.141#Better men than he have been killed or will be.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.142#Human offspring are hard to save."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.143#Ares gave in, and sat back down on his throne.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.144#Then Hera called Apollo out of the palace,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.145#And Iris, too, the immortals' messenger,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.146#And said to them in a quick flurry of words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.147#"Zeus wants you to go to Ida immediately.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.148#When you arrive you will look upon his face
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.149#And do whatever he orders you to do."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.150#Having said that, Lady Hera turned away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.151#And sat down on her throne.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.152#The pair darted off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.153#And came to Ida, mountain mother of beasts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.154#And found Cronus' son on Gargaron Peak,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.155#Sitting in a wreath of fragrant cloud.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.156#They stood respectfully before the face of Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.157#And his mood brightened when he saw how promptly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.158#The two of them had obeyed his wife's words.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.159#He addressed Iris first, with words on wings:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.160#"Go, swift Iris, to Lord Poseidon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.161#And tell him this as true messenger.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.162#Bid him cease from war and battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.163#And go off to the other gods, or to the bright sea.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.164#If he is inclined to disregard my words
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.165#Have him consider in his mind and heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.166#That strong as he is he cannot withstand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.167#My onset, since I am mightier by far
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.168#And elder born. Yet he has the gall to claim
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.169#He is equal to me, whom all the gods dread."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.170#He spoke, and Iris was off in a blur of wind,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.171#Moving down Ida's mountain to holy Troy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.172#Like snow or hail flying from the clouds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.173#Under a cold blast from the brilliant North.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.174#So Iris flew with the speed of desire
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.175#And confronted the glorious Shaker of Earth:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.176#"A message for you, blue-maned Sea God.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.177#I come here from Zeus who bears the aegis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.178#And who bids you cease from war and battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.179#And go off to the other gods, or to the bright sea.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.180#If you are inclined to disregard his words,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.181#He threatens to come here himself and wage war
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.182#Against you, and he strongly advises you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.183#To avoid his hands, since he is mightier by far
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.184#And elder born. Yet you have the gall to claim
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.185#You are equal to him, whom all the gods dread."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.186#The Earthshaker made this angry reply:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.187#"He may be strong, but this is outrageous,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.188#To force me, his peer, to stop against my will.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.189#We three brothers, whom Rhea bore to Cronus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.190#Zeus, myself, and Hades, lord of the dead,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.191#Divided up the universe into equal shares.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.192#When we shook the lots, I got the grey sea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.193#As my eternal domain; Hades, the nether gloom;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.194#Zeus, the broad sky with clouds and bright air.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.195#Earth and high Olympus remain common to all.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.196#I will not follow Zeus' whims. Mighty as he is,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.197#Let him remain content with his third share,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.198#And not try to frighten me as if I were a coward.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.199#Better for him to threaten his own children
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.200#With abusive language, the sons and daughters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.201#He begot himself, who will listen because they must."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.202#And Iris, her feet soft in the offshore wind:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.203#"Is this the message, blue-maned Sea God,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.204#I should take to Zeus, this hard, unyielding speech?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.205#Will you not relent, as noble hearts often do?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.206#You know how the Furies always side with the elder."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.207#And Poseidon Earthshaker answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.208#"That is very well spoken, Iris. It is good
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.209#When a messenger understands how things are.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.210#But bitter pain comes to my heart and soul
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.211#Whenever anyone attacks an equal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.212#A peer of equal status, with angry words.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.213#Although I am offended, I will yield for now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.214#But I will say this, and make this threat from my heart:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.215#If in spite of me and Pallas Athena,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.216#And Hera and Hermes and Hephaestus Lord,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.217#He spares steep Ilion, and is not willing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.218#To lay it waste, nor give power to the Greeks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.219#He can be sure of eternal strife between us."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.220#And with that Poseidon left the Greek army
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.221#And dove into the sea. They missed him sorely.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.222#Cumulus clouds piled high on Ida's summit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.223#Zeus turned and spoke to Apollo:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.224#"Go now, Phoebus, to bronze-clad Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.225#Tremendous Poseidon has gone into the sea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.226#That laps the earth, avoiding my precipitous
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.227#Wrath. Too bad. The fight would have been legend,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.228#Even among the gods below with Cronus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.229#But it was better for us both that he yielded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.230#Before me, angry and indignant as he was.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.231#It would not have been settled without some sweat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.232#At any rate, take the tasselled aegis in your hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.233#And shake it over the Greeks to rout their heroes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.234#And see to Hector yourself. Fortify him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.235#Until the Greeks have run back to their ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.236#On the Hellespont. I'll take it from there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.237#And see the Achaeans get some breathing space."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.238#Apollo did not disobey his father's words.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.239#He came down from Ida's peaks like a falcon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.240#That bloodies doves in flight, swift on the wing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.241#And found Hector, light of Troy, sitting up---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.242#He no longer lay down---and catching his breath.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.243#He recognized his friends, and his gasping
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.244#And sweating had stopped, since Zeus now had
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.245#A mind to revive him. Apollo stood close and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.246#"Hector, son of Priam, why are you sitting here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.247#Apart from the rest, scarcely alive? What is wrong?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.248#Hector's helmet shone in the light. He said weakly:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.249#"Which god are you, questioning me face to face?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.250#Haven't you heard that while I was killing his friends
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.251#At the rear of the ships, booming Ajax hit me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.252#In the chest with a stone and took the fight out of me?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.253#I thought I would see the dead in Hades' house
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.254#This very day, after I had breathed forth my last."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.255#And Apollo, Lord of bright distances:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.256#"Courage. The Son of Cronus has sent me from Ida
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.257#To help and stand by you---no one less than me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.258#Phoebus Apollo, the Gold Sword, who has in the past
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.259#Saved both you and your steep citadel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.260#Come now and rally your many charioteers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.261#To drive their horses against the hollow ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.262#I will go ahead and smooth all the ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.263#For the chariots, and I will turn the Greek heroes."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.264#And he breathed strength into the man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.265#Who tended Troy's army as a shepherd his flock.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.266#Picture a horse that has eaten barley in its stall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.267#Breaking its halter and galloping across the plain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.268#Making for his accustomed swim in the river,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.269#A glorious animal, head held high, mane streaming
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.270#Like wind on his shoulders. Sure of his splendor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.271#He prances by the horse-runs and the mares in pasture.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.272#That was Hector, knees and feet like wind,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.273#As he rallied the chariots. He had heard the god's voice.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.274#And the Greeks?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.275#Hunters and hounds have been hot on the trail
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.276#Of an antlered stag or a mountain goat,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.277#But a sudden sheer rock or a tangled wood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.278#Saves the animal, which was not theirs to catch,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.279#And their shouting brings a bearded lion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.280#Into their path. Then the eager hunters turn back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.281#Hordes of Greeks had been advancing relentlessly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.282#Carving their way forward with spears and swords.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.283#But when they saw Hector patrolling the ranks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.284#They tensed up with fear and stopped in their tracks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.285#Thoas assessed the situation for them. This man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.286#Son of Andraemon and by far the best of the Aetolians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.287#Was not only good with javelin and sword,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.288#But very few Greeks of his generation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.289#Could vie with him when the young men debated.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.290#Now he addressed the Greek command:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.291#"Is this a miracle my eyes are seeing?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.292#Hector has risen from the dead. At least,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.293#We all hoped he had died under Ajax's hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.294#One of the gods has delivered Hector again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.295#And he's going to go doing what he's always done---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.296#Cut the legs out from under many Danaans---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.297#Since he's not standing out there as a champion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.298#Contrary to the will of thundering Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.299#Now listen to what I say we should do.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.300#Let's have the troops fall back to the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.301#And have all of our best take a stand here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.302#So we can hit him first and push him back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.303#With a phalanx of spears. That should stop him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.304#From being so eager to get to our troops."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.305#They heard him out and did as he said.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.306#The leaders of this action were big Ajax,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.307#Idomeneus, Teucer, Meriones,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.308#And Meges. Collecting a few good men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.309#They took up a position opposite Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.310#As the main troops fell back to the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.311#The Trojans attacked en masse, Hector out front
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.312#Advancing with long strides, and before him Apollo,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.313#Shining, his shoulders capped with cloud, the aegis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.314#He bore in his hands a shaggy, electric glow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.315#This the craft of Hephaestus and given to Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.316#For the routing of armies, but now Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.317#Bore it in his hands before the Trojan army.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.318#The tight knot of Greeks met them, and a shrill cry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.319#Rose from each side. Arrows jumped from bowstrings,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.320#And spears hurled by bold hands either stuck
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.321#In young men fast (but not fast enough) in battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.322#Or stopped halfway before touching white skin
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.323#And stood quivering in the ground, lusting for flesh.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.324#As long as Apollo held the aegis still,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.325#Soldiers on both sides were hit and went down.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.326#But when he looked the Greeks full in the face
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.327#And shook the aegis, and yelled as only a god can,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.328#He shrivelled their hearts, and they lost their nerve.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.329#They became like cattle or a flock of sheep
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.330#When a pair of wolves attacks them at midnight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.331#Out of the darkness, and no herdsman is near,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.332#These pathetic, running Greeks, panicked by Apollo,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.333#Who gave all the glory to the Trojans and Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.334#The fighting was scattered, man to man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.335#Hector took out Stichius and Arcesilaus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.336#One was leader of the bronze-shirted Boeotians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.337#The other a comrade of the hero Menestheus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.338#Aeneas' victims were Medon and Iasus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.339#Medon was a bastard son of Oïleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.340#And Ajax's brother, but he lived in Phylace,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.341#Far from his homeland, because he had killed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.342#A relative of Eriopis, his stepmother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.343#Whom Oïleus had married. Iasus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.344#An Athenian captain, was son of Sphelus Boukolides.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.345#Polydamas took out Mecisteus, Polites
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.346#Killed Echius in the forefront of the fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.347#And Clonius fell to brilliant Agenor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.348#Paris got Deïochus from behind,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.349#Hitting him below the shoulder as he ran back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.350#Through the front lines, and driving the bronze home.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.351#While they were stripping the armor from these,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.352#The Greeks were crowding madly into the trench,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.353#Against the stakes, and, by sheer pressure, through the wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.354#Hector called to the Trojans, making his voice carry:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.355#"Forget the spoils and go for the ships!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.356#If I catch any man hanging back on this side
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.357#He's dead on the spot with no family funeral.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.358#Dogs will tear his body apart before the city."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.359#He brought the whip down on his horses' backs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.360#And called to the Trojans along the ranks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.361#They answered his shout and held their horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.362#Even with his. The noise was deafening.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.363#Before their rolling chariots Phoebus Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.364#Danced on the banks of the trench and pushed the earth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.365#Into the cavity, making for them a causeway
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.366#As wide as a field for the javelin throw.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.367#They poured over it, rank after rank, Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.368#Leading the way with the priceless aegis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.369#And casting down the Achaean wall with ease.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.370#A child playing on the seashore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.371#Will build the sand into fantastic shapes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.372#Then gleefully knock them down with his feet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.373#Yes, Apollo, all that Achaean toil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.374#Went down like sand, and you made them run
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.375#All the way back to their ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.376#Stopped by the line of vessels, they cried out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.377#To each other, but mostly to the gods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.378#Lifting their hands, each man praying,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.379#And Nestor of Gerenia praying the hardest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.380#Hands outstretched to the starry sky:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.381#"Father Zeus, if ever any man of us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.382#Burned to thee in wheat-bearing Argos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.383#Fat thigh-bones of bulls and of rams
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.384#And prayed to return, and thou didst promise
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.385#And nod thy head, remember it now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.386#And deliver us, O God of Olympus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.387#From the day of doom, nor allow the Achaeans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.388#Thus to be vanquished by the men of Troy."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.389#Zeus heard the old man's prayer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.390#And the sky pealed with thunder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.391#But when the Trojans heard the rumbling overhead,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.392#They redoubled their efforts against the Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.393#Far out at sea a huge wave washes over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.394#The gunnels of a ship driven by a gale,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.395#And the wind is whipping the waves even higher.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.396#The Trojans shrieked as they rushed over the wall,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.397#Driving their chariots into the Greek camp
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.398#To fight at the ships' sterns with bladed spears,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.399#They from their cars, the Greeks from the decks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.400#Of the tarred ships to which they had climbed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.401#And from which they fought with the long naval pikes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.402#They had on board for battles at sea---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.403#Huge jointed poles armed with bronze tips.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.404#And Patroclus, all during the fight for the wall,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.405#Which took place some distance from the beached ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.406#Sat in the hut of Eurypylus, his wounded host,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.407#Cheering him up with small talk and rubbing ointments
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.408#Onto his ugly wound to ease his dark pangs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.409#But when he saw the Trojans rushing onto the wall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.410#And the Greeks beating a noisy retreat, he groaned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.411#And slapped his thighs with his hands, saying:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.412#"Eurypylus, I know you're hurting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.413#But I can't stay with you here any longer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.414#A big fight is brewing. Have your man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.415#Take care of you. I'm off to see Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.416#To try to talk him into fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.417#God willing, I may be able to persuade him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.418#Persuasion works when it comes from a friend."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.419#As Patroclus ran off, the Greeks withstood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.420#The Trojan onslaught, but could not push them back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.421#From the ships, even with their superior numbers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.422#Nor could the Trojans break their resistance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.423#And get into the middle of the ships and huts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.424#The battle was stretched as taut as a carpenter's cord
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.425#Snapped onto a beam to mark a straight line.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.426#So even was the tension along the line of ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.427#Though at each ship there were different engagements.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.428#Hector had made straight for Ajax. Ajax stood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.429#As if scissored out of the sky, on a black ship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.430#And he and Hector now fought for that ship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.431#Hector trying to push him back and burn it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.432#Ajax holding him off. Neither could do much
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.433#About the other, so Ajax cast and hit Caletor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.434#Son of Clytius, who was bringing up fire.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.435#He fell heavily, the torch dropping from his hand.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.436#He was Hector's cousin, and when Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.437#Saw him go down in the sand before the ship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.438#He called to the Trojans and Lycians:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.439#"Stand your ground and fight for Clytius' son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.440#Don't let the Greeks strip him of his armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.441#Just because he has fallen by the ships."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.442#As he spoke his spear flashed toward Ajax,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.443#Missing him but hitting Lycophron,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.444#Mastor's son and one of Ajax's lieutenants
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.445#Who lived with him because he had killed a man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.446#In sacred Cythera. Hector's spear caught him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.447#Above the ear as he stood near Ajax,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.448#And he fell backward from the ship's stern.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.449#He was dead when he hit the ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.450#Ajax stiffened, and he said to his brother:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.451#"Teucer, we've lost a true friend, Lycophron,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.452#Whom we honored as we did our parents
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.453#When he came from Cythera to live with us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.454#Hector killed him. Where are your arrows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.455#And the bow that Phoebus Apollo gave you?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.456#Teucer lost no time in coming up to him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.457#With his strung bow and quiver of arrows.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.458#Shooting rapid-fire at the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.459#He hit Cleitus, who was the son of Peisenor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.460#And Polydamas' friend, as he drove,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.461#Busy with the reins, into the thick of battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.462#Rendering service to Hector and the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.463#None of whom could help him now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.464#The arrow whizzed into his neck from behind,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.465#And he fell from the chariot. The horses swerved,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.466#Rattling the empty car. Polydamas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.467#Saw it all and got to the horses first,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.468#Handing them over to Astynous,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.469#Son of Protiaon, with strict orders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.470#To hold them close and keep an eye on them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.471#Polydamas then returned to the front.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.472#Teucer drew out another arrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.473#This one for Hector, and it would have stopped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.474#That hero from fighting by the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.475#If it had only hit him and taken his life.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.476#But Zeus, who protected Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.477#Was watching closely and robbed Teucer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.478#Of his glory, breaking his twisted bowstring
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.479#Just as he was drawing it against Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.480#The bronze-armored arrow was shunted aside,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.481#And the bow dropped from his hand.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.482#Teucer shuddered, and he said to his brother:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.483#"Damn! So much for our battle plans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.484#Some god is cutting them pretty short,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.485#Knocking the bow from my hands and snapping
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.486#The new string I tied on this morning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.487#So it would hold up to repeated rounds."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.488#Telamonian Ajax answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.489#"That's too bad. But leave your bow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.490#And stash of arrows here, since a god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.491#Has tampered with them and begrudged us their use.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.492#Pick up a spear, get a shield on your shoulders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.493#And battle the Trojans that way. They may beat us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.494#But they're not going to take our ships without a fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.495#Let's keep our minds on what we have to do."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.496#So Teucer laid his bow up in his hut.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.497#He put a four-ply shield around his shoulders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.498#And on his mighty head a helmet crafted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.499#With a horsehair plume that nodded grimly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.500#And he took a stout spear tipped with bronze
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.501#And ran to take his place at Ajax's side.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.502#When Hector saw Teucer's arrows fail,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.503#He called to his men and made his voice carry:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.504#"Trojan, Lycian, and Dardanian soldiers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.505#Remember to be the warriors that you are
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.506#In this fight for the ships! My eyes have seen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.507#The shafts of one of their best blasted by Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.508#It is easy to see whom Zeus protects,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.509#To whom he gives glory and grants the victory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.510#And whom he lays low and will not protect,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.511#Even as now he lays low the Argives
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.512#And gives his protection to us. So close your ranks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.513#And fight along the ships, and if any of you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.514#Is hit and dies, then so be it. Death
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.515#In defense of your homeland is no dishonor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.516#Your wife is safe and your children's future,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.517#Your house and estate are inviolate---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.518#If the Greeks sail off to their own native land."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.519#With these words he raised their spirits,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.520#And Ajax did the same for the Greeks:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.521#"Shame on you, Argives! It's do or die now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.522#If Hector takes the ships, do you think
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.523#We'll all be walking home? Didn't you hear him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.524#Screaming at his men to burn our fleet?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.525#He's not inviting them to a dance, you know.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.526#Our only strategy is this: to take them on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.527#Hand to hand, our muscle against theirs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.528#Better to get it over with, live or die,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.529#Than to be strung out here along the ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.530#Pecked to death by inferior men."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.531#This bolstered their spirits,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.532#And the killing began. Hector took out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.533#A Phocian commander named Schedius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.534#Perimedes' son, and Ajax killed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.535#Laodamas, an infantry captain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.536#And son of Antenor. Polydamas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.537#Laid low Otus of Cyllene, a comrade
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.538#Of Meges, the Epeian commander.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.539#Meges saw this and jumped at him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.540#But Polydamas ducked and Meges missed:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.541#Apollo would not allow Polydamas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.542#To be killed in the front lines. But Meges
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.543#Did kill Croesmus with a thrust to the chest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.544#Croesmus fell heavily, and as Meges
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.545#Got busy stripping his armor, Dolops,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.546#Who knew what to do with a spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.547#Rushed at him. This man was the grandson
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.548#Of Laomedon and the son of Lampus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.549#His bravest son and a furious fighter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.550#His spear ground through Meges' shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.551#From close range, but the corselet saved him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.552#The intricate, plated corselet he wore.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.553#His father Phyleus had brought it home
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.554#From Ephyre, on the river Selleïs,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.555#Having received it from lord Euphetes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.556#A guest-friend, to protect him in war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.557#It now saved his son's life. Meges thrust back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.558#And got his spear onto Dolops' bronze helmet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.559#Shearing the horsehair plume from its socket.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.560#The whole plume, bright with its fresh scarlet dye,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.561#Fell in the dust. Meges continued fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.562#His still confident opponent until Menelaus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.563#Came up to help him, unnoticed by Dolops.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.564#Standing slightly behind him, Menelaus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.565#Heaved his spear through Dolops' shoulder,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.566#And the spear, with an eager life of its own,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.567#Punctured his sternum. Dolops fell on his face,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.568#And his two antagonists moved to strip him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.569#But Hector called to his many kinsmen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.570#Beginning with Melanippus, Hicetaon's son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.571#This man used to pasture his shambling cattle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.572#Off in Percote when there was no enemy near.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.573#But when the curved prows of the Danaans appeared
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.574#He moved back to Ilion, a distinguished Trojan,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.575#And lived in the house of Priam, who treated him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.576#As a son of his own. Hector prodded him now:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.577#"Melanippus, are we going to slack off like this?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.578#Don't you have any feeling for your dead kinsman?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.579#Look at how they are handling Dolops' armor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.580#Come on. We can no longer fight the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.581#From long range. Either we kill them or they
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.582#Take Ilion's heights and murder our people."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.583#Melanippus went with him, moving like a god,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.584#And Telamonian Ajax urged on the Greeks:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.585#"Be men, my friends, and show some shame.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.586#You should feel shame before each other in battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.587#More men with shame are saved than are slain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.588#There's no glory or power in shameless flight."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.589#They were already eager to ward off the enemy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.590#But they took his words to heart and fenced in the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.591#With a hedge of bronze, against which Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.592#Urged on the Trojans. Then Menelaus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.593#Good at the war cry, shouted to Antilochus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.594#"Antilochus, there is none of us younger,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.595#Faster, or braver than you in battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.596#Get moving and take some Trojan out."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.597#Menelaus melted back into the ranks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.598#When he had said this, but he inspired
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.599#Antilochus, who jumped out into no-man's-land.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.600#With a quick look around he hurled his spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.601#The Trojans recoiled from the flare it made,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.602#But the throw was not wasted. It hit Melanippus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.603#Hicetaon's high-hearted son, right in the chest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.604#Beside his nipple, as he came into battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.605#He fell heavily, and the light left his eyes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.606#Antilochus was all over him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.607#A dog goes after a wounded fawn a hunter hits
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.608#With unerring aim as it jumps from its lair.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.609#That was how Antilochus leapt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.610#At you, Melanippus, to strip off your armor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.611#But Hector saw him and came running over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.612#To meet him in battle, and Antilochus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.613#For all his speed as a combatant, fled.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.614#A marauding animal that has killed a hound,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.615#Or a drover beside his herd, will sometimes flee
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.616#Even before the crowd of men has gathered.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.617#As Nestor's son Antilochus was running,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.618#Hector and the Trojans showered him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.619#With a whining barrage of missiles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.620#He didn't turn and stand until he reached his own lines.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.621#It was then that the Trojans, like lions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.622#Who have tasted raw meat, charged the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.623#And completed this part of Zeus' design.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.624#He steadily turned up the Trojans' intensity
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.625#And softened the Greeks' resolve to win.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.626#Hector would win all the glory for now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.627#Priam's son would burn the beaked ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.628#With fire from heaven, and so fulfill
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.629#The last syllable of Thetis' prayer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.630#It was for this that Zeus waited,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.631#The glare from a burning ship. From then on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.632#He would will the Trojans back from the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.633#And shift glory to the Greeks. With this intent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.634#He roused Hector against the hollow ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.635#And Hector needed no urging. Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.636#Raged like the War God, the Spear Wielder,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.637#Fire that consumes a wooded mountainside,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.638#Foam flecking his mouth, eyes burning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.639#Under fierce brows, and the helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.640#Encasing his face a sinister glitter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.641#As Hector fought, as Zeus himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.642#Shed a cone of light from the aether
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.643#Around the solitary warrior, but only
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.644#For this brief moment. Pallas Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.645#Was hastening his doom under Achilles' hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.646#Yes, Hector was eager, but for all his efforts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.647#Probing the Greek lines where he saw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.648#The greatest concentration of fine weapons,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.649#He could not break their ranks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.650#They were as solid as a wall,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.651#Or an iron cliff that drops sheer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.652#Into the grey sea and withstands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.653#Whistling winds and swollen waves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.654#That break against its rock face.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.655#The Greeks were not going to budge,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.656#So Hector, with a nimbus of fire about him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.657#Leapt high and fell upon their bulk.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.658#Waves driven by winds sometimes reach
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.659#Tsunami proportions.When one breaks over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.660#A ship, the entire vessel is hidden by foam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.661#And the wind roars like devils in the sail.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.662#The crew shudders and their hearts turn to ice,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.663#So narrow is their passage out of Death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.664#So too the Greeks under Hector's charge.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.665#A maleficent lion charges a herd of cows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.666#Grazing in the bottom land of a great marsh,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.667#There is no counting how many, and with them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.668#Is only a single herdsman, inexperienced
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.669#At contesting a heifer's carcass with a wild beast.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.670#The herdsman walks at the front or rear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.671#But the lion attacks in the middle and is soon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.672#Feeding on its kill. The others stampede off.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.673#It was marvelous to see, the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.674#Scattering before Hector---and Father Zeus---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.675#Even though Hector killed only one man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.676#Periphetes of Mycenae, the son of that Copreus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.677#Who used to shuttle messages from Eurystheus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.678#To Heracles. His son was better in every way,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.679#Whether it came to running or fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.680#And he had one of the best minds in Mycenae.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.681#Now he yielded the glory to Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.682#As he turned, he tripped on the rim of his own shield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.683#A Mycenaean style that went down to his feet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.684#And protected him from spears, but not from himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.685#As he stumbled and fell backward, his helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.686#Ringing like a gong in his astonished ears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.687#Hector was quick to take advantage, putting a spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.688#Into his chest before his watching comrades
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.689#Were able to react. They grieved for their friend
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.690#But were too afraid of shining Hector to help him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.691#The Greeks regrouped within the ships' perimeter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.692#But the Trojans kept coming. The outermost ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.693#Were conceded, but the Greeks did take a stand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.694#By their huts. They were massed now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.695#Too afraid to spread out through the camp,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.696#And they kept calling back and forth to each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.697#Nestor of Gerenia, the old general,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.698#Implored them all in the name of their parents:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.699#"Fight like the men that you are, my friends,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.700#And feel some shame before the men around you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.701#Remember your children, your wives, your possessions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.702#And your parents, whether they are dead or alive.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.703#For the sake of those who are not here I beseech you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.704#To stand firm and fight, and not retreat."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.705#This helped, but Athena helped them more,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.706#Pushing aside the wondrous cloud of mist
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.707#From their eyes. Light flooded in from both sides,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.708#From the ships behind and the battlefield in front.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.709#They could all see Hector now, and his men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.710#The entire Greek army, from the idle in the rear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.711#To the champions in front, could see the enemy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.712#Ajax decided it was time to make his move.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.713#Separating himself from the rest of the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.714#He boarded a ship and strode along its deck
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.715#Wielding a long pike made for naval warfare,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.716#Some forty feet in length, jointed with iron rings.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.717#And then,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.718#as skillfully as a stunt rider
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.719#Jumps from horse to horse as his chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.720#Drawn by a team of hand-picked thoroughbreds,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.721#Speeds from plain to city down a highway
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.722#Lined with spectators, who cheer him on,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.723#Ajax leapt from ship to ship, and his voice,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.724#Like a shock wave from the wide, blue sky,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.725#Admonished the Greeks to defend their ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.726#And the huts clutched beneath them. Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.727#Reacted quickly, a streak of bronze armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.728#Flashing out from the general sea of bronze
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.729#Like a golden eagle dive-bombing down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.730#To a river bank where a flock of wild geese,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.731#Or cranes, or long-necked swans are feeding.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.732#Hector made like that for a dark-prowed ship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.733#And a great hand reached down from Ida
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.734#And pushed him on, and his army with him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.735#The fighting began again beside the ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.736#So keenly you would have thought the troops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.737#On both sides were fresh and had just entered battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.738#Their minds were different, though. The Greeks fought
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.739#As if they would never get out of this battle alive,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.740#While every Trojan heart beat with the hope
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.741#Of burning the ships and killing Greek heroes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.742#Such were their thoughts as they faced off in battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.743#Hector laid hold of the stern of a ship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.744#A beautiful vessel that had brought Protesilaus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.745#Over to Troy, but would not bring him back home.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.746#It was about this ship that the Greeks and Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.747#Fought in close combat. Instead of withstanding
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.748#Assaults from arrows and javelins in flight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.749#They fought toe to toe here, of one heart in battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.750#Hacking at each other with axes and hatchets,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.751#Enormous swords and double-edged spears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.752#Many fine blades with black leather ferrules
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.753#Fell to the ground, some from the hands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.754#Others from the shoulders of men as they fought.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.755#The earth flowed black with their blood. Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.756#Once he had grasped the horn of the ship's stern,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.757#Would not let go, and he called to the Trojans:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.758#"Fire! Bring fire! And raise the war cry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.759#All together! Zeus has given us this day
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.760#As payment for everything---to seize the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.761#That came here against the gods' will
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.762#And have brought us endless trouble
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.763#Because of the cowardice of our elders,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.764#Who, when I wanted to bring the fight here,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.765#Kept me back and withheld the army.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.766#But if Zeus clouded our minds then,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.767#There is no doubt he is urging us on now."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.768#At this, the Trojans intensified their attack.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.769#Ajax, battered by everything they could throw,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.770#And sensing death if he stayed where he was,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.771#Inched back along the seven-foot cross-plank
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.772#He had been standing on and jumped from the deck.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.773#He took up a position guarding the ship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.774#His spearpoint menacing any Trojan
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.775#Who tried to bring up fire, and his voice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.776#Kept booming out alarms to his compatriots:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.777#"Soldiers of Greece---be men, my friends!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.778#We have to dig in on defense now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.779#Do you think we have allies to back us up,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.780#Or some stronger wall that will protect us?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.781#There's no fortified city behind us now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.782#With reinforcements there to turn the tide.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.783#We're out here on the plain of Troy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.784#With the sea at our backs, far from home,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.785#Surrounded by armed men. If there's a way out,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.786#It's in our own hands, not in slacking off."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.787#And as Ajax spoke his spear carved holes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.788#In the various Trojans who thought that they
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.789#Might please Hector by bringing fire to the ship.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:15.790#He mangled a good dozen at close range like this.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.1#While they fought for this ship, Patroclus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.2#Came to Achilles and stood by him weeping,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.3#His face like a sheer rock where the goat trails end
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.4#And dark springwater washes down the stone.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.5#Achilles pitied him and spoke these feathered words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.6#"What are all these tears about, Patroclus?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.7#You're like a little girl, pestering her mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.8#To pick her up, pulling at her hem
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.9#As she tries to hurry off and looking up at her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.10#With tears in her eyes until she gets her way.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.11#That's just what you look like, you know.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.12#You have something to tell the Myrmidons?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.13#Or myself? Bad news from back home?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.14#Last I heard, Menoetius, your father,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.15#And Peleus, mine, were still alive and well.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.16#Their deaths would indeed give us cause to grieve.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.17#Or are you broken-hearted because some Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.18#Are being beaten dead beside our ships?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.19#They had it coming. Out with it, Patroclus---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.20#Don't try to hide it. I have a right to know."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.21#And with a deep groan you said to him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.22#Patroclus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.23#"Achilles, great as you are,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.24#Don't be vengeful. They are dying out there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.25#All of our best---or who used to be our best---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.26#They've all been hit and are lying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.27#Wounded in camp. Diomedes is out,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.28#And Odysseus, a good man with a spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.29#Even Agamemnon has taken a hit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.30#Eurypylus, too, an arrow in his thigh.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.31#The medics are working on them right now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.32#Stitching up their wounds. But you are incurable,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.33#Achilles. God forbid I ever feel the spite
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.34#You nurse in your heart. You and your damned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.35#Honor! What good will it do future generations
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.36#If you let us go down to this defeat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.37#In cold blood? Peleus was never your father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.38#Or Thetis your mother. No, the grey sea spat you out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.39#Onto crags in the surf, with an icy scab for a soul.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.40#What is it? If some secret your mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.41#Has learned from Zeus is holding you back,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.42#At least send me out, let me lead a troop
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.43#Of Myrmidons and light the way for our army.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.44#And let me wear your armor. If the Trojans think
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.45#I am you, they'll back off and give the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.46#Some breathing space, what little there is in war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.47#Our rested men will turn them with a shout
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.48#And push them back from our ships to Troy."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.49#That was how Patroclus, like a child
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.50#Begging for a toy, begged for death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.51#And Achilles, angry and deeply troubled:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.52#"Ah, my noble friend, what a thing to say.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.53#No, I'm not in on any divine secret,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.54#Nor has my mother told me anything from Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.55#But I take it hard when someone in power
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.56#Uses his authority to rob his equal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.57#And strip him of his honor. I take it hard.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.58#The girl the Greeks chose to be my prize---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.59#After I demolished a walled city to get her---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.60#Lord Agamemnon, son of Atreus, just took
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.61#From my hands, as if I were some tramp.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.62#But we'll let that be. I never meant
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.63#To hold my grudge forever. But I did say
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.64#I would not relent from my anger until
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.65#The noise of battle lapped at my own ships' hulls.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.66#So it's on your shoulders now. Wear my armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.67#And lead our Myrmidons into battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.68#If it is true that a dark cloud of Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.69#Has settled in over the ships and the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.70#Are hemmed in on a narrow strip of beach.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.71#The Trojans have become cocky, the whole city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.72#Because they do not see my helmeted face
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.73#Flaring close by. They would retreat so fast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.74#They would clog the ditches with their dead---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.75#If Lord Agamemnon knew how to respect me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.76#As it is they have brought the war to our camp.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.77#So Diomedes is out, eh? It was his inspired
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.78#Spear work that kept the Trojans at arm's length.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.79#And I haven't been hearing Agamemnon's battle cry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.80#As much as I hate the throat it comes from---only
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.81#Hector's murderous shout breaking like the sea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.82#Over the Trojans, urging them on. The whole plain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.83#Is filled with their whooping as they rout the Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.84#Hit them hard, Patroclus, before they burn the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.85#And leave us stranded here. But before you go,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.86#Listen carefully to every word I say.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.87#Win me my honor, my glory and my honor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.88#From all the Greeks, and, as their restitution,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.89#The girl Briseis, and many other gifts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.90#But once you've driven the Trojans from the ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.91#You come back, no matter how much
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.92#Hera's thundering husband lets you win.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.93#Any success you have against the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.94#Will be at the expense of my honor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.95#And if you get so carried away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.96#With killing the Trojans that you press on to Troy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.97#One of the immortals may intervene.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.98#Apollo, for one, loves them dearly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.99#So once you have made some daylight for the ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.100#You come back where you belong.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.101#The others can fight it out on the plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.102#O Patroclus, I wish to Father Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.103#And to Athena and Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.104#That all of them, Greeks and Trojans alike,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.105#Every last man on Troy's dusty plain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.106#Were dead, and only you and I were left
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.107#To rip Ilion down, stone by sacred stone."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.108#And while they talked, Ajax retreated.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.109#Zeus saw to it that everything the Trojans threw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.110#At Ajax hit him, and his helmet tickered and rang
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.111#From all the metal points its bronze deflected
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.112#From his temples and cheeks. His left arm was sore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.113#From holding up his shield, but the Trojans could not,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.114#For all their pressure, force it aside.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.115#Gulping in air, sweat pouring down his limbs,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.116#He could scarcely breathe and had nowhere to turn.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.117#Tell me now, Muses, who dwell on Olympus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.118#How fire first fell on the Achaean ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.119#It was Hector who forced his way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.120#To Ajax's side, and with his heavy sword
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.121#Lopped through the ash-wood shaft of his spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.122#At the socket's base, sending the bronze point
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.123#Clanging onto the ground far behind him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.124#And leaving in Ajax's hands a blunted stick.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.125#Ajax knew that this was the work of the gods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.126#That Zeus had cancelled Ajax's battle plans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.127#And planned instead a Trojan victory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.128#No one could blame him for getting out of range,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.129#And when he did, the Trojans threw their firebrands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.130#Onto the ship, and she went up in flames.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.131#Achilles slapped his thighs and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.132#"Hurry, Patroclus! I see fire from the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.133#Don't let them take the fleet and cut off our escape.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.134#Put on the armor while I gather the troops."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.135#And so Patroclus armed, putting on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.136#The bronze metalwork tailored to the body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.137#Of Aeacus' swift grandson: the greaves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.138#Trimmed with silver at the ankles, the corselet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.139#Spangled with stars, the silver-studded sword,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.140#The massive shield, and the crested helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.141#That made every nod a threat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.142#He took two spears of the proper heft,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.143#But left behind the massive battle pike
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.144#Of Aeacus' incomparable grandson.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.145#No one but Achilles could handle this spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.146#Made of ash, which the centaur Chiron
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.147#Had brought down from Mount Pelion and given
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.148#To Achilles' father to be the death of heroes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.149#Patroclus left the horses to Automedon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.150#The warrior he trusted most, after Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.151#To be at his side in the crush of battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.152#Automedon led beneath the yoke
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.153#The windswift horses Xanthus and Balius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.154#Immortal horses the gods gave to Peleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.155#When he married silver Thetis.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.156#The Harpy Podarge had conceived them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.157#When the West Wind blew through her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.158#As she grazed in a meadow near Ocean's stream.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.159#As trace horse Automedon brought up Pedasus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.160#Whom Achilles had acquired in the raid
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.161#On Eëtion's city. This faultless animal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.162#Though mortal, kept pace with immortal horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.163#Achilles toured the rows of huts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.164#That composed the Myrmidons' camp
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.165#And saw to it the men got armed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.166#Think of wolves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.167#Ravenous for meat. It is impossible
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.168#To describe their savage strength in the hunt,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.169#But after they have killed an antlered stag
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.170#Up in the hills and torn it apart, they come down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.171#With gore on their jowls, and in a pack
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.172#Go to lap the black surface water in a pool
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.173#Fed by a dark spring, and as they drink,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.174#Crimson curls float off from their slender tongues.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.175#But their hearts are still, and their bellies gorged.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.176#So too the Myrmidon commanders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.177#Flanking Achilles' splendid surrogate,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.178#And in their midst stood Achilles himself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.179#Urging on the horses and the men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.180#Achilles had brought fifty ships to Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.181#Each ship held fifty men, and the entire force
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.182#Was divided into five battalions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.183#Whose five commanders answered to Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.184#Menesthius led the first battalion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.185#His mother, Polydore, a daughter of Peleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.186#Had lain with the river god Spercheius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.187#Whose sky-swollen waters engendered the child.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.188#His nominal father was a man called Boros,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.189#Who gave many gifts to marry Polydore.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.190#The second battalion was led by Eudorus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.191#Polymele's bastard son. This woman
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.192#Once caught Hermes' eye as she danced
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.193#In Artemis' choir, and the god later
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.194#Went up to her bedroom and slept with her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.195#The son she bore shone like silver in battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.196#After childbirth Actor's son Echecles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.197#Led her to his house in marriage,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.198#And her father, Phylas, kept the boy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.199#And brought him up as if he were his own.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.200#Peisander led the third contingent.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.201#He was, next to Patroclus, the best
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.202#Of all the Myrmidons with a spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.203#Old Phoenix led the fourth contingent,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.204#And Alcimedon, Laerces' son, the fifth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.205#When Achilles had the troops assembled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.206#By battalions, he spoke to them bluntly:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.207#"Myrmidons! I would not have a man among you forget
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.208#The threats you have been issuing against the Trojans---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.209#From the safety of our camp---while I was in my rage.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.210#All this time you have been calling me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.211#The hard-boiled son of Peleus and saying to my face
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.212#That my mother must have weaned me on gall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.213#Or I wouldn't keep my friends from battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.214#That, together with hints you'd sail back home
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.215#If all I was going to do was sit and sulk. Now, however,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.216#That there is a major battle to hold your interest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.217#I hope that each of you remembers what it means to fight."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.218#The speech steeled their spirit. The Myrmidons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.219#Closed ranks until there was no more space between them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.220#Than between the stones a mason sets in the wall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.221#Of a high house when he wants to seal it from the wind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.222#Helmet on helmet, shield overlapping shield, man on man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.223#So close the horsehair plumes on their bright crests
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.224#Rubbed each other as their heads bobbed up and down.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.225#And in front of them all, two men with one heart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.226#Patroclus and Automedon made their final preparations
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.227#To lead the Myrmidons into war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.228#But Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.229#Went back to his hut and opened the lid
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.230#Of a beautiful, carved chest his mother Thetis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.231#Had put aboard his ship when he sailed for Troy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.232#Filled with tunics and cloaks and woolen rugs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.233#And in it too was a chalice that no one else
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.234#Ever drank from, and that he alone used for libation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.235#To no other god but Zeus. This chalice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.236#He now took from the chest, purified it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.237#With sulfur crystals, washed it with clear water,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.238#Then cleansed his hands and filled it with bright red wine.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.239#And then he prayed, standing in his courtyard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.240#Pouring out the wine as he looked up to heaven.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.241#And as he prayed, Zeus in his thunderhead listened.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.242#"Lord Zeus, God of Dodona, Pelasgian God
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.243#Who dwells afar in the snows of Dodona
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.244#With your barefoot priests who sleep
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.245#On the ground around your sacred oak:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.246#As you have heard my prayer before
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.247#And did honor me and smite the Achaeans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.248#So now too fulfill my prayer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.249#As I wait in the muster of the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.250#And send my Patroclus into battle with my men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.251#Send forth glory with him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.252#Make bold the heart in his breast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.253#So that Hector will see that my comrade
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.254#Knows how to fight and win without me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.255#And when he has driven the noise of battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.256#Away from our ships, may he come back to me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.257#Unharmed, with all his weapons and men."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.258#Zeus in his wisdom heard Achilles' prayer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.259#And granted half of it. Yes, Patroclus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.260#Would drive the Trojans back from the ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.261#But he would not return from battle unharmed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.262#Achilles placed the chalice back in the chest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.263#And stood outside his hut. He still longed to see
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.264#The grim struggle on Troy's windswept plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.265#The Myrmidons under Patroclus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.266#Filed out and swarmed up to the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.267#Boys will sometimes disturb a hornets' nest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.268#By the roadside, jabbing at it and infuriating
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.269#The hive---the little fools---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.270#Until the insects become a menace to all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.271#And attack any traveller who happens by,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.272#Swarming out in defense of their brood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.273#So too the Myrmidons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.274#Patroclus called to them over their shouts:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.275#"Remember whose men you are
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.276#And for whose honor you are fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.277#And fight so that even wide-ruling Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.278#Will recognize his blind folly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.279#In not honoring the best of the Achaeans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.280#FOR ACHILLES!"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.281#This raised their spirits even higher.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.282#They were all over the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.283#And the ships' hulls reverberated
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.284#With the sounds of their battle cries.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.285#The Trojans, when they saw Patroclus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.286#Gleaming in his armor, fell apart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.287#Convinced that Achilles had come out at last,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.288#His wrath renounced and solidarity restored.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.289#Each of them looked for a way to save his skin.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.290#Patroclus' spear shot out like stabbing light
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.291#To where the Trojans were clustered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.292#Around the stern of Protesilaus' ship
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.293#And hit a certain chariot commander
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.294#Named Pyraechmes, a Paeonian
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.295#Who had led a contingent of chariots
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.296#From the Axius river in Amydon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.297#He went down now, groaning in the dust
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.298#With Patroclus' spear in his right shoulder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.299#Having lost their leader and best fighter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.300#The Paeonians panicked, and Patroclus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.301#Drove them from the ships and doused the fire.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.302#The half-burnt ship was left there.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.303#The Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.304#Frantic and screaming, were on the run,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.305#And the Greeks poured in with an answering roar.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.306#Zeus will at times rein in his lightning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.307#And remove a dense cloud from a mountain top,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.308#And all the crests and headlands and high glades
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.309#Break into view, and brightness falls from the air.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.310#The Greeks had repelled the enemy fire
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.311#From the ships and could catch their breath,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.312#But only for a while. The battle was not over.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.313#The Trojans had withdrawn from the black ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.314#But were not giving up. They had taken a stand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.315#And would have to be pushed back by force.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.316#The fighting was scattered at first, as heroes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.317#Killed each other in individual combat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.318#Menoetius' brave son struck first, hitting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.319#Areïlycus in the thigh just as he turned.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.320#The bronze sheared through the flesh
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.321#And shattered the bone. He pitched forward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.322#Into the dirt.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.323#Then the warrior Menelaus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.324#Drove his spear into Thoas' chest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.325#Where it was unprotected by his shield.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.326#As Thoas sagged to the earth, Phyleus' son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.327#Was watching Amphiclus bear down on him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.328#But beat him to the punch, getting his spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.329#Into the thick muscle at the base of his thigh.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.330#The point skewered the sinews and split them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.331#And Amphiclus blacked out.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.332#Then Nestor's son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.333#Antilochus, sliced into Atumnius' flank
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.334#With his bronze spear and drove it through,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.335#Sending him sprawling. Maris wasted no time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.336#Getting his spear between Antilochus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.337#And his brother's corpse, but Thrasymedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.338#Another of Nestor's sons, was even quicker.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.339#Thrasymedes' spearblade cut through Maris' arm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.340#Where it joined the shoulder, neatly flaying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.341#The muscle off and crushing the bone.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.342#He fell heavily, eyes leaning into the dark.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.343#So these two brothers, killed by brothers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.344#Entered the undergloom, comrades of Sarpedon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.345#Spearmen sons of Amisodarus, who had reared
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.346#The raging Chimaera, an evil for many.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.347#In the confusion Oïlean Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.348#Jumped Cleobulus, taking him alive
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.349#And in the same instant ending his life
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.350#With a sword stroke to the neck. The blade
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.351#Ran warm with blood up to the hilt,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.352#And death's haze lay heavy on his eyes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.353#Peneleos and Lycon both cast, both missed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.354#Both drew their swords and charged each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.355#Lycon's sword landed hard on Peneleos' helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.356#But the heavy crest shattered the blade to the hilt.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.357#Peneleos' sword caught Lycon under the ear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.358#And sliced through the neck, leaving only
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.359#A ribbon of skin from which the head dangled.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.360#Lycon collapsed in a heap.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.361#Meanwhile, Meriones,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.362#Sprinting hard, caught up with Acamas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.363#As he was mounting his chariot and nailed him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.364#In his right shoulder. He fell from the rig
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.365#And mist poured over his eyes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.366#Idomeneus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.367#Plugged Erymas' mouth with cruel bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.368#The spearpoint passing beneath the brainpan,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.369#Shattering all the bones. His teeth rattled out,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.370#His eyes filled with blood, and he spurted blood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.371#Out through his nostrils and gaping mouth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.372#Until death's black nimbus enveloped him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.373#In this way, each Greek leader took out his man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.374#Wolves will unerringly pick off lambs or kids
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.375#That have become separated from the flock
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.376#Through the shepherd's lack of attention,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.377#The marauding predators making swift havoc
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.378#Of the defenseless young animals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.379#So too the Greeks had their way with the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.380#Whose only tactic now was dishonorable flight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.381#All this time big Ajax was trying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.382#To get a shot off at Hector, who,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.383#Knowing the ways of war, kept his shoulders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.384#Under his oxhide shield and listened
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.385#For the whistling of arrows and thud of spears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.386#He knew the fight was not going his way,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.387#But he held his ground and tried to save his friends.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.388#A cloud detaches itself from Olympus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.389#And moves across the clear blue sky
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.390#When Zeus is about to unleash a storm.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.391#The rout from the ships had begun,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.392#And in no good order. Hector's horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.393#Got him across the trench, but he left
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.394#His army behind it. The Trojans drove
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.395#Team after team into the trench
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.396#Only to see the horses break their poles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.397#Struggle free, and leave their lords
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.398#Stranded in their chariots. Patroclus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.399#Called his men in for the kill. The Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.400#Were screaming and running
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.401#In every direction, while a cloud of dust
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.402#Rose high over their horses as they left
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.403#The ships behind and strained for the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.404#Patroclus drove his chariot to wherever
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.405#The routed Trojans were thickest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.406#Shouting as he plowed over broken chariots
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.407#And the drivers who fell beneath his wheels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.408#The horses the gods had given to Peleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.409#Jumped the trench in one immortal leap,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.410#And Patroclus steered them after Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.411#In whose back he longed to plant his spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.412#But Hector's horses had too big a lead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.413#When the storm finally breaks, on a day
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.414#During harvest, the black earth is soaked
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.415#Until it can hold no more, and still the rain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.416#Comes down in sheets as Zeus' judgment
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.417#On men who govern by violence
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.418#And drive Justice out with their crooked verdicts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.419#As if they have never heard of an Angry God.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.420#All the rivers flood their banks, and every hill
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.421#Is rutted with torrents that feed the rivers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.422#And down from the mountains the waters roar
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.423#And sweep men's tillage into the shining sea.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.424#The Trojan mares were thundering down the plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.425#Patroclus let them go. But when he had cut off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.426#The foremost battalions, he hemmed them back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.427#Toward the ships, blocking their frantic retreat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.428#Toward the city, and in the space defined
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.429#By the ships, the river, and Troy's high wall,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.430#He made them pay in blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.431#Pronous was first, Patroclus' spear hitting him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.432#Like searing light where his shield left part
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.433#Of his chest exposed. His limbs were unstrung,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.434#And he fell with a thud.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.435#Thestor, son of Enops,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.436#Was next, crouching in his polished chariot basket,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.437#Half out of his mind with terror, the reins slack
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.438#And trailing out of his hands. Patroclus eased up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.439#Alongside him and shattered his right jaw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.440#With his spear, driving the point through his teeth,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.441#Then, gripping the shaft, levered him up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.442#And over his chariot rail, the way a man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.443#Sitting on a jutting rock with a fishing rod
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.444#Flips a flounder he has hooked out of the sea.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.445#So Thestor was prised gaping from his chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.446#And left flat on his face. His soul crawled off.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.447#Erylaus Patroclus got with a stone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.448#As he charged, crushing helmet and skull.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.449#Death sifted around him as he pitched to earth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.450#And then, and in quick succession, Patroclus killed:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.451#Erymas, Amphoterus, Epaltes, Echius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.452#Pyris, Tlepolemus, son of Damastor, Ipheus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.453#Euippus, and Polymelus, Argeas' son---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.454#Making Troy's rich earth fat with their blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.455#Sarpedon saw his comrades running
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.456#With their tunics flapping loose around their waists
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.457#And being swatted down like flies by Patroclus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.458#He called out, appealing to their sense of shame:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.459#"Why this sudden burst of speed, Lycian heroes?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.460#Slow down a little, while I make the acquaintance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.461#Of this nuisance of a Greek who seems by now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.462#To have hamstrung half the Trojan army."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.463#And he stepped down from his chariot in his bronze
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.464#As Patroclus, seeing him, stepped down from his.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.465#High above a cliff vultures are screaming
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.466#In the air as they savage each other's craws
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.467#With their hooked beaks and talons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.468#And higher still,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.469#Zeus watched with pity as the two heroes closed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.470#And said to his wife Hera, who is his sister too:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.471#"Fate has it that Sarpedon, whom I love more
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.472#Than any man, is to be killed by Patroclus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.473#Shall I take him out of battle while he still lives
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.474#And set him down in the rich land of Lycia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.475#Or shall I let him die under Patroclus' hands?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.476#And Hera, his lady, her eyes soft and wide:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.477#"Son of Cronus, what a thing to say!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.478#A mortal man, whose fate has long been fixed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.479#And you want to save him from rattling death?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.480#Do it. But don't expect all of us to approve.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.481#Listen to me. If you send Sarpedon home alive,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.482#You will have to expect other gods to do the same
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.483#And save their own sons---and there are many of them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.484#In this war around Priam's great city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.485#Think of the resentment you will create.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.486#But if you love him and are filled with grief,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.487#Let him fall in battle at Patroclus' hands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.488#And when his soul and life have left him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.489#Send Sleep and Death to bear him away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.490#To Lycia, where his people will give him burial
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.491#With mound and stone, as befits the dead."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.492#The Father of Gods and Men agreed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.493#Reluctantly, but shed drops of blood as rain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.494#Upon the earth in honor of his own dear son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.495#Whom Patroclus was about to kill
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.496#On Ilion's rich soil, far from his native land.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.497#When they were close, Patroclus cast, and hit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.498#Not Prince Sarpedon, but his lieutenant
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.499#Thrasymelus, a good man---a hard throw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.500#Into the pit of his belly. He collapsed in a heap.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.501#Sarpedon countered and missed. His bright spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.502#Sliced instead through the right shoulder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.503#Of Pedasus, who gave one pained, rasping whinny,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.504#Then fell in the dust. His spirit fluttered off.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.505#With the trace horse down, the remaining two
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.506#Struggled in the creaking yoke, tangling the reins.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.507#Automedon remedied this by drawing his sword
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.508#And cutting loose the trace horse. The other two
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.509#Righted themselves and pulled hard at the reins,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.510#And the two warriors closed again in mortal combat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.511#Sarpedon cast again. Another miss. The spearpoint
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.512#Glinted as it sailed over Patroclus' left shoulder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.513#Without touching him at all. Patroclus came back,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.514#Leaning into his throw, and the bronze point
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.515#Caught Sarpedon just below the rib cage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.516#Where it protects the beating heart. Sarpedon fell
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.517#As a tree falls, oak, or poplar, or spreading pine,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.518#When carpenters cut it down in the forest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.519#With their bright axes, to be the beam of a ship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.520#And he lay before his horses and chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.521#Groaning heavily and clawing the bloody dust,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.522#Like some tawny, spirited bull a lion has killed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.523#In the middle of the shambling herd, groaning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.524#As it dies beneath the predator's jaws.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.525#Thus beneath Patroclus the Lycian commander
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.526#Struggled in death. And he called his friend:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.527#"Glaucus, it's time to show what you're made of
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.528#And be the warrior you've always been,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.529#Heart set on evil war---if you're fast enough.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.530#Hurry, rally our best to fight for my body,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.531#All the Lycian leaders. Shame on you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.532#Glaucus, until your dying day, if the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.533#Strip my body bare beside their ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.534#Be strong and keep the others going."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.535#The end came as he spoke, and death settled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.536#On his nostrils and eyes. Patroclus put his heel
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.537#On Sarpedon's chest and pulled out his spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.538#The lungs came out with it, and Sarpedon's life.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.539#The Myrmidons steadied his snorting horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.540#They did not want to leave their master's chariot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.541#Glaucus could hardly bear to hear Sarpedon's voice,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.542#He was so grieved that he could not save him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.543#He pressed his arm with his hand. His wound
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.544#Tormented him, the wound he got when Teucer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.545#Shot him with an arrow as he attacked the wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.546#He prayed to Apollo, lord of bright distances:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.547#"Hear me, O Lord, wherever you are
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.548#In Lycia or Troy, for everywhere you hear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.549#Men in their grief, and grief has come to me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.550#I am wounded, Lord, my arm is on fire,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.551#And the blood can't be staunched. My shoulder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.552#Is so sore I cannot hold a steady spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.553#And fight the enemy. Sarpedon is dead,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.554#My Lord, and Zeus will not save his own son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.555#Heal my wound and deaden my pain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.556#And give me the strength to call the Lycians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.557#And urge them on to fight, and do battle myself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.558#About the body of my fallen comrade."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.559#Thus Glaucus' prayer, and Apollo heard him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.560#He stilled his pain and staunched the dark blood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.561#That flowed from his wound. Glaucus felt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.562#The god's strength pulsing through him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.563#Glad that his prayers were so quickly answered.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.564#He rounded up the Lycian leaders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.565#And urged them to fight for Sarpedon's body,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.566#Then went with long strides to the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.567#To Polydamas, Agenor, Aeneas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.568#And then saw Hector's bronze-strapped face,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.569#Went up to him and said levelly:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.570#"Hector, you have abandoned your allies.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.571#We have been putting our lives on the line for you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.572#Far from our homes and loved ones,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.573#And you don't care enough to lend us aid.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.574#Sarpedon is down, our great warlord,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.575#Whose word in Lycia was Lycia's law,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.576#Killed by Patroclus under Ares' prodding.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.577#Show some pride and fight for his body,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.578#Or the Myrmidons will strip off the armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.579#And defile his corpse, in recompense
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.580#For all the Greeks we have killed by the ships."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.581#This was almost too much for the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.582#Sarpedon, though a foreigner, had been
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.583#A mainstay of their city, the leader
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.584#Of a large force and its best fighter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.585#Hector led them straight at the Greeks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.586#"For Sarpedon!"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.587#And Patroclus, seeing them coming,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.588#Urged on the already eager two Ajaxes:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.589#"Let me see you push these Trojans back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.590#With everything you've ever had and more.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.591#Sarpedon is down, first to breach our wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.592#He's ours, to carve up his body and strip
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.593#The armor off. And all his little saviors
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.594#Are ours to massacre with cold bronze."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.595#They heard this as if hearing their own words.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.596#The lines on both sides hardened to steel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.597#Then Trojans and Lycians, Myrmidons and Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.598#Began fighting for the corpse, howling and cursing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.599#As they threw themselves into the grinding battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.600#And Zeus stretched hellish night over the armies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.601#So they might do their lethal work over his son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.602#The Trojans at first pushed back the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.603#When Epeigeus was hit, Agacles' son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.604#This man was far from the worst of the Myrmidons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.605#He once lived in Boudeum, but having killed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.606#A cousin of his, came as a suppliant
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.607#To Peleus and silver-footed Thetis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.608#Who sent him with Achilles to fight at Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.609#He had his hand on the corpse when Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.610#Brought down a stone on his head, splitting his skull
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.611#In two inside his heavy helmet. He collapsed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.612#On Sarpedon's body, and death drifted over him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.613#Patroclus ached for his friend and swooped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.614#Into the front like a hawk after sparrows---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.615#Yes, my Patroclus---and they scattered like birds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.616#Before your anger for your fallen comrade.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.617#Sthenelaos, Ithaemenes' beloved son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.618#Never knew what hit him. The stone Patroclus threw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.619#Severed the tendons at the nape of his neck.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.620#The Trojan champions, including Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.621#Now withdrew, about as far as a javelin flies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.622#When a man who knows how throws it hard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.623#In competition or in mortal combat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.624#The Greeks pressed after them, and Glaucus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.625#The Lycian commander now, wheeled around
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.626#And killed Bathycles, a native of Hellas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.627#And the wealthiest of the Myrmidons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.628#He was just catching up with Glaucus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.629#When the Lycian suddenly pivoted on his heel
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.630#And put his spear straight into Bathycles' chest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.631#He fell hard, and the Greeks winced.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.632#A good man was down, much to the pleasure
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.633#Of the Trojans, who thronged around his body.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.634#But the Greeks took the offensive again,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.635#And Meriones killed Laogonus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.636#A priest of Idaean Zeus who was himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.637#Honored as a god. Meriones thrust hard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.638#Into his jaw, just beneath the ear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.639#And he was dead, in the hated dark.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.640#Aeneas launched his spear at Meriones,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.641#Hoping to hit him as he advanced
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.642#Under cover of his shield, but Meriones
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.643#Saw the spear coming and ducked forward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.644#Leaving it to punch into the ground and stand there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.645#Quivering, as if Ares had twanged it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.646#So it could spend its fury. Aeneas fumed:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.647#"That would have been your last dance, Meriones,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.648#Your last dance, if only my spear had hit you!"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.649#And Meriones, himself famed for his spear:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.650#"Do you think you can kill everyone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.651#Who comes up against you, Aeneas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.652#And defends himself? You're mortal stuff too.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.653#If I got a solid hit on you with my spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.654#You'd be down in no time, for all your strength.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.655#You'd give me the glory, and your life to Hades."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.656#Patroclus would have none of this, and yelled:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.657#"Cut the chatter, Meriones. You're a good man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.658#But don't think the Trojans are going to retreat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.659#From the corpse because you make fun of them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.660#Use hands in war, words in council.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.661#Save your big speeches; we've got fighting to do."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.662#And he moved ahead, with Meriones,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.663#Who himself moved like a god, in his wake.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.664#Woodcutters are working in a distant valley,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.665#But the sound of their axes, and of trees falling,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.666#Can be heard for miles around in the mountains.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.667#The plain of Troy thrummed with the sound
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.668#Of bronze and hide stretched into shields,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.669#And of swords and spears knifing into these.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.670#Sarpedon's body was indistinguishable
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.671#From the blood and grime and splintered spears
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.672#That littered his body from head to foot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.673#But if you have ever seen how flies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.674#Cluster about the brimming milk pails
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.675#On a dairy farm in early summer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.676#You will have some idea of the throng
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.677#Around Sarpedon's corpse.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.678#And not once did Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.679#Avert his luminous eyes from the combatants.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.680#All this time he looked down at them and pondered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.681#When Patroclus should die, whether
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.682#Shining Hector should kill him then and there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.683#In the conflict over godlike Sarpedon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.684#And strip the armor from his body, or whether
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.685#He should live to destroy even more Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.686#And as he pondered it seemed preferable
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.687#That Achilles' spendid surrogate should once more
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.688#Drive the Trojans and bronze-helmed Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.689#Back to the city, and take many lives.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.690#And Hector felt it, felt his blood turn milky,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.691#And mounted his chariot, calling to the others
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.692#To begin the retreat, that Zeus' scales were tipping.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.693#Not even the Lycians stayed, not with Sarpedon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.694#Lying at the bottom of a pile of bodies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.695#That had fallen upon him in this node of war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.696#The Greeks stripped at last the glowing bronze
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.697#From Sarpedon's shoulders, and Patroclus gave it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.698#To some of his comrades to take back to the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.699#Then Zeus turned to Apollo and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.700#"Sun God, take our Sarpedon out of range.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.701#Cleanse his wounds of all the clotted blood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.702#And wash him in the river far away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.703#And anoint him with our holy chrism
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.704#And wrap the body in a deathless shroud
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.705#And give him over to be taken swiftly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.706#By Sleep and Death to Lycia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.707#Where his people shall give him burial
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.708#With mound and stone, as befits the dead."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.709#And Apollo went down from Ida
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.710#Into the howling dust of war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.711#And cleansed Sarpedon's wounds of all the blood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.712#And washed him in the river far away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.713#And anointed him with holy chrism
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.714#And wrapped the body in a deathless shroud
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.715#And gave him over to be taken swiftly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.716#By Sleep and Death to Lycia.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.717#Patroclus called to his horses and charioteer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.718#And pressed on after the Trojans and Lycians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.719#Forgetting everything Achilles had said
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.720#And mindless of the black fates gathering above.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.721#Even then you might have escaped them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.722#Patroclus, but Zeus' mind is stronger than men's,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.723#And Zeus now put fury in your heart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.724#Do you remember it, Patroclus, all the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.725#You killed as the gods called you to your death?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.726#Adrastus was first, then Autonous, and Echeclus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.727#Perimas, son of Megas, Epistor, Melanippus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.728#Elasus, Mulius, and last, Pylartes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.729#And it would have been more, but the others ran,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.730#Back to Troy, which would have fallen that day
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.731#By Patroclus' hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.732#But Phoebus Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.733#Had taken his stand on top of Troy's wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.734#Three times Patroclus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.735#Reached the parapet, and three times
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.736#Apollo's fingers flicked against the human's shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.737#And pushed him off. But when he came back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.738#A fourth time, like a spirit from beyond,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.739#Apollo's voice split the daylight in two:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.740#"Get back, Patroclus, back where you belong.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.741#Troy is fated to fall, but not to you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.742#Nor even to Achilles, a better man by far."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.743#And Patroclus was off, putting distance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.744#Between himself and that wrathful voice.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.745#Hector had halted his horses at the Western Gate
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.746#And was deciding whether to drive back into battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.747#Or call for a retreat to within the walls.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.748#While he pondered this, Phoebus Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.749#Came up to him in the guise of Asius.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.750#This man was Hector's uncle on his mother's side,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.751#And Apollo looked just like him as he spoke:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.752#"Why are you out of action, Hector? It's not right.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.753#If I were as much stronger than you as I am weaker,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.754#You'd pay dearly for withdrawing from battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.755#Get in that chariot and go after Patroclus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.756#Who knows? Apollo may give you the glory."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.757#Hector commanded Cebriones, his charioteer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.758#To whip the horses into battle. Apollo melted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.759#Into the throng, a god into the toil of men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.760#The Greeks felt a sudden chill,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.761#While Hector and the Trojans felt their spirits lift.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.762#Hector was not interested in the other Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.763#He drove through them and straight for Patroclus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.764#Who leapt down from his own chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.765#With a spear in one hand and in the other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.766#A jagged piece of granite he had scooped up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.767#And now cupped in his palm. He got set,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.768#And without more than a moment of awe
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.769#For who his opponent was, hurled the stone.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.770#The throw was not wasted. He hit Hector's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.771#Charioteer, Cebriones, Priam's bastard son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.772#As he stood there holding the reins. The sharp stone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.773#Caught him right in the forehead, smashing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.774#His brows together and shattering the skull
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.775#So that his eyeballs spurted out and dropped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.776#Into the dirt before his feet. He flipped backward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.777#From the chariot like a diver, and his soul
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.778#Dribbled away from his bones. And you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.779#Patroclus, you, my horseman, mocked him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.780#"What a spring the man has! Nice dive!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.781#Think of the oysters he could come up with
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.782#If he were out at sea, jumping off the boat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.783#In all sorts of weather, to judge by the dive
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.784#He just took from his chariot onto the plain."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.785#And with that he rushed at the fallen warrior
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.786#Like a lion who has been wounded in the chest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.787#As he ravages a farmstead, and his own valor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.788#Destroys him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.789#Yes, Patroclus, that is how you leapt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.790#Upon Cebriones.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.791#Hector vaulted from his chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.792#And the two of them fought over Cebriones
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.793#Like a pair of lions fighting over a slain deer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.794#In the high mountains, both of them ravenous,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.795#Both high of heart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.796#very much like these two
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.797#Human heroes hacking at each other with bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.798#Hector held Cebriones' head and would not let go.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.799#Patroclus had hold of a foot, and around them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.800#Greeks and Trojans squared off and fought.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.801#Winds sometimes rise in a deep mountain wood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.802#From different directions, and the trees---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.803#Beech, ash, and cornelian cherry---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.804#Batter each other with their long, tapered branches,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.805#And you can hear the sound from a long way off,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.806#The unnerving splintering of hardwood limbs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.807#The Trojans and Greeks collided in battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.808#And neither side thought of yielding ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.809#Around Cebriones many spears were stuck,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.810#Many arrows flew singing from the string,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.811#And many stones thudded onto the shields
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.812#Of men fighting around him. But there he lay
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.813#In the whirling dust, one of the great,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.814#Forgetful of his horsemanship.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.815#While the sun still straddled heaven's meridian,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.816#Soldiers on both sides were hit and fell.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.817#But when the sun moved down the sky and men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.818#All over earth were unyoking their oxen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.819#The Greeks' success exceeded their destiny.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.820#They pulled Cebriones from the Trojan lines
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.821#And out of range, and stripped his armor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.822#And then Patroclus unleashed himself.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.823#Three times he charged into the Trojan ranks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.824#With the raw power of Ares, yelling coldly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.825#And on each charge he killed nine men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.826#But when you made your fourth, demonic charge,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.827#Then---did you feel it, Patroclus?---out of the mist,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.828#Your death coming to meet you. It was
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.829#Apollo, whom you did not see in the thick of battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.830#Standing behind you, and the flat of his hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.831#Found the space between your shoulder blades.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.832#The sky's blue disk went spinning in your eyes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.833#As Achilles' helmet rang beneath the horses' hooves,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.834#And rolled in the dust---no, that couldn't be right---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.835#Those handsome horsehair plumes grimed with blood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.836#The gods would never let that happen to the helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.837#That had protected the head and graceful brow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.838#Of divine Achilles. But the gods did
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.839#Let it happen, and Zeus would now give the helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.840#To Hector, whose own death was not far off.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.841#Nothing was left of Patroclus' heavy battle spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.842#But splintered wood, his tasselled shield and baldric
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.843#Fell to the ground, and Apollo, Prince of the Sky,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.844#Split loose his breastplate. And he stood there, naked,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.845#Astounded, his silvery limbs floating away,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.846#Until one of the Trojans slipped up behind him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.847#And put his spear through, a boy named Euphorbus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.848#The best his age with a spear, mounted or on foot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.849#He had already distinguished himself in this war
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.850#By knocking twenty warriors out of their cars
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.851#The first time he went out for chariot lessons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.852#It was this boy who took his chance at you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.853#Patroclus, but instead of finishing you off,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.854#He pulled his spear out and ran back where he belonged,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.855#Unwilling to face even an unarmed Patroclus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.856#Who staggered back toward his comrades, still alive,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.857#But overcome by the god's stroke, and the spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.858#Hector was watching this, and when he saw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.859#Patroclus withdrawing with a wound, he muscled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.860#His way through to him and rammed his spearhead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.861#Into the pit of his belly and all the way through.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.862#Patroclus fell heavily. You could hear the Greeks wince.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.863#A boar does not wear out easily, but a lion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.864#Will overpower it when the two face off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.865#Over a trickling spring up in the mountains
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.866#They both want to drink from. The boar
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.867#Pants hard, but the lion comes out on top.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.868#So too did Hector, whose spear was draining the life
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.869#From Menoetius' son, who had himself killed many.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.870#His words beat down on Patroclus like dark wings:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.871#"So, Patroclus, you thought you could ransack my city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.872#And ship our women back to Greece to be your slaves.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.873#You little fool. They are defended by me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.874#By Hector, by my horses and my spear. I am the one,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.875#Troy's best, who keeps their doom at bay. But you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.876#Patroclus, the vultures will eat you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.877#On this very spot. Your marvelous Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.878#Has done you no good at all. I can just see it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.879#Him sitting in his tent and telling you as you left:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.880#'Don't bother coming back to the ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.881#Patroclus, until you have ripped Hector's heart out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.882#Through his bloody shirt.' That's what he said,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.883#Isn't it? And you were stupid enough to listen."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.884#And Patroclus, barely able to shake the words out:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.885#"Brag while you can, Hector. Zeus and Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.886#Have given you an easy victory this time.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.887#If they hadn't knocked off my armor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.888#I could have made mincemeat of twenty like you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.889#It was Fate, and Leto's son, who killed me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.890#Of men, Euphorbus. You came in third at best.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.891#And one more thing for you to think over.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.892#You're not going to live long. I see Death
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.893#Standing at your shoulder, and you going down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.894#Under the hands of Peleus' perfect son."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.895#Death's veil covered him as he said these things,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.896#And his soul, bound for Hades, fluttered out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.897#Resentfully, forsaking manhood's bloom.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.898#He was dead when Hector said to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.899#"Why prophesy my death, Patroclus?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.900#Who knows? Achilles, son of Thetis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.901#May go down first under my spear."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.902#And propping his heel against the body,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.903#He extracted his bronze spear and took off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.904#After Automedon. But Automedon was gone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.905#Pulled by immortal horses, the splendid gifts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:16.906#The gods once gave to Peleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.1#When Menelaus saw Patroclus go down,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.2#He shouldered his way through the heroes in front
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.3#And stood over the body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.4#the way a lowing heifer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.5#Stands over the first calf she has given birth to,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.6#Red-haired Menelaus above Patroclus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.7#With his spear out and shield over him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.8#Determined to kill anyone who approached.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.9#Panthous' son Euphorbus was still interested
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.10#In the fallen Patroclus. He came up,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.11#Planted himself close to Menelaus, and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.12#"Back off, son of Atreus, leave the corpse
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.13#And forget the blood-soaked spoils.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.14#No Trojan or Trojan ally hit Patroclus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.15#Before I did in the heat of battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.16#So let me have the glory that is mine
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.17#If you value your sweet life."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.18#This was too much for Menelaus, who said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.19#"It's not good to boast beyond your strength,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.20#Euphorbus. Leopards and lions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.21#And razorback boars, the wildest of beasts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.22#May be nothing compared to Panthous' sons,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.23#But mighty Hyperenor did not live
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.24#To enjoy his youth when he made light of me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.25#As the weakest warrior in all of Greece.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.26#He's not going home under his own power
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.27#To gladden his wife and devoted parents.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.28#I'll unstring you too if you stand against me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.29#Take my advice and get back to your troops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.30#Before you get hurt. Fools learn the hard way."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.31#Euphorbus was not convinced. He answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.32#"Now, Menelaus, you're going to pay the price
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.33#For killing my brother---and boasting about it---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.34#And for widowing his young bride
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.35#And causing our parents unspeakable pain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.36#But I could relieve their suffering for a while
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.37#By bringing back your head and armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.38#And placing them in Panthous' and Phrontis' hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.39#But it won't take long to settle this.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.40#Either put up a fight or clear out of here."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.41#His ash spear hit the disk of Menelaus' shield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.42#But the point bent and didn't break through
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.43#The heavy bronze. Menelaus charged
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.44#With a prayer to Zeus, and as Euphorbus stepped back,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.45#Put his spear through the base of his neck,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.46#Leaning into the thrust with a strong grip on the shaft.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.47#The point passed right through his soft neck
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.48#And he fell heavily with a clatter of armor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.49#His hair, braided like twisted myrtle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.50#With gold and silver, was drenched with blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.51#A man has been rearing an olive sapling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.52#In a lonely place, where it has enough water.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.53#It is beautiful and growing well, quivering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.54#In the breeze, its white buds blossoming.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.55#One day a storm comes with violent winds,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.56#Tears it from its trench, and leaves it on the ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.57#So too Panthous' son, Euphorbus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.58#Menelaus moved in to strip off the armor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.59#A mountain lion, supremely confident,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.60#Has seized the finest heifer in the grazing herd.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.61#First he crunches her neck in his strong jaws,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.62#Then greedily laps her blood and soft innards.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.63#The herdsmen and their hounds shout at him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.64#From a safe distance, but, pale with fear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.65#They lack the will to take him on.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.66#Not a single Trojan opposed Menelaus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.67#And he would have carried off Euphorbus' armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.68#Easily, had not Apollo begrudged it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.69#Taking the form of Mentes, a Ciconian commander,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.70#He went to work on Hector, and his words flew fast:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.71#"Hector, you're chasing something you'll never catch,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.72#The horses of Peleus, a team hard to handle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.73#For any mortal except Achilles, a goddess's son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.74#Meanwhile, Atreus' son Menelaus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.75#Has gotten in position over Patroclus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.76#And killed the best man we've got, Euphorbus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.77#Panthous' son, stopped him cold."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.78#And the god went back into the toil of men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.79#A dark shadow of grief passed over Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.80#He scanned the lines and saw one figure
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.81#Bending over another, stripping off armor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.82#The other beneath him in a pool of blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.83#He strode forward though the men in front,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.84#His armor blazing, and the cry from his lips
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.85#Was like Hephaestus' inextinguishable flame.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.86#Atreus' son heard it and said to himself:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.87#"Ah me, if I leave behind the fine armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.88#And Patroclus too, who fought for my honor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.89#All of the Greeks will hold it against me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.90#But if I fight Hector and the Trojans alone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.91#Out of a sense of shame, I'll be surrounded,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.92#One against many. Hector is leading
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.93#The whole Trojan army in this direction.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.94#But why am I talking to myself this way?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.95#There's nothing but trouble in bucking heaven
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.96#And fighting a man with a god on his side.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.97#No Greek looking on will hold it against me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.98#If I pull back from Hector, who has divine help.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.99#But if I could just find Ajax, the two of us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.100#Could go back in and think about fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.101#Even against heaven's will, make the best
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.102#Of a bad situation, and see if we can save
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.103#Patroclus' corpse for the son of Peleus."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.104#While he thought it over the Trojan ranks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.105#Closed in behind Hector. Menelaus pulled back,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.106#Leaving the corpse and constantly turning around
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.107#Like a bearded lion that men with dogs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.108#Drive from a pen with spears and shouts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.109#His heart is like ice, and he leaves reluctantly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.110#Red-haired Menelaus left Patroclus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.111#But when he reached his own lines
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.112#He looked around for Telamonian Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.113#And spotted him on the army's left flank,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.114#Cheering on his men and urging them to fight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.115#For Phoebus Apollo had panicked them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.116#Menelaus ran over and said to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.117#"Ajax, old friend, Patroclus is dead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.118#We'll have to hurry if we're going to get
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.119#His body back to Achilles---that is,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.120#The naked corpse. Hector has the armor."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.121#Ajax was moved when he heard this. He strode
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.122#To the front, Menelaus at his side.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.123#Hector had stripped the armor from Patroclus' body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.124#And was pulling at the corpse---he meant to sever
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.125#The head and feed the trunk to the dogs of Troy---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.126#When Ajax stood before him like a city wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.127#Hector gave ground and vaulted into his chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.128#Handing the exquisite gear to some Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.129#To take back to town, where he could glory in it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.130#Ajax covered Menoetius' son with his shield.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.131#A lioness stands over her cubs. She had been leading
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.132#The little ones through the forest when hunters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.133#Came across her, and now, savoring her strength,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.134#She narrows her eyes to cold yellow slits.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.135#Ajax stood over the fallen hero, and Menelaus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.136#Came up beside him, nursing his grief.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.137#Then Glaucus, the Lycian captain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.138#Glared at Hector and said angrily:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.139#"You're all good looks, Hector, and no fight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.140#Just another big name attached to a quitter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.141#Well, you'd better think now how to save your city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.142#With home-grown Trojans and nobody else.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.143#No Lycians, at least, are going to fight the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.144#To rescue Troy, since there's no gratitude
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.145#For nonstop combat with the enemy forces.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.146#Are you likely to save an ordinary soldier
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.147#In the press of battle when you left Sarpedon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.148#Your comrade and guest, as pickings for the Greeks?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.149#After all he'd done for you and your city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.150#While he was still alive, you didn't have the heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.151#To keep the dogs off his head. That's why now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.152#If any of the Lycians will listen to me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.153#We're heading home. Then Troy will be done for.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.154#If only the Trojans showed the sort of courage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.155#Real men have when they fight for their country
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.156#Against foreign invaders, laying it all on the line,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.157#We would drag Patroclus to Troy in no time.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.158#And if we did, if we got that man's corpse
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.159#Out of battle and into Priam's great city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.160#The Greeks would give back Sarpedon's armor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.161#And we could bring his body into Ilion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.162#That's how great a man the dead Patroclus served,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.163#The best of the Achaeans, and his soldiers too.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.164#But you didn't have the guts to stand up to Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.165#And look him in the eye just now, much less fight him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.166#The reason being that he's stronger than you."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.167#Hector, helmet shimmering, responded:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.168#"Glaucus, this insolence is not like you at all.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.169#I've always thought you were the most intelligent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.170#Of all the Lycians, but I have no use
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.171#For nonsense like this. What a thing to say,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.172#That I wouldn't take on big hulking Ajax.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.173#I don't rattle, Glaucus, or freeze up in combat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.174#Sure, Zeus can overpower the greatest hero,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.175#Make him panic, and rob him of victory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.176#Just as he can make men get up and fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.177#So come along if you want to see how I do
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.178#All day long---whether I'm the coward you say I am,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.179#Or stop a Greek or two cold, for all their fury,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.180#From fighting in defense of Patroclus' corpse."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.181#Then Hector made his voice carry:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.182#"Trojan, Lycian, and Dardanian soldiers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.183#Be men, my friends, and remember your strength
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.184#While I put on Achilles' resplendent armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.185#That I took off Patroclus when I cut him down."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.186#And his helmet flashed gold as he turned and ran
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.187#Out of the battle. He soon caught his comrades---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.188#They were not far, and he was running hard---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.189#As they carried Achilles' gear back to Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.190#There, on the edge of war's horrors, he changed armor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.191#He gave his own to be carried back to the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.192#By his fighting men, and he put on the inhuman gear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.193#Of Peleus' son Achilles that the gods of heaven
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.194#Had given to his father, and he to his son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.195#When he had grown old in them, as his son would not.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.196#Zeus saw him from his seat high in the clouds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.197#As he buckled on Achilles' armor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.198#Shaking his head the god said to himself:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.199#"Unhappy man, you have no thought of death,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.200#Yet death is close. You are putting on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.201#The immortal armor of a man who makes you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.202#And many others tremble. You killed his comrade,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.203#Gentle and strong, and you violated the order of things
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.204#When you took the armor from his shoulders and head.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.205#Yet I will grant you strength in recompense for this:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.206#Andromache will never welcome you home
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.207#Wearing the glorious armor of Achilles."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.208#And the Son of Cronus nodded, his brows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.209#Darkening the air. He made the armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.210#Fit Hector like his own skin, and Ares
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.211#In all his dread power entered into him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.212#Packing every muscle in his body with strength.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.213#Hector returned to the field with a great shout
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.214#And went among his allied forces,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.215#A gleaming image in Achilles' armor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.216#He encouraged them all, singling them out,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.217#Speaking to Mesthles and Glaucus and Medon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.218#Thersilochus, Asteropaeus, and Deisenor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.219#Hippothous, Phorcys, and Chromius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.220#And to Ennomus who read the flight of birds,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.221#Giving them heart with these soaring words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.222#"Hear me, my valiant allies and neighbors!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.223#I did not invite you to come here from your cities
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.224#Because I was looking for or needed a crowd,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.225#But because I thought you would fight with willing hearts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.226#To save the Trojan women and children
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.227#From these war-mongering Greeks. This is why
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.228#I have been feeding you at our expense
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.229#And giving you gifts to keep up your morale.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.230#So face the enemy and fight! Maybe you'll pull through
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.231#And maybe you won't. That's the charm of battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.232#Whoever gets Patroclus, mere corpse that he is,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.233#Back to our lines, and makes Ajax give in,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.234#Gets half the spoils. I'll split them with him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.235#Right down the middle---and he'll have glory like mine."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.236#This inspired them to charge the Greeks en masse,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.237#Spears held high, thinking they would surely
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.238#Pull the corpse from under Telamonian Ajax,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.239#The fools. Ajax killed many over that corpse,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.240#But finally turned to Menelaus and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.241#"Menelaus, old friend, I don't have much hope
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.242#Of us two getting out of this battle alive.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.243#I'm not only afraid that Patroclus' body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.244#Is soon going to glut Trojan dogs and birds,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.245#But that you and I are going to get it in the neck.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.246#There's a cloud of war covering everything---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.247#Hector---with one thing clear, our sudden death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.248#Call in our heroes. Maybe someone's within earshot."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.249#And Menelaus, who had a good battle cry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.250#Split the air with a shout to the Greeks:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.251#"Argive leaders! Everyone who drinks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.252#At Agamennon's table, commands a troop,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.253#And has honor and glory from Zeus---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.254#I can't make out every single captain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.255#In this battle's firestorm, but get out here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.256#On your own, out of shame that Patroclus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.257#Is becoming a ragbone for Trojan dogs."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.258#The Ajax that was Oïleus' swift son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.259#Heard him clearly and was the first man out.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.260#Sprinting behind him were Idomeneus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.261#And his comrade Meriones, a real killer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.262#As for the rest, who could remember
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.263#All of the Greeks who swarmed into battle?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.264#Bunched behind Hector the Trojans struck.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.265#A great wave sometimes rolls into the mouth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.266#Of a swollen river, pushing against its current.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.267#The headlands resound as the sea roars to get in.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.268#The Trojans came on, but the Greeks stood firm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.269#Around Menoetius' son, their hearts united,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.270#Their bronze shields locked.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.271#And from above
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.272#Zeus poured over their dark gold helmets
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.273#A profound mist, for Menoetius' son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.274#Had been far from hateful when in life he was
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.275#Achilles' companion. Now he loathed the thought
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.276#Of his enemies' dogs playing with his body,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.277#And so he roused his comrades to fight for him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.278#At first the Trojans drove the wild-eyed Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.279#Back from the body, and although for all their efforts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.280#And high spirits they failed to land a spear on anyone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.281#They started to pull the corpse away. The Greeks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.282#However, were back soon, rallied by Ajax,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.283#Who looked and acted more like a hero
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.284#Than any living Greek, except peerless Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.285#Ajax split the Trojan front lines
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.286#as a wild boar
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.287#In the mountains tosses dogs and men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.288#When he turns on them in a clearing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.289#This was the son of Telamon, glorious Ajax,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.290#Scattering the Trojan platoons that stood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.291#Around Patroclus and wanted nothing else more
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.292#Than the glory of dragging him back to their city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.293#Hippothous, a Pelasgian, had tied his war belt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.294#Around the corpse's ankles and was hauling it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.295#Inch by inch through the fierce fighting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.296#Much to the satisfaction of Hector and the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.297#None of them could have stopped what happened next,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.298#Ajax's spear coming from nowhere
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.299#And smashing through his plumed helmet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.300#Hippothous' brains, clotted with blood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.301#Spurted out from the wound along the spear's socket.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.302#He dropped Patroclus' foot and then fell himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.303#Face down on the corpse, far from Larissa
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.304#And his father Lethus, his debt to his parents
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.305#Unpaid, his life cut short by great Ajax's spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.306#Hector countered, but Ajax kept his eye
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.307#On the bright flare his spear made and managed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.308#Although just barely, to dodge the bronze point.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.309#Hector's spear went on to kill Schedius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.310#Son of Iphitus and the best of the Phocians,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.311#Who ruled over many from his home in Panopeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.312#The bronze point passed through his collarbone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.313#And went straight through to the base of his shoulder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.314#He fell with a heavy clanging of armor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.315#Ajax then hit Phorcys, Phaenops' son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.316#Right in the belly as he straddled Hippothous.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.317#The spearpoint broke the corselet plate,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.318#And his guts oozed through the bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.319#After he had fallen his hand still clawed at the dust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.320#The Trojan champions, including Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.321#Had enough. They backed off, and howling Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.322#Dragged off the dead, Phorcys and Hippothous,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.323#And got busy stripping off their armor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.324#It would have been another defeat for the Trojans---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.325#Driven by the Greeks, with Ares on their side,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.326#Back to Ilion---and an Argive victory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.327#Power and glory beyond Zeus' allotment,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.328#Had not Apollo himself aroused Aeneas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.329#Assuming the form of a herald, Periphas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.330#Son of Ephytos, a courteous man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.331#Who had grown old in Anchises' service.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.332#Apollo, a son of Zeus, spoke in his guise:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.333#"Aeneas, admittedly you will never defend
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.334#Steep Ilion in defiance of a god, although indeed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.335#I have seen other men trust their prowess and strength,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.336#Their courage and their superior numbers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.337#And defend their people against all odds.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.338#But in our case Zeus wants victory for us,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.339#Not for the Greeks. And yet you hang back in fear."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.340#Aeneas knew it was the god Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.341#When he looked him in the face. He called to Hector:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.342#"Hector, Trojan leaders, and allied commanders!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.343#Shame on us all if we are beaten back to Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.344#By the Achaeans without defending ourselves.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.345#One of the gods has just whispered in my ear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.346#That Zeus on high is on our side in this fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.347#Let's go straight at the Danaans! Don't let them take
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.348#Dead Patroclus to their ships at their leisure!"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.349#With that, he bounded to the front of the fight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.350#And took his stand. The Trojans rallied
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.351#And faced the Greeks. Then Aeneas thrust,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.352#Getting his spear into Leocritus, Arisbas' son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.353#And worthy comrade of Lycomedes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.354#When his friend went down, Lycomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.355#Felt for him and, standing right beside him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.356#Cast his bright spear and hit Apisaon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.357#Son of Hippasas, under the ribs in the liver.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.358#The man crumpled, the best warrior
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.359#In deep-soiled Paeonia, after Asteropaeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.360#Who watched him fall, pitied him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.361#Then charged the Greeks with everything he had.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.362#But there was nothing he could do. The Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.363#Had formed around Patroclus a wall of shields
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.364#Forward from which they held their spears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.365#Ajax was everywhere among them, seeing to it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.366#That not a man took one step backward
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.367#From the body, or went out in front to show off,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.368#But that all stood together and fought close in.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.369#That was how big Ajax managed it, and the earth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.370#Grew wet with dark blood as the dead fell
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.371#Thick and fast on both sides, Trojans, allies,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.372#Greeks too, who shed blood, but less of it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.373#And with fewer casualties, because they fought
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.374#In a tight group and protected each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.375#So the battle burned on, but you would have thought
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.376#The sun had gone out, and the moon too,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.377#For they fought in dark air, all the heroes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.378#Clustered around Menoetius' slain son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.379#The rest of the Trojans and Greeks had their war
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.380#Under the open sky and in brilliant sunlight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.381#Not a cloud on the horizon. They took breaks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.382#From the fighting, avoiding each other's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.383#Groaning shafts, making some open space in battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.384#But those in the center suffered the agony
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.385#Of combat in darkness with merciless bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.386#All the best were there, except for two Greeks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.387#Thrasymedes and Antilochus. They did not know
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.388#Blameless Patroclus was dead, and assumed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.389#He was still alive and fighting the Trojans in front.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.390#These two were struggling to keep their men alive
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.391#And in combat, fighting off at some distance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.392#Where Nestor had ordered them when they left the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.393#The day was passing. Men hacked slowly at each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.394#In pain, the sweat from their labor coating
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.395#Their thighs and knees, pooling under their feet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.396#Spattering from their arms into their glazed eyes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.397#As the two armies fought over Achilles' surrogate.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.398#A tanner gives his men an oxhide to stretch,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.399#Having first drenched it in oil. They stand in a circle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.400#And pull at it until its moisture is squeezed out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.401#By all of their tugging and the oil has a chance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.402#To penetrate the taut leather's pores.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.403#So too the tight circle of men on either side
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.404#Tugging at the corpse, the Trojans with high hopes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.405#Of dragging it back to Ilion, the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.406#With their own hopes of getting it back to the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.407#It was a savage fight, and not even Ares
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.408#Or Athena, in their most belligerent moods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.409#Could have watched it with disdain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.410#Such was the labor for men and horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.411#Zeus stretched over Patroclus that day.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.412#But all this time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.413#Achilles did not know Patroclus was dead,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.414#For they were fighting far from the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.415#Under Troy's walls, and Achilles never dreamed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.416#He would die there, but thought he would return alive
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.417#After he reached the gates. Nor did he think
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.418#Patroclus would take Troy without him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.419#Or with him for that matter. He had heard this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.420#Many times from his mother when they had their talks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.421#And she would tell him the intentions of Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.422#But his mother did not tell him now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.423#Of this great evil, his dearest friend dead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.424#Around the corpse they kept pressing hard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.425#With sharp spears and killing each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.426#Some Greek would say from his bronze mask:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.427#"Friends, there's no point in returning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.428#To the hollow ships. It would be better
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.429#For the black earth to swallow us here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.430#If we're going to let the Trojans haul him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.431#Back to the city and win all the glory."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.432#Or some Trojan would say:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.433#"Friends, even if we're all fated to die
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.434#By this body, don't take a step back."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.435#These words would lift everyone's strength.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.436#While they fought on, and as the iron noise
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.437#Rose through the barren air to the bronze sky,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.438#Achilles' horses, some distance from the battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.439#Were weeping, and had been since first they learned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.440#That their charioteer had fallen in the dust
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.441#Under the hands of man-slaying Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.442#Automedon, Diores' valiant son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.443#Was doing everything he could with lash,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.444#Gentle words, and curses to get them moving,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.445#But the pair would not go back to the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.446#By the level sea, or back into battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.447#With the Achaeans. They stood still as stone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.448#Still as a post on a man's or woman's tomb,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.449#There in front of the beautiful chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.450#Their heads bowed to the earth, their tears
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.451#Rolling warm from their eyes to the ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.452#As they wept in longing for their charioteer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.453#And their lustrous manes were fouled in the dust
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.454#As they streamed to either side of the yoke.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.455#When he saw them mourning the son of Cronus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.456#Felt pity. He shook his head and said to himself:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.457#"Ah, why did we give you to lord Peleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.458#To a mortal, while you are deathless and ageless?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.459#Was it so you could share men's pain?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.460#Nothing is more miserable than man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.461#Of all that breathes and moves upon earth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.462#But Priam's son Hector will not drive you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.463#Or your wrought chariot. That I will not allow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.464#Is it not enough that he has the armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.465#And struts vainly in it? No, in your knees
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.466#And in your heart I will put strength
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.467#So you may bear Automedon out of the war
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.468#To the hollow ships. For I will continue to give
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.469#The Trojans glory to kill, until they reach the ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.470#And the sun sets, and sacred darkness comes on."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.471#And he breathed into the horses great strength.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.472#The two shook the dust from their manes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.473#And raced with the chariot through the combatants.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.474#Automedon kept trying to fight, though grieving
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.475#For his comrade, swooping with the horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.476#Like a vulture on a flock of geese, easily
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.477#Leaving the clamor of the Trojans behind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.478#And just as easily bearing down on them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.479#But he could not kill any of his quarry
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.480#Since he was alone in the haunted chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.481#And could not handle a spear and drive too.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.482#Finally a friend saw him and caught his eye,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.483#Alcimedon, son of Laerces Haemonides,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.484#Who now stood behind the chariot and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.485#"Automedon, which god has put this bad idea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.486#Into your head and robbed you of your good sense,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.487#Fighting the Trojans up here in the thick of things
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.488#All alone? Your companion is dead, and Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.489#Is strutting around in old Peleus' armor."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.490#Diores' son Automedon answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.491#"Alcimedon, is there a man in the army
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.492#Who could control these immortal horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.493#Besides Patroclus? He had a will like a god's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.494#While he lived. Now death has caught up with him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.495#But take the lash anyway, and the reins,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.496#And I will dismount so I can fight."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.497#Alcimedon swung into the fast war chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.498#And took the reins and lash in his hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.499#Automedon jumped off. Hector saw the move
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.500#And said to Aeneas, who was at his side:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.501#"Aeneas, I've just spotted Achilles' horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.502#Coming into battle with a pair of weak drivers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.503#I think I could take them, if you would help.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.504#Their drivers couldn't stand up to men like us."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.505#Aeneas was willing, and the two went forward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.506#Shoulders hunched behind their shields,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.507#Pounds of bronze welded to hardened leather.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.508#With them went Chromius and godlike Aretus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.509#Who fully expected they would kill the men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.510#And drive off the high-necked horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.511#But Automedon would extract blood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.512#For these childish hopes. He prayed to Lord Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.513#And felt a dark surge of power within him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.514#Then spoke quickly to his trusted driver:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.515#"Alcimedon, keep the horses close enough
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.516#That I can feel their breath on my back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.517#Hector won't stop until he he mounts the chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.518#Behind Achilles' horses, with us dead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.519#And the rest of the Argive army in rout,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.520#Or until he himself goes down in the front."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.521#And he called to both Ajaxes and to Menelaus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.522#"Ajax, both of you, and Menelaus too,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.523#Leave the body for the best men you have
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.524#To defend it against the Trojan onslaught,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.525#And come help us out while we're still alive.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.526#Hector and Aeneas have weighed in here,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.527#The best Troy has. Well, it's in the gods' laps.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.528#I'll do what I can and leave the rest to Zeus."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.529#He balanced his long-shadowed spear and threw,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.530#Hitting Aretus' shield, which did not stop
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.531#The bronze point from penetrating all the way through
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.532#And into his belly just below his belt.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.533#When a strong man swings a sharp ax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.534#Onto a bull's neck just behind the horns
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.535#And cuts through all the sinews there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.536#The animal pitches forward as it falls.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.537#Aretus pitched forward and fell on his back,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.538#Undone by the razor-sharp spear that stuck
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.539#Quivering in his entrails. Hector rifled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.540#His polished spear at Automedon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.541#But Automedon saw it all the way and ducked,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.542#Leaving it to punch into the ground and stand there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.543#Trembling, until Ares finally stilled its fury.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.544#They would have closed on each other with swords,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.545#But the two Ajaxes, responding to their comrade's call
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.546#Stepped between them, sending cold chills
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.547#Through Hector, Aeneas, and Chromius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.548#Who all withdrew, letting Aretus lie there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.549#Mangled and dead. As Automedon stripped him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.550#He said with grim satisfaction:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.551#"This makes up for the death of Patroclus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.552#Though it is a lesser man I have killed."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.553#And he swung the bloody spoils into the chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.554#And mounted, his feet and arms smeared with gore,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.555#Like a lion that has just eaten a bull.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.556#The tense fight over Patroclus went on,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.557#Made even more tense now by Athena,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.558#Who stepped down from the sky, sent by Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.559#Zeus sometimes sends a shimmering arc from the sky
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.560#As a portent of war, or of a cold rainstorm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.561#That brings men in from the fields and vexes the flocks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.562#Athena wrapped herself in an iridescent mist
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.563#And entered the Greek throng, urging on each man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.564#Beginning with Atreus' son, Menelaus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.565#Standing by his side and speaking to him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.566#In the guise of Phoenix and using his voice:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.567#"The shame and dishonor will be mostly yours,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.568#Menelaus, if lord Achilles' faithful comrade
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.569#Is savaged by dogs under Ilion's walls.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.570#Hold your ground and urge on the army!"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.571#Menelaus, good at the war cry, answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.572#"Phoenix, old sir! If only Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.573#Would give me strength and shield me from spears,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.574#I would stand by Patroclus and protect him all day.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.575#I take his death hard. But Hector is on fire,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.576#Just carving us up with his bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.577#Zeus is giving him all the glory."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.578#Athena, eyes glinting in the sun, was glad
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.579#That Menelaus had put her first in his prayers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.580#She put power into his shoulders and knees,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.581#And into his breast the boldness of a horsefly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.582#That however often it is flicked away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.583#From human flesh, persists in biting,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.584#For human blood is sweet. Menelaus felt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.585#That kind of boldness in his dark heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.586#As he straddled Patroclus and threw his bright spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.587#There was among the Trojans a certain Podes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.588#A son of Eëtion, a rich, valiant man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.589#Whom Hector honored with a place at his table.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.590#Menelaus' spear hit him on the belt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.591#As he turned to run. The metal point went through
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.592#And he fell with a thud. Atreus' red-haired son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.593#Dragged the body to the main group of Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.594#Then Apollo stood close to Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.595#Seeming to be Asius' son Phaenops,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.596#A dear family friend who lived in Abydos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.597#In his likeness the Archer urged him on:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.598#"Hector, is there any Greek who will fear you now?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.599#Look how you lost your nerve before Menelaus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.600#A well-known weakling. He's taken the corpse
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.601#Out from under our noses all by himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.602#And is gone. And he's killed your true friend
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.603#And great hero Podes, son of Eëtion."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.604#A black cloud of grief enveloped Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.605#And he strode forward in a blaze of bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.606#At the same moment the Son of Cronus took his aegis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.607#A fringed glare in the sky, and wrapped Ida in clouds.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.608#He thundered and lightened and shook the aegis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.609#Giving victory to the Trojans and routing the Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.610#Peneleos the Boeotian bolted first.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.611#A spear grazed his shoulder as he faced the enemy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.612#But the blade sliced through to the bone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.613#A lucky throw by Polydamas from close range.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.614#Leitus was next, nicked on the wrist
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.615#By Hector, enough to make him quit the fight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.616#Seeing he couldn't grip a spear properly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.617#This man was the son of Alectryon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.618#As he withdrew, wide-eyed and apprehensive,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.619#Hector chased him, and Idomeneus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.620#Took a shot at the Trojan, hitting him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.621#On the breastplate right by the nipple,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.622#But the spear's shaft shattered in its socket.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.623#The Trojans cheered. Hector returned the favor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.624#His javelin just missing Idomeneus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.625#As he stood in his chariot but hitting Coeranus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.626#Meriones' charioteer and comrade from Lyctus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.627#Idomeneus had set out from the ships on foot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.628#And would have handed the Trojans a great coup
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.629#Had not Coeranus driven his fast horses by
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.630#And given him some daylight. He saved the day
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.631#But lost his life to man-slaughtering Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.632#Whose spear got him behind the jaw, under the ear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.633#Plowing out his teeth and slicing his tongue lengthwise.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.634#He fell from the car and dropped the reins to the ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.635#Meriones bent over and scooped them up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.636#From the dirt, and said to Idomeneus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.637#"Lay on the lash until you get back to the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.638#You know as well as I do the Greeks are washed up."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.639#He spoke, and Idomeneus, in a panic now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.640#Lashed the maned horses back to the hollow ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.641#Not even Ajax and Menelaus failed to notice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.642#That Zeus had shifted the momentum to the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.643#Big Ajax turned to his companion and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.644#"Any fool can see that Father Zeus himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.645#Is helping the Trojans. Everything they throw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.646#Hits home. It doesn't matter who throws it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.647#Brave man or coward, Zeus guides them all straight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.648#But we can't hit anything but the ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.649#Let's try to come up with the best plan we can
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.650#To haul the corpse out and build morale
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.651#By getting ourselves back to our comrades.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.652#They must feel despair when they look this way.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.653#I doubt if they think Hector can be stopped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.654#Before he lays his hands on our black sailing ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.655#If only one of our men could get a message through,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.656#Fast, to Achilles. I don't think he's heard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.657#The bad news, that his best friend is dead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.658#But I can't see any Greek who could do that job.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.659#They're all lost in dark mist, their horses too.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.660#Father Zeus, deliver the Greeks from the dark.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.661#Make the sky clear. Allow us to see with our eyes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.662#Destroy us in the light, since destroy us you will."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.663#He spoke, and the Father had pity for his tears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.664#Instantly he dispersed the darkness and mist,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.665#And the sun shone, and all the battle was clear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.666#Then Ajax turned to Menelaus and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.667#"Menelaus, see if you can spot Antilochus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.668#Still alive, Nestor's son. Have him go quickly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.669#To Achilles and tell him his best friend is dead."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.670#Menelaus, who was good at the war shout,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.671#Couldn't argue with this, and started to leave,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.672#Very much like a lion that leaves a corral
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.673#After it is tired of vexing the men and dogs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.674#Who, standing guard all night, will not allow it to seize
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.675#The herd's prime bull. Lusting for flesh,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.676#The lion charges, but gets nothing for it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.677#But a rain of javelins launched by bold hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.678#And flaming torches that stop it in its tracks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.679#At dawn the lion goes off in a sullen mood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.680#Menelaus was just as reluctant to leave
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.681#Patroclus' body, afraid of a general rout
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.682#That would leave him stranded behind enemy lines.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.683#He lingered to remind his comrades of their duty:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.684#"Both you Ajaxes, and Meriones too,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.685#Everyone should keep in mind what a good man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.686#Our Patroclus was, gentle and kind to all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.687#When he was alive. And now death has taken him."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.688#Finally, Menelaus left,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.689#Glancing every which way.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.690#An eagle, whose eyesight is the keenest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.691#Of all the birds in the sky, can spot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.692#From high altitude a rabbit crouching
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.693#Under a leafy bush and, swooping down,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.694#Catch it and instantly rip out its life.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.695#Yes, Menelaus, that's how your bright eyes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.696#Swept everywhere through the allied troops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.697#Searching for Nestor's son---was he still alive?---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.698#And, yes, spotted him on the battle's left,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.699#Encouraging his men and urging them to fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.700#Menelaus made his way to his side and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.701#"I have bad news, Antilochus. You know
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.702#Some god has turned the tide against us.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.703#Well, now the best of the Achaeans is dead,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.704#Patroclus. God, that it were not true.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.705#Run to the ships and tell Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.706#If he acts quickly he might still save the body---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.707#Naked, though. Hector has the armor."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.708#He spoke, and Antilochus was choked with horror.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.709#He was speechless, astounded; his eyes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.710#Welled with tears; his voice stuck in his throat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.711#But he did not disregard Menelaus' orders.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.712#He started to run, giving his armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.713#To his charioteer, who drove beside him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.714#He left the battlefield on foot and in tears,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.715#With a grim report for Achilles, son of Peleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.716#Menelaus had no intention of staying to help
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.717#The sore-pressed troops from Pylos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.718#Who already missed their commander Antilochus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.719#He dispatched Thrasymedes in his place
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.720#And ran back to take his stand over Patroclus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.721#Next to the Ajaxes, to whom he said at once:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.722#"I've sent Antilochus there ahead to the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.723#To go to Achilles, but we can't count on Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.724#Coming any time soon. He may want Hector badly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.725#But he can't fight the Trojans unarmed and naked.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.726#We have to come up with the best plan we can
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.727#To get the body out and escape ourselves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.728#From this deafening battle without any casualties."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.729#It was big Ajax who came up with the plan:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.730#"Right, Menelaus. You and Meriones
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.731#Get the body up on your shoulders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.732#And carry it out. We'll be behind you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.733#Holding off the Trojans and Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.734#We have the same name and the same heart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.735#And we've stuck with each other in battle before."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.736#They got their arms round the corpse and raised it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.737#High off the ground. The Trojans shouted out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.738#When they saw the Greeks lift the body, and charged.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.739#Hunting dogs after a wounded boar
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.740#Will run up in front of the hunters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.741#And for a while threaten to tear the boar apart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.742#But when the boar pivots and trusts its strength,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.743#The dogs quail and slink back one by one.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.744#So too the Trojans, who would launch mass attacks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.745#Thrusting with swords and double-edged spears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.746#But when the two Ajaxes wheeled and made a stand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.747#They would all turn pale, not a single man willing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.748#To make a quick move and contend for the corpse.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.749#In this way, this little knot of Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.750#Did their best to carry Patroclus' body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.751#Out of combat and back to their ribbed ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.752#While against them the battle strained and coiled,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.753#As wild as fire when it engulfs a city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.754#Suddenly, and sets it aflame, and the houses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.755#Shrivel in the heat and the wind roars like thunder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.756#So too, as they went on, the eternal din
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.757#Of horses, cars, and spearmen, noise like heat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.758#Or think of a team of mules, matched in strength,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.759#Dragging a load down a craggy mountain path,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.760#A beam, say, or a huge ship timber. Their spirits
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.761#Flag with the toil and sweat, but they push on.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.762#So these two Greeks pushed on with the corpse,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.763#And the two Ajaxes held the enemy off.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.764#A wooded ridge that lies across a plain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.765#Will check the cruel currents of swollen rivers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.766#Turning them back to spread over the plain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.767#And the floods, though strong, never break through.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.768#So the two Ajaxes contained the Trojans'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.769#Offensive push. But the Trojans kept coming,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.770#And two among them especially,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.771#Aeneas, Anchises' son, and glorious Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.772#A cloud of starlings or jackdaws will loop around
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.773#Shrieking doom when they see ahead of them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.774#A falcon, which brings death to smaller birds.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.775#So too before Aeneas and Hector the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.776#Ran shrieking, as if it were the end of the world.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.777#The trench was littered with their beautiful,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:17.778#Discarded weapons. But there was no armistice.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.1#The fight went on, like wildfire burning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.2#Antilochus, running hard like a herald,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.3#Found Achilles close to his upswept hulls,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.4#His great heart brooding with premonitions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.5#Of what had indeed already happened.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.6#"This looks bad,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.7#All these Greeks with their hair in the wind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.8#Stampeding off the plain and back to the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.9#God forbid that what my mother told me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.10#Has now come true, that while I'm still alive
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.11#Trojan hands would steal the sunlight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.12#From the best of all the Myrmidons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.13#Patroclus, Menoetius' brave son, is dead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.14#Damn him! I told him only to repel
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.15#The enemy fire from our ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.16#And not to take on Hector in a fight."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.17#Antilochus was in tears when he reached him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.18#And delivered his unendurable message:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.19#"Son of wise Peleus, this is painful news
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.20#For you to hear, and I wish it were not true.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.21#Patroclus is down, and they are fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.22#For his naked corpse. Hector has the armor."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.23#A mist of black grief enveloped Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.24#He scooped up fistfuls of sunburnt dust
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.25#And poured it on his head, fouling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.26#His beautiful face. Black ash grimed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.27#His fine-spun cloak as he stretched his huge body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.28#Out in the dust and lay there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.29#Tearing out his hair with his hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.30#The women, whom Achilles and Patroclus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.31#Had taken in raids, ran shrieking out of the tent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.32#To be with Achilles, and they beat their breasts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.33#Until their knees gave out beneath them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.34#Antilochus, sobbing himself, stayed with Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.35#And held his hands---he was groaning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.36#From the depths of his soul---for fear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.37#He would lay open his own throat with steel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.38#The sound of Achilles' grief stung the air.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.39#Down in the water his mother heard him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.40#Sitting in the sea depths beside her old father,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.41#And she began to wail.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.42#And the saltwater women
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.43#Gathered around her, all the deep-sea Nereids,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.44#Glauc and Thaleia and Cymodoc,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.45#Neseia and Speio, Tho and ox-eyed Hali,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.46#Cymotho, Actae, and Limnoeira,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.47#Melit and Iaera, Amphitho and Agau,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.48#Doris, Panop, and milk-white Galateia,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.49#Nemertes, Apseudes, and Callianassa,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.50#Clymen, Ianeira, Ianassa, and Maera,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.51#Oreithyia and Amatheia, hair streaming behind her,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.52#And all of the other deep-sea Nereids.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.53#They filled the silver, shimmering cave,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.54#And they all beat their breasts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.55#Thetis led the lament:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.56#"Hear me, sisters, hear the pain in my heart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.57#I gave birth to a son, and that is my sorrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.58#My perfect son, the best of heroes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.59#He grew like a sapling, and I nursed him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.60#As I would a plant on the hill in my garden,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.61#And I sent him to Ilion on a sailing ship
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.62#To fight the Trojans. And now I will never
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.63#Welcome him home again to Peleus' house.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.64#As long as he lives and sees the sunlight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.65#He will be in pain, and I cannot help him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.66#But I'll go now to see and hear my dear son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.67#Since he is suffering while he waits out the war."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.68#She left the cave, and they went with her,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.69#Weeping, and around them a wave
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.70#Broke through the sea, and they came to Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.71#They emerged on the beach where the Myrmidons' ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.72#Formed an encampment around Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.73#He was groaning deeply, and his mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.74#Stood next to him and held her son's head.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.75#Her lamentation hung sharp in the air,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.76#And then she spoke in low, sorrowful tones:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.77#"Child, why are you crying? What pain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.78#Has come to your heart? Speak, don't hide it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.79#Zeus has granted your prayer. The Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.80#Have all been beaten back to their ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.81#And suffered horribly. They can't do without you."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.82#Achilles answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.83#"Mother, Zeus may have done all this for me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.84#But how can I rejoice? My friend is dead,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.85#Patroclus, my dearest friend of all. I loved him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.86#And I killed him. And the armor---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.87#Hector cut him down and took off his body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.88#The heavy, splendid armor, beautiful to see,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.89#That the gods gave to Peleus as a gift
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.90#On the day they put you to bed with a mortal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.91#You should have stayed with the saltwater women,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.92#And Peleus should have married a mortal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.93#But now---it was all so you would suffer pain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.94#For your ravaged son. You will never again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.95#Welcome me home, since I no longer have the will
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.96#To remain alive among men, not unless Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.97#Loses his life on the point of my spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.98#And pays for despoiling Menoetius' son."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.99#And Thetis, in tears, said to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.100#"I won't have you with me for long, my child,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.101#If you say such things. Hector's death means yours."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.102#From under a great weight, Achilles answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.103#"Then let me die now. I was no help
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.104#To him when he was killed out there. He died
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.105#Far from home, and he needed me to protect him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.106#But now, since I'm not going home, and wasn't
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.107#A light for Patroclus or any of the rest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.108#Of my friends who have been beaten by Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.109#But just squatted by my ships, a dead weight on the earth . . .
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.110#I stand alone in the whole Greek army
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.111#When it comes to war---though some do speak better.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.112#I wish all strife could stop, among gods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.113#And among men, and anger too---it sends
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.114#Sensible men into fits of temper,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.115#It drips down our throats sweeter than honey
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.116#And mushrooms up in our bellies like smoke.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.117#Yes, the warlord Agamemnon angered me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.118#But we'll let that be, no matter how it hurts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.119#And conquer our pride, because we must.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.120#But I'm going now to find the man who destroyed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.121#My beloved---Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.122#As for my own fate,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.123#I'll accept it whenever it pleases Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.124#And the other immortal gods to send it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.125#Not even Heracles could escape his doom.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.126#He was dearest of all to Lord Zeus, but fate
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.127#And Hera's hard anger destroyed him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.128#If it is true that I have a fate like his, then I too
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.129#Will lie down in death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.130#But now to win glory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.131#And make some Trojan woman or deep-breasted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.132#Dardanian matron wipe the tears
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.133#From her soft cheeks, make her sob and groan.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.134#Let them feel how long I've been out of the war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.135#Don't try, out of love, to stop me. I won't listen."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.136#And Thetis, her feet silver on the sand:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.137#"Yes, child. It's not wrong to save your friends
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.138#When they are beaten to the brink of death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.139#But your beautiful armor is in the hands of the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.140#The mirrored bronze. Hector himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.141#Has it on his shoulders. He glories in it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.142#Not for long, though. I see his death is near.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.143#But you, don't dive into the red dust of war
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.144#Until with your own eyes you see me returning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.145#Tomorrow I will come with the rising sun
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.146#Bearing beautiful armor from Lord Hephaestus."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.147#Thetis spoke, turned away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.148#From her son, and said to her saltwater sisters:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.149#"Sink now into the sea's wide lap
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.150#And go down to our old father's house
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.151#And tell him all this. I am on my way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.152#Up to Olympus to visit Hephaestus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.153#The glorious smith, to see if for my sake
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.154#He will give my son glorious armor."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.155#As she spoke they dove into the waves,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.156#And the silver-footed goddess was gone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.157#Off to Olympus to fetch arms for her child.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.158#And while her feet carried her off to Olympus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.159#Hector yelled, a yell so bloodcurdling and loud
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.160#It stampeded the Greeks all the way back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.161#To their ships beached on the Hellespont's shore.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.162#They could not pull the body of Patroclus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.163#Out of javelin range, and soon Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.164#With his horses and men, stood over it again.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.165#Three times Priam's resplendent son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.166#Took hold of the corpse's heels and tried
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.167#To drag it off, bawling commands to his men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.168#Three times the two Ajaxes put their heads down,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.169#Charged, and beat him back. Unshaken, Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.170#Sidestepped, cut ahead, or held his ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.171#With a shout, but never yielded an inch.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.172#It was like shepherds against a starving lion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.173#Helpless to beat it back from a carcass,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.174#The two Ajaxes unable to rout
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.175#The son of Priam from Patroclus' corpse.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.176#And Hector would have, to his eternal glory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.177#Dragged the body off, had not Iris stormed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.178#Down from Olympus with a message for Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.179#Unbeknownst to Zeus and the other gods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.180#Hera had sent her, and this was her message:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.181#"Rise, son of Peleus, most formidable of men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.182#Rescue Patroclus, for whom a terrible battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.183#Is pitched by the ships, men killing each other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.184#Some fighting to save the dead man's body,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.185#The Trojans trying to drag it back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.186#To windy Ilion. Hector's mind especially
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.187#Is bent on this. He means to impale the head
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.188#On Troy's palisade after he strips off its skin.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.189#And you just lie there? Think of Patroclus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.190#Becoming a ragbone for Trojan dogs. Shame
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.191#To your dying day if his corpse is defiled."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.192#The shining sprinter Achilles answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.193#"Iris, which god sent you here?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.194#And Iris, whose feet are wind, responded:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.195#"None other than Hera, Zeus' glorious wife.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.196#But Zeus on high does not know this, nor do
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.197#Any of the immortals on snow-capped Olympus."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.198#And Achilles, the great runner:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.199#"How can I go to war? They have my armor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.200#And my mother told me not to arm myself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.201#Until with my own eyes I see her come back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.202#With fine weapons from Hephaestus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.203#I don't know any other armor that would fit,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.204#Unless maybe the shield of Telamonian Ajax.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.205#But he's out there in the front ranks, I hope,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.206#Fighting with his spear over Patroclus dead."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.207#Windfoot Iris responded:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.208#"We know very well that they have your armor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.209#Just go to the trench and let the Trojans see you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.210#One look will be enough. The Trojans will back off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.211#Out of fear of you, and this will give the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.212#Some breathing space, what little there is in war."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.213#Iris spoke and was gone. And Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.214#Whom the gods loved, rose. Around
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.215#His mighty shoulders Athena threw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.216#Her tasselled aegis, and the shining goddess
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.217#Haloed his head with a golden cloud
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.218#That shot flames from its incandescent glow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.219#Smoke is rising through the pure upper air
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.220#From a besieged city on a distant island.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.221#Its soldiers have fought hard all day,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.222#But at sunset they light innumerable fires
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.223#So that their neighbors in other cities
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.224#Might see the glare reflected off the sky
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.225#And sail to their help as allies in war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.226#So too the radiance that flared
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.227#From Achilles' head and up to the sky.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.228#He went to the trench---away from the wall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.229#And the other Greeks, out of respect
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.230#For his mother's tense command. Standing there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.231#He yelled, and behind him Pallas Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.232#Amplified his voice, and shock waves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.233#Reverberated through the Trojan ranks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.234#You have heard the piercing sound of horns
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.235#When squadrons come to destroy a city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.236#The Greek's voice was like that,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.237#Speaking bronze that made each Trojan heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.238#Wince with pain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.239#And the combed horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.240#Shied from their chariots, eyes wide with fear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.241#And their drivers went numb when they saw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.242#The fire above Achilles' head
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.243#Burned into the sky by the Grey-Eyed One.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.244#Three times Achilles shouted from the trench;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.245#Three times the Trojans and their confederates
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.246#Staggered and reeled, twelve of their best
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.247#Lost in the crush of chariots and spears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.248#But the Greeks were glad to pull Patroclus' body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.249#Out of range and placed it on a litter. His comrades
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.250#Gathered around, weeping, and with them Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.251#Shedding hot tears when he saw his loyal friend
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.252#Stretched out on the litter, cut with sharp bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.253#He had sent him off to war with horses and chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.254#But he never welcomed him back home again.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.255#And now the ox-eyed Lady Hera
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.256#Sent the tireless, reluctant sun
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.257#Under the horizon into Ocean's streams,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.258#Its last rays touching the departing Greeks with gold.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.259#It had been a day of brutal warfare.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.260#After the Trojans withdrew from battle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.261#They unhitched their horses from the chariots
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.262#And held an assembly before thinking of supper.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.263#They remained on their feet, too agitated to sit,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.264#Terrified, in fact, that Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.265#After a long absence, was back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.266#Polydamas was the first to speak, prudent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.267#Son of Panthous, the only Trojan who looked
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.268#Both ahead and behind. This man was born
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.269#The same night as Hector, and was his comrade,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.270#As good with words as Hector was with a spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.271#He had their best interests at heart when he spoke:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.272#"Take a good look around, my friends. My advice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.273#Is to return to the city and not wait for daylight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.274#On the plain by the ships. We are far from our wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.275#As long as this man raged against Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.276#The Greeks were easier to fight against.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.277#I too was glad when I spent the night by the ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.278#Hoping we would capture their upswept hulls.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.279#That hope has given way to a terrible fear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.280#Of Peleus' swift son. He is a violent man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.281#And will not be content to fight on the plain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.282#Where Greeks and Trojans engage in combat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.283#It is for our city he will fight, and our wives.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.284#We must go back. Trust me, this is how it will be:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.285#Night is holding him back now, immortal night.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.286#But if he finds us here tomorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.287#When he comes out in his armor in daylight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.288#Then you will know what Achilles is,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.289#And you will be glad to be back in sacred Ilion---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.290#If you make it back, and are not one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.291#Of the many Trojans the dogs and vultures
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.292#Will feast upon. I hope I'm not within earshot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.293#But if we trust my words, as much as it may gall,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.294#We will camp tonight in the marketplace, where
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.295#The city is protected by its towers, walls,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.296#And high gates closed with bolted, polished doors.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.297#At dawn we take our positions on the wall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.298#In full armor, and so much the worse for him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.299#If he wants to come out from the ships and fight us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.300#For our wall. He will go back to the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.301#After he has had enough of parading
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.302#His high-necked prancers in front of the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.303#He will not have the will to force his way in.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.304#Dogs will eat him before he takes our town."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.305#And Hector, glaring at him under his helmet:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.306#"Polydamas, I don't like this talk
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.307#About a retreat and holing up in the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.308#Aren't you sick of being penned inside our walls?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.309#People everywhere used to talk about how rich
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.310#Priam's city was, all the gold, all the bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.311#Now the great houses are empty, their heirlooms
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.312#Sold away to Phrygia, to Maeonia, since Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.313#Has turned wrathful. But now---when the great god,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.314#Son of Cronus, has vouchsafed me the glory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.315#Of hemming the Greeks in beside the sea---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.316#Now is no time for you to talk like a fool.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.317#Not a Trojan here will listen. I won't let them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.318#Now hear this! All troops will mess tonight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.319#With guards posted and on general alert.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.320#If any of you are worried about your effects,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.321#You can hand them over for distribution!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.322#Better our men should have them than the Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.323#At first light we strap on our armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.324#And start fighting hard by the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.325#If Achilles really has risen up again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.326#And wants to come out, he'll find it tough going,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.327#For I will be there. I, for one,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.328#Am not retreating. Maybe he'll win, maybe I will.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.329#The War God doesn't care which one he kills."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.330#Thus Hector, and the Trojans cheered,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.331#The fools, their wits dulled by Pallas Athena.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.332#Hector's poor counsel won all the applause,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.333#And not a man praised Polydamas' good sense.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.334#Then the troops started supper.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.335#But the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.336#Mourned Patroclus the whole night through.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.337#Achilles began the incessant lamentation,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.338#Laying his man-slaying hands on Patroclus' chest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.339#And groaning over and over like a bearded lion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.340#Whose cubs some deer hunter has smuggled out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.341#Of the dense woods. When the lion returns,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.342#It tracks the human from valley to valley,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.343#Growling low the whole time. Sometimes it finds him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.344#Achilles' deep voice sounded among the Myrmidons:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.345#"It was all for nothing, what I said that day
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.346#When I tried to hearten the hero Menoetius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.347#Telling him I would bring his glorious son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.348#Home to Opoeis with his share of the spoils
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.349#After I had sacked Ilion. Zeus does not fulfill
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.350#A man's every thought. We two are fated
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.351#To redden the selfsame earth with our blood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.352#Right here in Troy. I will never return home
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.353#To be welcomed by my old father, Peleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.354#Or Thetis, my mother. The earth here will hold me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.355#And since I will pass under the earth after you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.356#Patroclus, I will not bury you until
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.357#I have brought here the armor and head of Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.358#Who killed you, great soul. And I will cut
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.359#The throats of twelve Trojan princes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.360#Before your pyre in my wrath. Until then,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.361#You will lie here beside our upswept hulls
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.362#Just as you are, and round about you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.363#Deep-bosomed Trojan and Dardanian women
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.364#Will lament you day and night, weeping,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.365#Women we won with blood, sweat and tears,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.366#Women we cut through rich cities to get."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.367#With that, he ordered his companions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.368#To put a great cauldron on the fire,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.369#So they could wash the gore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.370#From Patroclus' body without further delay.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.371#They put a cauldron used for heating baths
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.372#Over a blazing fire and poured in the water,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.373#Then stoked the fire with extra wood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.374#The flames licked the cauldron's belly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.375#And the water grew warm. When it was boiling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.376#In the glowing bronze, they washed the body,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.377#Anointed it with rich olive oil,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.378#And filled the wounds with a seasoned ointment.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.379#Then they laid him on his bed, covered him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.380#From head to foot with a soft linen cloth,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.381#And spread a white mantle above it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.382#Then the whole night through the Myrmidons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.383#Stood with Achilles, mourning Patroclus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.384#Zeus said to Hera, his wife and sister:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.385#"So you have had your way, my ox-eyed lady.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.386#You have roused Achilles, swift of foot. Truly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.387#The long-haired Greeks must be from your womb."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.388#And the ox-eyed lady Hera replied:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.389#"Awesome son of Cronus, what a thing to say!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.390#Even a mortal man, without my wisdom,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.391#Will succeed in his efforts for another man.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.392#How then was I---the highest of goddesses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.393#Both by my own birth and by marriage to you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.394#The lord and ruler of all the immortals---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.395#Not to cobble up evil for Troy in my wrath?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.396#While they spoke to each other this way,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.397#Thetis' silver feet took her to Hephaestus' house,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.398#A mansion the lame god had built himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.399#Out of starlight and bronze, and beyond all time.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.400#She found him at his bellows, glazed with sweat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.401#As he hurried to complete his latest project,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.402#Twenty cauldrons on tripods to line his hall,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.403#With golden wheels at the base of each tripod
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.404#So they could move by themselves to the gods' parties
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.405#And return to his house---a wonder to see.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.406#They were almost done. The intricate handles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.407#Still had to be attached. He was getting these ready,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.408#Forging the rivets with inspired artistry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.409#When the silver-footed goddess came up to him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.410#And Charis, Hephaestus' wife, lovely
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.411#In her shimmering veil, saw her, and running up,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.412#She clasped her hand and said to her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.413#"My dear Thetis, so grave in your long robe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.414#What brings you here now? You almost never visit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.415#Do come inside so I can offer you something."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.416#And the shining goddess led her along
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.417#And had her sit down in a graceful
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.418#Silver-studded chair with a footstool.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.419#Then she called to Hephaestus, and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.420#"Hephaestus, come here.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.421#Thetis needs you for something."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.422#And the renowned smith called back:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.423#"Thetis? Then the dread goddess I revere
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.424#Is inside. She saved me when I lay suffering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.425#From my long fall, after my shameless mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.426#Threw me out, wanting to hide my infirmity.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.427#And I really would have suffered, had not Thetis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.428#And Eurynome, a daughter of Ocean Stream,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.429#Taken me into their bosom. I stayed with them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.430#Nine years, forging all kinds of jewelry,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.431#Brooches and bracelets and necklaces and pins,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.432#In their hollow cave, while the Ocean's tides,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.433#Murmuring with foam, flowed endlessly around.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.434#No one knew I was there, neither god nor mortal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.435#Except my rescuers, Eurynome and Thetis.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.436#Now the goddess has come to our house.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.437#I owe her my life and would repay her in full.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.438#Set out our finest for her, Charis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.439#While I put away my bellows and tools."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.440#He spoke and raised his panting bulk
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.441#Up from his anvil, limping along quickly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.442#On his spindly shanks. He set the bellows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.443#Away from the fire, gathered up the tools
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.444#He had been using, and put them away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.445#In a silver chest. Then he took a sponge
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.446#And wiped his face and hands, his thick neck,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.447#And his shaggy chest. He put on a tunic,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.448#Grabbed a stout staff, and as he went out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.449#Limping, attendants rushed up to support him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.450#Attendants made of gold who looked like real girls,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.451#With a mind within, and a voice, and strength,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.452#And knowledge of crafts from the immortal gods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.453#These busily moved to support their lord,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.454#And he came hobbling up to where Thetis was,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.455#Sat himself down on a polished chair,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.456#And clasping her hand in his, he said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.457#"My dear Thetis, so grave in your long robe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.458#What brings you here now? You almost never visit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.459#Tell me what you have in mind, and I will do it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.460#If it is anything that is at all possible to do."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.461#And Thetis, shedding tears as she spoke:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.462#"Hephaestus, is there a goddess on Olympus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.463#Who has suffered as I have? Zeus son of Cronus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.464#Has given me suffering beyond all the others.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.465#Of all the saltwater women he singled me out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.466#To be subject to a man, Aeacus' son Peleus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.467#I endured a man's bed, much against my will.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.468#He lies in his halls forspent with old age,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.469#But I have other griefs now. He gave me a son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.470#To bear and to rear, the finest of heroes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.471#He grew like a sapling, and I nursed him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.472#As I would nurse a plant in my hillside garden,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.473#And I sent him to Ilion on a sailing ship
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.474#To fight the Trojans. And now I will never
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.475#Welcome him home again to Peleus' house.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.476#As long as he lives and sees the sunlight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.477#He will be in pain, and I cannot help him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.478#The girl that the army chose as his prize
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.479#Lord Agamemnon took out of his arms.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.480#He was wasting his heart out of grief for her,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.481#But now the Trojans have penned the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.482#In their beachhead camp, and the Argive elders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.483#Have petitioned him with a long list of gifts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.484#He refused to beat off the enemy himself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.485#But he let Patroclus wear his armor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.486#And sent him into battle with many men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.487#All day long they fought by the Scaean Gates
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.488#And would have sacked the city that very day,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.489#But after Menoetius' valiant son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.490#Had done much harm, Apollo killed him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.491#In the front ranks and gave Hector the glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.492#So I have come to your knees, to see if you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.493#Will give my son, doomed to die young,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.494#A shield and helmet, a fine set of greaves,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.495#And a corselet too. His old armor was lost
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.496#When the Trojans killed his faithful companion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.497#And now he lies on the ground in anguish."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.498#And the renowned smith answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.499#"Take heart, Thetis, and do not be distressed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.500#I only regret I do not have the power
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.501#To hide your son from death when it comes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.502#But armor he will have, forged to a wonder,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.503#And its terrible beauty will be a marvel to men."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.504#Hephaestus left her there and went to his bellows,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.505#Turned them toward the fire and ordered them to work.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.506#And the bellows, all twenty, blew on the crucibles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.507#Blasting out waves of heat in whatever direction
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.508#Hephaestus wanted as he hustled here and there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.509#Around his forge and the work progressed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.510#He cast durable bronze onto the fire, and tin,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.511#Precious gold and silver. Then he positioned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.512#His enormous anvil up on its block
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.513#And grasped his mighty hammer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.514#In one hand, and in the other his tongs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.515#He made a shield first, heavy and huge,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.516#Every inch of it intricately designed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.517#He threw a triple rim around it, glittering
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.518#Like lightning, and he made the strap silver.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.519#The shield itself was five layers thick, and he
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.520#Crafted its surface with all of his genius.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.521#On it he made the earth, the sky, the sea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.522#The unwearied sun, and the moon near full,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.523#And all the signs that garland the sky,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.524#Pleiades, Hyades, mighty Orion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.525#And the Bear they also call the Wagon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.526#Which pivots in place and looks back at Orion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.527#And alone is aloof from the wash of Ocean.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.528#On it he made two cities, peopled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.529#And beautiful. Weddings in one, festivals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.530#Brides led from their rooms by torchlight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.531#Up through the town, bridal song rising,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.532#Young men reeling in dance to the tune
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.533#Of lyres and flutes, and the women
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.534#Standing in their doorways admiring them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.535#There was a crowd in the market-place
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.536#And a quarrel arising between two men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.537#Over blood money for a murder,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.538#One claiming the right to make restitution,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.539#The other refusing to accept any terms.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.540#They were heading for an arbitrator
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.541#And the people were shouting, taking sides,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.542#But heralds restrained them. The elders sat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.543#On polished stone seats in the sacred circle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.544#And held in their hands the staves of heralds.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.545#The pair rushed up and pleaded their cases,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.546#And between them lay two ingots of gold
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.547#For whoever spoke straightest in judgment.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.548#Around the other city two armies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.549#Of glittering soldiery were encamped.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.550#Their leaders were at odds---should they
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.551#Move in for the kill or settle for a division
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.552#Of all the lovely wealth the citadel held fast?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.553#The citizens wouldn't surrender, and armed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.554#For an ambush. Their wives and little children
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.555#Were stationed on the wall, and with the old men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.556#Held it against attack. The citizens moved out,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.557#Led by Ares and Pallas Athena,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.558#Both of them gold, and their clothing was gold,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.559#Beautiful and larger than life in their armor, as befits
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.560#Gods in their glory, and all the people were smaller.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.561#They came to a position perfect for an ambush,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.562#A spot on the river where stock came to water,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.563#And took their places, concealed by fiery bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.564#Farther up they had two lookouts posted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.565#Waiting to sight shambling cattle and sheep,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.566#Which soon came along, trailed by two herdsmen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.567#Playing their panpipes, completely unsuspecting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.568#When the townsmen lying in ambush saw this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.569#They ran up, cut off the herds of cattle and fleecy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.570#Silver sheep, and killed the two herdsmen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.571#When the armies sitting in council got wind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.572#Of the ruckus with the cattle, they mounted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.573#Their high-stepping horses and galloped to the scene.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.574#They took their stand and fought along the river banks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.575#Throwing bronze-tipped javelins against each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.576#Among them were Hate and Din and the Angel of Death,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.577#Holding a man just wounded, another unwounded,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.578#And dragging one dead by his heels from the fray,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.579#And the cloak on her shoulders was red with human blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.580#They swayed in battle and fought like living men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.581#And each side salvaged the bodies of their dead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.582#On it he put a soft field, rich farmland
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.583#Wide and thrice-tilled, with many plowmen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.584#Driving their teams up and down rows.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.585#Whenever they came to the end of the field
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.586#And turned, a man would run up and hand them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.587#A cup of sweet wine. Then they turned again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.588#Back up the furrow pushing on through deep soil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.589#To reach the other end. The field was black
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.590#Behind them, just as if plowed, and yet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.591#It was gold, all gold, forged to a wonder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.592#On it he put land sectioned off for a king,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.593#Where reapers with sharp sickles were working.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.594#Cut grain lay deep where it fell in the furrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.595#And binders made sheaves bound with straw bands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.596#Three sheaf-binders stood by, and behind them children
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.597#Gathered up armfuls and kept passing them on.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.598#The king stood in silence near the line of reapers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.599#Holding his staff, and his heart was happy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.600#Under an oaktree nearby heralds were busy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.601#Preparing a feast from an ox they had slaughtered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.602#In sacrifice, and women were sprinkling it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.603#With abundant white barley for the reapers' dinner.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.604#On it he put a vineyard loaded with grapes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.605#Beautiful in gold. The clusters were dark,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.606#And the vines were set everywhere on silver poles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.607#Around it he inlaid a blue enamel ditch
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.608#And a fence of tin. A solitary path led to it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.609#And vintagers filed along it to harvest the grapes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.610#Girls, all grown up, and light-hearted boys
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.611#Carried the honey-sweet fruit in wicker baskets.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.612#Among them a boy picked out on a lyre
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.613#A beguiling tune and sang the Linos song
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.614#In a low, light voice, and the harvesters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.615#Skipped in time and shouted the refrain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.616#On it he made a herd of straight-horn cattle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.617#The cows were wrought of gold and tin
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.618#And rushed out mooing from the farmyard dung
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.619#To a pasture by the banks of a roaring river,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.620#Making their way through swaying reeds.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.621#Four golden herdsmen tended the cattle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.622#And nine nimble dogs followed along.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.623#Two terrifying lions at the front of the herd
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.624#Were pulling down an ox. Its long bellows alerted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.625#The dogs and the lads, who were running on up,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.626#But the two lions had ripped the bull's hide apart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.627#And were gulping down the guts and black blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.628#The shepherds kept trying to set on the dogs,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.629#But they shied away from biting the lions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.630#And stood there barking just out of harm's way.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.631#On it the renowned lame god made a pasture
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.632#In a lovely valley, wide, with silvery sheep in it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.633#And stables, roofed huts, and stone animal pens.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.634#On it the renowned lame god embellished
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.635#A dancing ground, like the one Daedalus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.636#Made for ringleted Ariadne in wide Cnossus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.637#Young men and girls in the prime of their beauty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.638#Were dancing there, hands clasped around wrists.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.639#The girls wore delicate linens, and the men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.640#Finespun tunics glistening softly with oil.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.641#Flowers crowned the girls' heads, and the men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.642#Had golden knives hung from silver straps.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.643#They ran on feet that knew how to run
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.644#With the greatest ease, like a potter's wheel
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.645#When he stoops to cup it in the palms of his hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.646#And gives it a spin to see how it runs. Then they
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.647#Would run in lines that weaved in and out.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.648#A large crowd stood round the beguiling dance,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.649#Enjoying themselves, and two acrobats
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.650#Somersaulted among them on cue to the music.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.651#On it he put the great strength of the River Ocean,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.652#Lapping the outermost rim of the massive shield.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.653#And when he had wrought the shield, huge and heavy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.654#He made a breastplate gleaming brighter than fire
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.655#And a durable helmet that fit close at the temples,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.656#Lovely and intricate, and crested with gold.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.657#And he wrought leg-armor out of pliant tin.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.658#And when the renowned lame god had finished this gear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.659#He set it down before Achilles' mother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.660#And she took off like a hawk from snow-capped Olympus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:18.661#Carrying armor through the sky like summer lightning.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.1#Dawn shrouded in saffron
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.2#Rose out of the deep water with light
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.3#For immortals and humans alike.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.4#And Thetis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.5#Came to the ships with Hephaestus' gifts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.6#She found her son lying beside
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.7#His Patroclus, wailing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.8#And around him his many friends,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.9#Mourning. The silvery goddess
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.10#Stood in their midst, took his hand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.11#Whispered his name, and said to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.12#"Achilles, you must let him rest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.13#No matter our grief. This man was gentled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.14#By the gods. But you, my son, my darling,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.15#Take this glorious armor from Hephaestus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.16#So very beautiful, no man has ever worn
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.17#Anything like it."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.18#She spoke,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.19#And when she set the armor down before Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.20#All of the metalwork clattered and chimed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.21#The Myrmidons shuddered, and to a man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.22#Could not bear to look at it. But Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.23#When he saw it, felt his rage seep
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.24#Deeper into his bones, and his lids narrowed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.25#And lowered over eyes that glared
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.26#Like a white-hot steel flame. He turned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.27#The polished weapons the god had given him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.28#Over and over in his hands, and felt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.29#Pangs of joy at all its intricate beauty.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.30#And his words rose on wings
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.31#To meet his mother:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.32#"My mother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.33#A god has given me these weapons---no
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.34#Mortal could have made them---and it is time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.35#I arm myself in them. But I am afraid
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.36#For Patroclus, afraid that flies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.37#Will infest his wounds and breed worms
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.38#In his body, now the life is gone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.39#And his flesh turn foul and rotten."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.40#The silver-footed goddess answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.41#"Do not let that trouble you, child.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.42#I will protect him from the swarming flies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.43#That infest humans slain in war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.44#Even if he should lie out for a full year
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.45#His flesh would still be as firm, or better.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.46#But call an assembly now. Renounce
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.47#Your rage against Agamemnon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.48#Arm yourself for war and put on your strength."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.49#Saying this, she multiplied his heroic temper.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.50#Then she dripped ambrosia and ruby nectar
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.51#Through Patroclus' nostrils, to keep his flesh firm.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.52#And then Achilles went along the shore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.53#Etched in sunlight, and shouted so loud
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.54#That not only the heroes came out, but all those too
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.55#Who had spent the war among the encamped ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.56#All the pilots and oarsmen and stewards and cooks---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.57#They all came to the assembly then, because Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.58#Who had abstained a long time, was back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.59#Limping along were the two veterans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.60#Battle-scarred Diomedes and brilliant Odysseus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.61#Badly wounded, using their spears as crutches.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.62#They came in and sat at the front of the assembly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.63#And behind them came the warlord, Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.64#Wounded himself (that spear thrust by Coön,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.65#Son of Antenor, in a hard-fought battle).
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.66#When all of the Greeks were gathered together,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.67#Swift-footed Achilles rose and addressed them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.68#"Well, son of Atreus, are either of us better off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.69#For this anger that has eaten our hearts away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.70#Like acid, this bitter quarrel over a girl?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.71#Artemis should have shot her aboard my ship
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.72#The day I pillaged Lyrnessus and took her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.73#Far fewer Greeks would have gone down in the dust
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.74#Under Trojan hands, while I nursed my grudge.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.75#Hector and the Trojans are better off. But the Greeks?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.76#I think they will remember our quarrel forever.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.77#But we'll let all that be, no matter how it hurts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.78#And conquer our pride, because we must.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.79#I hereby end my anger. There is no need for me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.80#To rage relentlessly. But let's move quickly now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.81#To get our troops back into battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.82#So I can confront the Trojans and test their will
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.83#To bivouac among our ships. They will more likely
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.84#Be thankful to rest their knees at day's end,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.85#If any of them gets out of this alive."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.86#He spoke, and the Greeks cheered.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.87#Peleus' great son had renounced his rage.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.88#And then the warlord Agamemnon spoke
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.89#From where he sat, without rising among them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.90#"Friends, Danaan heroes, servants of Ares---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.91#It is right to listen to one who stands to speak
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.92#And unseemly for even a skilled orator
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.93#To interrupt him. Even if he could
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.94#Make himself heard above the crowd
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.95#He would be at a disadvantage.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.96#What I have to say is for the son of Peleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.97#But I want each one of you to mark my words.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.98#There's not a Greek here who has not said
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.99#Spiteful things about me. But I am not to blame.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.100#Zeus is, and Fate, and the Dark Avenger,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.101#Who put a fit of madness on me, in public,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.102#That day I robbed Achilles of his prize.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.103#But what could I do? Gods decide everything.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.104#Zeus' eldest daughter is the goddess Atê,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.105#Who blinds everyone, a deadly power.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.106#She has delicate feet, not made for the ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.107#But for treading on the skulls of men as she
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.108#Afflicts them. Now and again she pins one down.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.109#Once she even blinded Zeus, who is, they say,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.110#The best of all, human or divine---even him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.111#Hera, being female, hoodwinked him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.112#On the day Alcmena was due to give birth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.113#To mighty Heracles in coronated Thebes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.114#Zeus had made this boast to all the gods:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.115#'Hear me, all you gods and goddesses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.116#While I say to you what is on my mind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.117#This day shall Eileithyia, midwife goddess,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.118#Bring to light a man who shall rule his land,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.119#One of the race of men who are of my own blood.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.120#And his lady, Hera, said to him craftily:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.121#'Liar. You will never make this story come true.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.122#I dare you to swear me a great oath, Olympian,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.123#That whoever shall fall between a woman's legs today,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.124#Provided he is one of your own bloodline,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.125#Really will rule over all his neighbors.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.126#She spoke, and Zeus did not see through this trick
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.127#But swore a mighty oath, blinded as he was.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.128#Hera shot down from the peak of Olympus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.129#And came to Argos in Achaea, where she knew
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.130#That the strong wife of Sthenelus, Perseus' son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.131#Was in the seventh month of her pregnancy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.132#This child Hera brought to light prematurely,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.133#But delayed Alcmena's, holding back the birth-spirits.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.134#Then she brought the news to Zeus herself:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.135#'Father Zeus, Lord of Lightning, important news:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.136#A man has been born who will rule the Argives,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.137#Eurystheus, born to Sthenelus, Perseus' son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.138#Of your own bloodline, fit to rule the Argives.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.139#This rankled deep in Zeus' heart. He seized Atê
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.140#By her rich bright hair, angry as can be,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.141#And swore a great oath that she would never again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.142#Come to Olympus or to starry heaven.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.143#Whirling her around he threw her from the sky
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.144#And she fell quickly to the fields of men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.145#The very thought of her would make him groan,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.146#Especially when he saw his own dear son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.147#Performing unseemly labors for Eurystheus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.148#That's how I felt when I saw great Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.149#Slaughtering Argives at the sterns of our ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.150#I could not forget Atê, who had made me blind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.151#Yes, I was blind. Zeus robbed me of my wits.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.152#But I want to make reparation, generously.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.153#Rouse yourself, and your soldiers, for battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.154#I am here to promise you all of the gifts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.155#Odysseus proposed in your hut last night.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.156#Or wait, if you wish, though you are eager for war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.157#While my men start bringing things from my ship
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.158#So you can see that my gifts will please your heart."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.159#And Achilles, strong and swift, answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.160#"Son of Atreus, most glorious Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.161#Whether you offer me gifts, as is right,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.162#Or keep them, is your concern. War is mine.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.163#Let's not waste any more time with speeches.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.164#We have work to do. I want each one of you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.165#To see Achilles fighting on the front line,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.166#Destroying the Trojan ranks with his spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.167#Have that image in mind as you fight your man."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.168#Odysseus, the wily thinker, answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.169#"Achilles, we know how good you are,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.170#But don't send our men out to fight the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.171#Without any food in their stomachs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.172#It's not going to be a short battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.173#Once the two sides close and start feeling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.174#The god's breath working inside them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.175#You should have our men go to their ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.176#For food and wine, and get their strength up.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.177#No one can fight all day until sunset
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.178#On an empty stomach. He may have the heart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.179#But as hunger and thirst creep up on him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.180#His arms get heavy and his knees go slack.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.181#But a man who has had his fill of food and wine
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.182#Can fight all day long with confidence,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.183#And stays strong until the last man quits. So come,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.184#Dismiss the troops and have them prepare their meal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.185#As for the gifts, let Lord Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.186#Bring them out here, so that the whole army
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.187#Can see them. This will warm your heart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.188#And he should stand and swear a public oath
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.189#That he has not gone to the woman's bed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.190#You, Achilles, should be gracious about this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.191#And then he should complete his amends
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.192#By feasting you richly, so you have all your due.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.193#Next time, son of Atreus, you will act more justly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.194#But there is no cause at all for offense when kings
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.195#Make their amends for unprovoked anger."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.196#And the warlord Agamemnon answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.197#"Son of Laertes, I am glad to hear your words.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.198#You have laid it all out just as it should be.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.199#I am ready and willing to swear this oath,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.200#And I will not perjure myself. But Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.201#Should wait here, eager as he is for war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.202#All should wait here assembled, until the gifts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.203#Come from my hut, and we swear solemn oaths.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.204#And I lay this charge upon you, Odysseus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.205#Choose the finest young men in all the army
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.206#And bring from my ships all the gifts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.207#We promised Achilles yesterday, the women too.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.208#And Talthybius will prepare a boar for me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.209#To sacrifice before the army to Helios and Zeus."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.210#But swift-footed Achilles answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.211#"Son of Atreus, most glorious Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.212#You should do all this at some other time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.213#When there is a break in the war---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.214#And when my rage is not so great.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.215#Hector has beaten these men to death,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.216#They are lying here mangled, he has the glory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.217#And you two want us to eat? If it were up to me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.218#I'd have the troops out there fighting unfed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.219#No food all day. When the sun goes down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.220#We can have a big meal, our shame avenged.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.221#Until then no food or drink will pass
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.222#My lips at least. My comrade is dead,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.223#Lying in my hut mangled with bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.224#His feet turned toward the door, and around him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.225#Our friends grieve. Nothing matters to me now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.226#But killing, and blood, and men in agony."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.227#And Odysseus, with his many wiles:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.228#"Son of Peleus, strongest of the Achaeans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.229#Far stronger than me, certainly, with a spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.230#Yet I might be better than you in council,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.231#Since I have lived longer and come to know more:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.232#Have the patience to listen to my words.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.233#Men quickly have their fill of battle, where
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.234#Moving blades litter the ground with stalks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.235#But there's very little to reap after Zeus decides
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.236#The price in human lives with a tip of his scales.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.237#We can't mourn the dead with our bellies.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.238#There are too many corpses, and more each day.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.239#When would anyone get time off from grief?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.240#No, we have to bury all our dead,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.241#Steel our hearts, and mourn them for a day.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.242#The survivors must remember to eat and drink
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.243#So we can go on fighting, day after day, until
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.244#We wear out the enemy's bronze skin.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.245#Let no man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.246#Hold back awaiting some other call.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.247#This is the call: There will be hell to pay
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.248#For any man who stays here with the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.249#Now let's move out. This is War."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.250#Odysseus spoke and was off, taking with him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.251#Nestor's sons Antilochus and Thrasymedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.252#Along with Meriones and Lycomedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.253#Meges the Doulichian, Thoas the Aetolian
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.254#And Melanippus. They all went straight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.255#To Agamemnon's hut. No sooner said than done:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.256#They brought out seven tripods, as promised,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.257#A dozen bright cauldrons and as many horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.258#And they quickly led out the women, faultless
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.259#In their handiwork, seven of these,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.260#And Briseis made eight. Then Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.261#Weighed out the full ten talents of gold
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.262#And led back the youths, who carried the gifts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.263#And set them in the middle of the assembly grounds.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.264#Agamemnon rose up, and Talthybius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.265#Whose voice was like a god's, stood beside him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.266#Holding a boar. The son of Atreus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.267#Drew the knife that hung by his sword scabbard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.268#And cut the boar's hairs, then lifting his hands to Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.269#He prayed, and all the Greeks sat silently,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.270#In the proper way, each man listening to his king
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.271#As he spoke in prayer, looking at the sky:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.272#"Be Zeus my witness first,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.273#Highest and best of gods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.274#And Earth, and Sun,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.275#And the Furies who underground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.276#Take vengeance on men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.277#Who break their oaths:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.278#I swear I never laid a hand on the girl Briseis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.279#Either to bed her or for anything else,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.280#But that she stayed untouched in my quarters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.281#If any of what I swear is false
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.282#May the gods torment me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.283#As a transgressor of oaths."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.284#And he slashed the boar's throat with ruthless bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.285#Talthybius whirled and threw the carcass
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.286#Into the open sea to be food for fish. Then Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.287#Rose and addressed the war-loving Achaeans:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.288#"Father Zeus, great is the blindness you send to men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.289#Else Atreus' son never would have roused my rage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.290#Or insisted on leading the girl away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.291#Against my will. Somehow it has pleased Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.292#That many Greeks should die.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.293#Now go to your meal, so we can join battle."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.294#The assembly broke up and the men scattered,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.295#Each to his own ship. The Myrmidons got busy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.296#With the gifts, bringing them to Achilles' ship.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.297#They stored it all in his huts, left the women there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.298#And proudly drove the horses to the herd.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.299#Briseis stood there like golden Aphrodite.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.300#But when she saw Patroclus' mangled body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.301#She threw herself upon him and wailed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.302#In a high, piercing voice, and with her nails
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.303#She tore her breast and soft neck and lovely face.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.304#And this woman, so like a goddess, cried in anguish:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.305#"My poor Patroclus. You were so dear to me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.306#When I left this hut you were alive,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.307#And now I find you, the army's leader, dead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.308#When I come back. So it is for me always,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.309#Evil upon evil. I have seen my husband,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.310#The man my father and mother gave me to,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.311#Mangled with sharp bronze before my city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.312#And my three brothers, all from the same mother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.313#Brothers I loved---they all died that day.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.314#But you wouldn't let me cry when Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.315#Killed my husband and destroyed Mynes' city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.316#Wouldn't let me cry. You told me you'd make me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.317#Achilles' bride, told me you'd take me on a ship
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.318#To Phthia, for a wedding among the Myrmidons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.319#I will never stop grieving for you, forever sweet."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.320#Thus Briseis, and the women mourned with her,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.321#For Patroclus, yes, but each woman also
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.322#For her own private sorrows.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.323#Around Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.324#The Achaean elders gathered, begging him to eat,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.325#But he refused them, groaning:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.326#"I beg you, my friends---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.327#Aren't any of you listening? Don't keep asking me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.328#To satisfy my heart with food or drink
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.329#Before it is time. My grief is too great.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.330#I will stay as I am and endure until sunset."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.331#And he waved them off. Only Atreus' two sons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.332#Remained with him, along with Odysseus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.333#Nestor, and the old charioteer, Phoenix,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.334#Trying to comfort him in his grief's extremity.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.335#But he could not be comforted. His heart would ache
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.336#Until he lost himself in war's blood-stained mouth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.337#Memories welled up and caught in his throat:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.338#"There was a time, my ill-fated, beloved friend,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.339#You would serve me a fine dinner in this hut,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.340#Deftly and quickly, while the army hurried
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.341#To bring war's sorrow to the horse-breaking Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.342#Now you lie here a mangled corpse, and my heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.343#Fasts from the food and drink that are here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.344#Out of grief for you. I could not suffer worse,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.345#Not even if I learned my father were dead,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.346#Who perhaps is weeping back in Phthia right now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.347#Because he misses his son who is off fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.348#On Trojan soil---for Helen, at whom we all shudder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.349#Not even if it were my son, Neoptolemus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.350#Who is being reared for me in Scyrus, if indeed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.351#My dear child is still alive. I had hoped,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.352#Until now, that I alone would perish at Troy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.353#And that you would return, and take my boy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.354#In your swift black ship away from Scyrus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.355#And show him all my things back home in Phthia.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.356#For Peleus by now must be dead and gone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.357#Or if he does still live he draws his breath in pain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.358#Clinging to a shred of life and always expecting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.359#The grim message that will tell him I am dead."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.360#He wept, and the elders added their laments to his,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.361#Each remembering what he had left at home.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.362#Zeus saw them in their grief and, pitying them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.363#Spoke to Athena these feathered words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.364#"My child, have you deserted your warrior?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.365#Do you no longer have any thought for Achilles?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.366#He is mourning his friend, sitting there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.367#In front of his upswept hulls. Everyone else
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.368#Has gone off to dinner, but he refuses to eat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.369#Go drip some nectar and savory ambrosia
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.370#Into his breast, so he will not weaken with hunger."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.371#Athena needed no encouragement. She flew
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.372#From the crystal sky like a shrill raptor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.373#And pounced on Achilles. The other Achaeans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.374#Were busy arming for battle. Athena distilled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.375#Nectar and ambrosia into Achilles' chest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.376#So that grim hunger would not weaken his knees,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.377#And then was gone, back to her father's house,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.378#While the Greeks poured out from their beached ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.379#Snow flurries can come so thick and fast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.380#From the cold northern sky that the wind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.381#That bears them becomes an icy, blinding glare.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.382#So too the gleaming, polished weaponry---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.383#The helmets, shields, spears, and plated corselets---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.384#All the bronze paraphernalia of war
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.385#That issued from the ships. The rising glare
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.386#Reflected off the coppery sky, and the land beneath
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.387#Laughed under the arcing metallic glow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.388#A deep bass thrumming rose from the marching feet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.389#And, like a bronze bolt in the center, Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.390#Who now began to arm.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.391#His eyes glowed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.392#Like white-hot steel, and he gritted his teeth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.393#Against the grief that had sunk into his bones,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.394#And every motion he made in putting on the armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.395#Forged for him in heaven was an act of passion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.396#Directed against the Trojans: clasping on his shins
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.397#The greaves trimmed in silver at the ankles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.398#Strapping the corselet onto his chest, slinging
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.399#The silver-studded bronze sword around a shoulder,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.400#And then lifting the massive, heavy shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.401#That spilled light around it as if it were the moon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.402#Or a fire that has flared up in a lonely settlement
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.403#High in the hills of an island, reflecting light
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.404#On the faces of men who have put out to sea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.405#And must watch helplessly as rising winds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.406#Bear them away from their dear ones.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.407#So too the terrible beauty of Achilles' shield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.408#A fire in the sky.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.409#He lifted the helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.410#And placed it on his head, and it shone like a star,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.411#With the golden horsehair Hephaestus had set
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.412#Thickly on the crest rippling in waves.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.413#He tested the fit and flex of the armor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.414#Sprinting on the sand, and found that the metal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.415#Lifted him like wings. He pulled from its case
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.416#His father's spear, the massive, heavy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.417#Spear that only Achilles could handle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.418#Made of Pelian ash, which the centaur Chiron
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.419#Had brought down from Mount Pelion and given
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.420#To Achilles' father to be the death of heroes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.421#Automedon and Alcimus harnessed the horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.422#Cinched the leather straps, fit the bits in their jaws
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.423#And drew the reins back to the jointed chariot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.424#Automedon picked up the bright lash
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.425#And jumped into the car, and behind him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.426#Achilles stepped in, shining in his war gear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.427#Like an amber Sun, and in a cold voice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.428#He cried to his father's horses:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.429#"Xanthus and Balius, Podarge's famous colts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.430#See that you bring your charioteer back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.431#Safe this time when we have had enough of war
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.432#And not leave him for dead, as you left Patroclus."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.433#And from beneath the yoke Xanthus spoke back,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.434#Hooves shimmering, his head bowed so low
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.435#That his mane swept the ground, as Hera,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.436#The white-armed goddess, gave him a voice:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.437#"This time we will save you, mighty Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.438#This time---but your hour is near. We
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.439#Are not to blame, but a great god and strong Fate.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.440#Nor was it slowness or slackness on our part
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.441#That allowed the Trojans to despoil Patroclus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.442#No, the best of gods, fair-haired Leto's son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.443#Killed him in the front lines and gave Hector the glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.444#As for us, we could outrun the West Wind,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.445#Which men say is the swiftest, but it is your destiny
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.446#To be overpowered by a mortal and a god."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.447#Xanthus said this; then the Furies stopped his voice.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.448#And Achilles, greatly troubled, answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.449#"I don't need you to prophesy my death,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.450#Xanthus. I know in my bones I will die here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.451#Far from my father and mother. Still, I won't stop
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.452#Until I have made the Trojans sick of war."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:19.453#And with a cry he drove his horses to the front.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.1#While the Greeks armed themselves by their ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.2#Around you, Achilles, the vortex of war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.3#And while the Trojans waited for them on the high plain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.4#Zeus ordered Themis to call the gods to assembly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.5#She ranged far along Olympus' ridgeline,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.6#Commanding them to come to the house of Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.7#They all came---every last river (except Ocean)
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.8#And every last spirit-woman who ever haunted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.9#A pretty copse, spring, or meadow---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.10#They all came to the house of Zeus in the clouds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.11#And sat in the stone colonnades that Hephaestus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.12#The master architect, had built for his father.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.13#They were all inside when Poseidon came up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.14#From the sea. Not even he could ignore
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.15#The goddess' call. He took a seat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.16#In the middle and asked Zeus his purpose:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.17#"Lord of Lightning,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.18#Why have you assembled the gods?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.19#Are you pondering the Greek-Trojan issue
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.20#Now that the fighting has flared up again?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.21#And Zeus, who masses the clouds:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.22#"Earthshaker, you know my purpose.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.23#I care for them, even though they die.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.24#Even so, I will stay in a crevice of Olympus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.25#And sit and watch and take my pleasure.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.26#The rest of you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.27#Can go out among the Greeks and Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.28#And help whichever side you please.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.29#If Achilles is the only one fighting out there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.30#The Trojans won't last a minute against him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.31#The very sight of him used to make them tremble,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.32#And now he is in his passion. I fear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.33#He may exceed his fate and demolish the wall."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.34#With these words Zeus unleashed the war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.35#And the gods joined the battle on different sides.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.36#On the Greek side were Hera and Pallas Athena,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.37#And Poseidon Earthshaker and Hermes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.38#The Helper, his mind sharp as needles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.39#And Hephaestus, who exuded strength
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.40#Though he limped along on his spindly legs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.41#The Trojans got Ares, his helmet flashing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.42#Apollo and the archer goddess Artemis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.43#Leto, Xanthus, and smiling Aphrodite.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.44#As long as the gods had been on the sidelines,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.45#The Greeks kept on winning: Achilles'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.46#Reappearance after his absence from the war
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.47#Had reduced the Trojans to spineless jelly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.48#They quivered helplessly when they saw the hero
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.49#Glowing in metal like the War God himself.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.50#But when the Olympians joined the human fray,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.51#Strife, who drives armies on, lifted her head,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.52#And Athena shouted, now by the trench,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.53#Then long cries from the beach where the surf pounded in.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.54#On the other side Ares responded,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.55#Roaring to the Trojans like a dark whirlwind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.56#On the city's height, then swooping down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.57#Along the Simois' banks and across Callicolonê.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.58#In this way the gods prompted the two armies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.59#To clash in combat. Strife exploded in each camp.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.60#Overhead, the Father of gods and men thundered,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.61#And Poseidon shook all the ground underneath,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.62#And the tremors climbed the steep mountain slopes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.63#Ida shuddered from her roots to her peaks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.64#Along with Troy herself and the Achaean ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.65#And in the world below the Lord of the Shades,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.66#Unseen Hades, leapt from his throne and shrieked,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.67#Terrified that Poseidon would crack open the earth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.68#And his halls would lie open to immortals and men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.69#The moldering horror loathed even by the gods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.70#Such was the force of the gods in collision.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.71#Opposite Lord Poseidon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.72#Stood Phoebus Apollo with fletched arrows.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.73#Taking on Ares was grey-eyed Athena.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.74#Up against Hera went Apollo's sister,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.75#Golden Artemis, the huntress with her bow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.76#Leto was countered by Hermes the Ally,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.77#And against Hephaestus rolled the deep river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.78#The gods call Xanthus, and men Scamander.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.79#So god went up against god.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.80#Achilles, though,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.81#Wanted to take on no one but Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.82#It was Hector's blood that he wanted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.83#To glut Ares' thick belly. But it was Aeneas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.84#Not Hector, that Apollo put up to fight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.85#Peleus' son, and gave him the courage to do so.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.86#Disguising himself as Lycaon, one of Priam's sons,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.87#And imitating his voice, Apollo said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.88#"What about all those boasts, Aeneas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.89#To the Trojan princes over your wine
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.90#That you would take on Achilles man to man?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.91#Aeneas had this to say in answer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.92#"Why ask me to do something I'd rather not---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.93#Fight the hero Achilles, son of Peleus?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.94#This won't be the first time I've faced his speed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.95#Once before he chased me off with his spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.96#From Ida, when he came after our cattle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.97#And wasted Lyrnessus and Pedasus. Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.98#Pulled me out then, put some zip in my knees,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.99#Or Achilles and Athena would have blasted me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.100#She was there in front of him lighting things up,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.101#Had him skewer Leleges and other Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.102#There's no way for a man to fight Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.103#Some god is always there to protect him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.104#Not that his spear doesn't fly straight by itself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.105#Or doesn't stop until it draws blood. But if a god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.106#Were to level the playing field, he wouldn't beat me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.107#Easily, even if he could brag he were solid bronze."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.108#And Zeus' son, Lord Apollo:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.109#"Why not pray to the gods and get on with it?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.110#You're a hero too. They say Zeus' daughter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.111#Aphrodite, bore you. He's from a lesser god,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.112#His mother being born from the Old Man of the Sea.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.113#Go right at him with your bronze, and don't let him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.114#Turn you back with all his taunts and threats."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.115#And he breathed strength into the field marshal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.116#Who strode to the front corseleted in light.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.117#Hera saw Anchises' son as he advanced
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.118#Through the throng to confront Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.119#She huddled her gods and said to them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.120#"Poseidon and Athena, what about this?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.121#There goes Aeneas in full blazing armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.122#Against Achilles, and it's Apollo who sent him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.123#Come on, then, and let's turn him back,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.124#Or let's one of us at least stand by Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.125#And give him strength, keep up his morale,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.126#So he'll know that the best of the gods love him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.127#And the others are worthless as wind, all those
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.128#Divinities who have protected Troy in this war.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.129#We've all come down from Olympus to fight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.130#So that Achilles will not be hurt by the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.131#For this one day. Later he must suffer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.132#Whatever Fate has spun at his birth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.133#If he doesn't hear this from the voice of a god,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.134#He may lose heart when a god attacks him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.135#Gods are daunting when they appear as they are."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.136#Poseidon Earthshaker answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.137#"There's no need to get all worked up, Hera.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.138#I would not wish to have the gods in conflict.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.139#Let's find some out-of-the-way lookout
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.140#And have a seat. Leave the war to men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.141#If Ares or Phoebus Apollo starts something,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.142#Or holds Achilles back and won't let him fight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.143#Then we can get involved in the action,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.144#And before long they will take themselves out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.145#And go back to the other gods on Olympus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.146#Overpowered by our invincible hands."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.147#So saying, the blue-maned god led the way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.148#To that high heap of a wall the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.149#And Pallas Athena had built for Heracles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.150#To help him escape from the sea monster
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.151#When it chased him from shore to plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.152#There Poseidon and his companions sat down,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.153#Their shoulders mantled with banks of cloud.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.154#Opposite them the other gods sat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.155#On Callicolonê's brows, around you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.156#My Lord Apollo, and Ares the Plunderer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.157#So the two sides sat, planning strategies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.158#But reluctant to commence hostilities,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.159#Even with permission from Zeus on high.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.160#The whole plain was filled with horses and men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.161#And the glint of bronze, and the earth trembled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.162#Under their tramping feet. As the troops advanced,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.163#Two heroes, eager for combat, moved forth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.164#To face each other in no-man's land,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.165#Anchises' son Aeneas and noble Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.166#Aeneas strode out first, helmet nodding
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.167#With every threatening step, war shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.168#Curved around his chest, bronze spear poised.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.169#Then Achilles began to close ground quickly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.170#A marauding lion has been hunted down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.171#By an entire village determined to kill him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.172#At first he ignores them and goes his way,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.173#But then one of the young men wounds him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.174#With a spearcast, and he gathers himself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.175#Crouching with mouth open, foam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.176#Flecking his teeth, and, growling deep in his chest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.177#He lashes his flanks and ribs with his tail,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.178#Working himself into a frenzy. Eyes glaring,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.179#He charges, carried forward by sheer passion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.180#And no one can tell if he will kill or be killed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.181#Thus were Achilles' mood and temper
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.182#As he closed in on great Aeneas.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.183#When they were within each other's range
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.184#The shining sprinter was the first to speak:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.185#"Aeneas, what are you doing out here in front?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.186#Have you taken a mind to fight with me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.187#Because you hope to inherit Priam's honor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.188#Among the Trojans? Even if you kill me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.189#Priam's not going to hand his kingship to you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.190#He has sons of his own, and he's not senile yet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.191#Or have the Trojans cut a deal for you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.192#Some choice real estate in orchards and plowland
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.193#For you to possess---if only you kill me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.194#You won't find that easy. If I remember right,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.195#I've chased you off with my spear once before,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.196#When I made you run from your cattle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.197#Careening down Ida's slopes. You never looked back,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.198#Ran all the way to Lyrnessus, which I then sacked
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.199#By the grace of Athena and Father Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.200#I took the women captive and led them off,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.201#But you were saved by Zeus and other gods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.202#I rather doubt he will save you today,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.203#Which you seem to be counting on. My advice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.204#Is for you to get back to your troops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.205#Before you get hurt. Fools learn the hard way."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.206#Aeneas had this to say in reply:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.207#"Don't think you can scare me off with words,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.208#Son of Peleus, as if I were a child.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.209#I can trade insults pretty well myself. We know
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.210#Each other's ancestry, each other's parents
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.211#From hearing the old stories. I've never seen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.212#Your parents, as you have never seen mine,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.213#But men say that Peleus is your father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.214#And Thetis, the saltwater woman, your mother.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.215#I boast that I am the son of great Anchises
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.216#And that Aphrodite is my mother.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.217#One set of these parents will mourn a dear son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.218#This day, because we're not going to settle this
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.219#With childish words and walk off from battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.220#But if you really do want to hear my story,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.221#You're welcome to listen. Many men know it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.222#Cloud-herding Zeus first bore Dardanus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.223#Who founded Dardania. Sacred Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.224#Was not yet a town on the plain. The people then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.225#All lived on the slopes of spring-dotted Ida.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.226#Dardanus' son was King Erichthonius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.227#Who became the richest of mortal men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.228#With three thousand horses in marshland pasture,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.229#All of them fine mares with tender foals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.230#The North Wind lusted for them as they grazed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.231#And mated with them as a blue-maned stallion.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.232#They conceived and gave birth to a dozen fillies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.233#Who could prance over a field of grain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.234#And not ever break a tasselled ear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.235#Who could bound over the sea's broad back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.236#With their hooves on the crests of the breaking waves.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.237#Erichthonius begot Tros to rule the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.238#And then from Tros three peerless sons were born,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.239#Ilus, Assaracus, and Ganymedes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.240#A godlike man, the most beautiful mortal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.241#Whom the gods snatched up because of his beauty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.242#To pour for Zeus and live with the immortals.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.243#Then Ilus had a son, peerless Laomedon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.244#And Laomedon begot Tithonus, Priam,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.245#Clytius, and Hicetaon, a scion of Ares.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.246#Assaracus begot Capys, and he Anchises.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.247#Anchises begot me, and Priam Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.248#These are my bloodlines, my proud lineage.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.249#But Zeus gives men their worth, or lessens it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.250#As he wills, since he is strongest of all.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.251#At any rate, let's stop talking like children
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.252#As we stand here in the heat of battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.253#We could trade a boatload of insults
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.254#And not reach the end. Men's tongues are glib,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.255#And we have words for everything.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.256#Whatever you say, you'll hear back again.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.257#Why should we wrangle like angry women
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.258#Quarreling in the street, all worked up,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.259#Saying anything, whether it's true or not?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.260#Battle is what I want, and nothing you can say
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.261#Can turn me back from it, man to man with sharp bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.262#Come on, let's see what it tastes like."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.263#With that, he drove his heavy spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.264#Into the metal circles of Achilles' shield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.265#Making it clang like a cymbal. Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.266#Tightened his grip and held the shield forward,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.267#Afraid that Aeneas' tree of a spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.268#Would come all the way through---a foolish notion:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.269#He had forgotten that the gods' gloried gifts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.270#Do not fail, nor do men easily foil them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.271#Aeneas' war spear broke through
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.272#Two layers of the shield, but the gold layer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.273#Hephaestus' special gift, stopped it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.274#And there were still two more, for the lame god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.275#Had welded five: two bronze, two tin,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.276#And the gold that stopped the ash-wood spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.277#Achilles now threw his long-shadowed spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.278#And hit the disk of Aeneas' shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.279#Beneath the outer rim, where the bronze
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.280#And oxhide ran thinnest. The Pelian ash
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.281#Shot right through. The shield gave a loud crack,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.282#And Aeneas held it away and cringed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.283#While the spear rocketed over his back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.284#And stuck in the earth, taking two circles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.285#Of the shield with it. Having dodged the missile,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.286#Aeneas rose in a state of shock at how close
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.287#The spear stood to him. Achilles drew his sword
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.288#And leapt at him with a bloodcurdling yell.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.289#Aeneas recovered quickly and picked up a stone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.290#That two men---as men go now---couldn't lift,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.291#But which he handled easily. In an instant
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.292#Aeneas would have hit the charging Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.293#With that stone, on his helmet or on the shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.294#That had just saved him, and Peleus' son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.295#Would have killed Aeneas in close combat,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.296#But Poseidon had all this in sharp focus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.297#And spoke in that moment among the immortals:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.298#"Alas for great-hearted Aeneas, who will now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.299#Be killed by Achilles and go down to Hades
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.300#Because he innocently obeyed Apollo,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.301#Who will do nothing to keep him from perishing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.302#Why should he, a guiltless man, now suffer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.303#For the woes of others, a man who has always
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.304#Pleased the gods in heaven with his offerings?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.305#Let us deliver him from the shadow of death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.306#Zeus will be angry if Achilles kills him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.307#For it is destined that Aeneas escape
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.308#And the line of Dardanus not be destroyed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.309#And disappear without seed---Dardanus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.310#Whom Zeus loved more than any of the sons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.311#Born from his union with mortal women.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.312#The son of Cronus has come to hate Priam's line,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.313#And now Aeneas will rule the Trojans with might,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.314#And the sons born to his sons in the future."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.315#The ox-eyed lady Hera replied:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.316#"As for Aeneas, Earthshaker, you should do
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.317#Whatever seems best, whether to save him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.318#Or have Achilles kill him, good man though he be.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.319#But we two, Pallas Athena and I,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.320#Have taken oaths among all the immortals
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.321#Never to ward off doom for the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.322#Not even when the whole city goes up in flames,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.323#Burned by the warlike youth of Greece."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.324#When he heard this, the earthquaking god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.325#Went his way through the battlefield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.326#And the moving spears until he came
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.327#To where Aeneas was, and glorious Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.328#He poured a mist over Achilles' eyes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.329#And drew his bronze-tipped, ash-wood spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.330#From the remnants of Aeneas' shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.331#And placed it before Achilles' feet.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.332#Aeneas he swung up from the ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.333#And sent sailing over row after row
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.334#Of heroes and horses in an immortal vault
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.335#From the god's hand, to land finally
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.336#On the perimeter of the battlefield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.337#Where the Caucones were arming themselves.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.338#Poseidon came up very close,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.339#And his words flew into Aeneas' ears:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.340#[340]
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.341#"Aeneas, what god hoodwinked you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.342#Into fighting with Peleus' high-hearted son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.343#A better man than you and dearer to the gods?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.344#Draw back whenever you encounter him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.345#Or else enter Hades before your doom.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.346#When Achilles has met his own destined death,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.347#Take courage and fight among the foremost,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.348#For no other Achaean will take your life."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.349#Poseidon left him with this revelation,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.350#Then quickly scattered from Achilles' eyes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.351#The magic mist. Achilles stared hard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.352#And, deeply troubled, said to himself:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.353#"This is a miracle right before my eyes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.354#My spear's on the ground, but the man I threw it at,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.355#Trying to kill him, is nowhere in sight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.356#It seems Aeneas really is dear to the gods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.357#I thought he was just boasting. To hell with him!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.358#He'll never have the guts to face me again,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.359#Glad as he must be to have gotten off this time.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.360#Well, I'd better call up our war-loving troops
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.361#And try my hand with the rest of the Trojans."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.362#He leapt along the ranks and called to each man:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.363#"Greeks! Close this ground and engage the enemy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.364#Man to man. I want to see some spirit!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.365#Do you think I can fight all those men by myself?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.366#Not even Ares, an immortal, or Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.367#Could close this battle's jaws alone.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.368#I'll shoulder as much of this as I can
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.369#And I don't think I'll come up short---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.370#Break right through their lines and ruin the day
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.371#Of any Trojan who comes close to my spear."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.372#That was his exhortation. Hector responded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.373#By promising the Trojans he would face Achilles:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.374#"Trojans! Don't be afraid of Peleus' son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.375#I could fight the immortals too---with words.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.376#It's harder with a spear. They're much too strong.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.377#Nor will Achilles accomplish all he says.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.378#He'll finish some and leave the rest half done.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.379#I'm going after him, even if he has hands of fire,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.380#Hands of fire, and fury like cold steel."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.381#Thus Hector. The Trojans lifted their spears
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.382#In response, and the battle was on. Amid the noise
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.383#Phoebus Apollo stood near Hector and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.384#"Do not challenge Achilles, Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.385#Wait for him in the throng to lessen the chance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.386#Of being hit by his spear or his sword close in."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.387#Hector fell back when he heard this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.388#Terrified by the voice of the speaking god.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.389#But Achilles sprinted into the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.390#With a cold yell. He first killed Iphition,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.391#Commander of a large contingent.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.392#This man was the son of Otrynteus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.393#A raider of cities, and a water nymph
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.394#Who bore him under snowy Tmolus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.395#In the rich land of Hyde. Achilles' spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.396#Split his head in two as he came on,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.397#And he fell heavily. Achilles crowed:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.398#"Lie there, son of Otrynteus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.399#Iphition, most formidable of men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.400#Dead here, born there---by Lake Gygaea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.401#Your ancestral land, near the Hyllus, isn't it?---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.402#Where the fish teem and the Hermus swirls."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.403#He spoke, but Iphition lay folded in darkness,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.404#And his body was soon shredded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.405#By the metal rims of Greek chariot wheels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.406#Next came Demoleon, Antenor's son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.407#A good soldier. Achilles pierced his temple
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.408#Through his helmet's bronze cheek pieces.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.409#The spear's business end sheared right through
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.410#Bronze and bone, scrambling the skull's contents
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.411#And stopping him cold.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.412#Hippodamas had jumped
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.413#From his chariot and was running the other way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.414#When Achilles' spear landed in his back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.415#He gasped and then bellowed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.416#the way a bull
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.417#Will bellow when dragged by young men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.418#Around Poseidon's altar in Helice,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.419#Making the Earthshaker beam with pleasure.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.420#Hippodamas' manly spirit left his bones.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.421#Achilles went next after Polydorus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.422#Priam's son. His father would not allow him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.423#To fight at all, since he was his youngest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.424#And the apple of his eye. He was the fastest too,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.425#And now he was childishly showing off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.426#Just how fast he was, running through the front lines
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.427#Until he lost his life. Achilles, the great sprinter,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.428#Hit him in the back as he flashed by,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.429#The spear going through just where the corselet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.430#Folded under the golden clasps of his belt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.431#And exiting just beside his navel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.432#He fell to his knees with a groan, and as he sank
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.433#In the dark mist, he clutched his bowels to him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.434#When Hector saw his brother Polydorus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.435#Sinking to the earth with his entrails in his hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.436#Everything turned hazy. No longer able
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.437#To pace the sidelines, he came at Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.438#His spear like a branch of flame. When Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.439#Saw who he was, he was exultant:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.440#"Here he is, the man who has reamed my heart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.441#Who has killed my noble friend. Not for long
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.442#Will we skirt each other in the battle lanes."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.443#And with a dark scowl he called to Hector:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.444#"Keep on coming. You're as good as dead."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.445#And Hector, without a trace of fear:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.446#"Don't think you can scare me off with words,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.447#Son of Peleus, as if I were a child.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.448#I can trade insults with the best of them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.449#I know you're really good, a lot better than me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.450#But it is up to the gods to decide whether I,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.451#A lesser man, will rob you of life with my spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.452#It's been proven to have an edge before."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.453#And he poised his spear and let it fly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.454#But Athena blew it away from Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.455#Wafting it back with the lightest of breaths
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.456#To fall at Hector's feet. Achilles charged
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.457#With a terrifying yell, his whole being
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.458#Inspired to kill. But the god Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.459#Whisked Hector away, as only a god can,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.460#And swirled fog around him. Three times
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.461#The shining sprinter charged with his bronze spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.462#And three times he struck nothing but deep mist.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.463#On his fourth, last charge he howled to the winds:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.464#"You've escaped death again, dog!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.465#Apollo saved you in another close call.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.466#You must pray to him every time you go out.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.467#But I'll get you yet, next time we meet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.468#If I have a god to help me too. For now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.469#I'll make do with whoever comes my way."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.470#And he put his spear through Dryops' neck,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.471#Dropping him at his feet. He left him there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.472#And took out Demuchus, Philetor's tall son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.473#First hitting him on the knee with his spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.474#Then finishing him off with his sword.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.475#Bias' two sons, Laogonus and Dardanus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.476#He shoved from their chariot, killing one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.477#With a spearcast, the other in close with his sword.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.478#And then Tros, Alastor's son, tried to clasp
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.479#Achilles' knees to see if he would spare him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.480#Take him captive and then let him go
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.481#And not kill him because they were the same age.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.482#He actually thought he would persuade him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.483#But this was a man with no gentleness in him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.484#A man with one purpose. As Tros clasped his knees
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.485#In supplication, Achilles shoved his sword
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.486#Down into his liver. The liver slid out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.487#Into Tros' lap with a clot of black blood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.488#And the world went dark as he expired.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.489#Achilles was already upon Mulius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.490#Putting his bronze javelin through one ear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.491#And all the way out the other, while,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.492#In almost the same motion, he struck
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.493#Agenor's son Echeclus full on the head
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.494#With his hilted sword. Echeclus' blood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.495#Warmed the whole blade, and death came
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.496#In an overpowering violet haze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.497#Deucalion was next, Achilles' spearpoint
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.498#Piercing his elbow just where the sinews join.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.499#His arm hung uselessly as he stood there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.500#Staring death in the face. Achilles closed in
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.501#And sliced into his neck, sending the head,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.502#Helmet and all, flying through the air.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.503#Marrow spurted up through his spinal cord,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.504#And then the corpse was lengthwise on the ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.505#Rhigmus, Peiros' peerless son, had come
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.506#From farm country in Thrace. Achilles' spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.507#Transfixed him and stuck in his belly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.508#He fell from his chariot, and as his driver,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.509#Areïthous, was turning the horses around
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.510#Achilles hit him in the back, the blow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.511#Pushing him from his car. The horses ran wild.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.512#Fire raging through a parched forest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.513#In a mountain valley, when the wind rises
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.514#And spirals the flames in every direction
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.515#Will give you some idea of Achilles' presence
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.516#As the black earth ran with blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.517#A team of broad-browed oxen has been yoked
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.518#And is now treading white barley
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.519#On a solid threshing floor. It does not take long
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.520#For the bellowing bulls to tread out the grain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.521#So the hooves of Achilles' horses trampled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.522#Dead bodies, shields. The chariot's axle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.523#And rails were splashed with blood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.524#Kicked up by the wheels and horses' hooves.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.525#But the son of Peleus pressed on to glory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:20.526#His invincible hands spattered with gore.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.1#When they came to the ford of Xanthus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.2#The eddying river that Zeus begot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.3#Achilles split the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.4#Half he chased
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.5#Toward the city, across the plain where yesterday
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.6#The Greeks had fled from Hector's shining rage.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.7#Hera, to slow this stampede of Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.8#Spread a curtain of fog before them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.9#The others swerved---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.10#And found themselves herded into the river.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.11#They crashed down into the deep, silver water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.12#As it tumbled and roared through its banks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.13#You could hear their screams as they floundered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.14#And were whirled around in the eddies.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.15#Fire will sometimes cause a swarm of locusts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.16#To rise in the air and fly to a river. The fire
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.17#Keeps coming, burning them instantly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.18#And the insects shrink down into the water.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.19#Just so Achilles. And Xanthus' noisy channel
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.20#Was clogged with chariots, horses, and men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.21#Achilles wasted no time. Leaving his spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.22#Propped against a tamarisk
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.23#And holding only his sword, he leapt from the bank
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.24#Like a spirit from hell bent on slaughter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.25#He struck over and over, in a widening spiral.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.26#Hideous groans rose from the wounded,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.27#And the river water turned crimson with blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.28#Fish fleeing a dolphin's huge maw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.29#Hide by the hundreds in the harbor's crannies,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.30#But the dolphin devours whatever it catches.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.31#Likewise the Trojans beneath the riverbanks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.32#When Achilles' hands were sore from killing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.33#He culled twelve boys live from the river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.34#To pay for the blood of dead Patroclus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.35#They were dazed as fawns when he led them out,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.36#Their hands bound behind them with the leather belts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.37#They had been wearing around their corded tunics.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.38#Achilles' men led them back to the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.39#And Achilles returned to his killing frenzy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.40#On the way back he met a son of Priam,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.41#Lycaon by name, running from the river.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.42#This boy Achilles had captured once before
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.43#In his father's orchard, where he had come one night
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.44#To cut fig saplings for chariot rails
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.45#But found Achilles' iron mask in his face.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.46#That time Achilles sold him, for a good price,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.47#To Jason's son on Lemnos, where he had shipped him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.48#A family friend, Eëtion of Imbros, had ransomed him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.49#For even more money and sent him to Arisbe.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.50#From there he managed to make his way home.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.51#For eleven days he celebrated with friends
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.52#His escape from Lemnos. On the twelfth day Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.53#Gave him back to Achilles, who would send him now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.54#Off again against his will, this time to Hades.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.55#He was all but naked when Achilles noticed him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.56#Having discarded helmet, spear, and shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.57#Because they made him sweat as he clambered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.58#Up from the river, and his knees were giving out.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.59#Achilles was indignant and said to himself:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.60#"What's this I see? The Trojan princes I've killed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.61#Are going to start rising from the moldering gloom,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.62#Judging from how this one has escaped his fate
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.63#After being shipped off to Lemnos and sold.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.64#All that grey sea couldn't keep him back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.65#Let's give him a taste of my spearhead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.66#And see whether he comes back from that
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.67#Or stays put in the teeming earth."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.68#And he waited. Lycaon aproached in a daze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.69#Intent on grasping his knees. All he wanted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.70#Was to wriggle away from death and black fate.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.71#All Achilles wanted was to run him through.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.72#His spear flashed out, but Lycaon, stooping
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.73#To touch his knees, ducked under it. The spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.74#Passed over his back and stuck in the earth,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.75#Quivering with desire for a man's flesh.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.76#Lycaon caught Achilles' knees with one hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.77#And held the pointed spear with the other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.78#And would not let go of either as he begged:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.79#"I am at your knees, Achilles. Pity me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.80#You have to respect me as your suppliant
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.81#For I tasted Demeter's holy grain with you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.82#On that day you took me captive in the orchard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.83#And sent me far from my father and friends,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.84#Sold into sacred Lemnos for a hundred oxen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.85#I ransomed myself for three times that. This morning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.86#Was my twelfth since getting back to Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.87#After many hard turns. And now Fate
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.88#Has put me in your hands again. Father Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.89#Must hate me to give me to you twice.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.90#My mother bore me for a shortened life,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.91#Laothoë, old Altes' daughter, Altes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.92#Lord of the Leleges, whose stronghold
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.93#Is steep Pedasus on the Satnioeis.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.94#Priam had his daughter as one of his wives,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.95#And we're her two sons, and you'll butcher us both.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.96#Godlike Polydorus you've already killed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.97#Got him with your spear as he led the charge.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.98#And now this is it for me. I doubt I can escape,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.99#Since it was some god who put me in your hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.100#But I'll say this too, and you can think it over:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.101#Don't kill me, since I'm not from the same womb
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.102#As Hector, who killed your gentle, valiant friend."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.103#Priam's glorious son spoke words of entreaty,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.104#But heard a voice without a trace of softness say:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.105#"Shut up, fool, and stop talking ransom.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.106#Before Patroclus met his destiny
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.107#It was more to my taste to spare Trojan lives,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.108#Capture them, and sell them overseas.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.109#But now they all die, every last Trojan
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.110#God puts into my hands before Ilion's walls,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.111#All of them, and especially Priam's children.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.112#You die too, friend. Don't take it hard.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.113#Patroclus died, and he was far better than you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.114#Take a look at me. Do you see how huge I am,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.115#How beautiful? I have a noble father,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.116#My mother was a goddess, but I too
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.117#Am in death's shadow. There will come a time,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.118#Some dawn or evening or noon in this war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.119#When someone will take my life from me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.120#With a spear thrust or an arrow from a string."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.121#He spoke. Lycaon's knees and heart went slack.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.122#He let go the spear and sat there, both hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.123#Outstretched. Achilles drew his honed sword
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.124#And struck near the collar bone. The whole blade
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.125#Sank into his trunk, and he fell prone to the ground,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.126#Black blood trickling out and wetting the dirt.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.127#Achilles slung him into the river by his foot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.128#And crowed over him as the current bore him off:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.129#"Lie there with the fish. They will lick the blood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.130#From your wound, your cold funeral rites. Your mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.131#Will not lay you on a bier and lament. No,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.132#Eddying Scamander will roll you out to sea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.133#And fish will dart up under the black ripples
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.134#And nibble at Lycaon's shining fat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.135#All of you Trojans will die like that,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.136#Die all the way back to Troy's sacred town
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.137#As I whittle you down from behind!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.138#Your river won't help you with his silver eddies,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.139#The water you've sanctified no doubt with bulls
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.140#And with live horses thrown into his pools.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.141#No, you'll all die, die ugly deaths, until you have paid
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.142#For the Greeks' loss, for Patroclus dead,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.143#Killed by the ships while I was away."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.144#As he spoke the river roiled in wrath
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.145#And pondered how to foil Achilles' efforts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.146#And save the Trojans from this pestilence.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.147#Meanwhile Achilles attacked Asteropaeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.148#Son of that Pelagon who was born of a river,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.149#The wide Axius, who lay with Periboea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.150#Eldest of the daughters of Acessamenus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.151#As Achilles charged him, Asteropaeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.152#Carrying two spears, stepped from the river
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.153#To face him, his courage coming from Xanthus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.154#Who was angry because of all the young men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.155#Cut down in his stream by Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.156#When they were within range of each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.157#The shining sprinter addressed Asteropaeus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.158#"Who are you, with the nerve to face me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.159#And where are you from? It's your parents' loss."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.160#Pelegon's glorious son answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.161#"Why ask about my lineage, son of Peleus?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.162#I come from Paeonian soil, a distant land,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.163#And I led its spearmen here to Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.164#Eleven days ago. My lineage
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.165#Is from wide-flowing Axius, whose river water
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.166#Flows loveliest on the face of the earth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.167#Pelegon was his son and my father, men say.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.168#Now let's do battle, glorious Achilles."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.169#It was a threat, and as Achilles raised high
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.170#His spear of Pelian ash, Asteropaeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.171#Who was ambidexterous, hurled both his spears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.172#One hit Achilles' shield but did not penetrate,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.173#Stopped by the layer of god-given gold.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.174#The other spear grazed his raised right forearm,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.175#Drawing a welt of black blood and sailing on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.176#Until it punched into earth unsatisfied.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.177#Then it was Achilles' turn, and he rifled his shaft
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.178#At Asteropaeus with murderous aim
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.179#But missed the man, the ashen spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.180#Boring into the bank up to half its length.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.181#Drawing his sharp sword from beside his thigh
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.182#The son of Peleus made a furious leap,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.183#And in the space of that leap, Asteropaeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.184#Tried once, twice, three times
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.185#To pull Achilles' spear from the bank
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.186#But only got it to quiver. The fourth time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.187#He tried desperately to break the shaft,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.188#But Achilles got to him first with a quick slash
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.189#Across his belly. His guts oozed out,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.190#And he went down gasping in darkness.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.191#Achilles jumped on his chest, and as he
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.192#Ripped off his armor, his boasts rang out:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.193#"Lie there like that! Sons of Zeus almighty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.194#Are too tough for even a river's offspring.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.195#You say you are born from a wide-flowing river,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.196#But I boast that I am descended from Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.197#My father rules the Myrmidons, Peleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.198#Son of Aeacus, and Aeacus came from Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.199#And just as Zeus is stronger than any river,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.200#Zeus' sons are stronger than any river's sons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.201#There's a great river beside you right now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.202#If he can help, but no one fights Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.203#Not even the great Achelous, not even Ocean,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.204#From whose deeps every river and sea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.205#Every spring and well flows. Even he fears
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.206#The lightning of Zeus and his crackling thunder."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.207#He pulled his bronze spear from the bank
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.208#And left Asteropaeus lying in the sand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.209#Quite dead. The dark water lapped at his body,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.210#And the eels and fish went to work on him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.211#Nibbling at the fat around his kidneys.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.212#Achilles' next move was to go after
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.213#The Paeonian charioteers along the river.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.214#They were in shock at what they had just seen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.215#Their best man and leader utterly destroyed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.216#By one strong swipe of Achilles' sword.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.217#He killed them easily---Thersilochus, Mydon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.218#Astypylus, Mnesus, Thrasius, Aenius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.219#Ophelestes---and with his blinding speed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.220#He would have killed more, had not the River,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.221#Assuming human semblance, called to Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.222#In a voice that came deep from his eddies:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.223#"Achilles, you are stronger and do more harm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.224#Than any man, for the very gods assist you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.225#If Zeus has allowed you to kill all the Trojans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.226#At least drive them from me, and do it on the plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.227#My beautiful streams are clogged with dead men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.228#I can no longer pour my waters into the sea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.229#Choked with corpses, while you blindly go on killing.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.230#Let it be. I am stunned, O warlord!"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.231#And Achilles, the great sprinter:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.232#"As you wish, sky-bred Scamander.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.233#But I will not stop killing these insolent Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.234#Until I have penned them all inside their city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.235#And taken on Hector. It's him or me now."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.236#And he leapt on the Trojans like a god.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.237#Then the swirling River spoke to Apollo:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.238#"Silverbow, child of Zeus! You have not kept
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.239#His stern commandment to stand by the Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.240#And aid them until the evening comes on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.241#And shadows darken the planet's deep soil."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.242#He spoke, and Achilles took a flying leap
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.243#Off the bank and came down in midstream.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.244#The River rushed upon him in full spate
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.245#And with all the force of its current swept along
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.246#The bodies of Achilles' many victims
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.247#And washed them ashore, roaring like a bull.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.248#At the same time he sheltered the living
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.249#In deep pools where his water flowed smooth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.250#Around Achilles the wall of water arched high
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.251#And pushed against his shield. He lost his footing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.252#And grasped at an elm, a tall, stately tree,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.253#But it fell uprooted, and tearing away the bank
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.254#Crashed with its thick branches into the water,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.255#Bridging the river's width. Achilles jumped out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.256#And, afraid now, began to sprint across the plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.257#But the great god wouldn't stop, chasing him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.258#With a black crest, determined to stop
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.259#The shining sprinter and save Troy from ruin.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.260#Achilles got about a spearcast ahead, swooping
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.261#Like a black eagle, the great raptor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.262#That is strongest and swiftest of all winged things,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.263#The bronze plate clanging on his chest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.264#As he leaned into his stride to escape the River
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.265#That followed him with a tremendous roar.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.266#A farmer has dug an irrigation ditch
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.267#To lead the water from a dark spring
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.268#Into his garden plots. Now, hoe in hand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.269#He is knocking out the dams from the channel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.270#And the water sweeps all the pebbles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.271#Along the bottom as it sluices down,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.272#And the man leading the water is left behind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.273#So the River kept overtaking Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.274#Fast as he was: Gods are stronger than men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.275#Whenever Achilles tried to make a stand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.276#And put up a fight (and see if perhaps
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.277#All the gods in heaven weren't pursuing him),
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.278#The sky-swollen River would pound
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.279#On his shoulders, and Achilles would jump.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.280#His morale was sinking. The strong current
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.281#Was wearing his knees out and cutting the ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.282#From under his feet. With a look at the sky,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.283#The son of Peleus cried out in distress:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.284#"Father Zeus, not a single god is stepping in
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.285#To save me from the River, pitiful as I am!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.286#If I escape this, I don't mind dying later.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.287#I blame my mother more than any deity,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.288#With her lullabies that I would meet my death
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.289#Under Ilion's walls, shot by Apollo.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.290#Better to be killed by Hector, Troy's best,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.291#One good man killed by another.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.292#As it is, I am doomed to a wretched death,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.293#Caught in this river, like a swineherd boy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.294#Swept away while crossing a winter torrent."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.295#Then Poseidon and Athena were with him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.296#In human form, clasping his hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.297#And pledging support, Poseidon saying:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.298#"Fear not, son of Peleus, nor be afraid.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.299#Two gods are with you, with Zeus' consent,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.300#Pallas Athena and I. It is not your doom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.301#To be vanquished by a River.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.302#He will soon relent, as you will see yourself.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.303#We have good counsel for you to accept.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.304#Do not cease from war until you have driven
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.305#All the Trojans who escape from your hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.306#Within Ilion's walls. When you have killed Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.307#Return to the ships. We grant you this glory."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.308#And they were off to the company of spirits,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.309#While Achilles, aroused by the gods' command,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.310#Turned toward the plain. It was all flooded now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.311#Awash with splendid gear and the floating corpses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.312#Of slain young men. Achilles sprinted hard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.313#Straight into the current, and the wide River
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.314#Could not hold him back. Athena's strength was in him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.315#But Scamander was still in spate, and raged
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.316#Even more strongly against Peleus' son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.317#Lifting his waters into an arching wave,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.318#He surged to a crest and called Simois:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.319#"Join with me, brother, to hold in check
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.320#This human's strength, or he will soon storm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.321#Lord Priam's great city. The Trojans can't stop him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.322#Help me beat him back now. Fill your currents
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.323#With water from your springs, rouse your torrents,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.324#Raise a great wave and make it churn and rumble
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.325#With logs and stones so we can stop this wild man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.326#Who thinks he can fight on par with the gods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.327#His strength will not help him, nor his beauty,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.328#Nor his splendid armor, which will lie deep in slime,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.329#And I will shroud his body in tons and tons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.330#Of pebbly sand, nor shall the Achaeans know
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.331#Where to find his bones, so deep the silt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.332#I will bury him in. This will be his monument.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.333#No need to heap a mound for his funeral."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.334#And he arched high over Achilles---boiling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.335#And seething with foam, blood, and corpses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.336#The livid surge of the sky-swollen River
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.337#Cresting and poised to overwhelm Peleus' son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.338#Hera shrieked, terrified that the great River
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.339#Would sweep Achilles away in its current.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.340#She called to her son Hephaestus and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.341#"Let's go, Clubfoot! We thought that you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.342#Were matched up with Xanthus. Hurry up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.343#And show your fire here, and I'll rouse up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.344#Onshore winds from the west and south
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.345#To drive your flames over the Trojan dead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.346#And burn them and their gear to a crisp.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.347#You burn the trees around Xanthus' banks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.348#And surround him with fire. Don't back off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.349#No matter how he whines or threatens.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.350#Keep the pressure on until you hear me shout."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.351#So Hephaestus kindled his fire,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.352#And it swept across the plain, burning the dead,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.353#The many corpses left by Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.354#And evaporating the glittering water.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.355#Late in the summer, the North Wind
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.356#Dries out a freshly watered orchard,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.357#And the man who tills the orchard is glad.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.358#The plain was parched, and the dead consumed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.359#Then the Fire moved toward the River.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.360#The elms, the willows, and the tamarisks burned,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.361#The lotus, the rushes, and the galingale
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.362#That grew lush on the beautiful riverbanks, burned.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.363#The eels and the fish in the eddying pools,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.364#Tortured by the heat Hephaestus concocted,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.365#Plunged and darted through the glassy currents.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.366#The River itself burned, and pleaded with the god:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.367#"Hephaestus, no god can oppose you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.368#And I will not fight you in your blaze of fire.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.369#Stop! As for the Trojans, let bright Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.370#Drive them from Ilion. I will not help or hinder."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.371#And as he spoke, his water seethed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.372#As if in a cauldron set on a fire
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.373#Stoked with kindling, boiling to melt
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.374#Rich hog fat, and bubbling over.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.375#The River burned, and his water boiled,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.376#Impossible for it to flow any further
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.377#In the tormenting blast of Hephaestus' heat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.378#Then his words rose up on wings to Hera:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.379#"Hera, why has your son singled me out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.380#For punishment. I am not so guilty,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.381#In your eyes, as Troy's other allies.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.382#But I will stop if you order me to.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.383#Make him stop too. And I will swear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.384#Not to ward off Ilion's doom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.385#On that day when Troy goes up in flames,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.386#Burned by the warlike youth of Greece."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.387#Ivory-armed Hera heard his plea
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.388#And spoke to her darling son Hephaestus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.389#"Hephaestus, my glory, hold back. It is not right
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.390#To attack an immortal for the sake of a mortal,"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.391#So Hephaestus quenched his fire,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.392#And the river Xanthus flowed again,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.393#But its fury was quelled. Hera,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.394#Though angry herself, had calmed these two.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.395#The other gods, though, were at each others' throats,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.396#Clashing like contrary winds. At the force
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.397#Of their collision the earth clanged like a cymbal
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.398#And the sky blared like a trumpet. Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.399#Sitting on Olympus, took it all in
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.400#And laughed with delight at the spectacle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.401#Of the gods closing with each other in combat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.402#Ares began with an assault on Athena,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.403#Landing in front of her with a bronze spear:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.404#"What are you doing now, dogfly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.405#Setting the gods against each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.406#Whatever way your high spirits dictate.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.407#Remember when you goaded on Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.408#To wound me? With everyone watching
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.409#You guided the spear into my noble flesh.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.410#You'll pay the price now for what you did then."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.411#And he stabbed at her tasselled aegis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.412#Which not even Zeus' lightning can pierce.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.413#Athena backpedalled from his bloody snout
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.414#And scooped up a jagged piece of black granite
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.415#That lay on the plain, a huge boundary stone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.416#From days gone by. It flew from her sculpted hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.417#And caught Ares on the neck. His knees buckled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.418#And he went down, covering a good acre or two,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.419#Hair grimed with dust, armor clattering around him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.420#Athena broke into a laugh and crowed:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.421#"You simpleton!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.422#You still haven't learned that I'm too strong
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.423#For you, or you wouldn't try to match up with me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.424#Maybe this is what your mother wanted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.425#When she cursed you for abandoning the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.426#And giving aid and comfort to the Trojans."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.427#And while she turned her luminous eyes away,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.428#Aphrodite came up and led him off by the hand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.429#Groaning heavily. He was barely conscious.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.430#Ivory-armed Hera took notice of this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.431#And her words took wing to Pallas Athena:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.432#"Mystic daughter of Zeus, that bloated tick
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.433#Is leading Ares out of battle. Get on her!"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.434#Athena was only too glad to comply,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.435#Charging Aphrodite and punching her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.436#In the breast with her clenched fist. Aphrodite
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.437#Collapsed in a heap, taking Ares down with her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.438#The two of them lay on the teeming sod,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.439#And Athena's boast flew up to the sky:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.440#"May everyone who fights for Troy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.441#Against the Greeks wind up like this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.442#And may they all be as brave as Aphrodite was
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.443#When she helped Ares and confronted me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.444#We would have ended this war a long time ago
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.445#And destroyed Ilion's foundation stone."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.446#This brought a smile to Hera's lips.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.447#Then Lord Poseidon spoke to Apollo:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.448#"Phoebus, why are we two holding back?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.449#It's not fitting. All the others have started.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.450#More shame on us if we return to Olympus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.451#And cross Zeus' bronze threshold without fighting.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.452#You start, since you're younger. It would not be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.453#Proper for me, since I am older and know more.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.454#Has your mind gone soft? Don't you remember
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.455#The suffering we two, alone of all the gods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.456#Endured at Ilion that time we came here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.457#From Zeus' side and served proud Laomedon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.458#For a year at fixed wages. He was our boss,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.459#And I built for the Trojans their city wall,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.460#Wide and beautiful, to make Ilion invulnerable.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.461#And you, Phoebus, herded their cattle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.462#In the wooded foothills of ridged Mount Ida.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.463#But when the year was up and the time came
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.464#For us to be paid, Laomedon outrageously
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.465#Robbed us of our wages, threatening
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.466#To bind us hand and foot and sell us off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.467#To distant islands, and to lop off our ears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.468#So back we went, angry and disgruntled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.469#Over the wages he promised but did not pay.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.470#It is his people you are favoring now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.471#When you should instead be working with us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.472#For the utter destruction of these insolent Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.473#Together with their children and blushing wives."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.474#And Apollo, Lord of the Distances:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.475#"Earthshaker, you would call me imprudent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.476#If I fought with you for the sake of mortals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.477#Pitiful creatures who like leaves on a tree
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.478#Flame briefly to life, eat the fruit of the fields,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.479#Then wither and die. No, we should desist
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.480#Immediately and let them fight on their own."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.481#And Apollo withdrew, too well-bred
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.482#To slug it out with his paternal uncle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.483#But his hellcat sister Artemis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.484#Queen of wild things, reviled him mercilessly:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.485#"Running away, Apollo? What a collapse!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.486#Poseidon can claim an easy victory now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.487#That bow you carry is as worthless as wind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.488#Don't let me catch you bragging again,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.489#As you always used to in our father's house,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.490#That you would take on Poseidon in open combat."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.491#Apollo turned away without a word,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.492#But Zeus' august wife was furious with her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.493#"Do you think you can cross me like this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.494#You bitch? I'm not an easy opponent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.495#For the likes of you, even if you do
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.496#Carry a bow---Zeus' little lioness,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.497#With license to kill whatever woman you please.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.498#You'd do better to hunt wild game, deer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.499#In the woods, than tangle with your betters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.500#But if you want a taste of war, you might as well
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.501#Find out how undermatched you are against me."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.502#She seized her wrists with her left hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.503#And ripped the bow from her shoulders
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.504#With her right, and with a smile on her face
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.505#Used these weapons to beat her about the ears
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.506#As she twisted and squirmed, spilling the arrows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.507#Out of her quiver. She finally got away
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.508#And fled from Hera, weeping, as a dove
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.509#Flies from a falcon into a cleft in the rock,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.510#Leaving her bow and arrows on the ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.511#At this, Hermes turned to Leto and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.512#"Tell you what, Leto, I won't fight with you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.513#Zeus' wives are pretty tough customers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.514#You have my permission to boast openly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.515#That you have beaten the daylights out of me."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.516#Thus Hermes, and Leto gathered up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.517#Her daughter's curved bow and arrows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.518#From the swirling dust, and then withdrew.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.519#Artemis crossed Zeus' bronze threshold
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.520#And sat down sobbing on her father's lap,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.521#Her fragrant robe fluttering. He held her tight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.522#And laughing pleasantly, asked her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.523#"Which god has done this to you, child?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.524#Outrageous. It's not as if you would misbehave."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.525#And the huntress, ribbons in her hair:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.526#"Your wife Hera beat me up, father.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.527#She's always causing trouble among the gods."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.528#And while they talked in heaven,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.529#Phoebus Apollo entered sacred Ilion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.530#Afraid that the Greeks would breach its wall
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.531#And exceed their destiny that very day.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.532#The other immortals went to Olympus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.533#Some of them angry and some jubilant,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.534#And they sat down around their father,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.535#The Dark Cloud.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.536#Meanwhile, Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.537#Was still killing Trojans, both men and horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.538#When a city burns, the smoke rises
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.539#To the wide heavens, and the gods' wrath
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.540#Fans the fire and drives it on.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.541#Everyone suffers, many grievously.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.542#Such was the suffering Achilles caused the Trojans.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.543#Old Priam stood on Troy's sacred wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.544#He saw Achilles as a prodigious force
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.545#Before whom the Trojans were being driven
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.546#Helplessly. Groaning, he climbed down to the ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.547#And called to the gatekeepers along the wall:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.548#"Hold the gates wide open until the army
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.549#Can run inside the city. Achilles is here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.550#Driving them on, and I fear the worst.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.551#When they are all inside and can rest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.552#Close the double doors tight. I dread the thought
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.553#Of that monster leaping inside the wall."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.554#He spoke, they thrust back the bars,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.555#And light poured from the gates. Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.556#Leapt out to keep Achilles from Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.557#The Trojans were streaming toward the city's high walls,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.558#Parched with thirst and white with dust from the plain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.559#With Achilles at their backs with his spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.560#Maniacal in his rage and lust for glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.561#The Greeks would have taken Troy right then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.562#Had not Apollo lifted Antenor's son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.563#Agenor, to one bright, peerless moment.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.564#He put into his heart the fortitude
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.565#To defend himself from Death's heavy hands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.566#Then stood nearby, leaning on the oak tree
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.567#And enfolded in mist. So when Agenor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.568#Caught sight of Achilles, sacker of cities,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.569#He halted. His heart brooded darkly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.570#And with a sense of great oppression he said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.571#"Now I'm in for it. If I run from Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.572#The way the others are, like panicked animals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.573#He'll catch me anyway and butcher me like a lamb.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.574#But what if I let these others go,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.575#Let them be driven by Achilles, and run myself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.576#Away from the wall, toward the Ilean plain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.577#Until I reach the foothills of Ida
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.578#And hide out in the thickets? Toward evening
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.579#I could bathe in the river, cool off,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.580#And maybe make it back to Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.581#Why am I talking to myself like this?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.582#It's all over if he spots me turning off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.583#Away from the city and toward the plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.584#He'll chase me down with his great speed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.585#And then there'll be no way to escape from death,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.586#Since he is far stronger than any man alive.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.587#Then why not face him in front of the city?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.588#His skin is not impervious to bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.589#And he only has one life in him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.590#Everyone says he is human. It's just that
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.591#Zeus, son of Cronus, gives him glory."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.592#And he crouched to await Achilles' onset,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.593#Heart pumping, ready for battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.594#A leopard steps out from the deep bush
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.595#In full sight of a hunter, completely unafraid.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.596#Even if she hears the hounds baying,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.597#She will not turn tail and run, and even if
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.598#The human is lucky enough to strike first
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.599#And hit her with his spear, she will not give up,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.600#But will fight on with the spear in her body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.601#Until she is killed---or gets her claws in him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.602#So too Agenor, lord Antenor's son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.603#Would not give up until he had tested Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.604#He poised his balanced shield before him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.605#Took aim at Achilles, and shouted:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.606#"I'll bet you hope to capture Troy today,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.607#Don't you, Achilles the Splendid?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.608#You fool! There's still a lot of sorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.609#To be endured for her sake, and within her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.610#Our many brave men standing before
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.611#Our parents, our wives, and our sons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.612#And protecting Ilion. No, it is you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.613#Who will meet your doom today,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.614#I don't care how great a warrior you are."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.615#And the javelin flew from his heavy hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.616#Hitting Achilles' shin just beneath the knee.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.617#The newly-forged tin greave clanged loudly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.618#And the bronze spearpoint ricocheted off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.619#The armor that the god had given him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.620#It was Achilles' turn to charge Agenor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.621#But Apollo denied him victory,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.622#Snatching Agenor off in a curtain of mist,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.623#And escorting him softly out of battle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.624#Then, with a ruse, Apollo got the son of Peleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.625#Away from the Trojan army. Likening himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.626#To Agenor in every detail, he stood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.627#Just before Achilles, who gave chase,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.628#Pursuing him across the plain, then turning him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.629#Along the banks of the swirling Scamander.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.630#All the while Apollo, beguiling him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.631#Stayed just out of reach, and Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.632#With his footspeed, thought he would catch him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.633#This bought time for the panicked Trojans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.634#To swarm gratefully into the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.635#They no longer had the will to wait for each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.636#Outside the city walls to see who had made it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.637#And who had died in battle. Everyone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:21.638#Whose legs could carry him stampeded in.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.1#Everywhere you looked in Troy, exhausted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.2#Soldiers, glazed with sweat like winded deer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.3#Leaned on the walls, cooling down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.4#And slaking their thirst.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.5#Outside, the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.6#Formed up close to the wall, locking their shields.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.7#In the dead air between the Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.8#And Troy's Western Gate, Destiny
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.9#Had Hector pinned, waiting for death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.10#Then Apollo called back to Achilles:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.11#"Son of Peleus, you're fast on your feet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.12#But you'll never catch me, man chasing god.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.13#Or are you too raging mad to notice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.14#I'm a god? Don't you care about fighting
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.15#The Trojans any more? You've chased them back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.16#Into their town, but now you've veered off here.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.17#You'll never kill me. You don't hold my doom."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.18#And the shining sprinter, Achilles:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.19#"That was a dirty trick, Apollo,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.20#Turning me away from the wall like that!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.21#I could have ground half of Troy face down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.22#In the dirt! Now you've robbed me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.23#Of my glory and saved them easily
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.24#Because you have no retribution to fear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.25#I swear, I'd make you pay if I could!"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.26#His mind opened to the clear space before him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.27#And he was off toward the town, moving
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.28#Like a thoroughbred stretching it out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.29#Over the plain for the final sprint home---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.30#Achilles, lifting his knees as he lengthened his stride.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.31#Priam saw him first, with his old man's eyes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.32#A single point of light on Troy's dusty plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.33#Sirius rises late in the dark, liquid sky
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.34#On summer nights, star of stars,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.35#Orion's Dog they call it, brightest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.36#Of all, but an evil portent, bringing heat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.37#And fevers to suffering humanity.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.38#Achilles' bronze gleamed like this as he ran.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.39#And the old man groaned, and beat his head
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.40#With his hands, and stretched out his arms
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.41#To his beloved son, Hector, who had
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.42#Taken his stand before the Western Gate,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.43#Determined to meet Achilles in combat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.44#Priam's voice cracked as he pleaded:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.45#"Hector, my boy, you can't face Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.46#Alone like that, without any support---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.47#You'll go down in a minute. He's too much
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.48#For you, son, he won't stop at anything!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.49#O, if only the gods loved him as I do:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.50#Vultures and dogs would be gnawing his corpse.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.51#Then some grief might pass from my heart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.52#So many fine sons he's taken from me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.53#Killed or sold them as slaves in the islands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.54#Two of them now, Lycaon and Polydorus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.55#I can't see with the Trojans safe in town,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.56#Laothoë's boys. If the Greeks have them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.57#We'll ransom them with the gold and silver
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.58#Old Altes gave us. But if they're dead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.59#And gone down to Hades, there will be grief
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.60#For myself and the mother who bore them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.61#The rest of the people won't mourn so much
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.62#Unless you go down at Achilles' hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.63#So come inside the wall, my boy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.64#Live to save the men and women of Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.65#Don't just hand Achilles the glory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.66#And throw your life away. Show some pity for me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.67#Before I go out of my mind with grief
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.68#And Zeus finally destroys me in my old age,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.69#After I have seen all the horrors of war---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.70#My sons butchered, my daughters dragged off,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.71#Raped, bedchambers plundered, infants
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.72#Dashed to the ground in this terrible war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.73#My sons' wives abused by murderous Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.74#And one day some Greek soldier will stick me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.75#With cold bronze and draw the life from my limbs,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.76#And the dogs that I fed at my table,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.77#My watchdogs, will drag me outside and eat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.78#My flesh raw, crouched in my doorway, lapping
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.79#My blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.80#When a young man is killed in war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.81#Even though his body is slashed with bronze,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.82#He lies there beautiful in death, noble.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.83#But when the dogs maraud an old man's head,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.84#Griming his white hair and beard and private parts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.85#There's no human fate more pitiable."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.86#And the old man pulled the white hair from his head,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.87#But did not persuade Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.88#His mother then,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.89#Wailing, sobbing, laid open her bosom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.90#And holding out a breast spoke through her tears:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.91#"Hector, my child, if ever I've soothed you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.92#With this breast, remember it now, son, and
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.93#Have pity on me. Don't pit yourself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.94#Against that madman. Come inside the wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.95#If Achilles kills you I will never
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.96#Get to mourn you laid out on a bier, O
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.97#My sweet blossom, nor will Andromache,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.98#Your beautiful wife, but far from us both
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.99#Dogs will eat your body by the Greek ships."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.100#So the two of them pleaded with their son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.101#But did not persuade him or touch his heart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.102#Hector held his ground as Achilles' bulk
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.103#Loomed larger. He waited as a snake waits,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.104#Tense and coiled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.105#As a man approaches
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.106#Its lair in the mountains,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.107#Venom in its fangs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.108#And poison in its heart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.109#Glittering eyes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.110#Glaring from the rocks:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.111#So Hector waited, leaning his polished shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.112#Against one of the towers in Troy's bulging wall,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.113#But his heart was troubled with brooding thoughts:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.114#"Now what? If I take cover inside,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.115#Polydamas will be the first to reproach me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.116#He begged me to lead the Trojans back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.117#To the city on that black night when Achilles rose.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.118#But I wouldn't listen, and now I've destroyed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.119#Half the army through my recklessness.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.120#I can't face the Trojan men and women now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.121#Can't bear to hear some lesser man say,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.122#'Hector trusted his strength and lost the army.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.123#That's what they'll say. I'll be much better off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.124#Facing Achilles, either killing him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.125#Or dying honorably before the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.126#But what if I lay down all my weapons,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.127#Bossed shield, heavy helmet, prop my spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.128#Against the wall, and go meet Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.129#Promise him we'll surrender Helen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.130#And everything Paris brought back with her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.131#In his ships' holds to Troy---that was the beginning
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.132#Of this war---give all of it back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.133#To the sons of Atreus and divide
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.134#Everything else in the town with the Greeks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.135#And swear a great oath not to hold
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.136#Anything back, but share it all equally,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.137#All the treasure in Troy's citadel.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.138#But why am I talking to myself like this?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.139#I can't go out there unarmed. Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.140#Will cut me down in cold blood if I take off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.141#My armor and go out to meet him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.142#Naked like a woman. This is no time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.143#For talking, the way a boy and a girl
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.144#Whisper to each other from oak tree or rock,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.145#A boy and a girl with all their sweet talk.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.146#Better to lock up in mortal combat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.147#As soon as possible and see to whom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.148#God on Olympus grants the victory."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.149#Thus Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.150#And Achilles closed in
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.151#Like the helmeted God of War himself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.152#The ash-wood spear above his right shoulder
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.153#Rocking in the light that played from his bronze
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.154#In gleams of fire and the rising sun.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.155#And when Hector saw it he lost his nerve,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.156#Panicked, and ran, leaving the gates behind,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.157#With Achilles on his tail, confident in his speed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.158#You have seen a falcon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.159#In a long, smooth dive
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.160#Attack a fluttering dove
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.161#Far below in the hills.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.162#The falcon screams,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.163#Swoops, and plunges
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.164#In its lust for prey.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.165#So Achilles swooped and Hector trembled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.166#In the shadow of Troy's wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.167#Running hard,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.168#They passed Lookout Rock and the windy fig tree,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.169#Following the loop of the wagon road.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.170#They came to the wellsprings of eddying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.171#Scamander, two beautiful pools, one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.172#Boiling hot with steam rising up,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.173#The other flowing cold even in summer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.174#Cold as freezing sleet, cold as tundra snow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.175#There were broad basins there, lined with stone,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.176#Where the Trojan women used to wash their silky clothes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.177#In the days of peace, before the Greeks came.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.178#They ran by these springs, pursuer and pursued---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.179#A great man out front, a far greater behind---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.180#And they ran all out. This was not a race
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.181#For such a prize as athletes compete for,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.182#An oxhide or animal for sacrifice, but a race
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.183#For the lifeblood of Hector, breaker of horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.184#But champion horses wheeling round the course,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.185#Hooves flying, pouring it on in a race for a prize---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.186#A woman or tripod---at a hero's funeral games
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.187#Will give you some idea of how these heroes looked
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.188#As they circled Priam's town three times running
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.189#While all the gods looked on.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.190#Zeus, the gods' father and ours, spoke:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.191#"I do not like what I see, a man close
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.192#To my heart chased down around Troy's wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.193#Hector has burned many an ox's thigh
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.194#To me, both on Ida's peaks and in the city's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.195#High holy places, and now Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.196#Is running him down around Priam's town.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.197#Think you now, gods, and take counsel whether
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.198#We should save him from death or deliver him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.199#Into Achilles' hands, good man though he be."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.200#The grey-eyed goddess Athena answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.201#"O Father,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.202#You may be the Lord of Lightning and the Dark Cloud,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.203#But what a thing to say, to save a mortal man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.204#With his fate already fixed, from rattling death!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.205#Do it. But don't expect us all to approve."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.206#Zeus loomed like a thunderhead, but answered gently:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.207#"There, there, daughter, my heart wasn't in it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.208#I did not mean to displease you, my child. Go now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.209#Do what you have in mind without delay."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.210#Athena had been longing for action
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.211#And at his word shot down from Olympus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.212#As Achilles bore down on Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.213#A hunting hound starts a fawn in the hills,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.214#Follows it through brakes and hollows,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.215#And if it hides in a thicket, circles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.216#Picks up the trail, and renews the chase.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.217#No more could Hector elude Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.218#Every time Hector surged for the Western Gate
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.219#Under the massive towers, hoping for
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.220#Trojan archers to give him some cover,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.221#Achilles cut him off and turned him back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.222#Toward the plain, keeping the inside track.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.223#Running in a dream, you can't catch up,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.224#You can't catch up and you can't get away.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.225#No more could Achilles catch Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.226#Or Hector escape.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.227#And how could Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.228#Have ever escaped death's black birds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.229#If Apollo had not stood by his side
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.230#This one last time and put life in his knees?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.231#Achilles shook his head at his soldiers:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.232#He would not allow anyone to shoot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.233#At Hector and win glory with a hit,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.234#Leaving him only to finish him off.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.235#But when they reached the springs the fourth time,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.236#Father Zeus stretched out his golden scales
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.237#And placed on them two agonizing deaths,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.238#One for Achilles and one for Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.239#When he held the beam, Hector's doom sank down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.240#Toward Hades. And Phoebus Apollo left him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.241#By now the grey-eyed goddess Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.242#Was at Achilles' side, and her words flew fast:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.243#"There's nothing but glory on the beachhead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.244#For us now, my splendid Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.245#Once we take Hector out of action, and
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.246#There's no way he can escape us now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.247#Not even if my brother Apollo has a fit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.248#And rolls on the ground before the Almighty.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.249#You stay here and catch your breath while I go
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.250#To persuade the man to put up a fight."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.251#Welcome words for Achilles. He rested,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.252#Leaning on his heavy ash and bronze spear,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.253#While the goddess made her way to Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.254#The spitting image of Deïphobus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.255#And her voice sounded like his as she said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.256#"Achilles is pushing you hard, brother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.257#In this long footrace around Priam's town.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.258#Why don't we stand here and give him a fight?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.259#Hector's helmet flashed as he turned and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.260#"Deïphobus, you've always been my favorite
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.261#Brother, and again you've shown me why,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.262#Having the courage to come out for me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.263#Leaving the safety of the wall, while all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.264#Priam's other sons are cowering inside."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.265#And Athena, her eyes as grey as winter moons:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.266#"Mother and father begged me by my knees
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.267#To stay inside, and so did all my friends.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.268#That's how frightened they are, Hector. But I
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.269#Could not bear the pain in my heart, brother.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.270#Now let's get tough and fight and not spare
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.271#Any spears. Either Achilles kills us both
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.272#And drags our blood-soaked gear to the ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.273#Or he goes down with your spear in his guts."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.274#That's how Athena led him on, with guile.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.275#And when the two heroes faced each other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.276#Great Hector, helmet shining, spoke first:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.277#"I'm not running any more, Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.278#Three times around the city was enough.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.279#I've got my nerve back. It's me or you now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.280#But first we should swear a solemn oath.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.281#With all the gods as witnesses, I swear:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.282#If Zeus gives me the victory over you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.283#I will not dishonor your corpse, only
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.284#Strip the armor and give the body back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.285#To the Greeks. Promise you'll do the same."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.286#And Achilles, fixing his eyes on him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.287#"Don't try to cut any deals with me, Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.288#Do lions make peace treaties with men?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.289#Do wolves and lambs agree to get along?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.290#No, they hate each other to the core,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.291#And that's how it is between you and me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.292#No talk of agreements until one of us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.293#Falls and gluts Ares with his blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.294#By God, you'd better remember everything
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.295#You ever knew about fighting with spears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.296#But you're as good as dead. Pallas Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.297#And my spear will make you pay in a lump
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.298#For the agony you've caused by killing my friends."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.299#With that he pumped his spear arm and let fly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.300#Hector saw the long flare the javelin made, and ducked.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.301#The bronze point sheared the air over his head
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.302#And rammed into the earth. But Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.303#Pulled it out and gave it back to Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.304#Without Hector noticing. And Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.305#Prince of Troy, taunted Achilles:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.306#"Ha! You missed! Godlike Achilles! It looks like
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.307#You didn't have my number after all.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.308#You said you did, but you were just trying
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.309#To scare me with big words and empty talk.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.310#Did you think I'd run and you'd plant a spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.311#In my back? It'll take a direct hit in my chest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.312#Coming right at you, that and a god's help too.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.313#Now see if you can dodge this piece of bronze.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.314#I'd like for you to swallow it whole! The war will be much easier
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.315#On the Trojans with you dead and gone."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.316#And Hector let his heavy javelin fly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.317#A good throw, too, hitting Achilles' shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.318#Dead center, but it only rebounded away.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.319#Angry that his throw was wasted, Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.320#Fumbled about for a moment, reaching
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.321#For another spear. He shouted to Deïphobus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.322#But Deïphobus was nowhere in sight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.323#It was then that Hector knew in his heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.324#What had happened, and said to himself:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.325#"I hear the gods calling me to my death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.326#I thought I had a good man here with me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.327#Deïphobus, but he's still on the wall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.328#Athena tricked me. Death is closing in
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.329#And there's no escape. Zeus and Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.330#Must have chosen this long ago, even though
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.331#They used to be on my side. Well, this is fate,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.332#But I will not perish without doing some great deed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.333#That future generations will remember."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.334#And he drew the sharp broadsword that hung
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.335#By his side and gathered himself for a charge.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.336#A high-flying eagle dives
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.337#Through ebony clouds down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.338#To the sun-scutched plain to claw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.339#A lamb or a quivering hare.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.340#Thus Hector's charge, and the light
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.341#That played from his blade's honed edge.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.342#Opposite him, Achilles exploded forward, fury
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.343#Incarnate behind the curve of his shield,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.344#A glory of metalwork, and the plumes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.345#Nodded and rippled on his helmet's crest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.346#Thick golden horsehair set by Hephaestus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.347#And his spearpoint glinted like the Evening Star
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.348#In the gloom of night,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.349#Star of perfect splendor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.350#A gleam in the air as Achilles poised
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.351#His spear with murderous aim at Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.352#Eyes boring into the beautiful skin,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.353#Searching for the weak spot. Hector's body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.354#Was encased in the glowing bronze armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.355#He had stripped from the fallen Patroclus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.356#But where the collarbones join at the neck
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.357#The gullet offered swift and certain death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.358#It was there Achilles drove his spear through
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.359#As Hector charged. The heavy bronze apex
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.360#Pierced the soft neck but did not slit the windpipe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.361#So that Hector could speak still.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.362#He fell back in the dust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.363#And Achilles exulted:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.364#"So you thought you could get away with it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.365#Didn't you, Hector? Killing Patroclus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.366#And ripping off his armor, my armor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.367#Thinking I was too far away to matter.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.368#You fool. His avenger was far greater---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.369#And far closer---than you could imagine,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.370#Biding his time back in our beachhead camp.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.371#And now I have laid you out on the ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.372#Dogs and birds are going to draw out your guts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.373#While the Greeks give Patroclus burial."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.374#And Hector, barely able to shake the words out:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.375#"I beg you, Achilles, by your own soul
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.376#And by your parents, do not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.377#Allow the dogs to mutilate my body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.378#By the Greek ships. Accept the gold and bronze
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.379#Ransom my father and mother will give you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.380#And send my body back home to be burned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.381#In honor by the Trojans and their wives."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.382#And Achilles, fixing him with a stare:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.383#"Don't whine to me about my parents,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.384#You dog! I wish my stomach would let me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.385#Cut off your flesh in strips and eat it raw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.386#For what you've done to me. There is no one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.387#And no way to keep the dogs off your head,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.388#Not even if they bring ten or twenty
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.389#Ransoms, pile them up here and promise more,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.390#Not even if Dardanian Priam weighs your body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.391#Out in gold, not even then will your mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.392#Ever get to mourn you laid out on a bier.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.393#No, dogs and birds will eat every last scrap."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.394#Helmet shining, Hector spoke his last words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.395#"So this is Achilles. There was no way
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.396#To persuade you. Your heart is a lump
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.397#Of iron. But the gods will not forget this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.398#And I will have my vengeance on that day
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.399#When Paris and Apollo destroy you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.400#In the long shadow of Troy's Western Gate."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.401#Death's veil covered him as he said these things,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.402#And his soul, bound for Hades, fluttered out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.403#Resentfully, forsaking manhood's bloom.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.404#He was dead when Achilles spoke to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.405#"Die and be done with it. As for my fate,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.406#I'll accept it whenever Zeus sends it."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.407#And he drew the bronze spear out of the corpse,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.408#Laid it aside, then stripped off the blood-stained armor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.409#The other Greeks crowded around
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.410#And could not help but admire Hector's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.411#Beautiful body, but still they stood there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.412#Stabbing their spears into him, smirking.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.413#"Hector's a lot softer to the touch now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.414#Than he was when he was burning our ships,"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.415#One of them would say, pulling out his spear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.416#After Achilles had stripped the body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.417#He rose like a god and addressed the Greeks:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.418#"Friends, Argive commanders and counsellors,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.419#The gods have granted us this man's defeat,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.420#Who did us more harm than all the rest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.421#Put together. What do you say we try
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.422#Laying a close siege on the city now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.423#So we can see what the Trojans intend---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.424#Whether they will give up the citadel
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.425#With Hector dead, or resolve to fight on?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.426#But what am I thinking of? Patroclus' body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.427#Still lies by the ships, unmourned, unburied,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.428#Patroclus, whom I will never forget
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.429#As long as I am among the living,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.430#Until I rise no more; and even if
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.431#In Hades the dead do not remember,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.432#Even there I will remember my dear friend.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.433#Now let us chant the victory paean, sons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.434#Of the Achaeans, and march back to our ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.435#With this hero in tow. The power and the glory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.436#Are ours. We have killed great Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.437#Whom all the Trojans honored as a god."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.438#But it was shame and defilement Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.439#Had in mind for Hector. He pierced the tendons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.440#Above the heels and cinched them with leather thongs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.441#To his chariot, letting Hector's head drag.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.442#He mounted, hoisted up the prize armor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.443#And whipped his team to a willing gallop
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.444#Across the plain. A cloud of dust rose
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.445#Where Hector was hauled, and the long black hair
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.446#Fanned out from his head, so beautiful once,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.447#As it trailed in the dust. In this way Zeus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.448#Delivered Hector into his enemies' hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.449#To be defiled in his own native land.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.450#Watching this from the wall, Hector's mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.451#Tore off her shining veil and screamed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.452#And his old father groaned pitifully,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.453#And all through town the people were convulsed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.454#With lamentation, as if Troy itself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.455#The whole towering city, were in flames.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.456#They were barely able to restrain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.457#The old man, frantic to run through the gates,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.458#Imploring them all, rolling in the dung,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.459#And finally making this desperate appeal:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.460#"Please let me go, alone, to the Greek ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.461#I don't care if you're worried. I want to see
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.462#If that monster will respect my age, pity me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.463#For the sake of his own father, Peleus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.464#Who is about my age, old Peleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.465#Who bore him and bred him to be a curse
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.466#For the Trojans, but he's caused me more pain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.467#Than anyone, so many of my sons,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.468#Beautiful boys, he's killed. I miss them all,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.469#But I miss Hector more than all of them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.470#My grief for him will lay me in the earth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.471#Hector! You should have died in my arms, son!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.472#Then we could have satisfied our sorrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.473#Mourning and weeping, your mother and I."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.474#The townsmen moaned as Priam was speaking.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.475#Then Hecuba raised the women's lament:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.476#"Hector, my son, I am desolate!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.477#How can I live with suffering like this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.478#With you dead? You were the only comfort
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.479#I had, day and night, wherever you were
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.480#In the town, and you were the only hope
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.481#For Troy's men and women. They honored you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.482#As a god when you were alive, Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.483#Now death and doom have overtaken you."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.484#And all this time Andromache had heard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.485#Nothing about Hector---news had not reached her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.486#That her husband was caught outside the walls.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.487#She was working the loom in an alcove
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.488#Of the great hall, embroidering flowers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.489#Into a purple cloak, and had just called
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.490#To her serving women, ordering them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.491#To put a large cauldron on the fire, so
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.492#A steaming bath would be ready for Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.493#When he came home from battle. Poor woman,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.494#She had little idea how far from warm baths
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.495#Hector was, undone by the Grey-Eyed One
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.496#And delivered into the hands of the Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.497#Then she heard the lamentation from the tower.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.498#She trembled, and the shuttle fell
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.499#To the floor. Again she called her women:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.500#"Two of you come with me. I must see
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.501#What has happened. That was Hecuba's voice.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.502#My heart is in my throat, my knees are like ice.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.503#Something terrible has happened to one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.504#Of Priam's sons. O God, I'm afraid
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.505#Achilles has cut off my brave Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.506#Alone on the plain outside the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.507#And has put an end to my husband's
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.508#Cruel courage. Hector never held back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.509#Safe in the ranks; he always charged ahead,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.510#Second to no one in fighting spirit."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.511#With these words on her lips Andromache
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.512#Ran outdoors like a madwoman, heart racing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.513#Her two waiting-women following behind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.514#She reached the tower, pushed through the crowd,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.515#And looking out from the wall saw her husband
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.516#As the horses dragged him disdainfully
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.517#Away from the city to the hollow Greek ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.518#Black night swept over her eyes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.519#She reeled backward, gasping, and her veil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.520#And glittering headbands flew off,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.521#The diadem golden Aphrodite
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.522#Gave her on that day when tall-helmed Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.523#Led her from her father's house in marriage.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.524#And now her womenfolk were around her,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.525#Hector's sisters and his brother's wives,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.526#Holding her as she raved madly for death,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.527#Until she caught her breath and her distraught
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.528#Spirit returned to her breast. She moaned then
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.529#And, surrounded by Trojan women, spoke:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.530#"Hector, you and I have come to the grief
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.531#We were both born for, you in Priam's Troy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.532#And I in Thebes in the house of Eëtion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.533#Who raised me there beneath wooded Plakos
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.534#Under an evil star. Better never to have been born.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.535#And now you are going to Hades' dark world,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.536#Underground, leaving me in sorrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.537#A widow in the halls, with an infant,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.538#The son you and I bore but cannot bless.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.539#You can't help him now you are dead, Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.540#And he can never help you. Even if
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.541#He lives through this unbearable war,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.542#There's nothing left for him in life but pain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.543#And deprivation, all his property
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.544#Lost to others. An orphan has no friends.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.545#He hangs his head, his cheeks are wet with tears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.546#He has to beg from his dead father's friends,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.547#Tugging on one man's cloak, another's tunic,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.548#And if they pity him he gets to sip
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.549#From someone's cup, just enough to moisten
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.550#His lips but not enough to quench his thirst.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.551#Or a child with both parents still alive
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.552#Will push him away from a feast, taunting him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.553#'Go away, your father doesn't eat with us.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.554#And the boy will go to his widowed mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.555#In tears, Astyanax, who used to sit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.556#In his father's lap and eat nothing but
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.557#Mutton and marrow. When he got sleepy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.558#And tired of playing he would take a nap
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.559#In a soft bed nestled in his nurse's arms
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.560#His dreaming head filled with blossoming joy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.561#But now he'll suffer, now he's lost his father.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.562#The Trojans called him Astyanax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.563#Because you alone were Troy's defender,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.564#You alone protected their walls and gates.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.565#Now you lie by the curved prows of the ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.566#Far from your parents. The dogs will glut
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.567#On your naked body, and shiny maggots
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.568#Will eat what's left.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.569#Your clothes are stored away,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.570#Beautiful, fine clothes made by women's hands---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.571#I'll burn them all now in a blazing fire.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.572#They're no use to you, you'll never lie
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.573#On the pyre in them. Burning them will be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.574#Your glory before Trojan men and women."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:22.575#And the women's moans came in over her lament.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.1#While the Trojans lamented throughout the city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.2#The Greeks came to their beachhead camp
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.3#On the Hellespont and dispersed, each man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.4#To his own ship.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.5#But Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.6#Did not dismiss the Myrmidons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.7#He addressed his troops, men who lived for war:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.8#"Myrmidons! I know you love your horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.9#But before we unhitch them from the chariots
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.10#Let us all stay in armor and drive up close
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.11#And weep for Patroclus. We owe it to the dead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.12#After we've indulged in grief and sorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.13#We can loosen our horses and eat together."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.14#He spoke, and led them in their lamentation.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.15#Three times they drove their horses round the corpse,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.16#Wailing as they went. Thetis was with them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.17#And she honed their desire for grief. The sand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.18#Was wet, and the warriors' armor, wet with tears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.19#They missed him. God, how he could fight!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.20#Achilles' voice rose through their choked sobbing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.21#As he placed his man-slaying hands on his friend's breast:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.22#"I hail you, Patroclus, even in Hades!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.23#I am fulfilling all that I promised before,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.24#To drag Hector here and feed him raw to the dogs,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.25#And to cut the throats of twelve fine Trojan boys
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.26#Before your pyre, in my rage at your murder."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.27#He spoke, and treated glorious Hector foully,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.28#Stretching him out in the dust before the bier
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.29#Of Menoetius' son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.30#The men took off their armor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.31#Bronze gleaming in the dusk, and unhitched
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.32#Their whinnying horses, and sat down by the ship
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.33#Of Aeacus' swift grandson, too many to count.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.34#And he made a funeral feast to satisfy their hearts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.35#Many sleek bulls bellowed beneath the knife
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.36#As they were slaughtered, many sheep, bleating goats,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.37#And white-tusked boars, rich with fat,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.38#Were skewered to roast over the fire's flame.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.39#The ground around the corpse ran cup-deep with blood.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.40#The other Greek leaders had come for Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.41#And were now escorting him to Agamemnon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.42#It had not been easy to convince him to come---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.43#His heart raged for his friend. When they reached
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.44#Agamemnon's hut, they ordered the heralds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.45#To put a cauldron on the fire, hoping to persuade
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.46#Achilles to bathe and wash off the gore.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.47#He refused outright and swore this oath:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.48#"By Zeus on high, there will not be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.49#Any washing of my head until I have laid
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.50#Patroclus on the fire, and heaped his barrow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.51#And shorn my hair, for never will I grieve
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.52#Like this again, while I am among the living.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.53#Now let's force ourselves to eat this feast.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.54#But at the break of dawn, Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.55#Order your men to bring wood and make ready
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.56#All that is fit for a dead man to have
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.57#When he goes beneath the murky gloom,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.58#So that the fire may burn him quickly out of sight
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.59#And the men return to what they have to do."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.60#He spoke, they listened, and they did as he said.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.61#They prepared a meal and each man feasted,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.62#And when they all had enough of food and drink,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.63#They went to their huts and took their rest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.64#But the son of Peleus lay groaning heavily
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.65#Among his Myrmidons on the open beach
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.66#Where the waves crashed and seethed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.67#When sleep finally took him, unknotting his heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.68#And enveloping his shining limbs---so fatigued
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.69#From chasing Hector to windy Ilion---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.70#Patroclus' sad spirit came, with his same form
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.71#And with his beautiful eyes and his voice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.72#And wearing the same clothes. He stood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.73#Above Achilles' head, and said to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.74#"You're asleep and have forgotten me, Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.75#You never neglected me when I was alive,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.76#But now, when I am dead! Bury me quickly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.77#So I may pass through Hades' gates.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.78#The spirits keep me at a distance, the phantoms
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.79#Of men outworn, and will not yet allow me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.80#To join them beyond the River. I wander
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.81#Aimlessly through Hades' wide-doored house.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.82#And give me your hand, for never again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.83#Will I come back from Hades, once you burn me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.84#In my share of fire. Never more in life
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.85#Shall we sit apart from our comrades and talk.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.86#The Fate I was born to has swallowed me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.87#And it is your destiny, though you are like the gods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.88#Achilles, to die beneath the wall of Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.89#And one thing more, Achilles. Do not lay my bones
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.90#Apart from yours, but let them lie together,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.91#Just as we were reared together in your house
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.92#After Menoetius brought me, still just a boy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.93#From Opoeis to your land because I had killed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.94#Amphidamas' son on that day we played dice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.95#And I foolishly became angry. I didn't mean to.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.96#Peleus took me into his house then and reared me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.97#With kindness, and he named me your comrade.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.98#So let one coffer enfold the bones of us both,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.99#The two-handled gold one your mother gave you."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.100#And Achilles answered him, saying:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.101#"Why have you come to me here, dear heart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.102#With all these instructions? I promise you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.103#I will do everything just as you ask.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.104#But come closer. Let us give in to grief,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.105#However briefly, in each other's arms."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.106#Saying this, Achilles reached out with his hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.107#But could not touch him. His spirit vanished like smoke,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.108#Gone under the earth, with a last, shrill cry.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.109#Awestruck, Achilles leapt up, clapping
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.110#His palms together, and said lamenting:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.111#"Ah, so there is something in Death's house,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.112#A phantom spirit, although not in a body.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.113#All night long poor Patroclus' spirit
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.114#Stood over me, weeping and wailing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.115#And giving me detailed instructions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.116#About everything. He looked so like himself."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.117#His words aroused in them a longing for grief,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.118#And they were still wailing around the corpse
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.119#When Dawn's roselight touched them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.120#Then Lord Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.121#Sent out from all over the camp a contingent
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.122#Of mules and men to gather wood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.123#Putting a good man in charge, Meriones,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.124#Idomeneus' henchman. The men went out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.125#With axes and ropes, and the mules before them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.126#Upward, downward, sideways, and slantwise,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.127#Until they came to the spurs of spring-dotted Ida.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.128#There they set to work felling high-crowned oaks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.129#With bronze axes. The trees kept crashing down.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.130#They split the trunks and bound them together
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.131#Behind the mules, who tore up the ground
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.132#As they tramped through underbrush toward the plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.133#Meriones ordered the whole crew of woodcutters
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.134#To carry back logs, and they cast them down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.135#On the shore in order, where Achilles planned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.136#A great mound for Patroclus and for himself.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.137#When they had laid out an immense amount of wood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.138#The crowd sat down and waited. Then Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.139#Ordered the Myrmidons to put on their armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.140#And yoke the horses to the chariots. They armed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.141#And mounted, charioteers and warriors both,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.142#And the chariots rolled out, with foot soldiers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.143#Following behind in an endless cloud.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.144#In the middle his comrades bore Patroclus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.145#Covering his body, as if with a garment,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.146#With hair they sheared off and cast upon it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.147#Behind them Achilles cradled his head, grieving
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.148#For the peerless friend he was sending to Hades.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.149#When they came to the place Achilles had told them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.150#They put the body down and quickly heaped up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.151#Enough wood and plenty. Then Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.152#Acting on impulse, stood apart from the pyre
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.153#And sheared off his hair, the tawny hair
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.154#He had been growing long for the River Spercheius.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.155#Brooding, he turned toward the open sea,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.156#The water glinting like wine, and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.157#"Spercheius, my father Peleus vowed in vain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.158#That when I had come home to my native land
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.159#I would shear my hair for you and sacrifice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.160#Bulls by the hundred and fifty rams unblemished
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.161#Into your springs, where your precinct is
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.162#And your smoking altar. An old man's prayer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.163#Which you did not fulfill. Since I will never
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.164#Return home to my native land, I would give
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.165#To the hero Patroclus this lock to bear with him."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.166#And he placed it in his beloved friend's hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.167#This started them all weeping, and the sun
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.168#Would have set on their lamentation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.169#Had not Achilles said to Agamemnon:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.170#[170]
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.171#"Son of Atreus---you have the widest command---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.172#These men can mourn all they want, but for now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.173#Disperse them from the pyre and have them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.174#Prepare their dinner. Those of us who are
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.175#Closest to the dead will do everything here.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.176#And we would have all the leaders stay too."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.177#The warlord Agamemnon heard him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.178#And dismissed the troops to the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.179#The funeral party stayed and heaped up wood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.180#Building a pyre a hundred feet on each side,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.181#And with heavy hearts they set the corpse on top.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.182#Then they flayed many fine sheep and oxen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.183#And laid them dressed out before the pyre.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.184#Achilles gathered the fat from them all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.185#And enfolded the body from head to foot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.186#Then heaped around it the flayed carcasses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.187#Next he set amphoras of honey and oil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.188#Against the bier, and with heavy groans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.189#Quickly cast on the pyre four high-necked horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.190#Nine dogs once fed under the prince's table.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.191#Achilles cut the throats of two and cast them on,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.192#And twelve Trojans also, sons from good families,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.193#Slashing them with bronze in a vengeful spirit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.194#Then he kindled the fire and let its iron will rage.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.195#With a groan he called his beloved friend's name:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.196#"Hear me, Patroclus, even from Hades.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.197#All that I promised you I am completing now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.198#Twelve Trojans, sons of good families,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.199#The fire consumes with you. Hector, though,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.200#I will not give to the fire to eat, but to dogs."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.201#Thus went his threat, but no dogs would eat Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.202#Aphrodite kept the dogs from his corpse
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.203#By day and by night, and she anointed him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.204#With ambrosial oil of rose, so that when Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.205#Dragged his body it would not be torn.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.206#And Phoebus Apollo drew a dark blue cloud
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.207#From the sky to the plain, covering the spot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.208#Where the body lay, so that the sun's heat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.209#Would not shrivel the flesh on his bones.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.210#But Patroclus' pyre would not kindle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.211#Achilles thought of something else to try.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.212#Standing apart from the pyre, he prayed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.213#To the North Wind and West Wind, promising
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.214#Fine offerings, pouring libations from a gold cup,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.215#And earnestly beseeching them to come and blow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.216#So the wood would kindle and the body burn.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.217#Iris heard his prayer and was off to the Winds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.218#With the message. They were all in the house
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.219#Of the brisk West Wind, eating a banquet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.220#And Iris swooped to a stop on the stone threshold.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.221#When they saw her there, they all whooshed up,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.222#And each Wind invited her to sit next to him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.223#But she refused to sit, and made this speech:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.224#"No seat for me. I'm off to Ocean's streams,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.225#To the Ethiopians. They are offering sacrifices
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.226#To the immortals, and I want to get my share.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.227#But Achilles is praying for the Winds to come---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.228#The North Wind and the howling West---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.229#And he is promising fine offerings
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.230#If you will raise the fire on Patroclus' pyre,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.231#For whom all the Achaeans are groaning aloud."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.232#She spoke and was gone. And the Winds rose
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.233#With an eerie noise, driving clouds before them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.234#They reached the sea quickly, and the waves swelled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.235#Under their whistling blast. When they came to Troy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.236#They fell on the pyre, and the flames roared to life.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.237#The whole night long the shrill winds blew steadily
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.238#On the funeral fire, and all the long night Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.239#Drew wine from a golden bowl and poured it out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.240#From a two-handled cup, wetting the earth,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.241#Ever summoning the spirit of forlorn Patroclus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.242#A father wails for his son as he burns
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.243#His bones, a son newly wed, a son whose death
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.244#Has brought his parents inconsolable grief.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.245#Achilles wailed for his friend as he burned his bones,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.246#Moving slowly about the pyre, groaning heavily.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.247#The morning star rose, speaking light to the earth,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.248#And dawn opened over the sea like a crocus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.249#The flames died down and the fire subsided.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.250#The Winds left and returned to their home
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.251#Over the Thracian sea, and it moaned beneath them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.252#Then the son of Peleus left the pyre
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.253#And lay down exhausted. He was soon asleep,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.254#But the men with Agamemnon gathered around,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.255#And the sound of their tramping woke him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.256#He sat up and spoke to them, saying:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.257#"Son of Atreus and princes of Greece,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.258#First quench the funeral fire with wine,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.259#Wherever it burned. Then gather the bones
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.260#Of Patroclus, son of Menoetius. Pick them out
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.261#Carefully. They are easily recognized,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.262#For he lay in the middle, while the others burned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.263#Off to the sides, men and horses jumbled.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.264#Then let us wrap the bones in fat and keep them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.265#In a golden bowl, until I am hidden in Hades.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.266#You need not labor over a huge barrow for him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.267#But only what is seemly. Later the Achaeans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.268#Can build it broad and high, all of you still left
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.269#Amid our thwarted ships when I am gone."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.270#Thus Peleus' swift son, and they obeyed him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.271#First they doused the pyre with wine
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.272#Wherever it had burned and the embers were thick.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.273#Then they gathered the bones of their gentle comrade
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.274#Into a golden bowl, wrapping them twice in fat,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.275#And they placed the bowl in the hut and covered it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.276#With a soft linen cloth. Then they traced a circle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.277#For a mound and laid a foundation around the pyre
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.278#And piled up earth to form a tumulus over it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.279#Then they started to go back. But Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.280#Kept all the people there and had them sit down.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.281#Then he brought prizes from his ship:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.282#Cauldrons, tripods, horses, mules, oxen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.283#Silken-waisted women, and grey iron.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.284#First he set out prizes for the chariot race:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.285#A woman whose work was immaculate
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.286#And a twenty-two gallon tripod with handles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.287#For first place; for second place, a mare,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.288#Six years old, unbroken, pregnant with a mule foal;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.289#For third place, a beautiful cauldron, unfired,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.290#Holding four gallons, still pristine white;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.291#For fourth place, two bars of gold;
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.292#For fifth, a two-handled bowl, unfired.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.293#He put out these prizes, then stood up and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.294#"Son of Atreus and Greek heroes all:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.295#These prizes await the charioteers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.296#If our games were in someone else's honor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.297#I would win first prize hands down,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.298#For you know how superior my horses are,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.299#Immortal in fact, a gift from Poseidon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.300#To my father Peleus, who gave them to me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.301#But I will sit this one out, and my horses too,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.302#Who have lost the glorious, brave charioteer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.303#Who was so kind to them, who would often
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.304#Rub down their coats with soft olive oil
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.305#After bathing them with bright water. It is for him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.306#The two of them now stand in grief, their manes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.307#Trailing on the ground, standing there in sorrow.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.308#But this is the call for any other Achaean
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.309#Who trusts his horses and jointed chariot."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.310#The charioteers responded quickly.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.311#Eumelus was first up, Admetus' son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.312#A prince and a fine horseman,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.313#Followed by Diomedes, who yoked up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.314#The horses of Tros, which he had taken
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.315#From Aeneas (though Apollo saved the man).
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.316#Atreus' son Menelaus was next, yoking up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.317#A fast team, Agamemnon's mare, Aethe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.318#And his own horse, Podargus. The mare
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.319#Had been given to Agamemnon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.320#By Echepolus, Anchises' son, as a bribe
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.321#So he wouldn't have to go to windy Ilion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.322#But could stay at home and enjoy the wealth
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.323#Zeus had given him in spacious Sicyon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.324#The mare, at any rate, was eager to race.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.325#Antilochus was the fourth entry, Nestor's son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.326#His fleet, combed horses were bred in Pylos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.327#And as Antilochus was yoking them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.328#His noble father came up to give him advice,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.329#Well-meant, but his son already understood:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.330#"Antilochus, young as you are, Zeus and Poseidon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.331#Have taught you all there is to know about horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.332#There is no need for me to teach you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.333#What you already know---how to round a turn
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.334#And so forth. However, your horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.335#Are the slowest in the race, and that spells trouble.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.336#But if the others' horses are faster, that doesn't mean
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.337#They know more than you or are better strategists.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.338#Well then, my boy, develop your strategy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.339#So that prizes in games won't elude your grasp.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.340#Strategy makes a better woodcutter than strength.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.341#Strategy keeps a pilot's ship on course
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.342#When crosswinds blow it over the wine-blue sea.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.343#And strategy wins races for charioteers.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.344#One type of driver trusts his horses and car
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.345#And swerves mindlessly this way and that,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.346#All over the course, without reining his horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.347#But a man who knows how to win with lesser horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.348#Keeps his eye on the post and cuts the turn close,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.349#And from the start keeps tension on the reins
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.350#With a firm hand as he watches the leader.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.351#[350]
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.352#Now here's a sign you can't possibly miss:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.353#A dry stump stands about a fathom high,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.354#Either oak or pine, something rain won't rot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.355#With two white stones set close on each side
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.356#Where the smooth stretches of the course converge,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.357#Either the grave marker of a man long dead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.358#Or the goal of a race in an earlier age.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.359#Achilles has made this his turning post.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.360#Crowd it when you drive your horses by,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.361#Leaning gently to their left in your leather rig
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.362#As you urge your right horse on and give him rein
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.363#Have your left horse crimp the turning post
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.364#So close that the hub of your well-made wheel
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.365#Seems to scrape its edge. But don't touch the stone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.366#Or you'll wreck your chariot and injure your team,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.367#A humiliation for you which the others would love.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.368#So keep your wits about you, my boy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.369#If you drive past the rest at the turning post
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.370#No one will catch you or pass you in a sprint,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.371#Not even if Arion were following your wheel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.372#Adrastus' swift horse from a breed divine,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.373#Or one of Laomedon's excellent local stock."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.374#Thus Nestor, son of Neleus, who then sat down,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.375#Having explained to his dear son every last detail.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.376#Meriones was the fifth to enter the race.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.377#They mounted their chariots and cast in their lots.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.378#Achilles shook them and out jumped the lot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.379#Of Antilochus for the pole position.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.380#Eumelus drew the next slot. Then came
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.381#Meriones, and after him Menelaus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.382#Diomedes, the best man in the field,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.383#Drew the last position for his horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.384#They took their places on the line, and Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.385#Showed them the turning post far off on the plain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.386#And he posted Phoenix there, his father's comrade,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.387#To monitor the race and report the facts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.388#They curled their whips above their horses' backs,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.389#Smacked them with the reins, and with hurried yells
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.390#They were off, streaking across the plain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.391#And away from the ships, dust rising up under
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.392#The horses' chests like a line of thunderheads,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.393#Their manes streaming in the jets of wind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.394#The chariots sometimes rolled, sometimes hurtled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.395#Over the ground, and the drivers stood in them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.396#With their hearts pounding for victory, calling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.397#To their horses, who flew along in the dust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.398#It was when they were racing down the final stretch
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.399#Back toward the grey sea that the men showed their valor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.400#And the horses extended themselves. Eumelus' mares
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.401#Jumped into the lead, with Diomedes' stallions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.402#Not far behind, so close in fact they seemed to mount
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.403#Eumelus' chariot, and their breath was warm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.404#On his shoulders and back, their heads inches behind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.405#Diomedes would have passed him, or drawn up even,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.406#Had not Apollo become peeved with Tydeus' son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.407#And knocked the shining lash from his hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.408#Diomedes' eyes filled with angry tears
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.409#When he saw the mares pick up their speed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.410#And his own horses hampered, running without a goad.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.411#But Athena saw Apollo cheat Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.412#And swooped up behind the Greek commander,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.413#Returned his lash, and strengthened his horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.414#Then the angry goddess went after Eumelus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.415#And broke his horses' yoke. The mares swerved
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.416#Off course, and the pole slipped to the ground.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.417#Eumelus rolled from the car alongside one wheel,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.418#Skinning his elbows, mouth, and nose
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.419#And bruising his forehead above his eyebrows.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.420#His eyes filled with tears, and his voice choked.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.421#Diomedes steered his horses aside and drove on,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.422#Shooting out far ahead of the rest, for Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.423#Bolstered his horses and gave him the power.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.424#Fair-haired Menelaus was in second behind him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.425#Then Antilochus called to his father's horses:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.426#"Get in there, you two, and give it all you have!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.427#Don't worry about catching those horses up there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.428#That Diomedes is driving. Athena
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.429#Has speeded them up and given him glory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.430#But you'd better catch Menelaus' horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.431#And quickly, or be shamed by Aethe, a mare!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.432#Why are you studs being left behind?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.433#I'll tell you something you can count on, though:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.434#Lord Nestor won't put up with you two.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.435#He'll kill you with cold steel in a heartbeat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.436#If you pull in a cheap prize through lack of effort.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.437#So get on it! Pour on all the speed you have,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.438#And I'll take care of the rest, find a spot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.439#Where we can slip past them on the narrow road."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.440#The horses were frightened by their master's rebuke
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.441#And ran faster for a short time. Antilochus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.442#Who was a real fighter, saw that the course narrowed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.443#Into a gully just ahead, where the winter torrents
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.444#Had washed out the road. Menelaus drove in
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.445#So that their wheels wouldn't touch, but Antilochus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.446#Drove off parallel to the road and gave chase.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.447#Menelaus was afraid and shouted over to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.448#"Antilochus, you're driving recklessly! Rein in!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.449#You can pass up ahead where the road gets wider.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.450#You'll wreck us both if you graze my car."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.451#But Antilochus drove even harder,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.452#Plying the lash as if he hadn't heard.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.453#They kept on this way about the distance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.454#A discus flies after a good hard throw,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.455#But then Menelaus reined in his mares,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.456#Afraid that the horses would tangle their hooves,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.457#Overturn their rigs, and send them sprawling
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.458#Into the dust as they strained for victory.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.459#He had some angry words for Antilochus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.460#"Out of my way, you malicious brat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.461#To think we gave you credit for good sense!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.462#But you'll get no prize without going on oath."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.463#Then he called to his horses:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.464#"Don't hold back and stand around grieving.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.465#Their feet and knees will tire before yours.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.466#It's been a long time since those horses were young."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.467#Frightened by their master's rebuke, the horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.468#Picked up the pace and soon closed the gap.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.469#The assembled spectators watched as the horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.470#Flew across the plain in a cloud of dust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.471#The first to spot them was Idomeneus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.472#The Cretan commander, who had taken a seat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.473#On a lookout point apart from the crowd.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.474#When he heard Menelaus shout in the distance,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.475#He knew who it was, and he could make out a horse
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.476#With distinct markings leading the race,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.477#Bay all over, with a white moon on its forehead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.478#He stood up and announced to the crowd:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.479#"Friends, Argive commanders and rulers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.480#Am I the only one or do you see them too?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.481#We've got new horses in the lead now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.482#A new charioteer. The mares that were in front
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.483#On the way out must have gotten into trouble
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.484#Somewhere on the plain. I saw them swing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.485#Into the turn first, but now I can't see them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.486#Anywhere at all on the Trojan plain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.487#Maybe the reins slipped, and he lost control
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.488#Coming out of the turn. That must be it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.489#He must have crashed there, and the mares
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.490#Must have run off the course wild with terror.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.491#Stand up and have a look. I'm not sure,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.492#But the driver seems to be an Aetolian,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.493#Which would make him no other than the son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.494#Of Tydeus, breaker of horses, tough Diomedes."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.495#Oïlean Ajax gave him a hard time:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.496#"Do you always have to mouth off, Idomeneus?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.497#They're still galloping way the hell out there.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.498#You're not so young that your eyesight is perfect,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.499#But you have the biggest mouth, which you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.500#Shouldn't let flap in the presence of your betters.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.501#The same mares are in the lead as were before,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.502#Eumelus', and he's in the car holding the reins."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.503#Angry now, the Cretan commander answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.504#"You're big on insults, Ajax, but short on brains
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.505#And stubborn, which is why you're such a loser.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.506#Why don't we bet something, a tripod or cauldron,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.507#And have Agamemnon decide for us which mares
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.508#Are out front, so you can learn by paying."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.509#He spoke, and Ajax jumped up abruptly
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.510#In an ugly mood. It would have gone further
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.511#Had not Achilles himself stood up and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.512#"Let's break it up, Ajax and Idomeneus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.513#It's unseemly. If you heard someone else arguing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.514#With language like this you would be outraged.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.515#No, sit down now and watch for the horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.516#They'll be in the home stretch soon, running to win,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.517#And then each man can see for himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.518#Which horses are in first place and which in second."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.519#He had just said this when Diomedes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.520#Was almost upon them, pushing hard,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.521#Laying on the lash for all he was worth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.522#His horses leapt high as they ate up the road,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.523#Kicking flakes of dust back onto their driver,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.524#And the chariot, plated with gold and tin,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.525#Rolled on behind the swift-footed horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.526#Their wheels barely tracing a track
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.527#In the light dust as the team flew on.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.528#Diomedes stopped in the middle of the crowd,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.529#Sweat pouring from his horses' necks and chests,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.530#And he leapt down from his gleaming chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.531#And leaned the lash against the yoke. Sthenelus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.532#Lost no time in collecting the prize for him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.533#And delivering to his proud comrades the woman
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.534#And the eared tripod. Then he unyoked the horses.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.535#Antilochus pulled in next, taking second place
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.536#From Menelaus, with tactics rather than speed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.537#Even so, Menelaus was close behind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.538#A horse pulling a chariot across a plain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.539#Can be so close to the wheel that its tail
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.540#Scrapes the rim with its hindmost hairs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.541#Menelaus was that close behind Antilochus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.542#Although he had been a discus throw behind,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.543#He made up ground quickly when Aethe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.544#Agamemnon's pretty mare, began to feel her mettle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.545#And had the course been longer he would have
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.546#Passed Antilochus without any question.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.547#Meriones, Idomeneus' lieutenant,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.548#Was a spearcast behind. His horses were the slowest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.549#And he was the least skillful driver.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.550#Last of all came the son of Admetus, dragging
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.551#His chariot and driving his horses along.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.552#Achilles, the great sprinter, felt sorry for him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.553#And he addressed the crowd with winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.554#"Look, the best man is coming in last.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.555#He should get a prize, the prize for second.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.556#But let Tydeus' son take first prize."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.557#Everyone agreed, and he would have given
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.558#The mare to Eumelus---for he had their approval---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.559#But Antilochus, son of great-souled Nestor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.560#Registered this complaint with Achilles:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.561#"I will be really angry with you, Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.562#If you do what you say. You're going to rob me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.563#Of my prize, on the grounds that Eumelus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.564#Had an accident with his horses and chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.565#Good as he is. He should have prayed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.566#To the immortals, and he wouldn't have lost.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.567#But if you like him so much and feel so bad for him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.568#You have enough gold and bronze in your huts,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.569#And sheep and women and solid-hooved horses,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.570#To give him an even better prize later,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.571#Or do it right now so the Greeks can applaud you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.572#But I'm not giving up the mare. Anybody
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.573#Who wants to is welcome to fight me for her."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.574#And swift-footed, godlike Achilles smiled.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.575#He liked Antilochus and was glad for him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.576#And the onshore breeze carried his answer:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.577#"Antilochus, if you want me to give Eumelus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.578#Something else from my hut, I will do so.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.579#I'll give him the corselet I took from
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.580#Asteropaeus. It is bronze plated with circles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.581#Of bright tin, and something he will value."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.582#He asked Automedon to bring it from the hut,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.583#And he went and brought it, and placed it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.584#In Eumelus' hands, who received it gratefully.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.585#Then up rose Menelaus, troubled at heart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.586#And furious with Antilochus. A herald
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.587#Put the staff in his hands and asked for silence.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.588#Then the godlike man began to speak:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.589#"Antilochus, you have shown good sense
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.590#In the past, but look at what you have done now.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.591#You shamed my valor when you fouled my horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.592#And forced yours in front though they were not as good.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.593#Come now, Argive commanders and counsellors,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.594#And judge between us without any bias,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.595#So that no Achaean man at arms can say,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.596#'Menelaus beat out Antilochus with lies
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.597#And went off with the mare. His horses were worse
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.598#By a long shot, but he had more clout.'
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.599#Here's my judgment, and I don't think anyone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.600#Will reproach me for it, because it will be just.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.601#Antilochus, come here, prince, and as is the custom,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.602#Stand before your horses and chariot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.603#Hold in your hand the slender lash you drove with,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.604#And touching your horses swear to the Earthshaker
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.605#That you didn't deliberately block my chariot."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.606#And Antilochus very sensibly replied:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.607#"Bear with me now. I am much younger than you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.608#Lord Menelaus. You are the elder and the better man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.609#And familiar with the transgressions of youth,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.610#Our impulsive notions and light-headed thoughts.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.611#So please, be tolerant. The mule that I won
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.612#I will give to you, and if you should demand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.613#Something even better that I have in my house,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.614#I would rather give it to you, my prince,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.615#Than fall out of your good graces all of my days
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.616#And become a sinner in the eyes of the gods."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.617#Thus Nestor's son, and he led up the mare
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.618#And gave it to Menelaus, whose heart warmed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.619#Like morning dew on full ears of wheat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.620#When the sun ripens the bristling crop.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.621#Yes, Menelaus, your heart warmed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.622#And your words went to him on wings:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.623#"Antilochus, I accept your apology
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.624#Although I am angry, for never before
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.625#Have you been out of line or malicious.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.626#This time your youth got the better of you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.627#Just don't try to outsmart your betters again.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.628#There are very few men in this army
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.629#Who could have won me over like that,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.630#But you have gone through a lot for my sake,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.631#As have your brave father and brother.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.632#So I not only accept your apology,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.633#But I will give you the mare, which is mine by rights,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.634#To the end that everyone here may know
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.635#That my heart is not overbearing or hard."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.636#And he gave the mare to Noëmon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.637#Antilochus' comrade, and took for himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.638#The shining cauldron. Meriones took
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.639#The two talents of gold for fourth place,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.640#Which was where he finished, but the fifth prize,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.641#The two-handled bowl, was left unclaimed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.642#This bowl Achilles gave to Nestor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.643#Bringing it to him through the crowd and saying:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.644#"Take this, reverend sir, as your keepsake
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.645#And memorial of Patroclus' burial,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.646#For you will not see him again among the Greeks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.647#I simply give you this prize, for you will not compete
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.648#In boxing or wrestling, or enter the javelin throw,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.649#Or run in the sprints. Old age is heavy upon you."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.650#Nestor took the bowl from his hands and was glad.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.651#Then he addressed Achilles with winged words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.652#"Yes, my boy, right you are. My limbs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.653#Are no longer firm, my feet, my hands,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.654#And I have no punch left in my arms.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.655#O, if I were young and strong again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.656#As I was on that day when the Epeians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.657#Were burying lord Amarynceus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.658#At Buprasium, and his sons put up prizes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.659#In his honor. Not a man there was my equal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.660#Not an Epeian, Pylian, or Aetolian hero.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.661#I outboxed Clytomedes, Enops' son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.662#And in wrestling I threw Ancaeus of Pleuron.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.663#I beat out Iphiclus in the sprint, good as he was,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.664#And outthrew Phyleus and Polydorus both
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.665#In the javelin. It was only in the chariot race
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.666#That the twin sons of Actor outdrove me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.667#Crowding me out, jealous for victory
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.668#Because the best prizes were left for this race.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.669#They were joined at the hip. One of them drove
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.670#Steady as she goes, the other plied the whip.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.671#Well, that was then. I leave such exploits
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.672#To younger men now, and yield as I must
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.673#To grievous age. But I was the best back then.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.674#Now you bury your friend too with funeral games,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.675#And I am glad to receive this. My heart rejoices
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.676#That you are always kind enough to remember me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.677#And do not forget the honor that is my due.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.678#May the gods repay you and grant you grace."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.679#Achilles listened to all that Nestor said,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.680#Then went back again through the great throng.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.681#Then he set out prizes for the boxing match.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.682#He led in a sturdy mule and tethered her
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.683#In the assembly ground, a mule of six years,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.684#Unbroken, the hardest kind to tame.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.685#For the loser he set out a two-handled cup.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.686#Then he rose to announce to them all:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.687#"Son of Atreus and Greek heroes all:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.688#We need two men for these prizes, the two best
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.689#At trading punches. Whoever Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.690#Gives endurance to as the crowd looks on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.691#Will lead the sturdy mule to his hut.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.692#The loser's prize will be the two-handled cup."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.693#At this point a real boxer stood up, Epeius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.694#Son of Panopeus, tall and well-built,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.695#And laid hold of the sturdy mule, saying:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.696#"Anybody want the cup as his prize?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.697#Because no Greek alive is going to beat me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.698#In boxing and lead away this mule.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.699#I'm the best there is. Isn't it enough
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.700#I come up short in war? A man can't be
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.701#Good at everything. But let me tell you this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.702#And it's a sure thing: Anybody fights me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.703#I'll bust him wide open and crush his bones.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.704#Better have his next of kin standing by
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.705#To carry him out when I'm through with him."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.706#Dead silence. Only one man stood up,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.707#A godlike figure, Euryalus, whose father,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.708#Mecisteus, had once come to Thebes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.709#For the burial of Oedipus and beaten all
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.710#Of the native sons in the funeral games.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.711#Diomedes badly wanted him to win
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.712#And acted as his second. He gave him a pep talk,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.713#Then got him a loincloth and oxhide thongs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.714#To strap on his hands. When they were girded up,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.715#They stepped into the middle with hands held high
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.716#And were all over each other with flurries
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.717#Of hard punches, snapping jabs to the jaw,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.718#And the sweat was flying from their arms and legs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.719#As his opponent looked for an opening,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.720#Epeius moved in and got him with an uppercut,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.721#And Euryalus' legs were no longer under him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.722#A fish leaps out from wind-rippled shallows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.723#And is just as quickly in the black water again.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.724#Euryalus made like that when he was hit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.725#Epeius,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.726#Generous soul, pulled him upright, and his friends
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.727#Dragged him through the crowd with feet trailing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.728#Spitting out clots of blood, head hanging to one side.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.729#They set him down, groggy, among his companions
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.730#And went off to claim the two-handled cup.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.731#Then Peleus' son set out the prizes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.732#For the third event, a grueling wrestling match.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.733#For the winner he displayed a cauldron
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.734#Which the spectators guessed to be worth twelve oxen,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.735#And for the loser he put up a woman skilled
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.736#In various crafts. They rated her at four oxen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.737#Then he rose to announce to them all:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.738#"Will the contestants for this event please rise."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.739#Then up rose huge Telamonian Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.740#And wily Odysseus, who knew all the tricks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.741#They girded themselves, stepped to the middle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.742#And took their stance, gripping each other
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.743#Like crisscrossing rafters set in the gable
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.744#Of a high roof built to withstand the wind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.745#Their backs creaked under the strain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.746#Of their strong intertwined arms. Sweat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.747#Poured down their bodies, and bloody welts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.748#Rose up on their shoulders and ribs
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.749#As they struggled to win the exquisite cauldron.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.750#Odysseus couldn't trip or throw Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.751#Nor Ajax Odysseus, whose strength held firm.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.752#The crowd was getting bored, when Ajax said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.753#"Odysseus, either you lift me or let me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.754#Lift you, and let's leave it all up to Zeus."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.755#Ajax spoke and lifted him, but Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.756#Did not forget his tricks, clipping Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.757#In the back of his knee and sending him down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.758#With Odysseus on his chest. The crowd was amazed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.759#Then Odysseus tried to lift Ajax. He moved him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.760#A little from the ground but couldn't get him up.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.761#But he did hook his knee around Ajax's leg
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.762#So that they went down together. Grimy with dust,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.763#They were ready to go at it a third time,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.764#But Achilles himself rose and held them back:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.765#"No need to continue and wear yourselves out.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.766#You're both winners. Take equal prizes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.767#And go your way, so others can compete."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.768#Then Peleus' son set out prizes for a sprint.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.769#He had a silver mixing-bowl, highly wrought.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.770#It held six gallons and was the most beautiful
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.771#On earth, a masterpiece of Sidonian art.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.772#Phoenician merchants had carried it over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.773#The misty sea to the harbor of Lemnos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.774#There they gave it as a gift to Thoas,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.775#And Jason's son Euneus gave it as ransom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.776#For Priam's son Lycaon to the hero Patroclus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.777#This bowl Achilles offered as a prize
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.778#To the winning sprinter, in honor of his friend.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.779#For second he put up a great, fattened ox,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.780#And a half talent of gold for third.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.781#Then he stood up and announced:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.782#"Will the contestants for this event please rise."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.783#Up rose swift Oïlean Ajax, wily Odysseus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.784#And Nestor's son Antilochus, the fastest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.785#Of all the army's young men. They lined up,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.786#Achilles showed them the finish line,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.787#And they were off, running flat out from the pole
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.788#With Ajax moving quickly into the lead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.789#And Odysseus following close behind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.790#A woman weaving pulls the shed rod back
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.791#Close to her breast and holds it there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.792#While she spools the weft through.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.793#That's how close Odysseus was. His feet landed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.794#In Ajax's tracks before the dust had settled,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.795#And his breath beat down on Ajax's head
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.796#As he sped on. The crowd was screaming
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.797#For Odysseus to win and kept cheering him on.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.798#When they reached the final stretch, Odysseus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.799#Said a silent prayer to grey-eyed Athena:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.800#"Hear me, goddess, and don't fail my feet now."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.801#Pallas Athena heard his prayer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.802#And made his feet and hands light.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.803#But when they were about to make their final spurt,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.804#Ajax slipped as he ran---Athena's doing---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.805#In the dung that was left from all the bulls
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.806#Achilles had sacrificed in Patroclus' honor.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.807#Odysseus, finishing first, collected the bowl,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.808#And glorious Ajax, spewing out dung
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.809#From his nostrils and mouth, took the ox.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.810#With his hands on one horn, he addressed the crowd:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.811#"Shit! The goddess tripped me up. It's like
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.812#She's Odysseus' mother, always at his side."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.813#They all had a good laugh at his expense.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.814#Then Antilochus took off the last prize,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.815#Smiling, and addressed the crowd:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.816#"As you all well know, the gods to this day
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.817#Still honor the older generation of men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.818#Ajax is just a little older than I am,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.819#But Odysseus belongs to an older generation---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.820#Old but still with plenty of juice, as they say of him---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.821#And tough to outrun, except for Achilles."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.822#Thus Antilochus, paying a compliment
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.823#To the great sprinter Achilles, who answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.824#"Antilochus, your praise will not go unrewarded.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.825#I will add a half-talent of gold to your prize."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.826#Antilochus received it gladly from his hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.827#Then Peleus' son brought onto the field
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.828#A long-shadowed spear, a shield, and a helmet,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.829#Gear that Patroclus had stripped from Sarpedon.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.830#And he announced to the crowd:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.831#"We invite two men to compete for these prizes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.832#Two good men who will fight in full armor
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.833#Before the crowd with bronze sharp to the touch.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.834#The first man to reach the other man's skin,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.835#Pierce the armor and draw blood, is the winner
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.836#And gets as his prize this silver-studded sword,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.837#Good Thracian work, I took from Asteropaeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.838#The two will hold Sarpedon's arms in common,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.839#And we will feast them both well in our quarters."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.840#He spoke, and up rose huge Telamonian Ajax
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.841#And Tydeus' son, tough Diomedes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.842#They armed themselves on opposite sides of the crowd,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.843#Then stepped into the middle, eager to fight,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.844#A cold light in their eyes. The crowd was spellbound.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.845#Three times they lunged at each other, and the third time
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.846#Ajax hit the disk of his opponent's shield
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.847#But did not get through to his corseleted skin.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.848#Diomedes kept trying to get his spear over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.849#Ajax's shield and touch his neck with the point.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.850#The crowd feared for Ajax and wanted them to stop
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.851#And take equal prizes, but Achilles gave
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.852#The sword to Diomedes with its scabbard and belt.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.853#Then Peleus' son set out a rough lump of iron
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.854#That mighty Eëtion once used to hurl.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.855#When brilliant, swift-footed Achilles killed him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.856#He took it to his ship with his other possessions.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.857#Now he rose and announced to the crowd:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.858#"Will the contestants for this event please rise.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.859#The winner here will have enough iron
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.860#To last his shepherd and plowman five full years
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.861#And not have to send them to town to buy more."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.862#Then up rose the battler Polypoetes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.863#Along with Leonteus, strong and godlike,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.864#Telamonian Ajax, and resplendent Epeius.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.865#They lined up and Epeius went first,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.866#Whirling around with the lump of iron
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.867#And heaving it out. The crowd laughed at his throw.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.868#Leonteus went second, and then big Ajax,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.869#Whose throw went farther than the other marks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.870#But when Polypoetes heaved the iron
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.871#He sent it sailing over the heads of the crowd
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.872#Like a cowhand's bolas over a herd of cattle.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.873#The crowd roared, and Polypoetes' men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.874#Carried the prize to their strong king's ship.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.875#Then Achilles set out iron for the archers,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.876#Ten double axeheads and ten single
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.877#With a violet sheen. And he set up the mast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.878#Of a tarred ship far off in the sand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.879#And attached to the top a fine cord
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.880#Tied onto the foot of a quivering dove.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.881#He told them this was their target:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.882#"Whoever hits the fluttering dove
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.883#Will take home the double axes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.884#Hitting the cord but not the bird
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.885#Gets second place and the single axes."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.886#Then up rose lord Teucer in his might
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.887#And Meriones, Idomeneus' comrade.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.888#They put their lots in a bronze helmet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.889#And shook it. Teucer drew first place.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.890#He let fly an arrow, a strong shot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.891#But he failed to vow to the Archer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.892#A sacrifice of a hundred firstling lambs.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.893#So he missed the bird---Apollo grudged him that---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.894#But he hit the cord close to where it was tied
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.895#To the bird's foot, and the keen edge severed it.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.896#The dove soared up to the sky as the cord
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.897#Sagged down to earth. Meriones grabbed the bow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.898#From Teucer---he had been holding an arrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.899#While Teucer aimed---and vowed a sacrifice
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.900#Of a hundred firstling lambs to the Archer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.901#He spotted the dove fluttering overhead
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.902#Beneath the clouds, and as she circled there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.903#He hit her smack beneath the wing. The arrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.904#Passed clean through and, falling down,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.905#Stuck in the ground before Meriones' foot.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.906#The dove landed on the mast. She hung her head,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.907#And her plumage drooped. Her life flitted away,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.908#And she dropped to the earth. The spectators
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.909#Were lost in wonder and could not believe their eyes.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.910#Meriones scooped up all ten double axeheads,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.911#And Teucer took the singles to his hollow ship.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.912#Then Peleus' son brought out a long-shadowed spear
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.913#And an unfired cauldron, worth an ox, embossed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.914#With flowers. The javelin throwers rose,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.915#Atreus' son, the warlord Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.916#And Meriones, Idomeneus' comrade.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.917#But Achilles, swift and godlike, addressed them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.918#"Son of Atreus, we recognize your power
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.919#And know you are the best at throwing spears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.920#Take the prize and return to your hollow ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.921#But we will give the spear to Meriones,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.922#With your consent. At least that's how I want it."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.923#The warlord did not disagree. He gave
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.924#The bronze spear to Meriones, then handed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:23.925#To his herald Talthybius the beautiful prize.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.1#The funeral games were over.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.2#The troops dispersed and went to their ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.3#Where they turned their attention to supper
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.4#And a good night's sleep. But sleep
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.5#That masters all had no hold on Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.6#Tears wet his face as he remembered his friend.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.7#He tossed and turned, yearning for Patroclus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.8#For his manhood and his noble heart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.9#And all they had done together, the shared pain,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.10#The battles fought, the hard times at sea.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.11#Thinking on all this, he would weep softly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.12#Lying now on his side, now on his back,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.13#And now face down. Then he would rise
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.14#To his feet and wander in a daze along the shore.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.15#Dawn never escaped him. As soon as she appeared
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.16#Over the sea and the dunes, he would hitch
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.17#Horses to his chariot and drag Hector behind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.18#When he had hauled him three times around
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.19#Patroclus' tomb, he would rest again in his hut,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.20#Leaving Hector stretched face down in the dust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.21#But Apollo kept Hector's flesh undefiled,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.22#Pitying the man even in death. He kept him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.23#Wrapped in his golden aegis, so that Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.24#Would not scour the skin as he dragged him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.25#So Achilles defiled Hector in his rage.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.26#The gods, looking on, pitied Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.27#And urged Hermes to steal the body,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.28#A plan that pleased all but Hera,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.29#Poseidon, and the Grey-Eyed One,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.30#Who were steady in their hatred
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.31#For sacred Ilion and Priam's people
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.32#Ever since Paris in his blindness
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.33#Offended these two goddesses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.34#And honored the one who fed his fatal lust.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.35#Twelve days went by. Dawn.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.36#Phoebus Apollo addressed the immortals:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.37#"How callous can you get? Has Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.38#Never burned for you thighs of bulls and goats?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.39#Of course he has. But now you cannot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.40#Bring yourselves to save even his bare corpse
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.41#For his wife to look upon, and his mother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.42#And child, and Priam, and his people, who would
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.43#Burn him in fire and perform his funeral rites.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.44#No, it's the dread Achilles that you prefer.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.45#His twisted mind is set on what he wants,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.46#As savage as a lion bristling with pride,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.47#Attacking men's flocks to make himself a feast.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.48#Achilles has lost all pity and has no shame left.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.49#Shame sometimes hurts men, but it helps them too.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.50#A man may lose someone dearer than Achilles has,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.51#A brother from the same womb, or a son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.52#But when he has wept and mourned, he lets go.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.53#The Fates have given men an enduring heart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.54#But this man? After he kills Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.55#He ties him behind his chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.56#And drags him around his dear friend's tomb.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.57#Does this make him a better or nobler man?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.58#He should fear our wrath, good as he may be,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.59#For he defiles the dumb earth in his rage."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.60#This provoked an angry response from Hera:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.61#"What you say might be true, Silverbow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.62#If we valued Achilles and Hector equally.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.63#But Hector is mortal and suckled at a woman's breast,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.64#While Achilles is born of a goddess whom I
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.65#Nourished and reared myself, and gave to a man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.66#Peleus, beloved of the gods, to be his wife.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.67#All of you gods came to her wedding,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.68#And you too were at the feast, lyre in hand,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.69#Our forever faithless and fair-weather friend."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.70#And Zeus, who masses the thunderheads:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.71#"Calm down, Hera, and don't be so indignant.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.72#Their honor will not be the same. But Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.73#Was dearest to the gods of all in Ilion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.74#At least to me. He never failed to offer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.75#A pleasing sacrifice. My altar never lacked
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.76#Libation or burnt savor, our worship due.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.77#But we will not allow his body to be stolen---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.78#Achilles would notice in any case. His mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.79#Visits him continually night and day.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.80#But I would have one of you summon Thetis
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.81#So that I might have a word with her. Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.82#Must agree to let Priam ransom Hector."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.83#Thus spoke Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.84#And Iris stormed down to deliver his message.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.85#Midway between Samos and rocky Imbros,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.86#She dove into the dark sea. The water moaned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.87#As it closed above her, and she sank into the deep
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.88#Like a lead sinker on a line
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.89#That takes a hook of sharpened horn
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.90#Down to deal death to nibbling fish.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.91#She found Thetis in a cave's hollow, surrounded
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.92#By her saltwater women and wailing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.93#The fate of her faultless son, who would die
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.94#On Trojan soil, far from his homeland.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.95#Iris, whose feet are like wind, stood near her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.96#"Rise, Thetis. Zeus in his wisdom commands you."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.97#And the silver-footed goddess answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.98#"Why would the great god want me? I am ashamed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.99#To mingle with the immortals, distraught as I am.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.100#But I will go, and he will not speak in vain."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.101#And she veiled her brightness in a shawl
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.102#Of midnight blue and set out with Iris before her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.103#The sea parted around them in waves.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.104#They stepped forth on the beach
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.105#And sped up the sky, and found themselves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.106#Before the face of Zeus. Around him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.107#Were seated all the gods, blessed, eternal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.108#Thetis sat next to him, and Athena gave place.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.109#Hera put in her hand a fine golden cup
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.110#And said some comforting words. Thetis drank
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.111#And handed the cup back. Then Zeus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.112#The father of gods and men, began to speak:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.113#"You have come to Olympus, Thetis,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.114#For all your incurable sorrow. I know.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.115#Even so, I will tell you why I have called you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.116#For nine days the gods have argued
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.117#About Hector's corpse and about Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.118#Some want Hermes to steal the body away,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.119#But I accord Achilles the honor in this, hoping
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.120#To retain your friendship along with your respect.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.121#Go quickly now and tell your son our will.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.122#The gods are indignant, and I, above all,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.123#Am angry that in his heart's fury
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.124#He holds Hector by the beaked ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.125#And will not give him up. He may perhaps fear me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.126#And so release the body. Meanwhile,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.127#I will send Iris to great-souled Priam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.128#To have him ransom his son, going to the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.129#With gifts that will warm Achilles' heart."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.130#Zeus had spoken, and the silver-footed goddess
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.131#Streaked down from the peaks of Olympus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.132#And came to her son's hut. She found him there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.133#Lost in grief. His friends were all around,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.134#Busily preparing their morning meal,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.135#For which a great, shaggy ram had been slaughtered.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.136#Settling herself beside her weeping child,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.137#She stroked him with her hand and talked to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.138#"My son, how long will you let this grief
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.139#Eat at your heart, mindless of food and rest?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.140#It would be good to make love to a woman.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.141#It hurts me to say it, but you will not live
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.142#Much longer. Death and Doom are beside you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.143#Listen now, I have a message from Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.144#The gods are indignant, and he, above all,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.145#Is angry that in your heart's fury
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.146#You hold Hector by these beaked ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.147#And will not give him up. Come now,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.148#Release the body and take ransom for the dead."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.149#And Achilles, swift of foot, answered her:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.150#"So be it. Let them ransom the dead,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.151#If the god on Olympus wills it so."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.152#So mother and son spoke many words
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.153#To each other, with the Greek ships all around.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.154#Meanwhile, Zeus dispatched Iris to Troy:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.155#"Up now, swift Iris, leave Olympus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.156#For sacred Ilion and tell Priam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.157#He must go to the Greek ships to ransom his son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.158#With gifts that will soften Achilles' heart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.159#Alone he must go, with only one attendant,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.160#An elder, to drive the mule cart and bear the man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.161#Slain by Achilles back to the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.162#He need have no fear. We will send
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.163#As his guide and escort Hermes himself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.164#Who will lead him all the way to Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.165#And when he is inside Achilles' hut,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.166#Achilles will not kill him, but will protect him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.167#From all the rest, for he is not a fool,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.168#Nor hardened, nor past awe for the gods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.169#He will in kindness spare a suppliant."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.170#Iris stormed down to deliver this message.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.171#She came to the house of Priam and found there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.172#Mourning and lamentation. Priam's sons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.173#Sat in the courtyard around their father,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.174#Fouling their clothes with tears. The old man,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.175#Wrapped in his mantle, sat like graven stone.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.176#His head and neck were covered with dung
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.177#He had rolled in and scraped up with his hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.178#His daughters and sons' wives were wailing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.179#Throughout the house, remembering their men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.180#So many and fine, dead by Greek hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.181#Zeus' messenger stood near Priam,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.182#Who trembled all over as she whispered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.183#"Courage, Priam, son of Dardanus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.184#And have no fear. I have come to you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.185#Not to announce evil, but good.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.186#I am a messenger from Zeus, who
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.187#Cares for you greatly and pities you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.188#You must go to the Greek ships to ransom Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.189#With gifts that will soften Achilles' heart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.190#You must go alone, with only one attendant,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.191#An elder, to drive the mule cart and bear the man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.192#Slain by Achilles back to the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.193#You need have no fear. We will send
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.194#As your guide and escort Hermes himself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.195#Who will lead you all the way to Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.196#And when you are inside Achilles' hut,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.197#Achilles will not kill you, but will protect you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.198#From all the rest, for he is not a fool,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.199#Nor hardened, nor past awe for the gods.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.200#He will in kindness spare a suppliant."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.201#Iris spoke and was gone, a blur in the air.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.202#Priam ordered his sons to ready the mule cart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.203#And fasten onto it the wicker trunk.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.204#He himself went down to a high-vaulted chamber,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.205#Fragrant with cedar, that glittered with jewels.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.206#And he called to Hecuba, his wife, and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.207#"A messenger has come from Olympian Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.208#I am to go to the ships to ransom our son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.209#And bring gifts that will soften Achilles' heart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.210#What do you make of this, Lady? For myself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.211#I have a strange compulsion to go over there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.212#Into the wide camp of the Achaean ships."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.213#Her first response was a shrill cry, and then:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.214#"This is madness. Where is the wisdom
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.215#You were once respected for at home and abroad?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.216#How can you want to go to the Greek ships alone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.217#And look into the eyes of the man who has killed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.218#So many of your fine sons? Your heart is iron.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.219#If he catches you, or even sees you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.220#He will not pity you or respect you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.221#Savage and faithless as he is. No, we must mourn
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.222#From afar, sitting in our hall. This is how Fate
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.223#Spun her stern thread for him in my womb,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.224#That he would glut lean hounds far from his parents,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.225#With that violent man close by. I could rip
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.226#His liver bleeding from his guts and eat it whole.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.227#That would be at least some vengeance
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.228#For my son. He was no coward, but died
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.229#Protecting the men and women of Troy
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.230#Without a thought of shelter or flight."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.231#And the old man, godlike Priam:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.232#"Don't hold me back when I want to go,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.233#And don't be a bird of ill omen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.234#In my halls. You will not persuade me!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.235#If anyone else on earth told me to do this,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.236#A seer, diviner, or priest, we would
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.237#Set it aside and count it false.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.238#But I heard the goddess myself and saw her face.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.239#I will go, and her word will not be in vain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.240#If I am fated to die by the Achaean ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.241#It must be so. Let Achilles cut me down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.242#As soon as I have taken my son in my arms
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.243#And have satisfied my desire for grief."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.244#He began to lift up the lids of chests
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.245#And took out a dozen beautiful robes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.246#A dozen single-fold cloaks, as many rugs,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.247#And added as many white mantles and tunics.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.248#He weighed and brought out ten talents of gold,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.249#Two glowing tripods and four cauldrons with them,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.250#And an exquisite cup, a state gift from the Thracians
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.251#And a great treasure. The old man spared nothing
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.252#In his house, not even this, in his passion
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.253#To ransom his son. Once out in the portico,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.254#He drove off the men there with bitter words:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.255#"Get out, you sorry excuses for Trojans!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.256#Don't you have enough grief at home that you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.257#Have to come here and plague me? Isn't it enough
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.258#That Zeus has given me the pain and sorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.259#Of losing my finest son? You'll feel it yourselves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.260#Soon enough. With him dead you'll be much easier
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.261#For the Greeks to pick off. But may I be dead and gone
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.262#Before I see my city plundered and destroyed."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.263#And he waded through them, scattering them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.264#With his staff. Then he called to his sons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.265#In a harsh voice---Helenus and Paris,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.266#Agathon, Pammon, Antiphonus, Polites,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.267#Deïphobus, Hippothous, and noble Dius---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.268#These nine, and shouted at them:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.269#"Come here, you miserable brats. I wish
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.270#All of you had been killed by the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.271#Instead of Hector. I have no luck at all.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.272#I have fathered the best sons in all wide Troy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.273#And not one, not one I say, is left. Not Mestor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.274#Godlike Mestor, not Troilus, the charioteer,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.275#Not Hector, who was like a god among men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.276#Like the son of a god, not of a mortal.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.277#Ares killed them, and now all I have left
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.278#Are these petty delinquents, pretty boys, and cheats,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.279#These dancers, toe-tapping champions,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.280#Renowned throughout the neighborhood for filching goats!
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.281#Now will you please get the wagon ready
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.282#And load all this on, so I can leave?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.283#They cringed under their father's rebuke
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.284#And brought out the smooth-rolling wagon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.285#A beauty, just joinered, and clamped on
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.286#The wicker trunk. They took the mule yoke
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.287#Down from its peg, a knobbed boxwood yoke
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.288#Fitted with guide rings, and the yoke-band with it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.289#A rope fifteen feet long. They set the yoke with care
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.290#Upon the upturned end of the polished pole,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.291#Placing the ring on the thole-pin, and lashed it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.292#Tight to the knob with three turns each way,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.293#Then tied the ends to the hitch under the hook.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.294#This done, they brought from the treasure chamber
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.295#The lavish ransom for Hector's head and heaped it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.296#On the hand-rubbed wagon. Then they yoked the mules,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.297#Strong-hooved animals that pull in harness,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.298#Splendid gifts of the Mysians to Priam.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.299#And for Priam they yoked to a chariot horses
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.300#Reared by the king's hand at their polished stall.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.301#So Priam and his herald, their minds racing,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.302#Were having their rigs yoked in the high palace
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.303#When Hecuba approached them sorrowfully.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.304#She held in her right hand a golden cup
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.305#Of honeyed wine for them to pour libation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.306#Before they went. Standing by the horses she said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.307#"Here, pour libation to Father Zeus, and pray
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.308#For your safe return from the enemy camp,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.309#Since you are set on going there against my will.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.310#Pray to Cronion, the Dark Cloud of Ida,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.311#Who watches over the the whole land of Troy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.312#And ask for an omen, that swiftest of birds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.313#That is his messenger, the king of birds,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.314#To appear on the right before your own eyes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.315#Something to trust in as you go to the ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.316#But if Zeus will not grant his own messenger,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.317#I would not advise or encourage you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.318#To go to the ships, however eager you are."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.319#And Priam, with grave dignity:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.320#"I will not disregard your advice, my wife.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.321#It is good to lift hands to Zeus for mercy."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.322#And he nodded to the handmaid to pour
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.323#Pure water over his hands, and she came up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.324#With basin and pitcher. Hands washed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.325#He took the cup from his wife and prayed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.326#Standing in the middle of the courtyard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.327#And pouring out wine as he looked up to heaven:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.328#"Father Zeus, who rules from Ida,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.329#Most glorious, most great,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.330#Send me to Achilles welcome and pitied.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.331#And send me an omen, that swiftest of birds
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.332#That is your messenger, the king of birds,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.333#To appear on the right before my own eyes,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.334#That I may trust it as I go to the ships."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.335#Zeus heard his prayer and sent an eagle,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.336#The surest omen in the sky, a dusky hunter
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.337#Men call the dark eagle, a bird as large
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.338#As a doorway, with a wingspan as wide
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.339#As the folding doors to a vaulted chamber
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.340#In a rich man's house. It flashed on the right
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.341#As it soared through the city, and when they saw it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.342#Their mood brightened.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.343#Hurrying now, the old man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.344#Stepped into his chariot and drove off
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.345#From the gateway and echoing portico.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.346#In front of him the mules pulled the wagon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.347#With Idaeus at the reins. Priam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.348#Kept urging his horses with the lash
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.349#As they drove quickly through the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.350#His kinsmen trailed behind, all of them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.351#Wailing as if he were going to his death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.352#When they had gone down from the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.353#And onto the plain, his sons and sons-in-law
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.354#Turned back to Troy. But Zeus saw them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.355#As they entered the plain, and he pitied
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.356#The old man, and said to his son, Hermes:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.357#"Hermes, there's nothing you like more
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.358#Than being a companion to men, and you do obey---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.359#When you have a mind to. So go now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.360#And lead Priam to the Achaean ships, unseen
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.361#And unnoticed, until he comes to Achilles."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.362#Thus Zeus, and the quicksilver courier complied,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.363#Lacing on his feet the beautiful sandals,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.364#Immortal and golden, that carry him over
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.365#Landscape and seascape in a rush of wind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.366#And he took the wand he uses to charm
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.367#Mortal eyes asleep and make sleepers awake.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.368#Holding this wand, the tough quicksilver god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.369#Flew down to Troy on the Hellespont,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.370#And walked off as a young prince whose beard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.371#Was just darkening, youth at its loveliest.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.372#Priam and Idaeus had just driven past
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.373#The barrow of Ilus and had halted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.374#The mules and horses in the river to drink.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.375#By now it was dusk. Idaeus looked up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.376#And was aware of Hermes close by.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.377#He turned to Priam and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.378#"Beware, son of Dardanus, there's someone here,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.379#And if we're not careful we'll be cut to bits.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.380#Should we escape in the chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.381#Or clasp his knees and see if he will pity us?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.382#But the old man's mind had melted with fear.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.383#The hair bristled on his gnarled limbs,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.384#And he stood frozen with fear. But the Helper came up
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.385#And took the old man's hand and said to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.386#"Sir, where are you driving your horses and mules
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.387#At this hour of the night, when all else is asleep?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.388#Don't you fear the fury of the Achaeans,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.389#Your ruthless enemies, who are close at hand?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.390#If one of them should see you bearing such treasure
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.391#Through the black night, what would you do?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.392#You are not young, sir, and your companion is old,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.393#Unable to defend you if someone starts a fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.394#But I will do you no harm and will protect you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.395#From others. You remind me of my own dear father."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.396#And the old man, godlike Priam, answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.397#"Yes, dear son, it is just as you say.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.398#But some god has stretched out his hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.399#And sent an auspicious wayfarer to meet me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.400#You have an impressive build, good looks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.401#And intelligence. Blessed are your parents."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.402#And the Guide, limned in silver light:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.403#"A very good way to put it, old sir.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.404#But tell me this now, and tell me the truth:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.405#Are you taking all of this valuable treasure
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.406#For safekeeping abroad or are you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.407#All forsaking sacred Ilion in fear?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.408#You have lost such a great warrior, the noblest,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.409#Your son. He never let up against the Achaeans."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.410#And the old man, godlike Priam, answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.411#"Who are you, and from what parents born,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.412#That you speak so well about my ill-fated son?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.413#And Hermes, limned in silver, answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.414#"Ah, a test! And a question about Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.415#I have often seen him win glory in battle
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.416#He would drive the Argives back to their ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.417#And carve them to pieces with his bronze blade.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.418#And we stood there and marvelled, for Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.419#Angry with Agamemnon, would not let us fight.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.420#I am his comrade in arms, from the same ship,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.421#A Myrmidon. My father is Polyctor,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.422#A wealthy man, and about as old as you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.423#He has six other sons, seven, counting me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.424#We cast lots, and I was chosen to come here.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.425#Now I have come out to the plain from the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.426#Because at dawn the Achaeans
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.427#Will lay siege to the city. They are restless,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.428#And their lords cannot restrain them from battle."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.429#And the old man, godlike Priam, answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.430#"If you really are one of Achilles' men,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.431#Tell me this, and I want the whole truth.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.432#Is my son still by the ships, or has Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.433#Cut him up by now and thrown him to the dogs?"
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.434#And Hermes, limned in silver light:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.435#"Not yet, old sir. The dogs and birds have not
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.436#Devoured him. He lies beside Achilles' ship
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.437#Amid the huts just as he was at first. This is now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.438#The twelfth day he has been lying there,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.439#But his flesh has not decayed at all, nor is it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.440#Consumed by worms that eat the battle-slain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.441#Achilles does drag him around his dear friend's tomb,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.442#And ruthlessly, every morning at dawn,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.443#But he stays unmarred. You would marvel, if you came,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.444#To see him lie as fresh as dew, washed clean of blood,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.445#And uncorrupted. All the wounds he had are closed,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.446#And there were many who drove their bronze in him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.447#This is how the blessed gods care for your son,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.448#Corpse though he be, for he was dear to their hearts."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.449#And the old man was glad, and answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.450#"Yes, my boy. It is good to offer
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.451#The immortals their due. If ever
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.452#There was anyone in my house
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.453#Who never forgot the Olympian gods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.454#It was my son. And so now they have
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.455#Remembered him, even in death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.456#But come, accept from me this fine cup,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.457#And give me safe escort with the gods
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.458#Until I come to the hut of Peleus' son."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.459#And Hermes, glimmering in the dark:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.460#"Ah, an old man testing a young one.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.461#But you will not get me to take gifts from you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.462#Without Achilles' knowledge. I respect him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.463#And fear him too much to defraud him.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.464#I shudder to think of the consequences.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.465#But I would escort you all the way to Argos,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.466#With attentive care, by ship or on foot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.467#And no one would fight you for scorn of your escort."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.468#And he leapt onto the chariot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.469#Took the reins and whip, and breathed
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.470#Great power into the horses and mules.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.471#When they came to the palisade and trench
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.472#Surrounding the ships, the guards were at supper.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.473#Hermes sprinkled them with drowsiness,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.474#Then opened the gates, pushed back the bars,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.475#And led in Priam and the cart piled with ransom.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.476#They came to the hut of the son of Peleus
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.477#That the Myrmidons had built for their lord.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.478#They built it high, out of hewn fir beams,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.479#And roofed it with thatch reaped from the meadows.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.480#Around it they made him a great courtyard
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.481#With thick-set staves. A single bar of fir
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.482#Held the gate shut. It took three men
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.483#To drive this bar home and three to pull it back,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.484#But Achilles could work it easily alone.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.485#Hermes opened the gate for Priam
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.486#And brought in the gifts for Peleus' swift son.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.487#As he stepped to the ground he said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.488#"I am one of the immortals, old sir---the god
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.489#Hermes. My father sent me to escort you here.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.490#I will go back now and not come before
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.491#Achilles' eyes. It would be offensive
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.492#For a god to greet a mortal face to face.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.493#You go in, though, and clasp the knees
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.494#Of the son of Peleus, and entreat him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.495#By his father and rich-haired mother
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.496#And by his son, so you will stir his soul."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.497#And with that Hermes left and returned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.498#To high Olympus. Priam jumped down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.499#And left Idaeus to hold the horses and mules.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.500#The old man went straight to the house
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.501#Where Achilles, dear to Zeus, sat and waited.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.502#He found him inside. His companions sat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.503#Apart from him, and a solitary pair,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.504#Automedon and Alcimus, warriors both,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.505#Were busy at his side. He had just finished
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.506#His evening meal. The table was still set up.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.507#Great Priam entered unnoticed. He stood
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.508#Close to Achilles, and touching his knees,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.509#He kissed the dread and murderous hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.510#That had killed so many of his sons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.511#Passion sometimes blinds a man so completely
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.512#That he kills one of his own countrymen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.513#In exile, he comes into a wealthy house,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.514#And everyone stares at him with wonder.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.515#So Achilles stared in wonder at Priam.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.516#Was he a god?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.517#And the others there stared
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.518#And wondered and looked at each other.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.519#But Priam spoke, a prayer of entreaty:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.520#"Remember your father, godlike Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.521#He and I both are on the doorstep
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.522#Of old age. He may well be now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.523#Surrounded by enemies wearing him down
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.524#And have no one to protect him from harm.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.525#But then he hears that you are still alive
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.526#And his heart rejoices, and he hopes all his days
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.527#To see his dear son come back from Troy.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.528#But what is left for me? I had the finest sons
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.529#In all wide Troy, and not one of them is left.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.530#Fifty I had when the Greeks came over,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.531#Nineteen out of one belly, and the rest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.532#The women in my house bore to me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.533#It doesn't matter how many they were,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.534#The god of war has cut them down at the knees.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.535#And the only one who could save the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.536#You've just now killed as he fought for his country,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.537#My Hector. It is for him I have come to the Greek ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.538#To get him back from you. I've brought
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.539#A fortune in ransom. Respect the gods, Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.540#Think of your own father, and pity me.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.541#I am more pitiable. I have borne what no man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.542#Who has walked this earth has ever yet borne.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.543#I have kissed the hand of the man who killed my son."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.544#He spoke, and sorrow for his own father
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.545#Welled up in Achilles. He took Priam's hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.546#And gently pushed the old man away.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.547#The two of them remembered. Priam,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.548#Huddled in grief at Achilles' feet, cried
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.549#And moaned softly for his man-slaying Hector.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.550#And Achilles cried for his father and
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.551#For Patroclus. The sound filled the room.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.552#When Achilles had his fill of grief
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.553#And the aching sorrow left his heart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.554#He rose from his chair and lifted the old man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.555#By his hand, pitying his white hair and beard.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.556#And his words enfolded him like wings:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.557#"Ah, the suffering you've had, and the courage.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.558#To come here alone to the Greek ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.559#And meet my eye, the man who slaughtered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.560#Your many fine sons! You have a heart of iron.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.561#But come, sit on this chair. Let our pain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.562#Lie at rest a while, no matter how much we hurt.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.563#There's nothing to be gained from cold grief.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.564#Yes, the gods have woven pain into mortal lives,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.565#While they are free from care.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.566#Two jars
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.567#Sit at the doorstep of Zeus, filled with gifts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.568#That he gives, one full of good things,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.569#The other of evil. If Zeus gives a man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.570#A mixture from both jars, sometimes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.571#Life is good for him, sometimes not.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.572#But if all he gives you is from the jar of woe,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.573#You become a pariah, and hunger drives you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.574#Over the bright earth, dishonored by gods and men.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.575#Now take Peleus. The gods gave him splendid gifts
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.576#From the day he was born. He was the happiest
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.577#And richest man on earth, king of the Myrmidons,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.578#And although he was a mortal, the gods gave him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.579#An immortal goddess to be his wife.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.580#But even to Peleus the god gave some evil:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.581#He would not leave offspring to succeed him in power,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.582#Just one child, all out of season. I can't be with him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.583#To take care of him now that he's old, since I'm far
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.584#From my fatherland, squatting here in Troy,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.585#Tormenting you and your children. And you, old sir,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.586#We hear that you were prosperous once.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.587#From Lesbos down south clear over to Phrygia
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.588#And up to the Hellespont's boundary,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.589#No one could match you in wealth or in sons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.590#But then the gods have brought you trouble,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.591#This constant fighting and killing around your town.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.592#You must endure this grief and not constantly grieve.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.593#You will not gain anything by torturing yourself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.594#Over the good son you lost, not bring him back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.595#Sooner you will suffer some other sorrow."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.596#And Priam, old and godlike, answered him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.597#"Don't sit me in a chair, prince, while Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.598#Lies uncared for in your hut. Deliver him now
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.599#So I can see him with my own eyes, and you---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.600#Take all this ransom we bring, take pleasure in it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.601#And go back home to your own fatherland,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.602#Since you've taken this first step and allowed me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.603#To live and see the light of day."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.604#Achilles glowered at him and said:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.605#"Don't provoke me, old man. It's my own decision
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.606#To release Hector to you. A messenger came to me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.607#From Zeus---my own natural mother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.608#Daughter of the old sea god. And I know you,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.609#Priam, inside out. You don't fool me one bit.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.610#Some god escorted you to the Greek ships.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.611#No mortal would have dared come into our camp,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.612#Not even your best young hero. He couldn't have
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.613#Gotten past the guards or muscled open the gate.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.614#So just stop stirring up grief in my heart,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.615#Or I might not let you out of here alive, old man---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.616#Suppliant though you are---and sin against Zeus."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.617#The old man was afraid and did as he was told.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.618#The son of Peleus leapt out the door like a lion,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.619#Followed by Automedon and Alcimus, whom Achilles
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.620#Honored most now that Patroclus was dead.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.621#They unyoked the horses and mules, and led
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.622#The old man's herald inside and seated him on a chair.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.623#Then they unloaded from the strong-wheeled cart
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.624#The endless ransom that was Hector's blood price,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.625#Leaving behind two robes and a fine-spun tunic
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.626#For the body to be wrapped in and brought inside.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.627#Achilles called the women and ordered them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.628#To wash the body well and anoint it with oil,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.629#Removing it first for fear that Priam might see his son
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.630#And in his grief be unable to control his anger
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.631#At the sight of his child, and that this would arouse
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.632#Achilles' passion and he would kill the old man
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.633#And so sin against the commandments of Zeus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.634#After the female slaves had bathed Hector's body
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.635#And anointed it with olive, they wrapped it 'round
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.636#With a beautiful robe and tunic, and Achilles himself
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.637#Lifted him up and placed him on a pallet
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.638#And with his friends raised it onto the polished cart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.639#Then he groaned and called out to Patroclus:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.640#"Don't be angry with me, dear friend, if somehow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.641#You find out, even in Hades, that I have released
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.642#Hector to his father. He paid a handsome price,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.643#And I will share it with you, as much as is right."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.644#Achilles reentered his hut and sat down again
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.645#In his ornately decorated chair
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.646#Across the room from Priam, and said to him:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.647#"Your son is released, sir, as you ordered.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.648#He is lying on a pallet. At dawn's first light
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.649#You will go see him yourself.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.650#Now let's think about supper.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.651#Even Niobe remembered to eat
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.652#Although her twelve children were dead in her house,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.653#Six daughters and six sturdy sons.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.654#Apollo killed them with his silver bow,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.655#And Artemis, showering arrows, angry with Niobe
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.656#Because she compared herself to beautiful Leto.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.657#Leto, she said, had borne only two, while she
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.658#Had borne many. Well, these two killed them all.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.659#Nine days they lay in their gore, with no one
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.660#To bury them, because Zeus had turned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.661#The people to stone. On the tenth day
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.662#The gods buried them. But Niobe remembered
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.663#She had to eat, exhausted from weeping.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.664#Now she is one of the rocks in the lonely hills
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.665#Somewhere in Sipylos, a place they say is haunted
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.666#By nymphs who dance on the Achelous' banks,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.667#And although she is stone she broods on the sorrows
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.668#The gods gave her.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.669#Well, so should we, old sir,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.670#Remember to eat. You can mourn your son later
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.671#When you bring him to Troy. You owe him many tears."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.672#A moment later Achilles was up and had slain
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.673#A silvery sheep. His companions flayed it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.674#And prepared it for a meal, sliced it, spitted it,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.675#Roasted the morsels and drew them off the spits.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.676#Automedon set out bread in exquisite baskets
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.677#While Achilles served the meat. They helped themselves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.678#And satisfied their desire for food and drink.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.679#Then Priam, son of Dardanus, gazed for a while
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.680#At Achilles, so big, so much like one of the gods,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.681#And Achilles returned his gaze, admiring
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.682#Priam's face, his words echoing in his mind.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.683#When they had their fill of gazing at each other,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.684#Priam, old and godlike, broke the silence:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.685#"Show me to my bed now, prince, and quickly,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.686#So that at long last I can have the pleasure of sleep.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.687#My eyes have not closed since my son lost his life
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.688#Under your hands. I have done nothing but groan
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.689#And brood over my countless sorrows,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.690#Rolling in the dung of my courtyard stables.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.691#Finally I have tasted food and let flaming wine
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.692#Pass down my throat. I had eaten nothing till now."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.693#Achilles ordered his companions and women
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.694#To set bedsteads on the porch and pad them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.695#With fine, dyed rugs, spread blankets on top,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.696#And cover them over with fleecy cloaks.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.697#The women went out with torches in their hands
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.698#And quickly made up two beds. And Achilles,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.699#The great sprinter, said in a bitter tone:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.700#"You will have to sleep outside, dear Priam.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.701#One of the Achaean counselors may come in,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.702#As they always do, to sit and talk with me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.703#As well they should. If one of them saw you here
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.704#In the dead of night, he would tell Agamemnon,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.705#And that would delay releasing the body.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.706#But tell me this, as precisely as you can.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.707#How many days do you need for the funeral?
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.708#I will wait that long and hold back the army."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.709#And the old man, godlike Priam, answered:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.710#"If you really want me to bury my Hector,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.711#Then you could do this for me, Achilles.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.712#You know how we are penned in the city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.713#Far from any timber, and the Trojans are afraid.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.714#We would mourn him for nine days in our halls,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.715#And bury him on the tenth, and feast the people.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.716#On the eleventh we would heap a barrow over him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.717#And on the twelfth day fight, if fight we must."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.718#And Achilles, strong, swift, and godlike:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.719#"You will have your armistice."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.720#And he clasped the old man's wrist
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.721#So he would not be afraid.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.722#And so they slept,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.723#Priam and his herald, in the covered courtyard,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.724#Each with a wealth of thoughts in his breast.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.725#But Achilles slept inside his well-built hut,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.726#And by his side lay lovely Briseis.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.727#Gods and heroes slept the night through,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.728#Wrapped in soft slumber. Only Hermes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.729#Lay awake in the dark, pondering how
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.730#To spirit King Priam away from the ships
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.731#And elude the strong watchmen at the camp's gates.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.732#He hovered above Priam's head and spoke:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.733#"Well, old man, you seem to think it's safe
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.734#To sleep on and on in the enemy camp
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.735#Since Achilles spared you. Think what it cost you
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.736#To ransom your son. Your own life will cost
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.737#Three times that much to the sons you have left
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.738#If Agamemnon and the Greeks know you are here."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.739#Suddenly the old man was afraid. He woke up the herald.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.740#Hermes harnessed the horses and mules
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.741#And drove them through the camp. No one noticed.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.742#And when they reached the ford of the Xanthus,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.743#The beautiful, swirling river that Zeus begot,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.744#Hermes left for the long peaks of Olympus.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.745#Dawn spread her saffron light over earth,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.746#And they drove the horses into the city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.747#With great lamentation. The mules pulled the corpse.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.748#No one in Troy, man or woman, saw them before
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.749#Cassandra, who stood like golden Aphrodite
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.750#On Pergamum's height. Looking out she saw
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.751#Her dear father standing in the chariot
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.752#With the herald, and then she saw Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.753#Lying on the stretcher in the mule cart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.754#And her cry went out through all the city:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.755#"Come look upon Hector, Trojan men and women,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.756#If ever you rejoiced when he came home alive
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.757#From battle, a joy to the city and all its people."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.758#She spoke. And there was not a man or woman
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.759#Left in the city, for an unbearable sorrow
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.760#Had come upon them. They met Priam by the gates
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.761#As he brought the body through, and in the front
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.762#Hector's dear wife and queenly mother threw themselves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.763#On the rolling cart and pulled out their hair
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.764#As they clasped his head amid the grieving crowd.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.765#They would have mourned Hector outside the gates
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.766#All the long day until the sun went down,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.767#Had not the old man spoken from his chariot:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.768#"Let the mules come through. Later you will have
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.769#Your fill of grieving, after I have brought him home."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.770#He spoke, and the crowd made way for the cart.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.771#And they brought him home and laid him
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.772#On a corded bed, and set around him singers
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.773#To lead the dirge and chant the death song.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.774#They chanted the dirge, and the women with them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.775#White-armed Andromache led the lamentation
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.776#As she cradled the head of her man-slaying Hector:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.777#"You have died young, husband, and left me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.778#A widow in the halls. Our son is still an infant,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.779#Doomed when we bore him. I do not think
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.780#He will ever reach manhood. No, this city
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.781#Will topple and fall first. You were its savior,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.782#And now you are lost. All the solemn wives
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.783#And children you guarded will go off soon
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.784#In the hollow ships, and I will go with them.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.785#And you, my son, you will either come with me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.786#And do menial labor for a cruel master,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.787#Or some Greek will lead you by the hand
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.788#And throw you from the tower, a hideous death,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.789#Angry because Hector killed his brother,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.790#Or his father, or son. Many, many Greeks
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.791#Fell in battle under Hector's hands.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.792#Your father was never gentle in combat.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.793#And so all the townspeople mourn for him,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.794#And you have caused your parents unspeakable
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.795#Sorrow, Hector, and left me endless pain.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.796#You did not stretch your hand out to me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.797#As you lay dying in bed, nor did you whisper
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.798#A final word I could remember as I weep
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.799#All the days and nights of my life."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.800#The women's moans washed over her lament,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.801#And from the sobbing came Hecuba's voice:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.802#"Hector, my heart, dearest of all my children,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.803#The gods loved you when you were alive for me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.804#And they have cared for you also in death.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.805#My other children Achilles sold as slaves
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.806#When he captured them, shipped them overseas
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.807#To Samos, Imbros, and barren Lemnos.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.808#After he took your life with tapered bronze
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.809#He dragged you around Patroclus' tomb, his friend
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.810#Whom you killed, but still could not bring him back.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.811#And now you lie here for me as fresh as dew,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.812#Although you have been slain, like one whom Apollo
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.813#Has killed softly with his silver arrows."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.814#The third woman to lament was Helen.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.815#"Oh, Hector, you were the dearest to me by far
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.816#Of all my husband's brothers. Yes, Paris
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.817#Is my husband, the godlike prince
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.818#Who led me to Troy. I should have died first.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.819#This is now the twentieth year
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.820#Since I went away and left my home,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.821#And I have never had an unkind word from you.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.822#If anyone in the house ever taunted me,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.823#Any of my husband's brothers or sisters,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.824#Or his mother---my father-in-law was kind always---
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.825#You would draw them aside and calm them
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.826#With your gentle heart and gentle words.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.827#And so I weep for you and for myself,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.828#And my heart is heavy, because there is no one left
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.829#In all wide Troy who will pity me
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.830#Or be my friend. Everyone shudders at me."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.831#And the people's moan came in over her voice.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.832#Then the old man, Priam, spoke to his people:
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.833#"Men of Troy, start bringing wood to the city,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.834#And have no fear of an Argive ambush.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.835#When Achilles sent me from the black ships,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.836#He gave his word he would not trouble us
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.837#Until the twelfth day should dawn."
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.838#He spoke, and they yoked oxen and mules
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.839#To wagons, and gathered outside the city.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.840#For nine days they hauled in loads of timber.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.841#When the tenth dawn showed her mortal light,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.842#They brought out their brave Hector
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.843#And all in tears lifted the body high
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.844#Onto the bier, and threw on the fire.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.845#Light blossomed like roses in the eastern sky.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.846#The people gathered around Hector's pyre,
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.847#And when all of Troy was assembled there
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.848#They drowned the last flames with glinting wine.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.849#Hector's brothers and friends collected
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.850#His white bones, their cheeks flowered with tears.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.851#They wrapped the bones in soft purple robes
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.852#And placed them in a golden casket, and laid it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.853#In the hollow of the grave, and heaped above it
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.854#A mantle of stones. They built the tomb
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.855#Quickly, with lookouts posted all around
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.856#In case the Greeks should attack early.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.857#When the tomb was built, they all returned
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.858#To the city and assembled for a glorious feast
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.859#In the house of Priam, Zeus' cherished king.
urn:cts:greekLit:tlg0012.tlg001.sl:24.860#That was the funeral of Hector, breaker of horses.